INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1,'To Sherlock Holmes she is always _the_ woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2,'I have seldom heard him mention her under any other name.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3,'In his eyes she eclipses and predominates the whole of her sex.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4,'It was not that he felt any emotion akin to love for Irene Adler.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5,'All emotions, and that one particularly, were abhorrent to his cold, precise, but admirably balanced mind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(6,'He was, I take it, the most perfect reasoning and observing machine that the world has seen; but, as a lover, he would have placed himself in a false position.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(7,'He never spoke of the softer passions, save with a gibe and a sneer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(8,'They were admirable things for the observer—excellent for drawing the veil from men’s motives and actions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(9,'But for the trained reasoner to admit such intrusions into his own delicate and finely adjusted temperament was to introduce a distracting factor which might throw a doubt upon all his mental results.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(10,'Grit in a sensitive instrument, or a crack in one of his own high-power lenses, would not be more disturbing than a strong emotion in a nature such as his.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(11,'And yet there was but one woman to him, and that woman was the late Irene Adler, of dubious and questionable memory.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(12,'I had seen little of Holmes lately.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(13,'My marriage had drifted us away from each other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(14,'My own complete happiness, and the home-centred interests which rise up around the man who first finds himself master of his own establishment, were sufficient to absorb all my attention; while Holmes, who loathed every form of society with his whole Bohemian soul, remained in our lodgings in Baker Street, buried among his old books, and alternating from week to week between cocaine and ambition, the drowsiness of the drug, and the fierce energy of his own keen nature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(15,'He was still, as ever, deeply attracted by the study of crime, and occupied his immense faculties and extraordinary powers of observation in following out those clues, and clearing up those mysteries, which had been abandoned as hopeless by the official police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(16,'From time to time I heard some vague account of his doings: of his summons to Odessa in the case of the Trepoff murder, of his clearing up of the singular tragedy of the Atkinson brothers at Trincomalee, and finally of the mission which he had accomplished so delicately and successfully for the reigning family of Holland.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(17,'Beyond these signs of his activity, however, which I merely shared with all the readers of the daily press, I knew little of my former friend and companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(18,'One night—it was on the 20th of March, 1888—I was returning from a journey to a patient (for I had now returned to civil practice), when my way led me through Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(19,'As I passed the well-remembered door, which must always be associated in my mind with my wooing, and with the dark incidents of the Study in Scarlet, I was seized with a keen desire to see Holmes again, and to know how he was employing his extraordinary powers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(20,'His rooms were brilliantly lit, and, even as I looked up, I saw his tall, spare figure pass twice in a dark silhouette against the blind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(21,'He was pacing the room swiftly, eagerly, with his head sunk upon his chest and his hands clasped behind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(22,'To me, who knew his every mood and habit, his attitude and manner told their own story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(23,'He was at work again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(24,'He had arisen out of his drug-created dreams, and was hot upon the scent of some new problem.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(25,'I rang the bell, and was shown up to the chamber which had formerly been in part my own.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(26,'His manner was not effusive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(27,'It seldom was; but he was glad, I think, to see me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(28,'With hardly a word spoken, but with a kindly eye, he waved me to an arm-chair, threw across his case of cigars, and indicated a spirit case and a gasogene in the corner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(29,'Then he stood before the fire, and looked me over in his singular introspective fashion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(30,'Wedlock suits you, he remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(31,'I think, Watson, that you have put on seven and a half pounds since I saw you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(32,'Seven! I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(33,'Indeed, I should have thought a little more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(34,'Just a trifle more, I fancy, Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(35,'And in practice again, I observe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(36,'You did not tell me that you intended to go into harness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(37,'Then, how do you know?  I see it, I deduce it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(38,'How do I know that you have been getting yourself very wet lately, and that you have a most clumsy and careless servant girl?  My dear Holmes, said I, this is too much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(39,'You would certainly have been burned, had you lived a few centuries ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(40,'It is true that I had a country walk on Thursday and came home in a dreadful mess; but, as I have changed my clothes, I can’t imagine how you deduce it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(41,'As to Mary Jane, she is incorrigible, and my wife has given her notice; but there, again, I fail to see how you work it out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(42,'He chuckled to himself and rubbed his long, nervous hands together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(43,'It is simplicity itself, said he; my eyes tell me that on the inside of your left shoe, just where the firelight strikes it, the leather is scored by six almost parallel cuts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(44,'Obviously they have been caused by some one who has very carelessly scraped round the edges of the sole in order to remove crusted mud from it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(45,'Hence, you see, my double deduction that you had been out in vile weather, and that you had a particularly malignant boot-slitting specimen of the London slavey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(46,'As to your practice, if a gentleman walks into my rooms smelling of iodoform, with a black mark of nitrate of silver upon his right forefinger, and a bulge on the side of his top-hat to show where he has secreted his stethoscope, I must be dull, indeed, if I do not pronounce him to be an active member of the medical profession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(47,'I could not help laughing at the ease with which he explained his process of deduction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(48,'When I hear you give your reasons, I remarked, the thing always appears to me to be so ridiculously simple that I could easily do it myself, though at each successive instance of your reasoning I am baffled, until you explain your process.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(49,'And yet I believe that my eyes are as good as yours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(50,'Quite so, he answered, lighting a cigarette, and throwing himself down into an arm-chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(51,'You see, but you do not observe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(52,'The distinction is clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(53,'For example, you have frequently seen the steps which lead up from the hall to this room.  Frequently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(54,'How often?  Well, some hundreds of times.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(55,'Then how many are there?  How many? I don’t know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(56,'Quite so! You have not observed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(57,'And yet you have seen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(58,'That is just my point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(59,'Now, I know that there are seventeen steps, because I have both seen and observed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(60,'By-the-way, since you are interested in these little problems, and since you are good enough to chronicle one or two of my trifling experiences, you may be interested in this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(61,'He threw over a sheet of thick, pink-tinted note-paper which had been lying open upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(62,'It came by the last post, said he. Read it aloud.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(63,'The note was undated, and without either signature or address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(64,'There will call upon you to-night, at a quarter to eight o’clock, it said, a gentleman who desires to consult you upon a matter of the very deepest moment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(65,'Your recent services to one of the royal houses of Europe have shown that you are one who may safely be trusted with matters which are of an importance which can hardly be exaggerated.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(66,'This account of you we have from all quarters received.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(67,'Be in your chamber then at that hour, and do not take it amiss if your visitor wear a mask.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(68,'This is indeed a mystery, I remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(69,'What do you imagine that it means?  I have no data yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(70,'It is a capital mistake to theorize before one has data.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(71,'Insensibly one begins to twist facts to suit theories, instead of theories to suit facts. But the note itself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(72,'What do you deduce from it?  I carefully examined the writing, and the paper upon which it was written.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(73,'The man who wrote it was presumably well to do, I remarked, endeavoring to imitate my companion’s processes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(74,'Such paper could not be bought under half a crown a packet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(75,'It is peculiarly strong and stiff.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(76,'Peculiar—that is the very word, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(77,'It is not an English paper at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(78,'Hold it up to the light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(79,'I did so, and saw a large _E_ with a small _g_, a _P_, and a large _G_ with a small _t_ woven into the texture of the paper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(80,'What do you make of that? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(81,'The name of the maker, no doubt; or his monogram, rather.  Not at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(82,'The _G_ with the small _t_ stands for ‘Gesellschaft,’ which is the German for ‘Company.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(83,'’ It is a customary contraction like our ‘Co.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(84,'’ _P_, of course, stands for ‘Papier.’ Now for the _Eg_.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(85,'Let us glance at our Continental Gazetteer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(86,'He took down a heavy brown volume from his shelves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(87,'Eglow, Eglonitz—here we are, Egria.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(88,'It is in a German-speaking country—in Bohemia, not far from Carlsbad.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(89,'‘Remarkable as being the scene of the death of Wallenstein, and for its numerous glass-factories and paper-mills.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(90,'’ Ha, ha, my boy, what do you make of that? His eyes sparkled, and he sent up a great blue triumphant cloud from his cigarette.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(91,'The paper was made in Bohemia, I said.  Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(92,'And the man who wrote the note is a German.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(93,'Do you note the peculiar construction of the sentence—‘This account of you we have from all quarters received.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(94,'’ A Frenchman or Russian could not have written that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(95,'It is the German who is so uncourteous to his verbs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(96,'It only remains, therefore, to discover what is wanted by this German who writes upon Bohemian paper, and prefers wearing a mask to showing his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(97,'And here he comes, if I am not mistaken, to resolve all our doubts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(98,'As he spoke there was the sharp sound of horses’ hoofs and grating wheels against the curb, followed by a sharp pull at the bell. Holmes whistled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(99,'A pair, by the sound, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(100,'Yes, he continued, glancing out of the window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(101,'A nice little brougham and a pair of beauties.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(102,'A hundred and fifty guineas apiece.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(103,'There’s money in this case, Watson, if there is nothing else.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(104,'I think that I had better go, Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(105,'Not a bit, doctor. Stay where you are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(106,'I am lost without my Boswell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(107,'And this promises to be interesting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(108,'It would be a pity to miss it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(109,'But your client—  Never mind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(110,'I may want your help, and so may he. Here he comes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(111,'Sit down in that arm-chair, doctor, and give us your best attention.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(112,'A slow and heavy step, which had been heard upon the stairs and in the passage, paused immediately outside the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(113,'Then there was a loud and authoritative tap.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(114,'Come in! said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(115,'[Illustration: A MAN ENTERED]  A man entered who could hardly have been less than six feet six inches in height, with the chest and limbs of a Hercules.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(116,'His dress was rich with a richness which would, in England, be looked upon as akin to bad taste.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(117,'Heavy bands of Astrakhan were slashed across the sleeves and fronts of his double-breasted coat, while the deep blue cloak which was thrown over his shoulders was lined with flame-colored silk, and secured at the neck with a brooch which consisted of a single flaming beryl.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(118,'Boots which extended half-way up his calves, and which were trimmed at the tops with rich brown fur, completed the impression of barbaric opulence which was suggested by his whole appearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(119,'He carried a broad-brimmed hat in his hand, while he wore across the upper part of his face, extending down past the cheekbones, a black vizard mask, which he had apparently adjusted that very moment, for his hand was still raised to it as he entered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(120,'From the lower part of the face he appeared to be a man of strong character, with a thick, hanging lip, and a long, straight chin, suggestive of resolution pushed to the length of obstinacy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(121,'You had my note? he asked, with a deep harsh voice and a strongly marked German accent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(122,'I told you that I would call.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(123,'He looked from one to the other of us, as if uncertain which to address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(124,'Pray take a seat, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(125,'This is my friend and colleague, Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(126,'Watson, who is occasionally good enough to help me in my cases.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(127,'Whom have I the honor to address?  You may address me as the Count Von Kramm, a Bohemian nobleman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(128,'I understand that this gentleman, your friend, is a man of honor and discretion, whom I may trust with a matter of the most extreme importance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(129,'If not, I should much prefer to communicate with you alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(130,'I rose to go, but Holmes caught me by the wrist and pushed me back into my chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(131,'It is both, or none, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(132,'You may say before this gentleman anything which you may say to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(133,'The count shrugged his broad shoulders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(134,'Then I must begin, said he, by binding you both to absolute secrecy for two years, at the end of that time the matter will be of no importance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(135,'At present it is not too much to say that it is of such weight it may have an influence upon European history.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(136,'I promise, said Holmes.  And I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(137,'You will excuse this mask, continued our strange visitor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(138,'The august person who employs me wishes his agent to be unknown to you, and I may confess at once that the title by which I have just called myself is not exactly my own.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(139,'I was aware of it, said Holmes, dryly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(140,'The circumstances are of great delicacy, and every precaution has to be taken to quench what might grow to be an immense scandal and seriously compromise one of the reigning families of Europe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(141,'To speak plainly, the matter implicates the great House of Ormstein, hereditary kings of Bohemia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(142,'I was also aware of that, murmured Holmes, settling himself down in his arm-chair and closing his eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(143,'Our visitor glanced with some apparent surprise at the languid, lounging figure of the man who had been no doubt depicted to him as the most incisive reasoner and most energetic agent in Europe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(144,'Holmes slowly reopened his eyes and looked impatiently at his gigantic client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(145,'If your Majesty would condescend to state your case, he remarked, I should be better able to advise you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(146,'The man sprang from his chair and paced up and down the room in uncontrollable agitation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(147,'Then, with a gesture of desperation, he tore the mask from his face and hurled it upon the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(148,'You are right, he cried; I am the King.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(149,'Why should I attempt to conceal it?  Why, indeed? murmured Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(150,'Your Majesty had not spoken before I was aware that I was addressing Wilhelm Gottsreich Sigismond von Ormstein, Grand Duke of Cassel-Felstein, and hereditary King of Bohemia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(151,'But you can understand, said our strange visitor, sitting down once more and passing his hand over his high, white forehead, you can understand that I am not accustomed to doing such business in my own person.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(152,'Yet the matter was so delicate that I could not confide it to an agent without putting myself in his power.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(153,'I have come _incognito_ from Prague for the purpose of consulting you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(154,'Then, pray consult, said Holmes, shutting his eyes once more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(155,'The facts are briefly these: Some five years ago, during a lengthy visit to Warsaw, I made the acquaintance of the well-known adventuress, Irene Adler.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(156,'The name is no doubt familiar to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(157,'Kindly look her up in my index, doctor, murmured Holmes, without opening his eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(158,'For many years he had adopted a system of docketing all paragraphs concerning men and things, so that it was difficult to name a subject or a person on which he could not at once furnish information.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(159,'In this case I found her biography sandwiched in between that of a Hebrew Rabbi and that of a staff-commander who had written a monograph upon the deep-sea fishes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(160,'Let me see! said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(161,'Hum! Born in New Jersey in the year 1858.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(162,'Contralto—hum! La Scala, hum! Prima donna Imperial Opera of Warsaw—Yes! Retired from operatic stage—ha! Living in London—quite so! Your Majesty, as I understand, became entangled with this young person, wrote her some compromising letters, and is now desirous of getting those letters back.  Precisely so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(163,'But how—  Was there a secret marriage?  None.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(164,'No legal papers or certificates?  None.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(165,'Then I fail to follow your Majesty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(166,'If this young person should produce her letters for blackmailing or other purposes, how is she to prove their authenticity?  There is the writing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(167,'Pooh, pooh! Forgery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(168,'My private note-paper.  Stolen.  My own seal.  Imitated.  My photograph.  Bought.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(169,'We were both in the photograph.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(170,'Oh dear! That is very bad! Your Majesty has indeed committed an indiscretion.  I was mad—insane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(171,'You have compromised yourself seriously.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(172,'I was only Crown Prince then. I was young. I am but thirty now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(173,'It must be recovered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(174,'We have tried and failed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(175,'Your Majesty must pay. It must be bought.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(176,'She will not sell.  Stolen, then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(177,'Five attempts have been made.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(178,'Twice burglars in my pay ransacked her house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(179,'Once we diverted her luggage when she travelled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(180,'Twice she has been waylaid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(181,'There has been no result.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(182,'No sign of it?  Absolutely none.  Holmes laughed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(183,'It is quite a pretty little problem, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(184,'But a very serious one to me, returned the King, reproachfully.  Very, indeed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(185,'And what does she propose to do with the photograph?  To ruin me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(186,'But how?  I am about to be married.  So I have heard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(187,'To Clotilde Lothman von Saxe-Meningen, second daughter of the King of Scandinavia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(188,'You may know the strict principles of her family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(189,'She is herself the very soul of delicacy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(190,'A shadow of a doubt as to my conduct would bring the matter to an end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(191,'And Irene Adler?  Threatens to send them the photograph. And she will do it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(192,'I know that she will do it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(193,'You do not know her, but she has a soul of steel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(194,'She has the face of the most beautiful of women, and the mind of the most resolute of men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(195,'Rather than I should marry another woman, there are no lengths to which she would not go—none.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(196,'You are sure that she has not sent it yet?  I am sure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(197,'And why?  Because she has said that she would send it on the day when the betrothal was publicly proclaimed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(198,'That will be next Monday.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(199,'Oh, then, we have three days yet, said Holmes, with a yawn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(200,'That is very fortunate, as I have one or two matters of importance to look into just at present.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(201,'Your Majesty will, of course, stay in London for the present?  Certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(202,'You will find me at the Langham, under the name of the Count Von Kramm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(203,'Then I shall drop you a line to let you know how we progress.  Pray do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(204,'I shall be all anxiety.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(205,'Then, as to money?  You have _carte blanche_.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(206,'Absolutely?  I tell you that I would give one of the provinces of my kingdom to have that photograph.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(207,'And for present expenses?  The king took a heavy chamois leather bag from under his cloak and laid it on the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(208,'There are three hundred pounds in gold and seven hundred in notes, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(209,'Holmes scribbled a receipt upon a sheet of his note-book and handed it to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(210,'And mademoiselle’s address? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(211,'Is Briony Lodge, Serpentine Avenue, St. John’s Wood.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(212,'Holmes took a note of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(213,'One other question, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(214,'Was the photograph a cabinet?  It was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(215,'Then, good-night, your Majesty, and I trust that we shall soon have some good news for you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(216,'And good-night, Watson, he added, as the wheels of the royal brougham rolled down the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(217,'If you will be good enough to call to-morrow afternoon, at three o’clock, I should like to chat this little matter over with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(218,'II  At three o’clock precisely I was at Baker Street, but Holmes had not yet returned.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(219,'The landlady informed me that he had left the house shortly after eight o’clock in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(220,'I sat down beside the fire, however, with the intention of awaiting him, however long he might be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(221,'I was already deeply interested in his inquiry, for, though it was surrounded by none of the grim and strange features which were associated with the two crimes which I have already recorded, still, the nature of the case and the exalted station of his client gave it a character of its own.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(222,'Indeed, apart from the nature of the investigation which my friend had on hand, there was something in his masterly grasp of a situation, and his keen, incisive reasoning, which made it a pleasure to me to study his system of work, and to follow the quick, subtle methods by which he disentangled the most inextricable mysteries.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(223,'So accustomed was I to his invariable success that the very possibility of his failing had ceased to enter into my head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(224,'It was close upon four before the door opened, and a drunken-looking groom, ill-kempt and side-whiskered, with an inflamed face and disreputable clothes, walked into the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(225,'Accustomed as I was to my friend’s amazing powers in the use of disguises, I had to look three times before I was certain that it was indeed he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(226,'With a nod he vanished into the bedroom, whence he emerged in five minutes tweed-suited and respectable, as of old.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(227,'Putting his hands into his pockets, he stretched out his legs in front of the fire, and laughed heartily for some minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(228,'Well, really! he cried, and then he choked; and laughed again until he was obliged to lie back, limp and helpless, in the chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(229,'What is it?  It’s quite too funny.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(230,'I am sure you could never guess how I employed my morning, or what I ended by doing.  I can’t imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(231,'I suppose that you have been watching the habits, and perhaps the house, of Miss Irene Adler.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(232,'Quite so; but the sequel was rather unusual.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(233,'I will tell you, however.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(234,'I left the house a little after eight o’clock this morning, in the character of a groom out of work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(235,'There is a wonderful sympathy and freemasonry among horsey men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(236,'Be one of them, and you will know all that there is to know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(237,'I soon found Briony Lodge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(238,'It is a _bijou_ villa, with a garden at the back, but built out in front right up to the road, two stories.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(239,'Chubb lock to the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(240,'Large sitting-room on the right side, well furnished, with long windows almost to the floor, and those preposterous English window fasteners which a child could open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(241,'Behind there was nothing remarkable, save that the passage window could be reached from the top of the coach-house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(242,'I walked round it and examined it closely from every point of view, but without noting anything else of interest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(243,'I then lounged down the street, and found, as I expected, that there was a mews in a lane which runs down by one wall of the garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(244,'I lent the ostlers a hand in rubbing down their horses, and I received in exchange twopence, a glass of half-and-half, two fills of shag tobacco, and as much information as I could desire about Miss Adler, to say nothing of half a dozen other people in the neighborhood in whom I was not in the least interested, but whose biographies I was compelled to listen to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(245,'And what of Irene Adler? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(246,'Oh, she has turned all the men’s heads down in that part.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(247,'She is the daintiest thing under a bonnet on this planet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(248,'So say the Serpentine-mews, to a man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(249,'She lives quietly, sings at concerts, drives out at five every day, and returns at seven sharp for dinner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(250,'Seldom goes out at other times, except when she sings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(251,'Has only one male visitor, but a good deal of him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(252,'He is dark, handsome, and dashing, never calls less than once a day, and often twice. He is a Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(253,'Godfrey Norton, of the Inner Temple.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(254,'See the advantages of a cabman as a confidant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(255,'They had driven him home a dozen times from Serpentine-mews, and knew all about him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(256,'When I had listened to all that they had to tell, I began to walk up and down near Briony Lodge once more, and to think over my plan of campaign.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(257,'This Godfrey Norton was evidently an important factor in the matter. He was a lawyer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(258,'That sounded ominous.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(259,'What was the relation between them, and what the object of his repeated visits? Was she his client, his friend, or his mistress? If the former, she had probably transferred the photograph to his keeping.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(260,'If the latter, it was less likely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(261,'On the issue of this question depended whether I should continue my work at Briony Lodge, or turn my attention to the gentleman’s chambers in the Temple.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(262,'It was a delicate point, and it widened the field of my inquiry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(263,'I fear that I bore you with these details, but I have to let you see my little difficulties, if you are to understand the situation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(264,'I am following you closely, I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(265,'I was still balancing the matter in my mind, when a hansom cab drove up to Briony Lodge, and a gentleman sprang out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(266,'He was a remarkably handsome man, dark, aquiline, and mustached—evidently the man of whom I had heard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(267,'He appeared to be in a great hurry, shouted to the cabman to wait, and brushed past the maid who opened the door with the air of a man who was thoroughly at home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(268,'He was in the house about half an hour, and I could catch glimpses of him in the windows of the sitting-room, pacing up and down, talking excitedly, and waving his arms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(269,'Of her I could see nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(270,'Presently he emerged, looking even more flurried than before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(271,'As he stepped up to the cab, he pulled a gold watch from his pocket and looked at it earnestly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(272,'‘Drive like the devil,’ he shouted, ‘first to Gross & Hankey’s in Regent Street, and then to the church of St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(273,'Monica in the Edgware Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(274,'Half a guinea if you do it in twenty minutes!’  Away they went, and I was just wondering whether I should not do well to follow them, when up the lane came a neat little landau, the coachman with his coat only half-buttoned, and his tie under his ear, while all the tags of his harness were sticking out of the buckles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(275,'It hadn’t pulled up before she shot out of the hall door and into it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(276,'I only caught a glimpse of her at the moment, but she was a lovely woman, with a face that a man might die for.  ‘The Church of St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(277,'Monica, John,’ she cried, ‘and half a sovereign if you reach it in twenty minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(278,'’  This was quite too good to lose, Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(279,'I was just balancing whether I should run for it, or whether I should perch behind her landau, when a cab came through the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(280,'The driver looked twice at such a shabby fare; but I jumped in before he could object. ‘The Church of St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(281,'Monica,’ said I, ‘and half a sovereign if you reach it in twenty minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(282,'’ It was twenty-five minutes to twelve, and of course it was clear enough what was in the wind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(283,'My cabby drove fast.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(284,'I don’t think I ever drove faster, but the others were there before us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(285,'The cab and the landau with their steaming horses were in front of the door when I arrived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(286,'I paid the man and hurried into the church.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(287,'There was not a soul there save the two whom I had followed and a surpliced clergyman, who seemed to be expostulating with them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(288,'They were all three standing in a knot in front of the altar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(289,'I lounged up the side aisle like any other idler who has dropped into a church.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(290,'Suddenly, to my surprise, the three at the altar faced round to me, and Godfrey Norton came running as hard as he could towards me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(291,'Thank God! he cried. You’ll do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(292,'Come! Come!  What then? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(293,'Come, man, come, only three minutes, or it won’t be legal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(294,'I was half-dragged up to the altar, and, before I knew where I was, I found myself mumbling responses which were whispered in my ear, and vouching for things of which I knew nothing, and generally assisting in the secure tying up of Irene Adler, spinster, to Godfrey Norton, bachelor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(295,'It was all done in an instant, and there was the gentleman thanking me on the one side and the lady on the other, while the clergyman beamed on me in front.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(296,'It was the most preposterous position in which I ever found myself in my life, and it was the thought of it that started me laughing just now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(297,'It seems that there had been some informality about their license, that the clergyman absolutely refused to marry them without a witness of some sort, and that my lucky appearance saved the bridegroom from having to sally out into the streets in search of a best man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(298,'The bride gave me a sovereign, and I mean to wear it on my watch-chain in memory of the occasion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(299,'This is a very unexpected turn of affairs, said I; and what then?  Well, I found my plans very seriously menaced.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(300,'It looked as if the pair might take an immediate departure, and so necessitate very prompt and energetic measures on my part.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(301,'At the church door, however, they separated, he driving back to the Temple, and she to her own house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(302,'‘I shall drive out in the park at five as usual,’ she said, as she left him. I heard no more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(303,'They drove away in different directions, and I went off to make my own arrangements.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(304,'Which are?  Some cold beef and a glass of beer, he answered, ringing the bell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(305,'I have been too busy to think of food, and I am likely to be busier still this evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(306,'By the way, doctor, I shall want your co-operation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(307,'I shall be delighted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(308,'You don’t mind breaking the law?  Not in the least.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(309,'Nor running a chance of arrest?  Not in a good cause.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(310,'Oh, the cause is excellent!  Then I am your man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(311,'I was sure that I might rely on you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(312,'But what is it you wish?  When Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(313,'Turner has brought in the tray I will make it clear to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(314,'Now, he said, as he turned hungrily on the simple fare that our landlady had provided, I must discuss it while I eat, for I have not much time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(315,'It is nearly five now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(316,'In two hours we must be on the scene of action.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(317,'Miss Irene, or Madame, rather, returns from her drive at seven.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(318,'We must be at Briony Lodge to meet her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(319,'And what then?  You must leave that to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(320,'I have already arranged what is to occur.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(321,'There is only one point on which I must insist.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(322,'You must not interfere, come what may.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(323,'You understand?  I am to be neutral?  To do nothing whatever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(324,'There will probably be some small unpleasantness. Do not join in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(325,'It will end in my being conveyed into the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(326,'Four or five minutes afterwards the sitting-room window will open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(327,'You are to station yourself close to that open window.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(328,'You are to watch me, for I will be visible to you.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(329,'And when I raise my hand—so—you will throw into the room what I give you to throw, and will, at the same time, raise the cry of fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(330,'You quite follow me?  Entirely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(331,'It is nothing very formidable, he said, taking a long cigar-shaped roll from his pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(332,'It is an ordinary plumber’s smoke-rocket, fitted with a cap at either end to make it self-lighting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(333,'Your task is confined to that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(334,'When you raise your cry of fire, it will be taken up by quite a number of people.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(335,'You may then walk to the end of the street, and I will rejoin you in ten minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(336,'I hope that I have made myself clear?  I am to remain neutral, to get near the window, to watch you, and, at the signal, to throw in this object, then to raise the cry of fire, and to wait you at the corner of the street.  Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(337,'Then you may entirely rely on me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(338,'That is excellent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(339,'I think, perhaps, it is almost time that I prepare for the new role I have to play.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(340,'He disappeared into his bedroom, and returned in a few minutes in the character of an amiable and simple-minded Nonconformist clergyman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(341,'His broad black hat, his baggy trousers, his white tie, his sympathetic smile, and general look of peering and benevolent curiosity were such as Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(342,'John Hare alone could have equalled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(343,'It was not merely that Holmes changed his costume.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(344,'His expression, his manner, his very soul seemed to vary with every fresh part that he assumed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(345,'The stage lost a fine actor, even as science lost an acute reasoner, when he became a specialist in crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(346,'It was a quarter past six when we left Baker Street, and it still wanted ten minutes to the hour when we found ourselves in Serpentine Avenue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(347,'It was already dusk, and the lamps were just being lighted as we paced up and down in front of Briony Lodge, waiting for the coming of its occupant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(348,'The house was just such as I had pictured it from Sherlock Holmes’s succinct description, but the locality appeared to be less private that I expected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(349,'On the contrary, for a small street in a quiet neighborhood, it was remarkably animated.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(350,'There was a group of shabbily-dressed men smoking and laughing in a corner, a scissors-grinder with his wheel, two guardsmen who were flirting with a nurse-girl, and several well-dressed young men who were lounging up and down with cigars in their mouths.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(351,'You see, remarked Holmes, as we paced to and fro in front of the house, this marriage rather simplifies matters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(352,'The photograph becomes a double-edged weapon now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(353,'The chances are that she would be as averse to its being seen by Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(354,'Godfrey Norton, as our client is to its coming to the eyes of his princess.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(355,'Now the question is, Where are we to find the photograph?  Where, indeed?  It is most unlikely that she carries it about with her. It is cabinet size.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(356,'Too large for easy concealment about a woman’s dress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(357,'She knows that the King is capable of having her waylaid and searched.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(358,'Two attempts of the sort have already been made.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(359,'We may take it, then, that she does not carry it about with her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(360,'Where, then?  Her banker or her lawyer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(361,'There is that double possibility.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(362,'But I am inclined to think neither.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(363,'Women are naturally secretive, and they like to do their own secreting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(364,'Why should she hand it over to any one else? She could trust her own guardianship, but she could not tell what indirect or political influence might be brought to bear upon a business man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(365,'Besides, remember that she had resolved to use it within a few days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(366,'It must be where she can lay her hands upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(367,'It must be in her own house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(368,'But it has twice been burgled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(369,'Pshaw! They did not know how to look.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(370,'But how will you look?  I will not look.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(371,'What then?  I will get her to show me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(372,'But she will refuse.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(373,'She will not be able to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(374,'But I hear the rumble of wheels. It is her carriage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(375,'Now carry out my orders to the letter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(376,'As he spoke the gleam of the side-lights of a carriage came round the curve of the avenue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(377,'It was a smart little landau which rattled up to the door of Briony Lodge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(378,'As it pulled up, one of the loafing men at the corner dashed forward to open the door in the hope of earning a copper, but was elbowed away by another loafer, who had rushed up with the same intention.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(379,'A fierce quarrel broke out, which was increased by the two guardsmen, who took sides with one of the loungers, and by the scissors-grinder, who was equally hot upon the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(380,'A blow was struck, and in an instant the lady, who had stepped from her carriage, was the centre of a little knot of flushed and struggling men, who struck savagely at each other with their fists and sticks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(381,'Holmes dashed into the crowd to protect the lady; but just as he reached her he gave a cry and dropped to the ground, with the blood running freely down his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(382,'At his fall the guardsmen took to their heels in one direction and the loungers in the other, while a number of better dressed people, who had watched the scuffle without taking part in it, crowded in to help the lady and to attend to the injured man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(383,'Irene Adler, as I will still call her, had hurried up the steps; but she stood at the top with her superb figure outlined against the lights of the hall, looking back into the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(384,'Is the poor gentleman much hurt? she asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(385,'He is dead, cried several voices.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(386,'No, no, there’s life in him! shouted another.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(387,'But he’ll be gone before you can get him to hospital.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(388,'He’s a brave fellow, said a woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(389,'They would have had the lady’s purse and watch if it hadn’t been for him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(390,'They were a gang, and a rough one, too.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(391,'Ah, he’s breathing now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(392,'He can’t lie in the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(393,'May we bring him in, marm?  Surely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(394,'Bring him into the sitting-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(395,'There is a comfortable sofa.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(396,'This way, please!  Slowly and solemnly he was borne into Briony Lodge and laid out in the principal room, while I still observed the proceedings from my post by the window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(397,'The lamps had been lit, but the blinds had not been drawn, so that I could see Holmes as he lay upon the couch.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(398,'I do not know whether he was seized with compunction at that moment for the part he was playing, but I know that I never felt more heartily ashamed of myself in my life than when I saw the beautiful creature against whom I was conspiring, or the grace and kindliness with which she waited upon the injured man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(399,'And yet it would be the blackest treachery to Holmes to draw back now from the part which he had intrusted to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(400,'I hardened my heart, and took the smoke-rocket from under my ulster.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(401,'After all, I thought, we are not injuring her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(402,'We are but preventing her from injuring another.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(403,'Holmes had sat up upon the couch, and I saw him motion like a man who is in need of air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(404,'A maid rushed across and threw open the window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(405,'At the same instant I saw him raise his hand, and at the signal I tossed my rocket into the room with a cry of Fire! The word was no sooner out of my mouth than the whole crowd of spectators, well dressed and ill—gentlemen, ostlers, and servant-maids—joined in a general shriek of Fire! Thick clouds of smoke curled through the room and out at the open window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(406,'I caught a glimpse of rushing figures, and a moment later the voice of Holmes from within assuring them that it was a false alarm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(407,'Slipping through the shouting crowd I made my way to the corner of the street, and in ten minutes was rejoiced to find my friend’s arm in mine, and to get away from the scene of uproar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(408,'He walked swiftly and in silence for some few minutes, until we had turned down one of the quiet streets which lead towards the Edgware Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(409,'You did it very nicely, doctor, he remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(410,'Nothing could have been better. It is all right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(411,'You have the photograph?  I know where it is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(412,'And how did you find out?  She showed me, as I told you that she would.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(413,'I am still in the dark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(414,'I do not wish to make a mystery, said he, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(415,'The matter was perfectly simple.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(416,'You, of course, saw that every one in the street was an accomplice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(417,'They were all engaged for the evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(418,'I guessed as much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(419,'Then, when the row broke out, I had a little moist red paint in the palm of my hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(420,'I rushed forward, fell down, clapped my hand to my face, and became a piteous spectacle. It is an old trick.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(421,'That also I could fathom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(422,'Then they carried me in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(423,'She was bound to have me in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(424,'What else could she do? And into her sitting-room, which was the very room which I suspected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(425,'It lay between that and her bedroom, and I was determined to see which.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(426,'They laid me on a couch, I motioned for air, they were compelled to open the window, and you had your chance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(427,'How did that help you?  It was all-important.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(428,'When a woman thinks that her house is on fire, her instinct is at once to rush to the thing which she values most.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(429,'It is a perfectly overpowering impulse, and I have more than once taken advantage of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(430,'In the case of the Darlington Substitution Scandal it was of use to me, and also in the Arnsworth Castle business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(431,'A married woman grabs at her baby; an unmarried one reaches for her jewel-box.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(432,'Now it was clear to me that our lady of to-day had nothing in the house more precious to her than what we are in quest of.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(433,'She would rush to secure it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(434,'The alarm of fire was admirably done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(435,'The smoke and shouting were enough to shake nerves of steel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(436,'She responded beautifully.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(437,'The photograph is in a recess behind a sliding panel just above the right bell-pull.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(438,'She was there in an instant, and I caught a glimpse of it as she half-drew it out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(439,'When I cried out that it was a false alarm, she replaced it, glanced at the rocket, rushed from the room, and I have not seen her since.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(440,'I rose, and, making my excuses, escaped from the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(441,'I hesitated whether to attempt to secure the photograph at once; but the coachman had come in, and as he was watching me narrowly, it seemed safer to wait.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(442,'A little over-precipitance may ruin all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(443,'And now? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(444,'Our quest is practically finished.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(445,'I shall call with the King to-morrow, and with you, if you care to come with us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(446,'We will be shown into the sitting-room to wait for the lady, but it is probable that when she comes she may find neither us nor the photograph.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(447,'It might be a satisfaction to His Majesty to regain it with his own hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(448,'And when will you call?  At eight in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(449,'She will not be up, so that we shall have a clear field.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(450,'Besides, we must be prompt, for this marriage may mean a complete change in her life and habits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(451,'I must wire to the King without delay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(452,'We had reached Baker Street, and had stopped at the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(453,'He was searching his pockets for the key, when some one passing said:  Good-night, Mister Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(454,'There were several people on the pavement at the time, but the greeting appeared to come from a slim youth in an ulster who had hurried by.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(455,'I’ve heard that voice before, said Holmes, staring down the dimly-lit street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(456,'Now, I wonder who the deuce that could have been.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(457,'III  I slept at Baker Street that night, and we were engaged upon our toast and coffee in the morning when the King of Bohemia rushed into the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(458,'You have really got it! he cried, grasping Sherlock Holmes by either shoulder, and looking eagerly into his face.  Not yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(459,'But you have hopes?  I have hopes.  Then, come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(460,'I am all impatience to be gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(461,'We must have a cab.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(462,'No, my brougham is waiting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(463,'Then that will simplify matters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(464,'We descended, and started off once more for Briony Lodge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(465,'Irene Adler is married, remarked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(466,'Married! When?  Yesterday.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(467,'But to whom?  To an English lawyer named Norton.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(468,'But she could not love him?  I am in hopes that she does.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(469,'And why in hopes?  Because it would spare your Majesty all fear of future annoyance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(470,'If the lady loves her husband, she does not love your Majesty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(471,'If she does not love your Majesty, there is no reason why she should interfere with your Majesty’s plan.  It is true.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(472,'And yet—Well! I wish she had been of my own station! What a queen she would have made! He relapsed into a moody silence, which was not broken until we drew up in Serpentine Avenue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(473,'The door of Briony Lodge was open, and an elderly woman stood upon the steps.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(474,'She watched us with a sardonic eye as we stepped from the brougham.  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(475,'Sherlock Holmes, I believe? said she.  I am Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(476,'Holmes, answered my companion, looking at her with a questioning and rather startled gaze.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(477,'Indeed! My mistress told me that you were likely to call.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(478,'She left this morning with her husband by the 5.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(479,'15 train from Charing Cross for the Continent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(480,'What! Sherlock Holmes staggered back, white with chagrin and surprise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(481,'Do you mean that she has left England?  Never to return.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(482,'And the papers? asked the King, hoarsely. All is lost.  We shall see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(483,'He pushed past the servant and rushed into the drawing-room, followed by the King and myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(484,'The furniture was scattered about in every direction, with dismantled shelves and open drawers, as if the lady had hurriedly ransacked them before her flight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(485,'Holmes rushed at the bell-pull, tore back a small sliding shutter, and, plunging in his hand, pulled out a photograph and a letter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(486,'The photograph was of Irene Adler herself in evening dress, the letter was superscribed to Sherlock Holmes, Esq.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(487,'To be left till called for.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(488,'My friend tore it open, and we all three read it together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(489,'It was dated at midnight of the preceding night, and ran in this way:    MY DEAR MR.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(490,'SHERLOCK HOLMES,—You really did it very   well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(491,'You took me in completely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(492,'Until after the alarm of   fire, I had not a suspicion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(493,'But then, when I found how I had   betrayed myself, I began to think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(494,'I had been warned against   you months ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(495,'I had been told that, if the King employed an   agent, it would certainly be you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(496,'And your address had been   given me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(497,'Yet, with all this, you made me reveal what you   wanted to know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(498,'Even after I became suspicious, I found it hard   to think evil of such a dear, kind old clergyman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(499,'But, you   know, I have been trained as an actress myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(500,'Male costume   is nothing new to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(501,'I often take advantage of the freedom   which it gives.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(502,'I sent John, the coachman, to watch you, ran   up-stairs, got into my walking-clothes, as I call them, and   came down just as you departed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(503,'Well, I followed you to your door, and so made sure that I was   really an object of interest to the celebrated Mr. Sherlock   Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(504,'Then I, rather imprudently, wished you good-night, and   started for the Temple to see my husband.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(505,'We both thought the best resource was flight, when pursued by   so formidable an antagonist; so you will find the nest empty   when you call to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(506,'As to the photograph, your client may   rest in peace.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(507,'I love and am loved by a better man than he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(508,'The King may do what he will without hinderance from one whom   he has cruelly wronged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(509,'I keep it only to safeguard myself,   and to preserve a weapon which will always secure me from any   steps which he might take in the future.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(510,'I leave a photograph   which he might care to possess; and I remain, dear Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(511,'Sherlock   Holmes, very truly yours,      IRENE NORTON, _née_ ADLER.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(512,'What a woman—oh, what a woman! cried the King of Bohemia, when we had all three read this epistle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(513,'Did I not tell you how quick and resolute she was? Would she not have made an admirable queen? Is it not a pity that she was not on my level?  From what I have seen of the lady she seems indeed to be on a very different level to your Majesty, said Holmes, coldly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(514,'I am sorry that I have not been able to bring your Majesty’s business to a more successful conclusion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(515,'On the contrary, my dear sir, cried the King; nothing could be more successful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(516,'I know that her word is inviolate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(517,'The photograph is now as safe as if it were in the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(518,'I am glad to hear your Majesty say so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(519,'I am immensely indebted to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(520,'Pray tell me in what way I can reward you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(521,'This ring— He slipped an emerald snake ring from his finger and held it out upon the palm of his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(522,'Your Majesty has something which I should value even more highly, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(523,'You have but to name it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(524,'This photograph!  The King stared at him in amazement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(525,'Irene’s photograph! he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(526,'Certainly, if you wish it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(527,'I thank your Majesty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(528,'Then there is no more to be done in the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(529,'I have the honor to wish you a very good-morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(530,'He bowed, and, turning away without observing the hand which the King had stretched out to him, he set off in my company for his chambers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(531,'*       *       *       *       *  And that was how a great scandal threatened to affect the kingdom of Bohemia, and how the best plans of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(532,'Sherlock Holmes were beaten by a woman’s wit.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(533,'He used to make merry over the cleverness of women, but I have not heard him do it of late.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(534,'And when he speaks of Irene Adler, or when he refers to her photograph, it is always under the honorable title of _the_ woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(535,'Adventure II  THE RED-HEADED LEAGUE   I had called upon my friend, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(536,'Sherlock Holmes, one day in the autumn of last year, and found him in deep conversation with a very stout, florid-faced, elderly gentleman, with fiery red hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(537,'With an apology for my intrusion, I was about to withdraw, when Holmes pulled me abruptly into the room and closed the door behind me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(538,'You could not possibly have come at a better time, my dear Watson, he said, cordially.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(539,'I was afraid that you were engaged.  So I am. Very much so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(540,'Then I can wait in the next room.  Not at all. This gentleman, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(541,'Wilson, has been my partner and helper in many of my most successful cases, and I have no doubt that he will be of the utmost use to me in yours also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(542,'The stout gentleman half-rose from his chair and gave a bob of greeting, with a quick, little, questioning glance from his small, fat-encircled eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(543,'Try the settee, said Holmes, relapsing into his arm-chair and putting his finger-tips together, as was his custom when in judicial moods.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(544,'I know, my dear Watson, that you share my love of all that is bizarre and outside the conventions and humdrum routine of every-day life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(545,'You have shown your relish for it by the enthusiasm which has prompted you to chronicle, and, if you will excuse my saying so, somewhat to embellish so many of my own little adventures.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(546,'Your cases have indeed been of the greatest interest to me, I observed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(547,'You will remember that I remarked the other day, just before we went into the very simple problem presented by Miss Mary Sutherland, that for strange effects and extraordinary combinations we must go to life itself, which is always far more daring than any effort of the imagination.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(548,'A proposition which I took the liberty of doubting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(549,'You did, doctor, but none the less you must come round to my view, for otherwise I shall keep on piling fact upon fact on you, until your reason breaks down under them and acknowledges me to be right. Now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(550,'Jabez Wilson here has been good enough to call upon me this morning, and to begin a narrative which promises to be one of the most singular which I have listened to for some time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(551,'You have heard me remark that the strangest and most unique things are very often connected not with the larger but with the smaller crimes, and occasionally, indeed, where there is room for doubt whether any positive crime has been committed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(552,'As far as I have heard it is impossible for me to say whether the present case is an instance of crime or not, but the course of events is certainly among the most singular that I have ever listened to. Perhaps, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(553,'Wilson, you would have the great kindness to recommence your narrative.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(554,'I ask you, not merely because my friend Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(555,'Watson has not heard the opening part, but also because the peculiar nature of the story makes me anxious to have every possible detail from your lips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(556,'As a rule, when I have heard some slight indication of the course of events, I am able to guide myself by the thousands of other similar cases which occur to my memory.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(557,'In the present instance I am forced to admit that the facts are, to the best of my belief, unique.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(558,'The portly client puffed out his chest with an appearance of some little pride, and pulled a dirty and wrinkled newspaper from the inside pocket of his great-coat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(559,'As he glanced down the advertisement column, with his head thrust forward, and the paper flattened out upon his knee, I took a good look at the man, and endeavored, after the fashion of my companion, to read the indications which might be presented by his dress or appearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(560,'I did not gain very much, however, by my inspection.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(561,'Our visitor bore every mark of being an average commonplace British tradesman, obese, pompous, and slow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(562,'He wore rather baggy gray shepherd’s check trousers, a not over-clean black frock-coat, unbuttoned in the front, and a drab waistcoat with a heavy brassy Albert chain, and a square pierced bit of metal dangling down as an ornament.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(563,'A frayed top-hat and a faded brown overcoat with a wrinkled velvet collar lay upon a chair beside him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(564,'Altogether, look as I would, there was nothing remarkable about the man save his blazing red head, and the expression of extreme chagrin and discontent upon his features.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(565,'Sherlock Holmes’s quick eye took in my occupation, and he shook his head with a smile as he noticed my questioning glances.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(566,'Beyond the obvious facts that he has at some time done manual labor, that he takes snuff, that he is a Freemason, that he has been in China, and that he has done a considerable amount of writing lately, I can deduce nothing else.  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(567,'Jabez Wilson started up in his chair, with his forefinger upon the paper, but his eyes upon my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(568,'How, in the name of good-fortune, did you know all that, Mr. Holmes? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(569,'How did you know, for example, that I did manual labor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(570,'It’s as true as gospel, for I began as a ship’s carpenter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(571,'Your hands, my dear sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(572,'Your right hand is quite a size larger than your left.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(573,'You have worked with it, and the muscles are more developed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(574,'Well, the snuff, then, and the Freemasonry?  I won’t insult your intelligence by telling you how I read that, especially as, rather against the strict rules of your order, you use an arc-and-compass breastpin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(575,'Ah, of course, I forgot that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(576,'But the writing?  What else can be indicated by that right cuff so very shiny for five inches, and the left one with the smooth patch near the elbow where you rest it upon the desk.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(577,'Well, but China?  The fish that you have tattooed immediately above your right wrist could only have been done in China.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(578,'I have made a small study of tattoo marks, and have even contributed to the literature of the subject.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(579,'That trick of staining the fishes’ scales of a delicate pink is quite peculiar to China.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(580,'When, in addition, I see a Chinese coin hanging from your watch-chain, the matter becomes even more simple.  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(581,'Jabez Wilson laughed heavily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(582,'Well, I never! said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(583,'I thought at first that you had done something clever, but I see that there was nothing in it, after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(584,'I begin to think, Watson, said Holmes, that I make a mistake in explaining.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(585,'‘Omne ignotum pro magnifico,’ you know, and my poor little reputation, such as it is, will suffer shipwreck if I am so candid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(586,'Can you not find the advertisement, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(587,'Wilson?  Yes, I have got it now, he answered, with his thick, red finger planted half-way down the column. Here it is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(588,'This is what began it all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(589,'You just read it for yourself, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(590,'I took the paper from him, and read as follows:    TO THE RED-HEADED LEAGUE: On account of the bequest of the   late Ezekiah Hopkins, of Lebanon, Pa., U.S.A.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(591,', there is now   another vacancy open which entitles a member of the League   to a salary of £4 a week for purely nominal services.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(592,'All   red-headed men who are sound in body and mind, and above   the age of twenty-one years, are eligible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(593,'Apply in person on   Monday, at eleven o’clock, to Duncan Ross, at the offices of   the League, 7 Pope’s Court, Fleet Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(594,'What on earth does this mean? I ejaculated, after I had twice read over the extraordinary announcement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(595,'Holmes chuckled, and wriggled in his chair, as was his habit when in high spirits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(596,'It is a little off the beaten track, isn’t it? said he. And now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(597,'Wilson, off you go at scratch, and tell us all about yourself, your household, and the effect which this advertisement had upon your fortunes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(598,'You will first make a note, doctor, of the paper and the date.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(599,'It is _The Morning Chronicle_, of April 27, 1890. Just two months ago.  Very good. Now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(600,'Wilson?  Well, it is just as I have been telling you, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(601,'Sherlock Holmes, said Jabez Wilson, mopping his forehead; I have a small pawnbroker’s business at Coburg Square, near the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(602,'It’s not a very large affair, and of late years it has not done more than just give me a living.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(603,'I used to be able to keep two assistants, but now I only keep one; and I would have a job to pay him, but that he is willing to come for half wages, so as to learn the business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(604,'What is the name of this obliging youth? asked Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(605,'His name is Vincent Spaulding, and he’s not such a youth, either.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(606,'It’s hard to say his age.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(607,'I should not wish a smarter assistant, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(608,'Holmes; and I know very well that he could better himself, and earn twice what I am able to give him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(609,'But, after all, if he is satisfied, why should I put ideas in his head?  Why, indeed? You seem most fortunate in having an _employé_ who comes under the full market price.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(610,'It is not a common experience among employers in this age.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(611,'I don’t know that your assistant is not as remarkable as your advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(612,'Oh, he has his faults, too, said Mr. Wilson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(613,'Never was such a fellow for photography.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(614,'Snapping away with a camera when he ought to be improving his mind, and then diving down into the cellar like a rabbit into its hole to develope his pictures.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(615,'That is his main fault; but, on the whole, he’s a good worker.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(616,'There’s no vice in him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(617,'He is still with you, I presume?  Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(618,'He and a girl of fourteen, who does a bit of simple cooking, and keeps the place clean—that’s all I have in the house, for I am a widower, and never had any family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(619,'We live very quietly, sir, the three of us; and we keep a roof over our heads, and pay our debts, if we do nothing more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(620,'The first thing that put us out was that advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(621,'Spaulding, he came down into the office just this day eight weeks, with this very paper in his hand, and he says:  ‘I wish to the Lord, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(622,'Wilson, that I was a red-headed man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(623,'’  ‘Why that?’ I asks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(624,'‘Why,’ says he, ‘here’s another vacancy on the League of the Red-headed Men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(625,'It’s worth quite a little fortune to any man who gets it, and I understand that there are more vacancies than there are men, so that the trustees are at their wits’ end what to do with the money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(626,'If my hair would only change color, here’s a nice little crib all ready for me to step into.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(627,'’  ‘Why, what is it, then?’ I asked. You see, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(628,'Holmes, I am a very stay-at-home man, and as my business came to me instead of my having to go to it, I was often weeks on end without putting my foot over the door-mat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(629,'In that way I didn’t know much of what was going on outside, and I was always glad of a bit of news.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(630,'‘Have you never heard of the League of the Red-headed Men?’ he asked, with his eyes open.  ‘Never.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(631,'’  ‘Why, I wonder at that, for you are eligible yourself for one of the vacancies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(632,'’  ‘And what are they worth?’ I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(633,'‘Oh, merely a couple of hundred a year, but the work is slight, and it need not interfere very much with one’s other occupations.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(634,'’  Well, you can easily think that that made me prick up my ears, for the business has not been over-good for some years, and an extra couple of hundred would have been very handy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(635,'‘Tell me all about it,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(636,'‘Well,’ said he, showing me the advertisement, ‘you can see for yourself that the League has a vacancy, and there is the address where you should apply for particulars.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(637,'As far as I can make out, the League was founded by an American millionaire, Ezekiah Hopkins, who was very peculiar in his ways.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(638,'He was himself red-headed, and he had a great sympathy for all red-headed men; so, when he died, it was found that he had left his enormous fortune in the hands of trustees, with instructions to apply the interest to the providing of easy berths to men whose hair is of that color.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(639,'From all I hear it is splendid pay, and very little to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(640,'’  ‘But,’ said I, ‘there would be millions of red-headed men who would apply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(641,'’  ‘Not so many as you might think,’ he answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(642,'‘You see it is really confined to Londoners, and to grown men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(643,'This American had started from London when he was young, and he wanted to do the old town a good turn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(644,'Then, again, I have heard it is no use your applying if your hair is light red, or dark red, or anything but real bright, blazing, fiery red.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(645,'Now, if you cared to apply, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(646,'Wilson, you would just walk in; but perhaps it would hardly be worth your while to put yourself out of the way for the sake of a few hundred pounds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(647,'’  Now, it is a fact, gentlemen, as you may see for yourselves, that my hair is of a very full and rich tint, so that it seemed to me that, if there was to be any competition in the matter, I stood as good a chance as any man that I had ever met.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(648,'Vincent Spaulding seemed to know so much about it that I thought he might prove useful, so I just ordered him to put up the shutters for the day, and to come right away with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(649,'He was very willing to have a holiday, so we shut the business up, and started off for the address that was given us in the advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(650,'I never hope to see such a sight as that again, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(651,'From north, south, east, and west every man who had a shade of red in his hair had tramped into the city to answer the advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(652,'Fleet Street was choked with red-headed folk, and Pope’s Court looked like a coster’s orange barrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(653,'I should not have thought there were so many in the whole country as were brought together by that single advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(654,'Every shade of color they were—straw, lemon, orange, brick, Irish-setter, liver, clay; but, as Spaulding said, there were not many who had the real vivid flame-colored tint.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(655,'When I saw how many were waiting, I would have given it up in despair; but Spaulding would not hear of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(656,'How he did it I could not imagine, but he pushed and pulled and butted until he got me through the crowd, and right up to the steps which led to the office.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(657,'There was a double stream upon the stair, some going up in hope, and some coming back dejected; but we wedged in as well as we could, and soon found ourselves in the office.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(658,'Your experience has been a most entertaining one, remarked Holmes, as his client paused and refreshed his memory with a huge pinch of snuff.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(659,'Pray continue your very interesting statement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(660,'There was nothing in the office but a couple of wooden chairs and a deal table, behind which sat a small man, with a head that was even redder than mine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(661,'He said a few words to each candidate as he came up, and then he always managed to find some fault in them which would disqualify them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(662,'Getting a vacancy did not seem to be such a very easy matter, after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(663,'However, when our turn came, the little man was much more favorable to me than to any of the others, and he closed the door as we entered, so that he might have a private word with us.  ‘This is Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(664,'Jabez Wilson,’ said my assistant, ‘and he is willing to fill a vacancy in the League.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(665,'’  ‘And he is admirably suited for it,’ the other answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(666,'‘He has every requirement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(667,'I cannot recall when I have seen anything so fine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(668,'’ He took a step backward, cocked his head on one side, and gazed at my hair until I felt quite bashful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(669,'Then suddenly he plunged forward, wrung my hand, and congratulated me warmly on my success.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(670,'‘It would be injustice to hesitate,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(671,'‘You will, however, I am sure, excuse me for taking an obvious precaution.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(672,'’ With that he seized my hair in both his hands, and tugged until I yelled with the pain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(673,'‘There is water in your eyes,’ said he, as he released me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(674,'‘I perceive that all is as it should be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(675,'But we have to be careful, for we have twice been deceived by wigs and once by paint.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(676,'I could tell you tales of cobbler’s wax which would disgust you with human nature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(677,'’ He stepped over to the window, and shouted through it at the top of his voice that the vacancy was filled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(678,'A groan of disappointment came up from below, and the folk all trooped away in different directions, until there was not a red head to be seen except my own and that of the manager.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(679,'‘My name,’ said he, ‘is Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(680,'Duncan Ross, and I am myself one of the pensioners upon the fund left by our noble benefactor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(681,'Are you a married man, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(682,'Wilson? Have you a family?’  I answered that I had not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(683,'His face fell immediately.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(684,'‘Dear me!’ he said, gravely, ‘that is very serious indeed! I am sorry to hear you say that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(685,'The fund was, of course, for the propagation and spread of the red-heads as well as for their maintenance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(686,'It is exceedingly unfortunate that you should be a bachelor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(687,'’  My face lengthened at this, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(688,'Holmes, for I thought that I was not to have the vacancy after all; but, after thinking it over for a few minutes, he said that it would be all right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(689,'‘In the case of another,’ said he, ‘the objection might be fatal, but we must stretch a point in favor of a man with such a head of hair as yours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(690,'When shall you be able to enter upon your new duties?’  ‘Well, it is a little awkward, for I have a business already,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(691,'‘Oh, never mind about that, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(692,'Wilson!’ said Vincent Spaulding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(693,'‘I shall be able to look after that for you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(694,'’  ‘What would be the hours?’ I asked.  ‘Ten to two.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(695,'’  Now a pawnbroker’s business is mostly done of an evening, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(696,'Holmes, especially Thursday and Friday evening, which is just before pay-day; so it would suit me very well to earn a little in the mornings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(697,'Besides, I knew that my assistant was a good man, and that he would see to anything that turned up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(698,'‘That would suit me very well,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(699,'‘And the pay?’  ‘Is £4 a week.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(700,'’  ‘And the work?’  ‘Is purely nominal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(701,'’  ‘What do you call purely nominal?’  ‘Well, you have to be in the office, or at least in the building, the whole time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(702,'If you leave, you forfeit your whole position forever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(703,'The will is very clear upon that point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(704,'You don’t comply with the conditions if you budge from the office during that time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(705,'’  ‘It’s only four hours a day, and I should not think of leaving,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(706,'‘No excuse will avail,’ said Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(707,'Duncan Ross, ‘neither sickness nor business nor anything else.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(708,'There you must stay, or you lose your billet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(709,'’  ‘And the work?’  ‘Is to copy out the Encyclopædia Britannica.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(710,'There is the first volume of it in that press.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(711,'You must find your own ink, pens, and blotting-paper, but we provide this table and chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(712,'Will you be ready to-morrow?’  ‘Certainly,’ I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(713,'‘Then, good-bye, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(714,'Jabez Wilson, and let me congratulate you once more on the important position which you have been fortunate enough to gain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(715,'’ He bowed me out of the room, and I went home with my assistant, hardly knowing what to say or do, I was so pleased at my own good fortune.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(716,'Well, I thought over the matter all day, and by evening I was in low spirits again; for I had quite persuaded myself that the whole affair must be some great hoax or fraud, though what its object might be I could not imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(717,'It seemed altogether past belief that any one could make such a will, or that they would pay such a sum for doing anything so simple as copying out the ‘Encyclopædia Britannica.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(718,'’ Vincent Spaulding did what he could to cheer me up, but by bedtime I had reasoned myself out of the whole thing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(719,'However, in the morning I determined to have a look at it anyhow, so I bought a penny bottle of ink, and with a quill-pen, and seven sheets of foolscap paper, I started off for Pope’s Court.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(720,'Well, to my surprise and delight, everything was as right as possible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(721,'The table was set out ready for me, and Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(722,'Duncan Ross was there to see that I got fairly to work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(723,'He started me off upon the letter A, and then he left me; but he would drop in from time to time to see that all was right with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(724,'At two o’clock he bade me good-day, complimented me upon the amount that I had written, and locked the door of the office after me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(725,'This went on day after day, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(726,'Holmes, and on Saturday the manager came in and planked down four golden sovereigns for my week’s work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(727,'It was the same next week, and the same the week after.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(728,'Every morning I was there at ten, and every afternoon I left at two. By degrees Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(729,'Duncan Ross took to coming in only once of a morning, and then, after a time, he did not come in at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(730,'Still, of course, I never dared to leave the room for an instant, for I was not sure when he might come, and the billet was such a good one, and suited me so well, that I would not risk the loss of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(731,'Eight weeks passed away like this, and I had written about Abbots and Archery and Armor and Architecture and Attica, and hoped with diligence that I might get on to the B’s before very long.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(732,'It cost me something in foolscap, and I had pretty nearly filled a shelf with my writings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(733,'And then suddenly the whole business came to an end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(734,'To an end?  Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(735,'And no later than this morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(736,'I went to my work as usual at ten o’clock, but the door was shut and locked, with a little square of card-board hammered on to the middle of the panel with a tack.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(737,'Here it is, and you can read for yourself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(738,'He held up a piece of white card-board about the size of a sheet of note-paper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(739,'It read in this fashion:    THE RED-HEADED LEAGUE    IS    DISSOLVED.    _October 9, 1890.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(740,'_  Sherlock Holmes and I surveyed this curt announcement and the rueful face behind it, until the comical side of the affair so completely overtopped every other consideration that we both burst out into a roar of laughter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(741,'I cannot see that there is anything very funny, cried our client, flushing up to the roots of his flaming head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(742,'If you can do nothing better than laugh at me, I can go elsewhere.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(743,'No, no, cried Holmes, shoving him back into the chair from which he had half risen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(744,'I really wouldn’t miss your case for the world.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(745,'It is most refreshingly unusual.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(746,'But there is, if you will excuse my saying so, something just a little funny about it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(747,'Pray what steps did you take when you found the card upon the door?  I was staggered, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(748,'I did not know what to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(749,'Then I called at the offices round, but none of them seemed to know anything about it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(750,'Finally, I went to the landlord, who is an accountant living on the ground-floor, and I asked him if he could tell me what had become of the Red-headed League.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(751,'He said that he had never heard of any such body.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(752,'Then I asked him who Mr. Duncan Ross was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(753,'He answered that the name was new to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(754,'[Illustration: THE DOOR WAS SHUT AND LOCKED]  ‘Well,’ said I, ‘the gentleman at No. 4.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(755,'’  ‘What, the red-headed man?’  ‘Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(756,'’  ‘Oh,’ said he, ‘his name was William Morris.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(757,'He was a solicitor, and was using my room as a temporary convenience until his new premises were ready.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(758,'He moved out yesterday.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(759,'’  ‘Where could I find him?’  ‘Oh, at his new offices.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(760,'He did tell me the address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(761,'Yes, 17 King Edward Street, near St. Paul’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(762,'’  I started off, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(763,'Holmes, but when I got to that address it was a manufactory of artificial knee-caps, and no one in it had ever heard of either Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(764,'William Morris or Mr. Duncan Ross.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(765,'And what did you do then? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(766,'I went home to Saxe-Coburg Square, and I took the advice of my assistant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(767,'But he could not help me in any way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(768,'He could only say that if I waited I should hear by post.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(769,'But that was not quite good enough, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(770,'I did not wish to lose such a place without a struggle, so, as I had heard that you were good enough to give advice to poor folk who were in need of it, I came right away to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(771,'And you did very wisely, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(772,'Your case is an exceedingly remarkable one, and I shall be happy to look into it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(773,'From what you have told me I think that it is possible that graver issues hang from it than might at first sight appear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(774,'Grave enough! said Mr. Jabez Wilson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(775,'Why, I have lost four pound a week.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(776,'As far as you are personally concerned, remarked Holmes, I do not see that you have any grievance against this extraordinary league.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(777,'On the contrary, you are, as I understand, richer by some £30, to say nothing of the minute knowledge which you have gained on every subject which comes under the letter A.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(778,'You have lost nothing by them.  No, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(779,'But I want to find out about them, and who they are, and what their object was in playing this prank—if it was a prank—upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(780,'It was a pretty expensive joke for them, for it cost them two and thirty pounds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(781,'We shall endeavor to clear up these points for you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(782,'And, first, one or two questions, Mr. Wilson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(783,'This assistant of yours who first called your attention to the advertisement—how long had he been with you?  About a month then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(784,'How did he come?  In answer to an advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(785,'Was he the only applicant?  No, I had a dozen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(786,'Why did you pick him?  Because he was handy, and would come cheap.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(787,'At half-wages, in fact.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(788,'What is he like, this Vincent Spaulding?  Small, stout-built, very quick in his ways, no hair on his face, though he’s not short of thirty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(789,'Has a white splash of acid upon his forehead.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(790,'Holmes sat up in his chair in considerable excitement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(791,'I thought as much, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(792,'Have you ever observed that his ears are pierced for earrings?  Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(793,'He told me that a gypsy had done it for him when he was a lad.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(794,'Hum! said Holmes, sinking back in deep thought.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(795,'He is still with you?  Oh yes, sir; I have only just left him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(796,'And has your business been attended to in your absence?  Nothing to complain of, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(797,'There’s never very much to do of a morning.  That will do, Mr. Wilson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(798,'I shall be happy to give you an opinion upon the subject in the course of a day or two.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(799,'To-day is Saturday, and I hope that by Monday we may come to a conclusion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(800,'Well, Watson, said Holmes, when our visitor had left us, what do you make of it all?  I make nothing of it, I answered, frankly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(801,'It is a most mysterious business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(802,'As a rule, said Holmes, the more bizarre a thing is the less mysterious it proves to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(803,'It is your commonplace, featureless crimes which are really puzzling, just as a commonplace face is the most difficult to identify.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(804,'But I must be prompt over this matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(805,'What are you going to do, then? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(806,'To smoke, he answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(807,'It is quite a three-pipe problem, and I beg that you won’t speak to me for fifty minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(808,'He curled himself up in his chair, with his thin knees drawn up to his hawk-like nose, and there he sat with his eyes closed and his black clay pipe thrusting out like the bill of some strange bird.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(809,'I had come to the conclusion that he had dropped asleep, and indeed was nodding myself, when he suddenly sprang out of his chair with the gesture of a man who has made up his mind, and put his pipe down upon the mantel-piece.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(810,'Sarasate plays at the St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(811,'James’s Hall this afternoon, he remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(812,'What do you think, Watson? Could your patients spare you for a few hours?  I have nothing to do to-day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(813,'My practice is never very absorbing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(814,'Then put on your hat and come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(815,'I am going through the city first, and we can have some lunch on the way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(816,'I observe that there is a good deal of German music on the programme, which is rather more to my taste than Italian or French.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(817,'It is introspective, and I want to introspect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(818,'Come along!  We travelled by the Underground as far as Aldersgate; and a short walk took us to Saxe-Coburg Square, the scene of the singular story which we had listened to in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(819,'It was a pokey, little, shabby-genteel place, where four lines of dingy two-storied brick houses looked out into a small railed-in enclosure, where a lawn of weedy grass and a few clumps of faded laurel-bushes made a hard fight against a smoke-laden and uncongenial atmosphere.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(820,'Three gilt balls and a brown board with JABEZ WILSON in white letters, upon a corner house, announced the place where our red-headed client carried on his business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(821,'Sherlock Holmes stopped in front of it with his head on one side, and looked it all over, with his eyes shining brightly between puckered lids.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(822,'Then he walked slowly up the street, and then down again to the corner, still looking keenly at the houses.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(823,'Finally he returned to the pawnbroker’s, and, having thumped vigorously upon the pavement with his stick two or three times, he went up to the door and knocked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(824,'It was instantly opened by a bright-looking, clean-shaven young fellow, who asked him to step in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(825,'Thank you, said Holmes, I only wished to ask you how you would go from here to the Strand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(826,'Third right, fourth left, answered the assistant, promptly, closing the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(827,'Smart fellow, that, observed Holmes, as we walked away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(828,'He is, in my judgment, the fourth smartest man in London, and for daring I am not sure that he has not a claim to be third.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(829,'I have known something of him before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(830,'Evidently, said I, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(831,'Wilson’s assistant counts for a good deal in this mystery of the Red-headed League.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(832,'I am sure that you inquired your way merely in order that you might see him.  Not him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(833,'What then?  The knees of his trousers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(834,'And what did you see?  What I expected to see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(835,'Why did you beat the pavement?  My dear doctor, this is a time for observation, not for talk.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(836,'We are spies in an enemy’s country.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(837,'We know something of Saxe-Coburg Square.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(838,'Let us now explore the parts which lie behind it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(839,'The road in which we found ourselves as we turned round the corner from the retired Saxe-Coburg Square presented as great a contrast to it as the front of a picture does to the back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(840,'It was one of the main arteries which convey the traffic of the city to the north and west.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(841,'The roadway was blocked with the immense stream of commerce flowing in a double tide inward and outward, while the foot-paths were black with the hurrying swarm of pedestrians.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(842,'It was difficult to realize as we looked at the line of fine shops and stately business premises that they really abutted on the other side upon the faded and stagnant square which we had just quitted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(843,'Let me see, said Holmes, standing at the corner, and glancing along the line, I should like just to remember the order of the houses here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(844,'It is a hobby of mine to have an exact knowledge of London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(845,'There is Mortimer’s, the tobacconist, the little newspaper shop, the Coburg branch of the City and Suburban Bank, the Vegetarian Restaurant, and McFarlane’s carriage-building depot.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(846,'That carries us right on to the other block.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(847,'And now, doctor, we’ve done our work, so it’s time we had some play.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(848,'A sandwich and a cup of coffee, and then off to violin-land, where all is sweetness and delicacy and harmony, and there are no red-headed clients to vex us with their conundrums.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(849,'My friend was an enthusiastic musician, being himself not only a very capable performer, but a composer of no ordinary merit.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(850,'All the afternoon he sat in the stalls wrapped in the most perfect happiness, gently waving his long, thin fingers in time to the music, while his gently smiling face and his languid, dreamy eyes were as unlike those of Holmes, the sleuth-hound, Holmes the relentless, keen-witted, ready-handed criminal agent, as it was possible to conceive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(851,'In his singular character the dual nature alternately asserted itself, and his extreme exactness and astuteness represented, as I have often thought, the reaction against the poetic and contemplative mood which occasionally predominated in him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(852,'The swing of his nature took him from extreme languor to devouring energy; and, as I knew well, he was never so truly formidable as when, for days on end, he had been lounging in his arm-chair amid his improvisations and his black-letter editions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(853,'Then it was that the lust of the chase would suddenly come upon him, and that his brilliant reasoning power would rise to the level of intuition, until those who were unacquainted with his methods would look askance at him as on a man whose knowledge was not that of other mortals.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(854,'When I saw him that afternoon so enrapt in the music at St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(855,'James’s Hall I felt that an evil time might be coming upon those whom he had set himself to hunt down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(856,'You want to go home, no doubt, doctor, he remarked, as we emerged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(857,'Yes, it would be as well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(858,'And I have some business to do which will take some hours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(859,'This business at Coburg Square is serious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(860,'Why serious?  A considerable crime is in contemplation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(861,'I have every reason to believe that we shall be in time to stop it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(862,'But to-day being Saturday rather complicates matters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(863,'I shall want your help to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(864,'At what time?  Ten will be early enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(865,'I shall be at Baker Street at ten.  Very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(866,'And, I say, doctor, there may be some little danger, so kindly put your army revolver in your pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(867,'He waved his hand, turned on his heel, and disappeared in an instant among the crowd.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(868,'[Illustration: ALL AFTERNOON HE SAT IN THE STALLS]  I trust that I am not more dense than my neighbors, but I was always oppressed with a sense of my own stupidity in my dealings with Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(869,'Here I had heard what he had heard, I had seen what he had seen, and yet from his words it was evident that he saw clearly not only what had happened, but what was about to happen, while to me the whole business was still confused and grotesque.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(870,'As I drove home to my house in Kensington I thought over it all, from the extraordinary story of the red-headed copier of the Encyclopædia down to the visit to Saxe-Coburg Square, and the ominous words with which he had parted from me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(871,'What was this nocturnal expedition, and why should I go armed? Where were we going, and what were we to do? I had the hint from Holmes that this smooth-faced pawnbroker’s assistant was a formidable man—a man who might play a deep game.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(872,'I tried to puzzle it out, but gave it up in despair, and set the matter aside until night should bring an explanation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(873,'It was a quarter past nine when I started from home and made my way across the Park, and so through Oxford Street to Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(874,'Two hansoms were standing at the door, and, as I entered the passage, I heard the sound of voices from above.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(875,'On entering his room I found Holmes in animated conversation with two men, one of whom I recognized as Peter Jones, the official police agent, while the other was a long, thin, sad-faced man, with a very shiny hat and oppressively respectable frock-coat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(876,'Ha! our party is complete, said Holmes, buttoning up his pea-jacket, and taking his heavy hunting crop from the rack.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(877,'Watson, I think you know Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(878,'Jones, of Scotland Yard? Let me introduce you to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(879,'Merryweather, who is to be our companion in to-night’s adventure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(880,'We’re hunting in couples again, doctor, you see, said Jones, in his consequential way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(881,'Our friend here is a wonderful man for starting a chase.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(882,'All he wants is an old dog to help him to do the running down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(883,'I hope a wild goose may not prove to be the end of our chase, observed Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(884,'Merryweather, gloomily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(885,'You may place considerable confidence in Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(886,'Holmes, sir, said the police agent, loftily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(887,'He has his own little methods, which are, if he won’t mind my saying so, just a little too theoretical and fantastic, but he has the makings of a detective in him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(888,'It is not too much to say that once or twice, as in that business of the Sholto murder and the Agra treasure, he has been more nearly correct than the official force.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(889,'Oh, if you say so, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(890,'Jones, it is all right, said the stranger, with deference.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(891,'Still, I confess that I miss my rubber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(892,'It is the first Saturday night for seven-and-twenty years that I have not had my rubber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(893,'I think you will find, said Sherlock Holmes, that you will play for a higher stake to-night than you have ever done yet, and that the play will be more exciting. For you, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(894,'Merryweather, the stake will be some £30,000; and for you, Jones, it will be the man upon whom you wish to lay your hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(895,'John Clay, the murderer, thief, smasher, and forger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(896,'He’s a young man, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(897,'Merryweather, but he is at the head of his profession, and I would rather have my bracelets on him than on any criminal in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(898,'He’s a remarkable man, is young John Clay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(899,'His grandfather was a royal duke, and he himself has been to Eton and Oxford.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(900,'His brain is as cunning as his fingers, and though we meet signs of him at every turn, we never know where to find the man himself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(901,'He’ll crack a crib in Scotland one week, and be raising money to build an orphanage in Cornwall the next.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(902,'I’ve been on his track for years, and have never set eyes on him yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(903,'I hope that I may have the pleasure of introducing you to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(904,'I’ve had one or two little turns also with Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(905,'John Clay, and I agree with you that he is at the head of his profession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(906,'It is past ten, however, and quite time that we started.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(907,'If you two will take the first hansom, Watson and I will follow in the second.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(908,'Sherlock Holmes was not very communicative during the long drive, and lay back in the cab humming the tunes which he had heard in the afternoon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(909,'We rattled through an endless labyrinth of gas-lit streets until we emerged into Farringdon Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(910,'We are close there now, my friend remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(911,'This fellow Merryweather is a bank director, and personally interested in the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(912,'I thought it as well to have Jones with us also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(913,'He is not a bad fellow, though an absolute imbecile in his profession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(914,'He has one positive virtue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(915,'He is as brave as a bull-dog, and as tenacious as a lobster if he gets his claws upon any one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(916,'Here we are, and they are waiting for us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(917,'We had reached the same crowded thoroughfare in which we had found ourselves in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(918,'Our cabs were dismissed, and, following the guidance of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(919,'Merryweather, we passed down a narrow passage and through a side door, which he opened for us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(920,'Within there was a small corridor, which ended in a very massive iron gate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(921,'This also was opened, and led down a flight of winding stone steps, which terminated at another formidable gate. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(922,'Merryweather stopped to light a lantern, and then conducted us down a dark, earth-smelling passage, and so, after opening a third door, into a huge vault or cellar, which was piled all round with crates and massive boxes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(923,'You are not very vulnerable from above, Holmes remarked, as he held up the lantern and gazed about him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(924,'Nor from below, said Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(925,'Merryweather, striking his stick upon the flags which lined the floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(926,'Why, dear me, it sounds quite hollow! he remarked, looking up in surprise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(927,'I must really ask you to be a little more quiet, said Holmes, severely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(928,'You have already imperilled the whole success of our expedition.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(929,'Might I beg that you would have the goodness to sit down upon one of those boxes, and not to interfere?  The solemn Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(930,'Merryweather perched himself upon a crate, with a very injured expression upon his face, while Holmes fell upon his knees upon the floor, and, with the lantern and a magnifying lens, began to examine minutely the cracks between the stones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(931,'A few seconds sufficed to satisfy him, for he sprang to his feet again, and put his glass in his pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(932,'We have at least an hour before us, he remarked; for they can hardly take any steps until the good pawnbroker is safely in bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(933,'Then they will not lose a minute, for the sooner they do their work the longer time they will have for their escape.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(934,'We are at present, doctor—as no doubt you have divined—in the cellar of the city branch of one of the principal London banks. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(935,'Merryweather is the chairman of directors, and he will explain to you that there are reasons why the more daring criminals of London should take a considerable interest in this cellar at present.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(936,'It is our French gold, whispered the director.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(937,'We have had several warnings that an attempt might be made upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(938,'Your French gold?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(939,'We had occasion some months ago to strengthen our resources, and borrowed, for that purpose, 30,000 napoleons from the Bank of France.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(940,'It has become known that we have never had occasion to unpack the money, and that it is still lying in our cellar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(941,'The crate upon which I sit contains 2000 napoleons packed between layers of lead foil.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(942,'Our reserve of bullion is much larger at present than is usually kept in a single branch office, and the directors have had misgivings upon the subject.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(943,'Which were very well justified, observed Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(944,'And now it is time that we arranged our little plans.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(945,'I expect that within an hour matters will come to a head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(946,'In the mean time, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(947,'Merryweather, we must put the screen over that dark lantern.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(948,'And sit in the dark?  I am afraid so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(949,'I had brought a pack of cards in my pocket, and I thought that, as we were a _partie carrée_, you might have your rubber after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(950,'But I see that the enemy’s preparations have gone so far that we cannot risk the presence of a light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(951,'And, first of all, we must choose our positions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(952,'These are daring men, and though we shall take them at a disadvantage, they may do us some harm unless we are careful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(953,'I shall stand behind this crate, and do you conceal yourselves behind those.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(954,'Then, when I flash a light upon them, close in swiftly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(955,'If they fire, Watson, have no compunction about shooting them down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(956,'I placed my revolver, cocked, upon the top of the wooden case behind which I crouched.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(957,'Holmes shot the slide across the front of his lantern, and left us in pitch darkness—such an absolute darkness as I have never before experienced.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(958,'The smell of hot metal remained to assure us that the light was still there, ready to flash out at a moment’s notice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(959,'To me, with my nerves worked up to a pitch of expectancy, there was something depressing and subduing in the sudden gloom, and in the cold, dank air of the vault.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(960,'They have but one retreat, whispered Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(961,'That is back through the house into Saxe-Coburg Square.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(962,'I hope that you have done what I asked you, Jones?  I have an inspector and two officers waiting at the front door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(963,'Then we have stopped all the holes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(964,'And now we must be silent and wait.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(965,'What a time it seemed! From comparing notes afterwards it was but an hour and a quarter, yet it appeared to me that the night must have almost gone, and the dawn be breaking above us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(966,'My limbs were weary and stiff, for I feared to change my position; yet my nerves were worked up to the highest pitch of tension, and my hearing was so acute that I could not only hear the gentle breathing of my companions, but I could distinguish the deeper, heavier in-breath of the bulky Jones from the thin, sighing note of the bank director.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(967,'From my position I could look over the case in the direction of the floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(968,'Suddenly my eyes caught the glint of a light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(969,'At first it was but a lurid spark upon the stone pavement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(970,'Then it lengthened out until it became a yellow line, and then, without any warning or sound, a gash seemed to open and a hand appeared; a white, almost womanly hand, which felt about in the centre of the little area of light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(971,'For a minute or more the hand, with its writhing fingers, protruded out of the floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(972,'Then it was withdrawn as suddenly as it appeared, and all was dark again save the single lurid spark which marked a chink between the stones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(973,'Its disappearance, however, was but momentary.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(974,'With a rending, tearing sound, one of the broad, white stones turned over upon its side, and left a square, gaping hole, through which streamed the light of a lantern.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(975,'Over the edge there peeped a clean-cut, boyish face, which looked keenly about it, and then, with a hand on either side of the aperture, drew itself shoulder-high and waist-high, until one knee rested upon the edge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(976,'In another instant he stood at the side of the hole, and was hauling after him a companion, lithe and small like himself, with a pale face and a shock of very red hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(977,'It’s all clear, he whispered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(978,'Have you the chisel and the bags.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(979,'Great Scott! Jump, Archie, jump, and I’ll swing for it!  Sherlock Holmes had sprung out and seized the intruder by the collar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(980,'The other dived down the hole, and I heard the sound of rending cloth as Jones clutched at his skirts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(981,'The light flashed upon the barrel of a revolver, but Holmes’s hunting crop came down on the man’s wrist, and the pistol clinked upon the stone floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(982,'It’s no use, John Clay, said Holmes, blandly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(983,'You have no chance at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(984,'So I see, the other answered, with the utmost coolness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(985,'I fancy that my pal is all right, though I see you have got his coat-tails.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(986,'There are three men waiting for him at the door, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(987,'Oh, indeed! You seem to have done the thing very completely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(988,'I must compliment you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(989,'And I you, Holmes answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(990,'Your red-headed idea was very new and effective.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(991,'You’ll see your pal again presently, said Jones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(992,'He’s quicker at climbing down holes than I am.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(993,'Just hold out while I fix the derbies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(994,'I beg that you will not touch me with your filthy hands, remarked our prisoner, as the handcuffs clattered upon his wrists.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(995,'You may not be aware that I have royal blood in my veins.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(996,'Have the goodness, also, when you address me always to say ‘sir’ and ‘please.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(997,'’  All right, said Jones, with a stare and a snigger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(998,'Well, would you please, sir, march up-stairs, where we can get a cab to carry your highness to the police-station?  That is better, said John Clay, serenely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(999,'He made a sweeping bow to the three of us, and walked quietly off in the custody of the detective.  Really Mr. Holmes, said Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1000,'Merryweather, as we followed them from the cellar, I do not know how the bank can thank you or repay you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1001,'There is no doubt that you have detected and defeated in the most complete manner one of the most determined attempts at bank robbery that have ever come within my experience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1002,'I have had one or two little scores of my own to settle with Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1003,'John Clay, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1004,'I have been at some small expense over this matter, which I shall expect the bank to refund, but beyond that I am amply repaid by having had an experience which is in many ways unique, and by hearing the very remarkable narrative of the Red-headed League.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1005,'*       *       *       *       *  You see, Watson, he explained, in the early hours of the morning, as we sat over a glass of whiskey-and-soda in Baker Street, it was perfectly obvious from the first that the only possible object of this rather fantastic business of the advertisement of the League, and the copying of the ‘Encyclopædia,’ must be to get this not over-bright pawnbroker out of the way for a number of hours every day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1006,'It was a curious way of managing it, but, really, it would be difficult to suggest a better.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1007,'The method was no doubt suggested to Clay’s ingenious mind by the color of his accomplice’s hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1008,'The £4 a week was a lure which must draw him, and what was it to them, who were playing for thousands? They put in the advertisement, one rogue has the temporary office, the other rogue incites the man to apply for it, and together they manage to secure his absence every morning in the week.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1009,'From the time that I heard of the assistant having come for half wages, it was obvious to me that he had some strong motive for securing the situation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1010,'But how could you guess what the motive was?  Had there been women in the house, I should have suspected a mere vulgar intrigue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1011,'That, however, was out of the question.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1012,'The man’s business was a small one, and there was nothing in his house which could account for such elaborate preparations, and such an expenditure as they were at.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1013,'It must, then, be something out of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1014,'What could it be? I thought of the assistant’s fondness for photography, and his trick of vanishing into the cellar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1015,'The cellar! There was the end of this tangled clue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1016,'Then I made inquiries as to this mysterious assistant, and found that I had to deal with one of the coolest and most daring criminals in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1017,'He was doing something in the cellar—something which took many hours a day for months on end.');
