INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1483,'If ever circumstantial evidence pointed to a criminal it does so here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1484,'Circumstantial evidence is a very tricky thing, answered Holmes, thoughtfully.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1485,'It may seem to point very straight to one thing, but if you shift your own point of view a little, you may find it pointing in an equally uncompromising manner to something entirely different.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1486,'It must be confessed, however, that the case looks exceedingly grave against the young man, and it is very possible that he is indeed the culprit.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1487,'There are several people in the neighborhood, however, and among them Miss Turner, the daughter of the neighboring land-owner, who believe in his innocence, and who have retained Lestrade, whom you may recollect in connection with the Study in Scarlet, to work out the case in his interest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1488,'Lestrade, being rather puzzled, has referred the case to me, and hence it is that two middle-aged gentlemen are flying westward at fifty miles an hour, instead of quietly digesting their breakfasts at home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1489,'I am afraid, said I, that the facts are so obvious that you will find little credit to be gained out of this case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1490,'There is nothing more deceptive than an obvious fact, he answered, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1491,'Besides, we may chance to hit upon some other obvious facts which may have been by no means obvious to Mr. Lestrade.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1492,'You know me too well to think that I am boasting when I say that I shall either confirm or destroy his theory by means which he is quite incapable of employing, or even of understanding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1493,'To take the first example to hand, I very clearly perceive that in your bedroom the window is upon the right-hand side, and yet I question whether Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1494,'Lestrade would have noted even so self-evident a thing as that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1495,'How on earth—  My dear fellow, I know you well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1496,'I know the military neatness which characterizes you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1497,'You shave every morning, and in this season you shave by the sunlight; but since your shaving is less and less complete as we get farther back on the left side, until it becomes positively slovenly as we get round the angle of the jaw, it is surely very clear that that side is less well illuminated than the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1498,'I could not imagine a man of your habits looking at himself in an equal light, and being satisfied with such a result.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1499,'I only quote this as a trivial example of observation and inference.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1500,'Therein lies my _métier_, and it is just possible that it may be of some service in the investigation which lies before us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1501,'There are one or two minor points which were brought out in the inquest, and which are worth considering.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1502,'[Illustration: THEY FOUND THE BODY]  What are they?  It appears that his arrest did not take place at once, but after the return to Hatherley Farm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1503,'On the inspector of constabulary informing him that he was a prisoner, he remarked that he was not surprised to hear it, and that it was no more than his deserts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1504,'This observation of his had the natural effect of removing any traces of doubt which might have remained in the minds of the coroner’s jury.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1505,'It was a confession, I ejaculated.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1506,'No, for it was followed by a protestation of innocence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1507,'Coming on the top of such a damning series of events, it was at least a most suspicious remark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1508,'On the contrary, said Holmes, it is the brightest rift which I can at present see in the clouds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1509,'However innocent he might be, he could not be such an absolute imbecile as not to see that the circumstances were very black against him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1510,'Had he appeared surprised at his own arrest, or feigned indignation at it, I should have looked upon it as highly suspicious, because such surprise or anger would not be natural under the circumstances, and yet might appear to be the best policy to a scheming man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1511,'His frank acceptance of the situation marks him as either an innocent man, or else as a man of considerable self-restraint and firmness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1512,'As to his remark about his deserts, it was also not unnatural if you consider that he stood beside the dead body of his father, and that there is no doubt that he had that very day so far forgotten his filial duty as to bandy words with him, and even, according to the little girl whose evidence is so important, to raise his hand as if to strike him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1513,'The self-reproach and contrition which are displayed in his remark appear to me to be the signs of a healthy mind, rather than of a guilty one.  I shook my head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1514,'Many men have been hanged on far slighter evidence, I remarked.  So they have.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1515,'And many men have been wrongfully hanged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1516,'What is the young man’s own account of the matter?  It is, I am afraid, not very encouraging to his supporters, though there are one or two points in it which are suggestive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1517,'You will find it here, and may read it for yourself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1518,'He picked out from his bundle a copy of the local Herefordshire paper, and having turned down the sheet, he pointed out the paragraph in which the unfortunate young man had given his own statement of what had occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1519,'I settled myself down in the corner of the carriage, and read it very carefully.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1520,'It ran in this way:  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1521,'James McCarthy, the only son of the deceased, was then called, and gave evidence as follows: ‘I had been away from home for three days at Bristol, and had only just returned upon the morning of last Monday, the 3rd.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1522,'My father was absent from home at the time of my arrival, and I was informed by the maid that he had driven over to Ross with John Cobb, the groom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1523,'Shortly after my return I heard the wheels of his trap in the yard, and, looking out of my window, I saw him get out and walk rapidly out of the yard, though I was not aware in which direction he was going.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1524,'I then took my gun, and strolled out in the direction of the Boscombe Pool, with the intention of visiting the rabbit-warren which is upon the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1525,'On my way I saw William Crowder, the game-keeper, as he had stated in his evidence; but he is mistaken in thinking that I was following my father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1526,'I had no idea that he was in front of me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1527,'When about a hundred yards from the Pool I heard a cry of Cooee! which was a usual signal between my father and myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1528,'I then hurried forward, and found him standing by the Pool.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1529,'He appeared to be much surprised at seeing me, and asked me rather roughly what I was doing there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1530,'A conversation ensued which led to high words, and almost to blows, for my father was a man of a very violent temper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1531,'Seeing that his passion was becoming ungovernable, I left him, and returned towards Hatherley Farm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1532,'I had not gone more than 150 yards, however, when I heard a hideous outcry behind me, which caused me to run back again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1533,'I found my father expiring upon the ground, with his head terribly injured.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1534,'I dropped my gun, and held him in my arms, but he almost instantly expired.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1535,'I knelt beside him for some minutes, and then made my way to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1536,'Turner’s lodge-keeper, his house being the nearest, to ask for assistance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1537,'I saw no one near my father when I returned, and I have no idea how he came by his injuries.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1538,'He was not a popular man, being somewhat cold and forbidding in his manners; but he had, as far as I know, no active enemies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1539,'I know nothing further of the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1540,'’  The Coroner: Did your father make any statement to you before he died?  Witness: He mumbled a few words, but I could only catch some allusion to a rat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1541,'The Coroner: What did you understand by that?  Witness: It conveyed no meaning to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1542,'I thought that he was delirious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1543,'The Coroner: What was the point upon which you and your father had this final quarrel?  Witness: I should prefer not to answer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1544,'The Coroner: I am afraid that I must press it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1545,'Witness: It is really impossible for me to tell you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1546,'I can assure you that it has nothing to do with the sad tragedy which followed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1547,'The Coroner: That is for the court to decide.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1548,'I need not point out to you that your refusal to answer will prejudice your case considerably in any future proceedings which may arise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1549,'Witness: I must still refuse.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1550,'The Coroner: I understand that the cry of ‘Cooee’ was a common signal between you and your father?  Witness: It was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1551,'The Coroner: How was it, then, that he uttered it before he saw you, and before he even knew that you had returned from Bristol?  Witness (with considerable confusion): I do not know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1552,'A Juryman: Did you see nothing which aroused your suspicions when you returned on hearing the cry, and found your father fatally injured?  Witness: Nothing definite.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1553,'The Coroner: What do you mean?  Witness: I was so disturbed and excited as I rushed out into the open, that I could think of nothing except of my father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1554,'Yet I have a vague impression that as I ran forward something lay upon the ground to the left of me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1555,'It seemed to me to be something gray in color, a coat of some sort, or a plaid perhaps.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1556,'When I rose from my father I looked round for it, but it was gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1557,'‘Do you mean that it disappeared before you went for help?’  ‘Yes, it was gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1558,'’  ‘You cannot say what it was?’  ‘No, I had a feeling something was there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1559,'’  ‘How far from the body?’  ‘A dozen yards or so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1560,'’  ‘And how far from the edge of the wood?’  ‘About the same.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1561,'’  ‘Then if it was removed it was while you were within a dozen yards of it?’  ‘Yes, but with my back towards it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1562,'’  This concluded the examination of the witness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1563,'I see, said I, as I glanced down the column, that the coroner in his concluding remarks was rather severe upon young McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1564,'He calls attention, and with reason, to the discrepancy about his father having signalled to him before seeing him, also to his refusal to give details of his conversation with his father, and his singular account of his father’s dying words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1565,'They are all, as he remarks, very much against the son.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1566,'Holmes laughed softly to himself, and stretched himself out upon the cushioned seat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1567,'Both you and the coroner have been at some pains, said he, to single out the very strongest points in the young man’s favor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1568,'Don’t you see that you alternately give him credit for having too much imagination and too little.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1569,'Too little, if he could not invent a cause of quarrel which would give him the sympathy of the jury; too much, if he evolved from his own inner consciousness anything so _outré_ as a dying reference to a rat, and the incident of the vanishing cloth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1570,'No, sir, I shall approach this case from the point of view that what this young man says is true, and we shall see whither that hypothesis will lead us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1571,'And now here is my pocket Petrarch, and not another word shall I say of this case until we are on the scene of action.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1572,'We lunch at Swindon, and I see that we shall be there in twenty minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1573,'It was nearly four o’clock when we at last, after passing through the beautiful Stroud Valley, and over the broad gleaming Severn, found ourselves at the pretty little country-town of Ross.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1574,'A lean, ferret-like man, furtive and sly-looking, was waiting for us upon the platform.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1575,'In spite of the light brown dustcoat and leather-leggings which he wore in deference to his rustic surroundings, I had no difficulty in recognizing Lestrade, of Scotland Yard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1576,'With him we drove to the Hereford Arms, where a room had already been engaged for us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1577,'I have ordered a carriage, said Lestrade, as we sat over a cup of tea.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1578,'I knew your energetic nature, and that you would not be happy until you had been on the scene of the crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1579,'It was very nice and complimentary of you, Holmes answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1580,'It is entirely a question of barometric pressure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1581,'Lestrade looked startled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1582,'I do not quite follow, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1583,'How is the glass? Twenty-nine, I see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1584,'No wind, and not a cloud in the sky.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1585,'I have a caseful of cigarettes here which need smoking, and the sofa is very much superior to the usual country hotel abomination.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1586,'I do not think that it is probable that I shall use the carriage to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1587,'Lestrade laughed indulgently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1588,'You have, no doubt, already formed your conclusions from the newspapers, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1589,'The case is as plain as a pikestaff, and the more one goes into it the plainer it becomes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1590,'Still, of course, one can’t refuse a lady, and such a very positive one, too.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1591,'She had heard of you, and would have your opinion, though I repeatedly told her that there was nothing which you could do which I had not already done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1592,'Why, bless my soul! here is her carriage at the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1593,'He had hardly spoken before there rushed into the room one of the most lovely young women that I have ever seen in my life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1594,'Her violet eyes shining, her lips parted, a pink flush upon her cheeks, all thought of her natural reserve lost in her overpowering excitement and concern.  Oh, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1595,'Sherlock Holmes! she cried, glancing from one to the other of us, and finally, with a woman’s quick intuition, fastening upon my companion, I am so glad that you have come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1596,'I have driven down to tell you so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1597,'I know that James didn’t do it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1598,'I know it, and I want you to start upon your work knowing it, too.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1599,'Never let yourself doubt upon that point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1600,'We have known each other since we were little children, and I know his faults as no one else does; but he is too tender-hearted to hurt a fly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1601,'Such a charge is absurd to any one who really knows him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1602,'I hope we may clear him, Miss Turner, said Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1603,'You may rely upon my doing all that I can.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1604,'But you have read the evidence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1605,'You have formed some conclusion? Do you not see some loophole, some flaw? Do you not yourself think that he is innocent?  I think that it is very probable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1606,'There, now! she cried, throwing back her head, and looking defiantly at Lestrade.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1607,'You hear! He gives me hopes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1608,'Lestrade shrugged his shoulders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1609,'I am afraid that my colleague has been a little quick in forming his conclusions, he said.  But he is right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1610,'Oh! I know that he is right. James never did it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1611,'And about his quarrel with his father, I am sure that the reason why he would not speak about it to the coroner was because I was concerned in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1612,'In what way? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1613,'It is no time for me to hide anything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1614,'James and his father had many disagreements about me. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1615,'McCarthy was very anxious that there should be a marriage between us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1616,'James and I have always loved each other as brother and sister; but of course he is young, and has seen very little of life yet, and—and—well, he naturally did not wish to do anything like that yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1617,'So there were quarrels, and this, I am sure, was one of them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1618,'And your father? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1619,'Was he in favor of such a union?  No, he was averse to it also. No one but Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1620,'McCarthy was in favor of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1621,'A quick blush passed over her fresh young face as Holmes shot one of his keen, questioning glances at her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1622,'Thank you for this information, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1623,'May I see your father if I call to-morrow?  I am afraid the doctor won’t allow it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1624,'The doctor?  Yes, have you not heard? Poor father has never been strong for years back, but this has broken him down completely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1625,'He has taken to his bed, and Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1626,'Willows says that he is a wreck, and that his nervous system is shattered. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1627,'McCarthy was the only man alive who had known dad in the old days in Victoria.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1628,'Ha! In Victoria! That is important.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1629,'Yes, at the mines.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1630,'Quite so; at the gold-mines, where, as I understand, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1631,'Turner made his money.  Yes, certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1632,'Thank you, Miss Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1633,'You have been of material assistance to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1634,'You will tell me if you have any news to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1635,'No doubt you will go to the prison to see James. Oh, if you do, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1636,'Holmes, do tell him that I know him to be innocent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1637,'I will, Miss Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1638,'I must go home now, for dad is very ill, and he misses me so if I leave him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1639,'Good-bye, and God help you in your undertaking.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1640,'She hurried from the room as impulsively as she had entered, and we heard the wheels of her carriage rattle off down the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1641,'I am ashamed of you, Holmes, said Lestrade, with dignity, after a few minutes’ silence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1642,'Why should you raise up hopes which you are bound to disappoint? I am not over-tender of heart, but I call it cruel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1643,'I think that I see my way to clearing James McCarthy, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1644,'Have you an order to see him in prison?  Yes, but only for you and me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1645,'Then I shall reconsider my resolution about going out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1646,'We have still time to take a train to Hereford and see him to-night?  Ample.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1647,'Then let us do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1648,'Watson, I fear that you will find it very slow, but I shall only be away a couple of hours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1649,'I walked down to the station with them, and then wandered through the streets of the little town, finally returning to the hotel, where I lay upon the sofa and tried to interest myself in a yellow-backed novel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1650,'The puny plot of the story was so thin, however, when compared to the deep mystery through which we were groping, and I found my attention wander so continually from the fiction to the fact, that I at last flung it across the room, and gave myself up entirely to a consideration of the events of the day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1651,'Supposing that this unhappy young man’s story was absolutely true, then what hellish thing, what absolutely unforeseen and extraordinary calamity could have occurred between the time when he parted from his father, and the moment when, drawn back by his screams, he rushed into the glade? It was something terrible and deadly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1652,'What could it be? Might not the nature of the injuries reveal something to my medical instincts? I rang the bell, and called for the weekly county paper, which contained a verbatim account of the inquest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1653,'In the surgeon’s deposition it was stated that the posterior third of the left parietal bone and the left half of the occipital bone had been shattered by a heavy blow from a blunt weapon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1654,'I marked the spot upon my own head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1655,'Clearly such a blow must have been struck from behind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1656,'That was to some extent in favor of the accused, as when seen quarrelling he was face to face with his father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1657,'Still, it did not go for very much, for the older man might have turned his back before the blow fell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1658,'Still, it might be worth while to call Holmes’s attention to it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1659,'Then there was the peculiar dying reference to a rat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1660,'What could that mean? It could not be delirium.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1661,'A man dying from a sudden blow does not commonly become delirious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1662,'No, it was more likely to be an attempt to explain how he met his fate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1663,'But what could it indicate? I cudgelled my brains to find some possible explanation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1664,'And then the incident of the gray cloth, seen by young McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1665,'If that were true, the murderer must have dropped some part of his dress, presumably his overcoat, in his flight, and must have had the hardihood to return and to carry it away at the instant when the son was kneeling with his back turned not a dozen paces off.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1666,'What a tissue of mysteries and improbabilities the whole thing was! I did not wonder at Lestrade’s opinion, and yet I had so much faith in Sherlock Holmes’s insight that I could not lose hope as long as every fresh fact seemed to strengthen his conviction of young McCarthy’s innocence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1667,'It was late before Sherlock Holmes returned.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1668,'He came back alone, for Lestrade was staying in lodgings in the town.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1669,'The glass still keeps very high, he remarked, as he sat down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1670,'It is of importance that it should not rain before we are able to go over the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1671,'On the other hand, a man should be at his very best and keenest for such nice work as that, and I did not wish to do it when fagged by a long journey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1672,'I have seen young McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1673,'And what did you learn from him?  Nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1674,'Could he throw no light?  None at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1675,'I was inclined to think at one time that he knew who had done it, and was screening him or her, but I am convinced now that he is as puzzled as every one else.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1676,'He is not a very quick-witted youth, though comely to look at, and, I should think, sound at heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1677,'I cannot admire his taste, I remarked, if it is indeed a fact that he was averse to a marriage with so charming a young lady as this Miss Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1678,'Ah, thereby hangs a rather painful tale.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1679,'This fellow is madly, insanely in love with her, but some two years ago, when he was only a lad, and before he really knew her, for she had been away five years at a boarding-school, what does the idiot do but get into the clutches of a barmaid in Bristol, and marry her at a registry office? No one knows a word of the matter, but you can imagine how maddening it must be to him to be upbraided for not doing what he would give his very eyes to do, but what he knows to be absolutely impossible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1680,'It was sheer frenzy of this sort which made him throw his hands up into the air when his father, at their last interview, was goading him on to propose to Miss Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1681,'On the other hand, he had no means of supporting himself, and his father, who was by all accounts a very hard man, would have thrown him over utterly had he known the truth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1682,'It was with his barmaid wife that he had spent the last three days in Bristol, and his father did not know where he was. Mark that point. It is of importance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1683,'Good has come out of evil, however, for the barmaid, finding from the papers that he is in serious trouble, and likely to be hanged, has thrown him over utterly, and has written to him to say that she has a husband already in the Bermuda Dockyard, so that there is really no tie between them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1684,'I think that that bit of news has consoled young McCarthy for all that he has suffered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1685,'But if he is innocent, who has done it?  Ah! who? I would call your attention very particularly to two points.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1686,'One is that the murdered man had an appointment with some one at the Pool, and that the some one could not have been his son, for his son was away, and he did not know when he would return.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1687,'The second is that the murdered man was heard to cry ‘Cooee!’ before he knew that his son had returned.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1688,'Those are the crucial points upon which the case depends.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1689,'And now let us talk about George Meredith, if you please, and we shall leave all minor matters until to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1690,'There was no rain, as Holmes had foretold, and the morning broke bright and cloudless.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1691,'At nine o’clock Lestrade called for us with the carriage, and we set off for Hatherley Farm and the Boscombe Pool.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1692,'There is serious news this morning, Lestrade observed. It is said that Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1693,'Turner, of the Hall, is so ill that his life is despaired of.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1694,'An elderly man, I presume? said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1695,'About sixty; but his constitution has been shattered by his life abroad, and he has been in failing health for some time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1696,'This business has had a very bad effect upon him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1697,'He was an old friend of McCarthy’s, and, I may add, a great benefactor to him, for I have learned that he gave him Hatherley Farm rent free.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1698,'Indeed! That is interesting, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1699,'Oh yes! In a hundred other ways he has helped him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1700,'Everybody about here speaks of his kindness to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1701,'Really! Does it not strike you as a little singular that this McCarthy, who appears to have had little of his own, and to have been under such obligations to Turner, should still talk of marrying his son to Turner’s daughter, who is, presumably, heiress to the estate, and that in such a very cocksure manner, as if it were merely a case of a proposal and all else would follow? It is the more strange, since we know that Turner himself was averse to the idea.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1702,'The daughter told us as much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1703,'Do you not deduce something from that?  We have got to the deductions and the inferences, said Lestrade, winking at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1704,'I find it hard enough to tackle facts, Holmes, without flying away after theories and fancies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1705,'You are right, said Holmes, demurely; you do find it very hard to tackle the facts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1706,'Anyhow, I have grasped one fact which you seem to find it difficult to get hold of, replied Lestrade, with some warmth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1707,'And that is—  That McCarthy, senior, met his death from McCarthy, junior, and that all theories to the contrary are the merest moonshine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1708,'Well, moonshine is a brighter thing than fog, said Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1709,'But I am very much mistaken if this is not Hatherley Farm upon the left.  Yes, that is it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1710,'It was a wide-spread, comfortable-looking building, two-storied, slate roofed, with great yellow blotches of lichen upon the gray walls.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1711,'The drawn blinds and the smokeless chimneys, however, gave it a stricken look, as though the weight of this horror still lay heavy upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1712,'We called at the door, when the maid, at Holmes’s request, showed us the boots which her master wore at the time of his death, and also a pair of the son’s, though not the pair which he had then had.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1713,'Having measured these very carefully from seven or eight different points, Holmes desired to be led to the court-yard, from which we all followed the winding track which led to Boscombe Pool.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1714,'[Illustration: THE MAID SHOWED US THE BOOTS.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1715,']  Sherlock Holmes was transformed when he was hot upon such a scent as this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1716,'Men who had only known the quiet thinker and logician of Baker Street would have failed to recognize him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1717,'His face flushed and darkened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1718,'His brows were drawn into two hard, black lines, while his eyes shone out from beneath them with a steely glitter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1719,'His face was bent downward, his shoulders bowed, his lips compressed, and the veins stood out like whip-cord in his long, sinewy neck.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1720,'His nostrils seemed to dilate with a purely animal lust for the chase, and his mind was so absolutely concentrated upon the matter before him, that a question or remark fell unheeded upon his ears, or, at the most, only provoked a quick, impatient snarl in reply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1721,'Swiftly and silently he made his way along the track which ran through the meadows, and so by way of the woods to the Boscombe Pool.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1722,'It was damp, marshy ground, as is all that district, and there were marks of many feet, both upon the path and amid the short grass which bounded it on either side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1723,'Sometimes Holmes would hurry on, sometimes stop dead, and once he made quite a little _détour_ into the meadow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1724,'Lestrade and I walked behind him, the detective indifferent and contemptuous, while I watched my friend with the interest which sprang from the conviction that every one of his actions was directed towards a definite end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1725,'The Boscombe Pool, which is a little reed-girt sheet of water some fifty yards across, is situated at the boundary between the Hatherley Farm and the private park of the wealthy Mr. Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1726,'Above the woods which lined it upon the farther side we could see the red, jutting pinnacles which marked the site of the rich land-owner’s dwelling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1727,'On the Hatherley side of the Pool the woods grew very thick, and there was a narrow belt of sodden grass twenty paces across between the edge of the trees and the reeds which lined the lake.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1728,'Lestrade showed us the exact spot at which the body had been found, and, indeed, so moist was the ground, that I could plainly see the traces which had been left by the fall of the stricken man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1729,'To Holmes, as I could see by his eager face and peering eyes, very many other things were to be read upon the trampled grass.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1730,'He ran round, like a dog who is picking up a scent, and then turned upon my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1731,'What did you go into the Pool for? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1732,'I fished about with a rake.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1733,'I thought there might be some weapon or other trace.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1734,'But how on earth—  Oh, tut, tut! I have no time! That left foot of yours with its inward twist is all over the place.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1735,'A mole could trace it, and there it vanishes among the reeds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1736,'Oh, how simple it would all have been had I been here before they came like a herd of buffalo, and wallowed all over it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1737,'Here is where the party with the lodge-keeper came, and they have covered all tracks for six or eight feet round the body.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1738,'But here are three separate tracks of the same feet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1739,'He drew out a lens, and lay down upon his waterproof to have a better view, talking all the time rather to himself than to us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1740,'These are young McCarthy’s feet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1741,'Twice he was walking, and once he ran swiftly so that the soles are deeply marked, and the heels hardly visible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1742,'That bears out his story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1743,'He ran when he saw his father on the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1744,'Then here are the father’s feet as he paced up and down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1745,'What is this, then? It is the butt-end of the gun as the son stood listening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1746,'And this? Ha, ha! What have we here? Tiptoes! tiptoes! Square, too, quite unusual boots! They come, they go, they come again—of course that was for the cloak.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1747,'Now where did they come from? He ran up and down, sometimes losing, sometimes finding the track until we were well within the edge of the wood, and under the shadow of a great beech, the largest tree in the neighborhood.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1748,'Holmes traced his way to the farther side of this, and lay down once more upon his face with a little cry of satisfaction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1749,'For a long time he remained there, turning over the leaves and dried sticks, gathering up what seemed to me to be dust into an envelope, and examining with his lens not only the ground, but even the bark of the tree as far as he could reach.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1750,'A jagged stone was lying among the moss, and this also he carefully examined and retained.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1751,'Then he followed a pathway through the wood until he came to the high-road, where all traces were lost.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1752,'It has been a case of considerable interest, he remarked, returning to his natural manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1753,'I fancy that this gray house on the right must be the lodge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1754,'I think that I will go in and have a word with Moran, and perhaps write a little note.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1755,'Having done that, we may drive back to our luncheon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1756,'You may walk to the cab, and I shall be with you presently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1757,'It was about ten minutes before we regained our cab, and drove back into Ross, Holmes still carrying with him the stone which he had picked up in the wood.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1758,'This may interest you, Lestrade, he remarked, holding it out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1759,'The murder was done with it.  I see no marks.  There are none.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1760,'How do you know, then?  The grass was growing under it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1761,'It had only lain there a few days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1762,'There was no sign of a place whence it had been taken.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1763,'It corresponds with the injuries.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1764,'There is no sign of any other weapon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1765,'And the murderer?  Is a tall man, left-handed, limps with the right leg, wears thick-soled shooting-boots and a gray cloak, smokes Indian cigars, uses a cigar-holder, and carries a blunt penknife in his pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1766,'There are several other indications, but these may be enough to aid us in our search.  Lestrade laughed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1767,'I am afraid that I am still a sceptic, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1768,'Theories are all very well, but we have to deal with a hard-headed British jury.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1769,'_Nous verrons_, answered Holmes, calmly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1770,'You work your own method, and I shall work mine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1771,'I shall be busy this afternoon, and shall probably return to London by the evening train.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1772,'And leave your case unfinished?  No, finished.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1773,'But the mystery?  It is solved.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1774,'Who was the criminal, then?  The gentleman I describe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1775,'But who is he?  Surely it would not be difficult to find out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1776,'This is not such a populous neighborhood.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1777,'Lestrade shrugged his shoulders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1778,'I am a practical man, he said, and I really cannot undertake to go about the country looking for a left-handed gentleman with a game-leg.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1779,'I should become the laughing-stock of Scotland Yard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1780,'All right, said Holmes, quietly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1781,'I have given you the chance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1782,'Here are your lodgings. Good-bye.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1783,'I shall drop you a line before I leave.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1784,'Having left Lestrade at his rooms, we drove to our hotel, where we found lunch upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1785,'Holmes was silent and buried in thought with a pained expression upon his face, as one who finds himself in a perplexing position.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1786,'Look here, Watson, he said, when the cloth was cleared; just sit down in this chair and let me preach to you for a little.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1787,'I don’t quite know what to do, and I should value your advice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1788,'Light a cigar, and let me expound.  Pray do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1789,'Well, now, in considering this case there are two points about young McCarthy’s narrative which struck us both instantly, although they impressed me in his favor and you against him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1790,'One was the fact that his father should, according to his account, cry ‘Cooee!’ before seeing him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1791,'The other was his singular dying reference to a rat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1792,'He mumbled several words, you understand, but that was all that caught the son’s ear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1793,'Now from this double point our research must commence, and we will begin it by presuming that what the lad says is absolutely true.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1794,'What of this ‘Cooee!’ then?  Well, obviously it could not have been meant for the son.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1795,'The son, as far as he knew, was in Bristol.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1796,'It was mere chance that he was within ear-shot.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1797,'The ‘Cooee!’ was meant to attract the attention of whoever it was that he had the appointment with.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1798,'But ‘Cooee’ is a distinctly Australian cry, and one which is used between Australians.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1799,'There is a strong presumption that the person whom McCarthy expected to meet him at Boscombe Pool was some one who had been in Australia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1800,'What of the rat, then?  Sherlock Holmes took a folded paper from his pocket and flattened it out on the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1801,'This is a map of the Colony of Victoria, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1802,'I wired to Bristol for it last night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1803,'He put his hand over part of the map.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1804,'What do you read? he asked.  ARAT, I read.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1805,'And now? He raised his hand.  BALLARAT.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1806,'That was the word the man uttered, and of which his son only caught the last two syllables.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1807,'He was trying to utter the name of his murderer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1808,'So-and-so, of Ballarat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1809,'It is wonderful! I exclaimed.  It is obvious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1810,'And now, you see, I had narrowed the field down considerably.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1811,'The possession of a gray garment was a third point which, granting the son’s statement to be correct, was a certainty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1812,'We have come now out of mere vagueness to the definite conception of an Australian from Ballarat with a gray cloak.  Certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1813,'And one who was at home in the district, for the Pool can only be approached by the farm or by the estate, where strangers could hardly wander.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1814,'Then comes our expedition of to-day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1815,'By an examination of the ground I gained the trifling details which I gave to that imbecile Lestrade, as to the personality of the criminal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1816,'But how did you gain them?  You know my method.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1817,'It is founded upon the observance of trifles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1818,'His height I know that you might roughly judge from the length of his stride.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1819,'His boots, too, might be told from their traces.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1820,'Yes, they were peculiar boots.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1821,'But his lameness?  The impression of his right foot was always less distinct than his left.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1822,'He put less weight upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1823,'Why? Because he limped—he was lame.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1824,'But his left-handedness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1825,'You were yourself struck by the nature of the injury as recorded by the surgeon at the inquest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1826,'The blow was struck from immediately behind, and yet was upon the left side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1827,'Now, how can that be unless it were by a left-handed man? He had stood behind that tree during the interview between the father and son.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1828,'He had even smoked there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1829,'I found the ash of a cigar, which my special knowledge of tobacco ashes enabled me to pronounce as an Indian cigar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1830,'I have, as you know, devoted some attention to this, and written a little monograph on the ashes of 140 different varieties of pipe, cigar, and cigarette tobacco.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1831,'Having found the ash, I then looked round and discovered the stump among the moss where he had tossed it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1832,'It was an Indian cigar, of the variety which are rolled in Rotterdam.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1833,'And the cigar-holder?  I could see that the end had not been in his mouth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1834,'Therefore he used a holder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1835,'The tip had been cut off, not bitten off, but the cut was not a clean one, so I deduced a blunt pen-knife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1836,'Holmes, I said, you have drawn a net round this man from which he cannot escape, and you have saved an innocent human life as truly as if you had cut the cord which was hanging him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1837,'I see the direction in which all this points.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1838,'The culprit is—  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1839,'John Turner, cried the hotel waiter, opening the door of our sitting-room, and ushering in a visitor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1840,'The man who entered was a strange and impressive figure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1841,'His slow, limping step and bowed shoulders gave the appearance of decrepitude, and yet his hard, deep-lined, craggy features, and his enormous limbs showed that he was possessed of unusual strength of body and of character.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1842,'His tangled beard, grizzled hair, and outstanding, drooping eyebrows combined to give an air of dignity and power to his appearance, but his face was of an ashen white, while his lips and the corners of his nostrils were tinged with a shade of blue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1843,'It was clear to me at a glance that he was in the grip of some deadly and chronic disease.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1844,'Pray sit down on the sofa, said Holmes, gently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1845,'You had my note?  Yes, the lodge-keeper brought it up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1846,'You said that you wished to see me here to avoid scandal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1847,'I thought people would talk if I went to the Hall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1848,'And why did you wish to see me? He looked across at my companion with despair in his weary eyes, as though his question was already answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1849,'Yes, said Holmes, answering the look rather than the words. It is so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1850,'I know all about McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1851,'The old man sank his face in his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1852,'God help me! he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1853,'But I would not have let the young man come to harm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1854,'I give you my word that I would have spoken out if it went against him at the Assizes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1855,'I am glad to hear you say so, said Holmes, gravely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1856,'I would have spoken now had it not been for my dear girl.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1857,'It would break her heart—it will break her heart when she hears that I am arrested.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1858,'It may not come to that, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1859,'What!  I am no official agent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1860,'I understand that it was your daughter who required my presence here, and I am acting in her interests.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1861,'Young McCarthy must be got off, however.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1862,'I am a dying man, said old Turner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1863,'I have had diabetes for years.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1864,'My doctor says it is a question whether I shall live a month.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1865,'Yet I would rather die under my own roof than in a jail.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1866,'Holmes rose and sat down at the table with his pen in his hand and a bundle of paper before him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1867,'Just tell us the truth, he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1868,'I shall jot down the facts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1869,'You will sign it, and Watson here can witness it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1870,'Then I could produce your confession at the last extremity to save young McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1871,'I promise you that I shall not use it unless it is absolutely needed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1872,'It’s as well, said the old man; it’s a question whether I shall live to the Assizes, so it matters little to me, but I should wish to spare Alice the shock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1873,'And now I will make the thing clear to you; it has been a long time in the acting, but will not take me long to tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1874,'You didn’t know this dead man, McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1875,'He was a devil incarnate. I tell you that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1876,'God keep you out of the clutches of such a man as he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1877,'His grip has been upon me these twenty years, and he has blasted my life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1878,'I’ll tell you first how I came to be in his power.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1879,'It was in the early sixties at the diggings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1880,'I was a young chap then, hot-blooded and reckless, ready to turn my hand at anything; I got among bad companions, took to drink, had no luck with my claim, took to the bush, and in a word became what you would call over here a highway robber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1881,'There were six of us, and we had a wild, free life of it, sticking up a station from time to time, or stopping the wagons on the road to the diggings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1882,'Black Jack of Ballarat was the name I went under, and our party is still remembered in the colony as the Ballarat Gang.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1883,'One day a gold convoy came down from Ballarat to Melbourne, and we lay in wait for it and attacked it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1884,'There were six troopers and six of us, so it was a close thing, but we emptied four of their saddles at the first volley.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1885,'Three of our boys were killed, however, before we got the swag.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1886,'I put my pistol to the head of the wagon-driver, who was this very man McCarthy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1887,'I wish to the Lord that I had shot him then, but I spared him, though I saw his wicked little eyes fixed on my face, as though to remember every feature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1888,'We got away with the gold, became wealthy men, and made our way over to England without being suspected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1889,'There I parted from my old pals, and determined to settle down to a quiet and respectable life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1890,'I bought this estate, which chanced to be in the market, and I set myself to do a little good with my money, to make up for the way in which I had earned it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1891,'I married, too, and though my wife died young, she left me my dear little Alice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1892,'Even when she was just a baby her wee hand seemed to lead me down the right path as nothing else had ever done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1893,'In a word, I turned over a new leaf, and did my best to make up for the past.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1894,'All was going well when McCarthy laid his grip upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1895,'I had gone up to town about an investment, and I met him in Regent Street with hardly a coat to his back or a boot to his foot.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1896,'‘Here we are, Jack,’ says he, touching me on the arm; ‘we’ll be as good as a family to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1897,'There’s two of us, me and my son, and you can have the keeping of us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1898,'If you don’t—it’s a fine, law-abiding country is England, and there’s always a policeman within hail.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1899,'’  Well, down they came to the West country, there was no shaking them off, and there they have lived rent free on my best land ever since.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1900,'There was no rest for me, no peace, no forgetfulness; turn where I would, there was his cunning, grinning face at my elbow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1901,'It grew worse as Alice grew up, for he soon saw I was more afraid of her knowing my past than of the police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1902,'Whatever he wanted he must have, and whatever it was I gave him without question, land, money, houses, until at last he asked a thing which I could not give. He asked for Alice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1903,'His son, you see, had grown up, and so had my girl, and as I was known to be in weak health, it seemed a fine stroke to him that his lad should step into the whole property.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1904,'But there I was firm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1905,'I would not have his cursed stock mixed with mine; not that I had any dislike to the lad, but his blood was in him, and that was enough. I stood firm. McCarthy threatened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1906,'I braved him to do his worst.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1907,'We were to meet at the Pool midway between our houses to talk it over.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1908,'When I went down there I found him talking with his son, so I smoked a cigar, and waited behind a tree until he should be alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1909,'But as I listened to his talk all that was black and bitter in me seemed to come uppermost.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1910,'He was urging his son to marry my daughter with as little regard for what she might think as if she were a slut from off the streets.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1911,'It drove me mad to think that I and all that I held most dear should be in the power of such a man as this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1912,'Could I not snap the bond? I was already a dying and a desperate man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1913,'Though clear of mind and fairly strong of limb, I knew that my own fate was sealed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1914,'But my memory and my girl! Both could be saved, if I could but silence that foul tongue. I did it, Mr. Holmes. I would do it again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1915,'Deeply as I have sinned, I have led a life of martyrdom to atone for it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1916,'But that my girl should be entangled in the same meshes which held me was more than I could suffer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1917,'I struck him down with no more compunction than if he had been some foul and venomous beast.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1918,'His cry brought back his son; but I had gained the cover of the wood, though I was forced to go back to fetch the cloak which I had dropped in my flight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1919,'That is the true story, gentlemen, of all that occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1920,'Well, it is not for me to judge you, said Holmes, as the old man signed the statement which had been drawn out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1921,'I pray that we may never be exposed to such a temptation.  I pray not, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1922,'And what do you intend to do?  In view of your health, nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1923,'You are yourself aware that you will soon have to answer for your deed at a higher court than the Assizes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1924,'I will keep your confession, and, if McCarthy is condemned, I shall be forced to use it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1925,'If not, it shall never be seen by mortal eye; and your secret, whether you be alive or dead, shall be safe with us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1926,'Farewell, then, said the old man, solemnly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1927,'Your own death-beds, when they come, will be the easier for the thought of the peace which you have given to mine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1928,'Tottering and shaking in all his giant frame, he stumbled slowly from the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1929,'God help us! said Holmes, after a long silence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1930,'Why does fate play such tricks with poor, helpless worms? I never hear of such a case as this that I do not think of Baxter’s words, and say, ‘There, but for the grace of God, goes Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1931,'’  James McCarthy was acquitted at the Assizes, on the strength of a number of objections which had been drawn out by Holmes, and submitted to the defending counsel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1932,'Old Turner lived for seven months after our interview, but he is now dead; and there is every prospect that the son and daughter may come to live happily together, in ignorance of the black cloud which rests upon their past.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1933,'Adventure V  THE FIVE ORANGE PIPS   When I glance over my notes and records of the Sherlock Holmes cases between the years ’82 and ’90, I am faced by so many which present strange and interesting features that it is no easy matter to know which to choose and which to leave.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1934,'Some, however, have already gained publicity through the papers, and others have not offered a field for those peculiar qualities which my friend possessed in so high a degree, and which it is the object of these papers to illustrate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1935,'Some, too, have baffled his analytical skill, and would be, as narratives, beginnings without an ending, while others have been but partially cleared up, and have their explanations founded rather upon conjecture and surmise than on that absolute logical proof which was so dear to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1936,'There is, however, one of these last which was so remarkable in its details and so startling in its results that I am tempted to give some account of it, in spite of the fact that there are points in connection with it which never have been, and probably never will be, entirely cleared up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1937,'The year ’87 furnished us with a long series of cases of greater or less interest, of which I retain the records.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1938,'Among my headings under this one twelve months I find an account of the adventure of the Paradol Chamber, of the Amateur Mendicant Society, who held a luxurious club in the lower vault of a furniture warehouse, of the facts connected with the loss of the British bark _Sophy Anderson_, of the singular adventures of the Grice Patersons in the island of Uffa, and finally of the Camberwell poisoning case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1939,'In the latter, as may be remembered, Sherlock Holmes was able, by winding up the dead man’s watch, to prove that it had been wound up two hours before, and that therefore the deceased had gone to bed within that time—a deduction which was of the greatest importance in clearing up the case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1940,'All these I may sketch out at some future date, but none of them present such singular features as the strange train of circumstances which I have now taken up my pen to describe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1941,'It was in the latter days of September, and the equinoctial gales had set in with exceptional violence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1942,'All day the wind had screamed and the rain had beaten against the windows, so that even here in the heart of great, hand-made London we were forced to raise our minds for the instant from the routine of life, and to recognize the presence of those great elemental forces which shriek at mankind through the bars of his civilization, like untamed beasts in a cage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1943,'As evening drew in, the storm grew higher and louder, and the wind cried and sobbed like a child in the chimney.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1944,'Sherlock Holmes sat moodily at one side of the fireplace cross-indexing his records of crime, while I at the other was deep in one of Clark Russell’s fine sea-stories, until the howl of the gale from without seemed to blend with the text, and the splash of the rain to lengthen out into the long swash of the sea waves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1945,'My wife was on a visit to her mother’s, and for a few days I was a dweller once more in my old quarters at Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1946,'Why, said I, glancing up at my companion, that was surely the bell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1947,'Who could come to-night? Some friend of yours, perhaps?  Except yourself I have none, he answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1948,'I do not encourage visitors.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1949,'A client, then?  If so, it is a serious case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1950,'Nothing less would bring a man out on such a day and at such an hour.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1951,'But I take it that it is more likely to be some crony of the landlady’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1952,'Sherlock Holmes was wrong in his conjecture, however, for there came a step in the passage and a tapping at the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1953,'He stretched out his long arm to turn the lamp away from himself and towards the vacant chair upon which a new-comer must sit. Come in! said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1954,'The man who entered was young, some two-and-twenty at the outside, well-groomed and trimly clad, with something of refinement and delicacy in his bearing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1955,'The steaming umbrella which he held in his hand, and his long shining waterproof told of the fierce weather through which he had come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1956,'He looked about him anxiously in the glare of the lamp, and I could see that his face was pale and his eyes heavy, like those of a man who is weighed down with some great anxiety.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1957,'I owe you an apology, he said, raising his golden _pince-nez_ to his eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1958,'I trust that I am not intruding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1959,'I fear that I have brought some traces of the storm and rain into your snug chamber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1960,'Give me your coat and umbrella, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1961,'They may rest here on the hook, and will be dry presently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1962,'You have come up from the south-west, I see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1963,'Yes, from Horsham.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1964,'That clay and chalk mixture which I see upon your toe-caps is quite distinctive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1965,'I have come for advice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1966,'That is easily got.  And help.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1967,'That is not always so easy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1968,'I have heard of you, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1969,'I heard from Major Prendergast how you saved him in the Tankerville Club Scandal.  Ah, of course.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1970,'He was wrongfully accused of cheating at cards.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1971,'He said that you could solve anything.  He said too much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1972,'That you are never beaten.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1973,'I have been beaten four times—three times by men, and once by a woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1974,'But what is that compared with the number of your successes?  It is true that I have been generally successful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1975,'Then you may be so with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1976,'I beg that you will draw your chair up to the fire, and favor me with some details as to your case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1977,'It is no ordinary one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1978,'None of those which come to me are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1979,'I am the last court of appeal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1980,'And yet I question, sir, whether, in all your experience, you have ever listened to a more mysterious and inexplicable chain of events than those which have happened in my own family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1981,'You fill me with interest, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1982,'Pray give us the essential facts from the commencement, and I can afterwards question you as to those details which seem to me to be most important.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1983,'The young man pulled his chair up, and pushed his wet feet out towards the blaze.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1984,'My name, said he, is John Openshaw, but my own affairs have, as far as I can understand it, little to do with this awful business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1985,'It is an hereditary matter; so in order to give you an idea of the facts, I must go back to the commencement of the affair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1986,'You must know that my grandfather had two sons—my uncle Elias and my father Joseph.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1987,'My father had a small factory at Coventry, which he enlarged at the time of the invention of bicycling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1988,'He was the patentee of the Openshaw unbreakable tire, and his business met with such success that he was able to sell it, and to retire upon a handsome competence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1989,'My uncle Elias emigrated to America when he was a young man, and became a planter in Florida, where he was reported to have done very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1990,'At the time of the war he fought in Jackson’s army, and afterwards under Hood, where he rose to be a colonel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1991,'When Lee laid down his arms my uncle returned to his plantation, where he remained for three or four years.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1992,'About 1869 or 1870 he came back to Europe, and took a small estate in Sussex, near Horsham.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1993,'He had made a very considerable fortune in the States, and his reason for leaving them was his aversion to the negroes, and his dislike of the Republican policy in extending the franchise to them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1994,'He was a singular man, fierce and quick-tempered, very foul-mouthed when he was angry, and of a most retiring disposition.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1995,'During all the years that he lived at Horsham I doubt if ever he set foot in the town.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1996,'He had a garden and two or three fields round his house, and there he would take his exercise, though very often for weeks on end he would never leave his room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1997,'He drank a great deal of brandy, and smoked very heavily, but he would see no society, and did not want any friends, not even his own brother.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1998,'He didn’t mind me, in fact, he took a fancy to me, for at the time when he saw me first I was a youngster of twelve or so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(1999,'This would be in the year 1878, after he had been eight or nine years in England.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2000,'He begged my father to let me live with him, and he was very kind to me in his way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2001,'When he was sober he used to be fond of playing backgammon and draughts with me, and he would make me his representative both with the servants and with the tradespeople, so that by the time that I was sixteen I was quite master of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2002,'I kept all the keys, and could go where I liked and do what I liked, so long as I did not disturb him in his privacy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2003,'There was one singular exception, however, for he had a single room, a lumber-room up among the attics, which was invariably locked, and which he would never permit either me or anyone else to enter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2004,'With a boy’s curiosity I have peeped through the key-hole, but I was never able to see more than such a collection of old trunks and bundles as would be expected in such a room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2005,'One day—it was in March, 1883—a letter with a foreign stamp lay upon the table in front of the Colonel’s plate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2006,'It was not a common thing for him to receive letters, for his bills were all paid in ready money, and he had no friends of any sort.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2007,'‘From India!’ said he, as he took it up, ‘Pondicherry postmark! What can this be?’ Opening it hurriedly, out there jumped five little dried orange pips, which pattered down upon his plate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2008,'I began to laugh at this, but the laugh was struck from my lips at the sight of his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2009,'His lip had fallen, his eyes were protruding, his skin the color of putty, and he glared at the envelope which he still held in his trembling hand. ‘K. K. K.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2010,'!’ he shrieked, and then, ‘My God, my God, my sins have overtaken me!’  ‘What is it, uncle?’ I cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2011,'‘Death,’ said he, and rising from the table he retired to his room, leaving me palpitating with horror.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2012,'I took up the envelope, and saw scrawled in red ink upon the inner flap, just above the gum, the letter K three times repeated.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2013,'There was nothing else save the five dried pips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2014,'What could be the reason of his overpowering terror? I left the breakfast-table, and as I ascended the stair I met him coming down with an old rusty key, which must have belonged to the attic, in one hand, and a small brass box, like a cash-box, in the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2015,'‘They may do what they like, but I’ll checkmate them still,’ said he, with an oath.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2016,'‘Tell Mary that I shall want a fire in my room to-day, and send down to Fordham, the Horsham lawyer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2017,'’  I did as he ordered, and when the lawyer arrived I was asked to step up to the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2018,'The fire was burning brightly, and in the grate there was a mass of black, fluffy ashes, as of burned paper, while the brass box stood open and empty beside it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2019,'As I glanced at the box I noticed, with a start, that upon the lid were printed the treble K which I had read in the morning upon the envelope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2020,'‘I wish you, John,’ said my uncle, ‘to witness my will.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2021,'I leave my estate, with all its advantages and all its disadvantages to my brother, your father, whence it will, no doubt, descend to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2022,'If you can enjoy it in peace, well and good! If you find you cannot, take my advice, my boy, and leave it to your deadliest enemy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2023,'I am sorry to give you such a two-edged thing, but I can’t say what turn things are going to take.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2024,'Kindly sign the paper where Mr. Fordham shows you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2025,'’  I signed the paper as directed, and the lawyer took it away with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2026,'The singular incident made, as you may think, the deepest impression upon me, and I pondered over it, and turned it every way in my mind without being able to make anything of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2027,'Yet I could not shake off the vague feeling of dread which it left behind though the sensation grew less keen as the weeks passed, and nothing happened to disturb the usual routine of our lives.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2028,'I could see a change in my uncle, however.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2029,'He drank more than ever, and he was less inclined for any sort of society.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2030,'Most of his time he would spend in his room, with the door locked upon the inside, but sometimes he would emerge in a sort of drunken frenzy, and would burst out of the house and tear about the garden with a revolver in his hand, screaming out that he was afraid of no man, and that he was not to be cooped up, like a sheep in a pen, by man or devil.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2031,'When these hot fits were over, however, he would rush tumultuously in at the door, and lock and bar it behind him, like a man who can brazen it out no longer against the terror which lies at the roots of his soul.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2032,'At such times I have seen his face, even on a cold day, glisten with moisture, as though it were new raised from a basin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2033,'Well, to come to an end of the matter, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2034,'Holmes, and not to abuse your patience, there came a night when he made one of those drunken sallies from which he never came back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2035,'We found him, when we went to search for him, face downward in a little green-scummed pool, which lay at the foot of the garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2036,'There was no sign of any violence, and the water was but two feet deep, so that the jury, having regard to his known eccentricity, brought in a verdict of suicide.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2037,'But I, who knew how he winced from the very thought of death, had much ado to persuade myself that he had gone out of his way to meet it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2038,'The matter passed, however, and my father entered into possession of the estate, and of some £14,000, which lay to his credit at the bank.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2039,'One moment, Holmes interposed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2040,'Your statement is, I foresee, one of the most remarkable to which I have ever listened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2041,'Let me have the date of the reception by your uncle of the letter, and the date of his supposed suicide.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2042,'The latter arrived on March 10, 1883.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2043,'His death was seven weeks later, upon the night of May 2d.  Thank you. Pray proceed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2044,'When my father took over the Horsham property, he, at my request, made a careful examination of the attic, which had been always locked up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2045,'We found the brass box there, although its contents had been destroyed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2046,'On the inside of the cover was a paper label, with the initials of K. K. K.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2047,'repeated upon it, and ‘Letters, memoranda, receipts, and a register’ written beneath.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2048,'These, we presume, indicated the nature of the papers which had been destroyed by Colonel Openshaw.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2049,'For the rest, there was nothing of much importance in the attic, save a great many scattered papers and note-books bearing upon my uncle’s life in America.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2050,'Some of them were of the war time, and showed that he had done his duty well, and had borne the repute of a brave soldier.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2051,'Others were of a date during the reconstruction of the Southern States, and were mostly concerned with politics, for he had evidently taken a strong part in opposing the carpet-bag politicians who had been sent down from the North.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2052,'Well, it was the beginning of ’84 when my father came to live at Horsham, and all went as well as possible with us until the January of ’85.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2053,'On the fourth day after the new year I heard my father give a sharp cry of surprise as we sat together at the breakfast-table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2054,'There he was, sitting with a newly-opened envelope in one hand and five dried orange pips in the outstretched palm of the other one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2055,'He had always laughed at what he called my cock-and-a-bull story about the Colonel, but he looked very scared and puzzled now that the same thing had come upon himself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2056,'‘Why, what on earth does this mean, John?’ he stammered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2057,'My heart had turned to lead. ‘It is K. K. K.,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2058,'He looked inside the envelope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2059,'‘So it is,’ he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2060,'‘Here are the very letters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2061,'But what is this written above them?’  ‘Put the papers on the sundial,’ I read, peeping over his shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2062,'‘What papers? What sundial?’ he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2063,'‘The sundial in the garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2064,'There is no other,’ said I; ‘but the papers must be those that are destroyed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2065,'’  ‘Pooh!’ said he, gripping hard at his courage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2066,'‘We are in a civilized land here, and we can’t have tomfoolery of this kind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2067,'Where does the thing come from?’  ‘From Dundee,’ I answered, glancing at the post-mark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2068,'‘Some preposterous practical joke,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2069,'‘What have I to do with sundials and papers? I shall take no notice of such nonsense.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2070,'’  ‘I should certainly speak to the police,’ I said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2071,'‘And be laughed at for my pains. Nothing of the sort.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2072,'’  ‘Then let me do so?’  ‘No, I forbid you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2073,'I won’t have a fuss made about such nonsense.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2074,'’  It was in vain to argue with him, for he was a very obstinate man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2075,'I went about, however, with a heart which was full of forebodings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2076,'On the third day after the coming of the letter my father went from home to visit an old friend of his, Major Freebody, who is in command of one of the forts upon Portsdown Hill.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2077,'I was glad that he should go, for it seemed to me that he was farther from danger when he was away from home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2078,'In that, however, I was in error.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2079,'Upon the second day of his absence I received a telegram from the Major, imploring me to come at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2080,'My father had fallen over one of the deep chalk-pits which abound in the neighborhood, and was lying senseless, with a shattered skull.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2081,'I hurried to him, but he passed away without having ever recovered his consciousness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2082,'He had, as it appears, been returning from Fareham in the twilight, and as the country was unknown to him, and the chalk-pit unfenced, the jury had no hesitation in bringing in a verdict of ‘Death from accidental causes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2083,'’ Carefully as I examined every fact connected with his death, I was unable to find anything which could suggest the idea of murder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2084,'There were no signs of violence, no footmarks, no robbery, no record of strangers having been seen upon the roads.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2085,'And yet I need not tell you that my mind was far from at ease, and that I was wellnigh certain that some foul plot had been woven round him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2086,'In this sinister way I came into my inheritance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2087,'You will ask me why I did not dispose of it? I answer, because I was well convinced that our troubles were in some way dependent upon an incident in my uncle’s life, and that the danger would be as pressing in one house as in another.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2088,'It was in January, ’85, that my poor father met his end, and two years and eight months have elapsed since then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2089,'During that time I have lived happily at Horsham, and I had begun to hope that this curse had passed away from the family, and that it had ended with the last generation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2090,'I had begun to take comfort too soon, however; yesterday morning the blow fell in the very shape in which it had come upon my father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2091,'The young man took from his waistcoat a crumpled envelope, and, turning to the table, he shook out upon it five little dried orange pips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2092,'This is the envelope, he continued.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2093,'The post-mark is London—eastern division.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2094,'Within are the very words which were upon my father’s last message: ‘K. K. K.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2095,'’; and then ‘Put the papers on the sundial.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2096,'’  What have you done? asked Holmes.  Nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2097,'Nothing?  To tell the truth—he sank his face into his thin, white hands—I have felt helpless.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2098,'I have felt like one of those poor rabbits when the snake is writhing towards it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2099,'I seem to be in the grasp of some resistless, inexorable evil, which no foresight and no precautions can guard against.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2100,'Tut! tut! cried Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2101,'You must act, man, or you are lost.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2102,'Nothing but energy can save you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2103,'This is no time for despair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2104,'I have seen the police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2105,'Ah!  But they listened to my story with a smile.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2106,'I am convinced that the inspector has formed the opinion that the letters are all practical jokes, and that the deaths of my relations were really accidents, as the jury stated, and were not to be connected with the warnings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2107,'Holmes shook his clenched hands in the air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2108,'Incredible imbecility! he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2109,'They have, however, allowed me a policeman, who may remain in the house with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2110,'Has he come with you to-night?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2111,'His orders were to stay in the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2112,'Again Holmes raved in the air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2113,'Why did you come to me? he said; and, above all, why did you not come at once?  I did not know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2114,'It was only to-day that I spoke to Major Prendergast about my troubles, and was advised by him to come to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2115,'It is really two days since you had the letter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2116,'We should have acted before this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2117,'You have no further evidence, I suppose, than that which you have placed before us—no suggestive detail which might help us?  There is one thing, said John Openshaw.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2118,'He rummaged in his coat pocket, and drawing out a piece of discolored, blue-tinted paper, he laid it out upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2119,'I have some remembrance, said he, that on the day when my uncle burned the papers I observed that the small, unburned margins which lay amid the ashes were of this particular color.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2120,'I found this single sheet upon the floor of his room, and I am inclined to think that it may be one of the papers which has, perhaps, fluttered out from among the others, and in that way have escaped destruction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2121,'Beyond the mention of pips, I do not see that it helps us much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2122,'I think myself that it is a page from some private diary.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2123,'The writing is undoubtedly my uncle’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2124,'Holmes moved the lamp, and we both bent over the sheet of paper, which showed by its ragged edge that it had indeed been torn from a book.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2125,'It was headed, March, 1869, and beneath were the following enigmatical notices:  4th. Hudson came. Same old platform.  7th.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2126,'Set the pips on McCauley, Paramore, and John Swain, of St. Augustine.  9th. McCauley cleared.  10th. John Swain cleared.  12th. Visited Paramore. All well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2127,'Thank you! said Holmes, folding up the paper, and returning it to our visitor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2128,'And now you must on no account lose another instant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2129,'We cannot spare time even to discuss what you have told me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2130,'You must get home instantly and act.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2131,'What shall I do?  There is but one thing to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2132,'It must be done at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2133,'You must put this piece of paper which you have shown us into the brass box which you have described.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2134,'You must also put in a note to say that all the other papers were burned by your uncle, and that this is the only one which remains.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2135,'You must assert that in such words as will carry conviction with them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2136,'Having done this, you must at once put the box out upon the sundial, as directed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2137,'Do you understand?  Entirely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2138,'Do not think of revenge, or anything of the sort, at present.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2139,'I think that we may gain that by means of the law; but we have our web to weave, while theirs is already woven.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2140,'The first consideration is to remove the pressing danger which threatens you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2141,'The second is to clear up the mystery and to punish the guilty parties.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2142,'I thank you, said the young man, rising, and pulling on his overcoat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2143,'You have given me fresh life and hope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2144,'I shall certainly do as you advise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2145,'Do not lose an instant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2146,'And, above all, take care of yourself in the meanwhile, for I do not think that there can be a doubt that you are threatened by a very real and imminent danger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2147,'How do you go back?  By train from Waterloo.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2148,'It is not yet nine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2149,'The streets will be crowded, so I trust that you may be in safety.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2150,'And yet you cannot guard yourself too closely.  I am armed.  That is well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2151,'To-morrow I shall set to work upon your case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2152,'I shall see you at Horsham, then?  No, your secret lies in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2153,'It is there that I shall seek it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2154,'Then I shall call upon you in a day, or in two days, with news as to the box and the papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2155,'I shall take your advice in every particular.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2156,'He shook hands with us, and took his leave.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2157,'Outside the wind still screamed, and the rain splashed and pattered against the windows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2158,'This strange, wild story seemed to have come to us from amid the mad elements—blown in upon us like a sheet of sea-weed in a gale—and now to have been reabsorbed by them once more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2159,'Sherlock Holmes sat for some time in silence, with his head sunk forward and his eyes bent upon the red glow of the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2160,'Then he lit his pipe, and leaning back in his chair he watched the blue smoke-rings as they chased each other up to the ceiling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2161,'I think, Watson, he remarked at last, that of all our cases we have had none more fantastic than this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2162,'Save, perhaps, the Sign of Four.  Well, yes. Save, perhaps, that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2163,'And yet this John Openshaw seems to me to be walking amid even greater perils than did the Sholtos.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2164,'But have you, I asked, formed any definite conception as to what these perils are?  There can be no question as to their nature, he answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2165,'Then what are they? Who is this K. K. K.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2166,', and why does he pursue this unhappy family?  Sherlock Holmes closed his eyes and placed his elbows upon the arms of his chair, with his finger-tips together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2167,'The ideal reasoner, he remarked, would, when he had once been shown a single fact in all its bearings, deduce from it not only all the chain of events which led up to it, but also all the results which would follow from it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2168,'As Cuvier could correctly describe a whole animal by the contemplation of a single bone, so the observer who has thoroughly understood one link in a series of incidents, should be able to accurately state all the other ones, both before and after.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2169,'We have not yet grasped the results which the reason alone can attain to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2170,'Problems may be solved in the study which have baffled all those who have sought a solution by the aid of their senses.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2171,'To carry the art, however, to its highest pitch, it is necessary that the reasoner should be able to utilize all the facts which have come to his knowledge; and this in itself implies, as you will readily see, a possession of all knowledge, which, even in these days of free education and encyclopædias, is a somewhat rare accomplishment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2172,'It is not so impossible, however, that a man should possess all knowledge which is likely to be useful to him in his work, and this I have endeavored in my case to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2173,'If I remember rightly, you on one occasion, in the early days of our friendship, defined my limits in a very precise fashion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2174,'Yes, I answered, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2175,'It was a singular document.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2176,'Philosophy, astronomy, and politics were marked at zero, I remember.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2177,'Botany variable, geology profound as regards the mud-stains from any region within fifty miles of town, chemistry eccentric, anatomy unsystematic, sensational literature and crime records unique, violin-player, boxer, swordsman, lawyer, and self-poisoner by cocaine and tobacco.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2178,'Those, I think, were the main points of my analysis.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2179,'Holmes grinned at the last item.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2180,'Well, he said, I say now, as I said then, that a man should keep his little brain-attic stocked with all the furniture that he is likely to use, and the rest he can put away in the lumber-room of his library, where he can get it if he wants it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2181,'Now, for such a case as the one which has been submitted to us to-night, we need certainly to muster all our resources.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2182,'Kindly hand me down the letter K of the American Encyclopædia which stands upon the shelf beside you. Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2183,'Now let us consider the situation, and see what may be deduced from it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2184,'In the first place, we may start with a strong presumption that Colonel Openshaw had some very strong reason for leaving America.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2185,'Men at his time of life do not change all their habits, and exchange willingly the charming climate of Florida for the lonely life of an English provincial town.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2186,'His extreme love of solitude in England suggests the idea that he was in fear of some one or something, so we may assume as a working hypothesis that it was fear of some one or something which drove him from America.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2187,'As to what it was he feared, we can only deduce that by considering the formidable letters which were received by himself and his successors.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2188,'Did you remark the post-marks of those letters?  The first was from Pondicherry, the second from Dundee, and the third from London.  From East London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2189,'What do you deduce from that?  They are all seaports.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2190,'That the writer was on board of a ship.  Excellent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2191,'We have already a clew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2192,'There can be no doubt that the probability—the strong probability—is that the writer was on board of a ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2193,'And now let us consider another point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2194,'In the case of Pondicherry, seven weeks elapsed between the threat and its fulfilment, in Dundee it was only some three or four days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2195,'Does that suggest anything?  A greater distance to travel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2196,'But the letter had also a greater distance to come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2197,'Then I do not see the point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2198,'There is at least a presumption that the vessel in which the man or men are is a sailing-ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2199,'It looks as if they always sent their singular warning or token before them when starting upon their mission.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2200,'You see how quickly the deed followed the sign when it came from Dundee.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2201,'If they had come from Pondicherry in a steamer they would have arrived almost as soon as their letter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2202,'But as a matter of fact seven weeks elapsed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2203,'I think that those seven weeks represented the difference between the mail-boat which brought the letter, and the sailing-vessel which brought the writer.  It is possible.  More than that. It is probable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2204,'And now you see the deadly urgency of this new case, and why I urged young Openshaw to caution.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2205,'The blow has always fallen at the end of the time which it would take the senders to travel the distance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2206,'But this one comes from London, and therefore we cannot count upon delay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2207,'Good God! I cried; what can it mean, this relentless persecution?  The papers which Openshaw carried are obviously of vital importance to the person or persons in the sailing-ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2208,'I think that it is quite clear that there must be more than one of them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2209,'A single man could not have carried out two deaths in such a way as to deceive a coroner’s jury.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2210,'There must have been several in it, and they must have been men of resource and determination.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2211,'Their papers they mean to have, be the holder of them who it may.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2212,'In this way you see K. K. K.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2213,'ceases to be the initials of an individual, and becomes the badge of a society.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2214,'But of what society?  Have you never— said Sherlock Holmes, bending forward and sinking his voice—have you never heard of the Ku Klux Klan?  I never have.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2215,'Holmes turned over the leaves of the book upon his knee.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2216,'Here it is, said he, presently, ‘Ku Klux Klan.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2217,'A name derived from the fanciful resemblance to the sound produced by cocking a rifle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2218,'This terrible secret society was formed by some ex-Confederate soldiers in the Southern States after the Civil War, and it rapidly formed local branches in different parts of the country, notably in Tennessee, Louisiana, the Carolinas, Georgia, and Florida.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2219,'Its power was used for political purposes, principally for the terrorizing of the negro voters, and the murdering and driving from the country of those who were opposed to its views.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2220,'Its outrages were usually preceded by a warning sent to the marked man in some fantastic but generally recognized shape—a sprig of oak-leaves in some parts, melon seeds or orange pips in others.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2221,'On receiving this the victim might either openly abjure his former ways, or might fly from the country.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2222,'If he braved the matter out, death would unfailingly come upon him, and usually in some strange and unforeseen manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2223,'So perfect was the organization of the society, and so systematic its methods, that there is hardly a case upon record where any man succeeded in braving it with impunity, or in which any of its outrages were traced home to the perpetrators.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2224,'For some years the organization flourished, in spite of the efforts of the United States Government and of the better classes of the community in the South.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2225,'Eventually, in the year 1869, the movement rather suddenly collapsed, although there have been sporadic outbreaks of the same sort since that date.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2226,'’  You will observe, said Holmes, laying down the volume, that the sudden breaking up of the society was coincident with the disappearance of Openshaw from America with their papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2227,'It may well have been cause and effect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2228,'It is no wonder that he and his family have some of the more implacable spirits upon their track.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2229,'You can understand that this register and diary may implicate some of the first men in the South, and that there may be many who will not sleep easy at night until it is recovered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2230,'Then the page we have seen—  Is such as we might expect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2231,'It ran, if I remember right, ‘sent the pips to A, B, and C,’—that is, sent the society’s warning to them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2232,'Then there are successive entries that A and B cleared, or left the country, and finally that C was visited, with, I fear, a sinister result for C.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2233,'Well, I think, Doctor, that we may let some light into this dark place, and I believe that the only chance young Openshaw has in the mean time is to do what I have told him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2234,'There is nothing more to be said or to be done to-night, so hand me over my violin, and let us try to forget for half an hour the miserable weather and the still more miserable ways of our fellow-men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2235,'*       *       *       *       *  It had cleared in the morning, and the sun was shining with a subdued brightness through the dim veil which hangs over the great city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2236,'Sherlock Holmes was already at breakfast when I came down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2237,'You will excuse me for not waiting for you, said he; I have, I foresee, a very busy day before me in looking into this case of young Openshaw’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2238,'What steps will you take? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2239,'It will very much depend upon the results of my first inquiries.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2240,'I may have to go down to Horsham, after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2241,'You will not go there first?  No, I shall commence with the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2242,'Just ring the bell, and the maid will bring up your coffee.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2243,'As I waited, I lifted the unopened newspaper from the table and glanced my eye over it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2244,'It rested upon a heading which sent a chill to my heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2245,'Holmes, I cried, you are too late.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2246,'Ah! said he, laying down his cup, I feared as much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2247,'How was it done? He spoke calmly, but I could see that he was deeply moved.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2248,'My eye caught the name of Openshaw, and the heading, ‘Tragedy near Waterloo Bridge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2249,'’ Here is the account: ‘Between nine and ten last night Police-constable Cook, of the H Division, on duty near Waterloo Bridge, heard a cry for help and a splash in the water.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2250,'The night, however, was extremely dark and stormy, so that, in spite of the help of several passers-by, it was quite impossible to effect a rescue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2251,'The alarm, however, was given, and, by the aid of the water-police, the body was eventually recovered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2252,'It proved to be that of a young gentleman whose name, as it appears from an envelope which was found in his pocket, was John Openshaw, and whose residence is near Horsham.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2253,'It is conjectured that he may have been hurrying down to catch the last train from Waterloo Station, and that in his haste and the extreme darkness he missed his path and walked over the edge of one of the small landing-places for river steamboats.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2254,'The body exhibited no traces of violence, and there can be no doubt that the deceased had been the victim of an unfortunate accident, which should have the effect of calling the attention of the authorities to the condition of the river-side landing-stages.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2255,'’  We sat in silence for some minutes, Holmes more depressed and shaken than I had ever seen him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2256,'That hurts my pride, Watson, he said, at last.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2257,'It is a petty feeling, no doubt, but it hurts my pride.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2258,'It becomes a personal matter with me now, and, if God sends me health, I shall set my hand upon this gang.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2259,'That he should come to me for help, and that I should send him away to his death—! He sprang from his chair and paced about the room in uncontrollable agitation, with a flush upon his sallow cheeks, and a nervous clasping and unclasping of his long, thin hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2260,'They must be cunning devils, he exclaimed, at last.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2261,'How could they have decoyed him down there? The Embankment is not on the direct line to the station.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2262,'The bridge, no doubt, was too crowded, even on such a night, for their purpose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2263,'Well, Watson, we shall see who will win in the long run.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2264,'I am going out now!  [Illustration: ‘HOLMES,’ I CRIED, ‘YOU ARE TOO LATE’]  To the police?  No; I shall be my own police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2265,'When I have spun the web they may take the flies, but not before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2266,'All day I was engaged in my professional work, and it was late in the evening before I returned to Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2267,'Sherlock Holmes had not come back yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2268,'It was nearly ten o’clock before he entered, looking pale and worn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2269,'He walked up to the sideboard, and, tearing a piece from the loaf, he devoured it voraciously, washing it down with a long draught of water.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2270,'You are hungry, I remarked.  Starving.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2271,'It had escaped my memory.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2272,'I have had nothing since breakfast.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2273,'Nothing?  Not a bite.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2274,'I had no time to think of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2275,'And how have you succeeded?  Well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2276,'You have a clew?  I have them in the hollow of my hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2277,'Young Openshaw shall not long remain unavenged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2278,'Why, Watson, let us put their own devilish trade-mark upon them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2279,'It is well thought of!  What do you mean?  He took an orange from the cupboard, and, tearing it to pieces, he squeezed out the pips upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2280,'Of these he took five, and thrust them into an envelope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2281,'On the inside of the flap he wrote S. H. for J. O.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2282,'Then he sealed it and addressed it to Captain James Calhoun, Bark _Lone Star_, Savannah, Georgia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2283,'That will await him when he enters port, said he, chuckling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2284,'It may give him a sleepless night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2285,'He will find it as sure a precursor of his fate as Openshaw did before him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2286,'And who is this Captain Calhoun?  The leader of the gang.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2287,'I shall have the others, but he first.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2288,'How did you trace it, then?  He took a large sheet of paper from his pocket, all covered with dates and names.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2289,'I have spent the whole day, said he, over Lloyd’s registers and the files of the old papers, following the future career of every vessel which touched at Pondicherry in January and February in ’83.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2290,'There were thirty-six ships of fair tonnage which were reported there during those months.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2291,'Of these, one, the _Lone Star_, instantly attracted my attention, since, although it was reported as having cleared from London, the name is that which is given to one of the States of the Union.  Texas, I think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2292,'I was not and am not sure which; but I knew that the ship must have an American origin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2293,'What then?  I searched the Dundee records, and when I found that the bark _Lone Star_ was there in January, ’85, my suspicion became a certainty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2294,'I then inquired as to the vessels which lay at present in the port of London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2295,'Yes?  The _Lone Star_ had arrived here last week.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2296,'I went down to the Albert Dock, and found that she had been taken down the river by the early tide this morning, homeward bound to Savannah.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2297,'I wired to Gravesend, and learned that she had passed some time ago; and as the wind is easterly, I have no doubt that she is now past the Goodwins, and not very far from the Isle of Wight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2298,'What will you do, then?  Oh, I have my hand upon him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2299,'He and the two mates, are, as I learn, the only native-born Americans in the ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2300,'The others are Finns and Germans.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2301,'I know, also, that they were all three away from the ship last night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2302,'I had it from the stevedore who has been loading their cargo.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2303,'By the time that their sailing-ship reaches Savannah the mail-boat will have carried this letter, and the cable will have informed the police of Savannah that these three gentlemen are badly wanted here upon a charge of murder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2304,'There is ever a flaw, however, in the best laid of human plans, and the murderers of John Openshaw were never to receive the orange pips which would show them that another, as cunning and as resolute as themselves, was upon their track.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2305,'Very long and very severe were the equinoctial gales that year.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2306,'We waited long for news of the _Lone Star_ of Savannah, but none ever reached us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2307,'We did at last hear that somewhere far out in the Atlantic a shattered stern-post of a boat was seen swinging in the trough of a wave, with the letters L. S.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2308,'carved upon it, and that is all which we shall ever know of the fate of the _Lone Star_.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2309,'Adventure VI  THE MAN WITH THE TWISTED LIP   Isa Whitney, brother of the late Elias Whitney, D.D.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2310,', Principal of the Theological College of St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2311,'George’s, was much addicted to opium.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2312,'The habit grew upon him, as I understand, from some foolish freak when he was at college; for having read De Quincey’s description of his dreams and sensations, he had drenched his tobacco with laudanum in an attempt to produce the same effects.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2313,'He found, as so many more have done, that the practice is easier to attain than to get rid of, and for many years he continued to be a slave to the drug, an object of mingled horror and pity to his friends and relatives.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2314,'I can see him now, with yellow, pasty face, drooping lids, and pin-point pupils, all huddled in a chair, the wreck and ruin of a noble man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2315,'One night—it was in June, ’89—there came a ring to my bell, about the hour when a man gives his first yawn and glances at the clock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2316,'I sat up in my chair, and my wife laid her needle-work down in her lap and made a little face of disappointment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2317,'A patient! said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2318,'You’ll have to go out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2319,'I groaned, for I was newly come back from a weary day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2320,'We heard the door open, a few hurried words, and then quick steps upon the linoleum.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2321,'Our own door flew open, and a lady, clad in some dark-colored stuff, with a black veil, entered the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2322,'You will excuse my calling so late, she began, and then, suddenly losing her self-control, she ran forward, threw her arms about my wife’s neck, and sobbed upon her shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2323,'Oh, I’m in such trouble! she cried; I do so want a little help.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2324,'Why, said my wife, pulling up her veil, it is Kate Whitney.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2325,'How you startled me, Kate! I had not an idea who you were when you came in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2326,'I didn’t know what to do, so I came straight to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2327,'That was always the way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2328,'Folk who were in grief came to my wife like birds to a light-house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2329,'It was very sweet of you to come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2330,'Now, you must have some wine and water, and sit here comfortably and tell us all about it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2331,'Or should you rather that I sent James off to bed?  Oh, no, no! I want the Doctor’s advice and help, too. It’s about Isa.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2332,'He has not been home for two days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2333,'I am so frightened about him!  It was not the first time that she had spoken to us of her husband’s trouble, to me as a doctor, to my wife as an old friend and school companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2334,'We soothed and comforted her by such words as we could find.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2335,'Did she know where her husband was? Was it possible that we could bring him back to her?  It seemed that it was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2336,'She had the surest information that of late he had, when the fit was on him, made use of an opium den in the farthest east of the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2337,'Hitherto his orgies had always been confined to one day, and he had come back, twitching and shattered, in the evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2338,'But now the spell had been upon him eight-and-forty hours, and he lay there, doubtless among the dregs of the docks, breathing in the poison or sleeping off the effects.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2339,'There he was to be found, she was sure of it, at the Bar of Gold, in Upper Swandam Lane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2340,'But what was she to do? How could she, a young and timid woman, make her way into such a place, and pluck her husband out from among the ruffians who surrounded him?  There was the case, and of course there was but one way out of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2341,'Might I not escort her to this place? And then, as a second thought, why should she come at all? I was Isa Whitney’s medical adviser, and as such I had influence over him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2342,'I could manage it better if I were alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2343,'I promised her on my word that I would send him home in a cab within two hours if he were indeed at the address which she had given me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2344,'And so in ten minutes I had left my arm-chair and cheery sitting-room behind me, and was speeding eastward in a hansom on a strange errand, as it seemed to me at the time, though the future only could show how strange it was to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2345,'But there was no great difficulty in the first stage of my adventure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2346,'Upper Swandam Lane is a vile alley lurking behind the high wharves which line the north side of the river to the east of London Bridge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2347,'Between a slop-shop and a gin-shop, approached by a steep flight of steps leading down to a black gap like the mouth of a cave, I found the den of which I was in search.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2348,'Ordering my cab to wait, I passed down the steps, worn hollow in the centre by the ceaseless tread of drunken feet, and by the light of a flickering oil-lamp above the door I found the latch, and made my way into a long, low room, thick and heavy with the brown opium smoke, and terraced with wooden berths, like the forecastle of an emigrant ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2349,'Through the gloom one could dimly catch a glimpse of bodies lying in strange fantastic poses, bowed shoulders, bent knees, heads thrown back and chins pointing upward, with here and there a dark, lack-lustre eye turned upon the new-comer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2350,'Out of the black shadows there glimmered little red circles of light, now bright, now faint, as the burning poison waxed or waned in the bowls of the metal pipes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2351,'The most lay silent, but some muttered to themselves, and others talked together in a strange, low, monotonous voice, their conversation coming in gushes, and then suddenly tailing off into silence, each mumbling out his own thoughts, and paying little heed to the words of his neighbor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2352,'At the farther end was a small brazier of burning charcoal, beside which on a three-legged wooden stool there sat a tall, thin old man, with his jaw resting upon his two fists, and his elbows upon his knees, staring into the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2353,'As I entered, a sallow Malay attendant had hurried up with a pipe for me and a supply of the drug, beckoning me to an empty berth.  Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2354,'I have not come to stay, said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2355,'There is a friend of mine here, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2356,'Isa Whitney, and I wish to speak with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2357,'There was a movement and an exclamation from my right, and, peering through the gloom, I saw Whitney, pale, haggard, and unkempt, staring out at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2358,'My God! It’s Watson, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2359,'He was in a pitiable state of reaction, with every nerve in a twitter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2360,'I say, Watson, what o’clock is it?  Nearly eleven.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2361,'Of what day?  Of Friday, June 19th.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2362,'Good heavens! I thought it was Wednesday. It is Wednesday.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2363,'What d’you want to frighten a chap for? He sank his face onto his arms, and began to sob in a high treble key.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2364,'I tell you that it is Friday, man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2365,'Your wife has been waiting this two days for you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2366,'You should be ashamed of yourself!  So I am.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2367,'But you’ve got mixed, Watson, for I have only been here a few hours, three pipes, four pipes—I forget how many.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2368,'But I’ll go home with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2369,'I wouldn’t frighten Kate—poor little Kate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2370,'Give me your hand! Have you a cab?  Yes, I have one waiting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2371,'Then I shall go in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2372,'But I must owe something.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2373,'Find what I owe, Watson. I am all off color.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2374,'I can do nothing for myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2375,'I walked down the narrow passage between the double row of sleepers, holding my breath to keep out the vile, stupefying fumes of the drug, and looking about for the manager.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2376,'As I passed the tall man who sat by the brazier I felt a sudden pluck at my skirt, and a low voice whispered, Walk past me, and then look back at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2377,'The words fell quite distinctly upon my ear. I glanced down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2378,'They could only have come from the old man at my side, and yet he sat now as absorbed as ever, very thin, very wrinkled, bent with age, an opium pipe dangling down from between his knees, as though it had dropped in sheer lassitude from his fingers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2379,'I took two steps forward and looked back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2380,'It took all my self-control to prevent me from breaking out into a cry of astonishment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2381,'He had turned his back so that none could see him but I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2382,'His form had filled out, his wrinkles were gone, the dull eyes had regained their fire, and there, sitting by the fire, and grinning at my surprise, was none other than Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2383,'He made a slight motion to me to approach him, and instantly, as he turned his face half round to the company once more, subsided into a doddering, loose-lipped senility.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2384,'Holmes! I whispered, what on earth are you doing in this den?  As low as you can, he answered; I have excellent ears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2385,'If you would have the great kindness to get rid of that sottish friend of yours I should be exceedingly glad to have a little talk with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2386,'I have a cab outside.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2387,'Then pray send him home in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2388,'You may safely trust him, for he appears to be too limp to get into any mischief.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2389,'I should recommend you also to send a note by the cabman to your wife to say that you have thrown in your lot with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2390,'If you will wait outside, I shall be with you in five minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2391,'It was difficult to refuse any of Sherlock Holmes’s requests, for they were always so exceedingly definite, and put forward with such a quiet air of mastery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2392,'I felt, however, that when Whitney was once confined in the cab my mission was practically accomplished, and for the rest, I could not wish anything better than to be associated with my friend in one of those singular adventures which were the normal condition of his existence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2393,'In a few minutes I had written my note, paid Whitney’s bill, led him out to the cab, and seen him driven through the darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2394,'In a very short time a decrepit figure had emerged from the opium den, and I was walking down the street with Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2395,'For two streets he shuffled along with a bent back and an uncertain foot.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2396,'Then, glancing quickly round, he straightened himself out and burst into a hearty fit of laughter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2397,'I suppose, Watson, said he, that you imagine that I have added opium-smoking to cocaine injections, and all the other little weaknesses on which you have favored me with your medical views.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2398,'I was certainly surprised to find you there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2399,'But not more so than I to find you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2400,'I came to find a friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2401,'And I to find an enemy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2402,'An enemy?  Yes; one of my natural enemies, or, shall I say, my natural prey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2403,'Briefly, Watson, I am in the midst of a very remarkable inquiry, and I have hoped to find a clew in the incoherent ramblings of these sots, as I have done before now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2404,'Had I been recognized in that den my life would not have been worth an hour’s purchase; for I have used it before now for my own purposes, and the rascally Lascar who runs it has sworn to have vengeance upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2405,'There is a trap-door at the back of that building, near the corner of Paul’s Wharf, which could tell some strange tales of what has passed through it upon the moonless nights.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2406,'What! You do not mean bodies?  Aye, bodies, Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2407,'We should be rich men if we had £1000 for every poor devil who has been done to death in that den.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2408,'It is the vilest murder-trap on the whole river-side, and I fear that Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2409,'Clair has entered it never to leave it more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2410,'But our trap should be here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2411,'He put his two forefingers between his teeth and whistled shrilly—a signal which was answered by a similar whistle from the distance, followed shortly by the rattle of wheels and the clink of horses’ hoofs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2412,'Now, Watson, said Holmes, as a tall dog-cart dashed up through the gloom, throwing out two golden tunnels of yellow light from its side lanterns.');
