INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2473,'It was the toy which he had promised to bring home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2474,'This discovery, and the evident confusion which the cripple showed, made the inspector realize that the matter was serious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2475,'The rooms were carefully examined, and results all pointed to an abominable crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2476,'The front room was plainly furnished as a sitting-room, and led into a small bedroom, which looked out upon the back of one of the wharves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2477,'Between the wharf and the bedroom window is a narrow strip, which is dry at low tide, but is covered at high tide with at least four and a half feet of water.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2478,'The bedroom window was a broad one, and opened from below.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2479,'On examination traces of blood were to be seen upon the window-sill, and several scattered drops were visible upon the wooden floor of the bedroom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2480,'Thrust away behind a curtain in the front room were all the clothes of Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2481,'Clair, with the exception of his coat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2482,'His boots, his socks, his hat, and his watch—all were there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2483,'There were no signs of violence upon any of these garments, and there were no other traces of Mr. Neville St. Clair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2484,'Out of the window he must apparently have gone, for no other exit could be discovered, and the ominous blood-stains upon the sill gave little promise that he could save himself by swimming, for the tide was at its very highest at the moment of the tragedy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2485,'And now as to the villains who seemed to be immediately implicated in the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2486,'The Lascar was known to be a man of the vilest antecedents, but as, by Mrs. St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2487,'Clair’s story, he was known to have been at the foot of the stair within a very few seconds of her husband’s appearance at the window, he could hardly have been more than an accessory to the crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2488,'His defense was one of absolute ignorance, and he protested that he had no knowledge as to the doings of Hugh Boone, his lodger, and that he could not account in any way for the presence of the missing gentleman’s clothes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2489,'So much for the Lascar manager.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2490,'Now for the sinister cripple who lives upon the second floor of the opium den, and who was certainly the last human being whose eyes rested upon Neville St. Clair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2491,'His name is Hugh Boone, and his hideous face is one which is familiar to every man who goes much to the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2492,'He is a professional beggar, though, in order to avoid the police regulations, he pretends to a small trade in wax vestas.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2493,'Some little distance down Threadneedle Street, upon the left-hand side, there is, as you may have remarked, a small angle in the wall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2494,'Here it is that this creature takes his daily seat, cross-legged, with his tiny stock of matches on his lap, and, as he is a piteous spectacle, a small rain of charity descends into the greasy leather cap which lies upon the pavement beside him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2495,'I have watched the fellow more than once, before ever I thought of making his professional acquaintance, and I have been surprised at the harvest which he has reaped in a short time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2496,'His appearance, you see, is so remarkable that no one can pass him without observing him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2497,'A shock of orange hair, a pale face disfigured by a horrible scar, which, by its contraction, has turned up the outer edge of his upper lip, a bull-dog chin, and a pair of very penetrating dark eyes, which present a singular contrast to the color of his hair, all mark him out from amid the common crowd of mendicants, and so, too, does his wit, for he is ever ready with a reply to any piece of chaff which may be thrown at him by the passers-by.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2498,'This is the man whom we now learn to have been the lodger at the opium den, and to have been the last man to see the gentleman of whom we are in quest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2499,'But a cripple! said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2500,'What could he have done single-handed against a man in the prime of life?  He is a cripple in the sense that he walks with a limp; but in other respects he appears to be a powerful and well-nurtured man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2501,'Surely your medical experience would tell you, Watson, that weakness in one limb is often compensated for by exceptional strength in the others.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2502,'Pray continue your narrative.  Mrs. St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2503,'Clair had fainted at the sight of the blood upon the window, and she was escorted home in a cab by the police, as her presence could be of no help to them in their investigations.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2504,'Inspector Barton, who had charge of the case, made a very careful examination of the premises, but without finding anything which threw any light upon the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2505,'One mistake had been made in not arresting Boone instantly, as he was allowed some few minutes during which he might have communicated with his friend the Lascar, but this fault was soon remedied, and he was seized and searched, without anything being found which could incriminate him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2506,'There were, it is true, some blood-stains upon his right shirt-sleeve, but he pointed to his ring-finger, which had been cut near the nail, and explained that the bleeding came from there, adding that he had been to the window not long before, and that the stains which had been observed there came doubtless from the same source.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2507,'He denied strenuously having ever seen Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2508,'Clair, and swore that the presence of the clothes in his room was as much a mystery to him as to the police. As to Mrs. St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2509,'Clair’s assertion that she had actually seen her husband at the window, he declared that she must have been either mad or dreaming.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2510,'He was removed, loudly protesting, to the police-station, while the inspector remained upon the premises in the hope that the ebbing tide might afford some fresh clew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2511,'And it did, though they hardly found upon the mud-bank what they had feared to find. It was Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2512,'Clair’s coat, and not Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2513,'Clair, which lay uncovered as the tide receded.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2514,'And what do you think they found in the pockets?  I cannot imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2515,'No, I don’t think you would guess.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2516,'Every pocket stuffed with pennies and half-pennies—421 pennies and 270 half-pennies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2517,'It was no wonder that it had not been swept away by the tide.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2518,'But a human body is a different matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2519,'There is a fierce eddy between the wharf and the house.');
