INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2546,'I hate to meet her, Watson, when I have no news of her husband. Here we are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2547,'Whoa, there, whoa!  We had pulled up in front of a large villa which stood within its own grounds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2548,'A stable-boy had run out to the horse’s head, and, springing down, I followed Holmes up the small, winding gravel-drive which led to the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2549,'As we approached, the door flew open, and a little blonde woman stood in the opening, clad in some sort of light mousseline de soie, with a touch of fluffy pink chiffon at her neck and wrists.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2550,'She stood with her figure outlined against the flood of light, one hand upon the door, one half-raised in her eagerness, her body slightly bent, her head and face protruded, with eager eyes and parted lips, a standing question.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2551,'Well? she cried, well? And then, seeing that there were two of us, she gave a cry of hope which sank into a groan as she saw that my companion shook his head and shrugged his shoulders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2552,'No good news?  None.  No bad?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2553,'Thank God for that. But come in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2554,'You must be weary, for you have had a long day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2555,'This is my friend, Dr. Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2556,'He has been of most vital use to me in several of my cases, and a lucky chance has made it possible for me to bring him out and associate him with this investigation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2557,'I am delighted to see you, said she, pressing my hand warmly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2558,'You will, I am sure, forgive anything that may be wanting in our arrangements, when you consider the blow which has come so suddenly upon us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2559,'My dear madam, said I, I am an old campaigner, and if I were not, I can very well see that no apology is needed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2560,'If I can be of any assistance, either to you or to my friend here, I shall be indeed happy.  Now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2561,'Sherlock Holmes, said the lady, as we entered a well-lit dining-room, upon the table of which a cold supper had been laid out, I should very much like to ask you one or two plain questions, to which I beg that you will give a plain answer.  Certainly, madam.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2562,'Do not trouble about my feelings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2563,'I am not hysterical, nor given to fainting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2564,'I simply wish to hear your real, real opinion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2565,'Upon what point?  In your heart of hearts do you think that Neville is alive?  Sherlock Holmes seemed to be embarrassed by the question.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2566,'Frankly, now! she repeated, standing upon the rug and looking keenly down at him as he leaned back in a basket-chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2567,'Frankly, then, madam, I do not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2568,'You think that he is dead?  I do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2569,'Murdered?  I don’t say that. Perhaps.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2570,'And on what day did he meet his death?  On Monday.  Then perhaps, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2571,'Holmes, you will be good enough to explain how it is that I have received a letter from him to-day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2572,'Sherlock Holmes sprang out of his chair as if he had been galvanized.  What! he roared.  Yes, to-day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2573,'She stood smiling, holding up a little slip of paper in the air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2574,'May I see it?  Certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2575,'He snatched it from her in his eagerness, and smoothing it out upon the table, he drew over the lamp, and examined it intently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2576,'I had left my chair, and was gazing at it over his shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2577,'The envelope was a very coarse one, and was stamped with the Gravesend post-mark, and with the date of that very day, or rather of the day before, for it was considerably after midnight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2578,'Coarse writing, murmured Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2579,'Surely this is not your husband’s writing, madam.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2580,'No, but the enclosure is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2581,'I perceive also that whoever addressed the envelope had to go and inquire as to the address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2582,'How can you tell that?  The name, you see, is in perfectly black ink, which has dried itself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2583,'The rest is of the grayish color, which shows that blotting-paper has been used.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2584,'If it had been written straight off, and then blotted, none would be of a deep black shade.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2585,'This man has written the name, and there has then been a pause before he wrote the address, which can only mean that he was not familiar with it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2586,'It is, of course, a trifle, but there is nothing so important as trifles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2587,'Let us now see the letter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2588,'Ha! there has been an enclosure here!  Yes, there was a ring. His signet-ring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2589,'And you are sure that this is your husband’s hand?  One of his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2590,'One?  His hand when he wrote hurriedly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2591,'It is very unlike his usual writing, and yet I know it well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2592,'‘Dearest do not be frightened. All will come well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2593,'There is a huge error which it may take some little time to rectify. Wait in patience.—Neville.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2594,'’ Written in pencil upon the fly-leaf of a book, octavo size, no water-mark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2595,'Hum! Posted to-day in Gravesend by a man with a dirty thumb.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2596,'Ha! And the flap has been gummed, if I am not very much in error, by a person who had been chewing tobacco.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2597,'And you have no doubt that it is your husband’s hand, madam?  None.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2598,'Neville wrote those words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2599,'And they were posted to-day at Gravesend. Well, Mrs. St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2600,'Clair, the clouds lighten, though I should not venture to say that the danger is over.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2601,'But he must be alive, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2602,'Unless this is a clever forgery to put us on the wrong scent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2603,'The ring, after all, proves nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2604,'It may have been taken from him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2605,'No, no; it is, it is, it is his very own writing!  Very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2606,'It may, however, have been written on Monday, and only posted to-day.  That is possible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2607,'If so, much may have happened between.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2608,'Oh, you must not discourage me, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2609,'I know that all is well with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2610,'There is so keen a sympathy between us that I should know if evil came upon him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2611,'On the very day that I saw him last he cut himself in the bedroom, and yet I in the dining-room rushed up-stairs instantly with the utmost certainty that something had happened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2612,'Do you think that I would respond to such a trifle, and yet be ignorant of his death?  I have seen too much not to know that the impression of a woman may be more valuable than the conclusion of an analytical reasoner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2613,'And in this letter you certainly have a very strong piece of evidence to corroborate your view.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2614,'But if your husband is alive, and able to write letters, why should he remain away from you?  I cannot imagine. It is unthinkable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2615,'And on Monday he made no remarks before leaving you?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2616,'And you were surprised to see him in Swandam Lane?  Very much so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2617,'Was the window open?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2618,'Then he might have called to you?  He might.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2619,'He only, as I understand, gave an inarticulate cry?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2620,'A call for help, you thought?  Yes. He waved his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2621,'But it might have been a cry of surprise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2622,'Astonishment at the unexpected sight of you might cause him to throw up his hands?  It is possible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2623,'And you thought he was pulled back?  He disappeared so suddenly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2624,'He might have leaped back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2625,'You did not see any one else in the room?  No, but this horrible man confessed to having been there, and the Lascar was at the foot of the stairs.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2626,'Your husband, as far as you could see, had his ordinary clothes on?  But without his collar or tie.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2627,'I distinctly saw his bare throat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2628,'Had he ever spoken of Swandam Lane?  Never.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2629,'Had he ever showed any signs of having taken opium?  Never.  Thank you, Mrs. St. Clair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2630,'Those are the principal points about which I wished to be absolutely clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2631,'We shall now have a little supper and then retire, for we may have a very busy day to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2632,'A large and comfortable double-bedded room had been placed at our disposal, and I was quickly between the sheets, for I was weary after my night of adventure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2633,'Sherlock Holmes was a man, however, who, when he had an unsolved problem upon his mind, would go for days, and even for a week, without rest, turning it over, rearranging his facts, looking at it from every point of view, until he had either fathomed it, or convinced himself that his data were insufficient.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2634,'It was soon evident to me that he was now preparing for an all-night sitting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2635,'He took off his coat and waistcoat, put on a large blue dressing-gown, and then wandered about the room collecting pillows from his bed and cushions from the sofa and arm-chairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2636,'With these he constructed a sort of Eastern divan, upon which he perched himself cross-legged, with an ounce of shag tobacco and a box of matches laid out in front of him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2637,'In the dim light of the lamp I saw him sitting there, an old briar pipe between his lips, his eyes fixed vacantly upon the corner of the ceiling, the blue smoke curling up from him, silent, motionless, with the light shining upon his strong-set aquiline features.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2638,'So he sat as I dropped off to sleep, and so he sat when a sudden ejaculation caused me to wake up, and I found the summer sun shining into the apartment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2639,'The pipe was still between his lips, the smoke still curled upward, and the room was full of a dense tobacco haze, but nothing remained of the heap of shag which I had seen upon the previous night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2640,'Awake, Watson? he asked.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2641,'Game for a morning drive?  Certainly.  Then dress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2642,'No one is stirring yet, but I know where the stable-boy sleeps, and we shall soon have the trap out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2643,'He chuckled to himself as he spoke, his eyes twinkled, and he seemed a different man to the sombre thinker of the previous night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2644,'As I dressed I glanced at my watch.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2645,'It was no wonder that no one was stirring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2646,'It was twenty-five minutes past four.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2647,'I had hardly finished when Holmes returned with the news that the boy was putting in the horse.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2648,'I want to test a little theory of mine, said he, pulling on his boots.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2649,'I think, Watson, that you are now standing in the presence of one of the most absolute fools in Europe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2650,'I deserve to be kicked from here to Charing Cross.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2651,'But I think I have the key of the affair now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2652,'And where is it? I asked, smiling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2653,'In the bath-room, he answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2654,'Oh yes, I am not joking, he continued, seeing my look of incredulity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2655,'I have just been there, and I have taken it out, and I have got it in this Gladstone bag.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2656,'Come on, my boy, and we shall see whether it will not fit the lock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2657,'We made our way down-stairs as quietly as possible, and out into the bright morning sunshine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2658,'In the road stood our horse and trap, with the half-clad stable-boy waiting at the head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2659,'We both sprang in, and away we dashed down the London Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2660,'A few country carts were stirring, bearing in vegetables to the metropolis, but the lines of villas on either side were as silent and lifeless as some city in a dream.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2661,'It has been in some points a singular case, said Holmes, flicking the horse on into a gallop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2662,'I confess that I have been as blind as a mole, but it is better to learn wisdom late than never to learn it at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2663,'In town the earliest risers were just beginning to look sleepily from their windows as we drove through the streets of the Surrey side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2664,'Passing down the Waterloo Bridge Road we crossed over the river, and dashing up Wellington Street wheeled sharply to the right, and found ourselves in Bow Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2665,'Sherlock Holmes was well known to the Force, and the two constables at the door saluted him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2666,'One of them held the horse’s head while the other led us in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2667,'Who is on duty? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2668,'Inspector Bradstreet, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2669,'Ah, Bradstreet, how are you? A tall, stout official had come down the stone-flagged passage, in a peaked cap and frogged jacket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2670,'I wish to have a quiet word with you, Bradstreet.  Certainly, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2671,'Step into my room here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2672,'It was a small, office-like room, with a huge ledger upon the table, and a telephone projecting from the wall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2673,'The inspector sat down at his desk.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2674,'What can I do for you, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2675,'Holmes?  I called about that beggarman, Boone—the one who was charged with being concerned in the disappearance of Mr. Neville St. Clair, of Lee.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2676,'He was brought up and remanded for further inquiries.  So I heard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2677,'You have him here?  In the cells.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2678,'Is he quiet?  Oh, he gives no trouble.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2679,'But he is a dirty scoundrel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2680,'Dirty?  Yes, it is all we can do to make him wash his hands, and his face is as black as a tinker’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2681,'Well, when once his case has been settled, he will have a regular prison bath; and I think, if you saw him, you would agree with me that he needed it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2682,'I should like to see him very much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2683,'Would you? That is easily done. Come this way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2684,'You can leave your bag.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2685,'No, I think that I’ll take it.  Very good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2686,'Come this way, if you please.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2687,'He led us down a passage, opened a barred door, passed down a winding stair, and brought us to a whitewashed corridor with a line of doors on each side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2688,'The third on the right is his, said the inspector.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2689,'Here it is! He quietly shot back a panel in the upper part of the door and glanced through.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2690,'He is asleep, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2691,'You can see him very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2692,'We both put our eyes to the grating.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2693,'The prisoner lay with his face towards us, in a very deep sleep, breathing slowly and heavily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2694,'He was a middle-sized man, coarsely clad as became his calling, with a colored shirt protruding through the rent in his tattered coat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2695,'He was, as the inspector had said, extremely dirty, but the grime which covered his face could not conceal its repulsive ugliness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2696,'A broad wheal from an old scar ran right across it from eye to chin, and by its contraction had turned up one side of the upper lip, so that three teeth were exposed in a perpetual snarl.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2697,'A shock of very bright red hair grew low over his eyes and forehead.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2698,'He’s a beauty, isn’t he? said the inspector.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2699,'He certainly needs a wash, remarked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2700,'I had an idea that he might, and I took the liberty of bringing the tools with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2701,'He opened the Gladstone bag as he spoke, and took out, to my astonishment, a very large bath-sponge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2702,'He! he! You are a funny one, chuckled the inspector.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2703,'Now, if you will have the great goodness to open that door very quietly, we will soon make him cut a much more respectable figure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2704,'Well, I don’t know why not, said the inspector.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2705,'He doesn’t look a credit to the Bow Street cells, does he? He slipped his key into the lock, and we all very quietly entered the cell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2706,'The sleeper half turned, and then settled down once more into a deep slumber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2707,'Holmes stooped to the water-jug, moistened his sponge, and then rubbed it twice vigorously across and down the prisoner’s face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2708,'Let me introduce you, he shouted, to Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2709,'Clair, of Lee, in the county of Kent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2710,'Never in my life have I seen such a sight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2711,'The man’s face peeled off under the sponge like the bark from a tree.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2712,'Gone was the coarse brown tint! Gone, too, was the horrid scar which had seamed it across, and the twisted lip which had given the repulsive sneer to the face! A twitch brought away the tangled red hair, and there, sitting up in his bed, was a pale, sad-faced, refined-looking man, black-haired and smooth-skinned, rubbing his eyes, and staring about him with sleepy bewilderment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2713,'Then suddenly realizing the exposure, he broke into a scream, and threw himself down with his face to the pillow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2714,'Great heavens! cried the inspector, it is, indeed, the missing man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2715,'I know him from the photograph.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2716,'The prisoner turned with the reckless air of a man who abandons himself to his destiny. Be it so, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2717,'And pray, what am I charged with?  With making away with Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2718,'—— Oh, come, you can’t be charged with that, unless they make a case of attempted suicide of it, said the inspector, with a grin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2719,'Well, I have been twenty-seven years in the force, but this really takes the cake.  If I am Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2720,'Clair, then it is obvious that no crime has been committed, and that, therefore, I am illegally detained.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2721,'No crime, but a very great error has been committed, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2722,'You would have done better to have trusted your wife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2723,'It was not the wife, it was the children, groaned the prisoner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2724,'God help me, I would not have them ashamed of their father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2725,'My God! What an exposure! What can I do?  Sherlock Holmes sat down beside him on the couch and patted him kindly on the shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2726,'If you leave it to a court of law to clear the matter up, said he, of course you can hardly avoid publicity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2727,'On the other hand, if you convince the police authorities that there is no possible case against you, I do not know that there is any reason that the details should find their way into the papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2728,'Inspector Bradstreet would, I am sure, make notes upon anything which you might tell us, and submit it to the proper authorities.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2729,'The case would then never go into court at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2730,'God bless you! cried the prisoner, passionately.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2731,'I would have endured imprisonment, aye, even execution, rather than have left my miserable secret as a family blot to my children.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2732,'You are the first who have ever heard my story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2733,'My father was a school-master in Chesterfield, where I received an excellent education.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2734,'I travelled in my youth, took to the stage, and finally became a reporter on an evening paper in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2735,'One day my editor wished to have a series of articles upon begging in the metropolis, and I volunteered to supply them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2736,'There was the point from which all my adventures started.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2737,'It was only by trying begging as an amateur that I could get the facts upon which to base my articles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2738,'When an actor I had, of course, learned all the secrets of making up, and had been famous in the greenroom for my skill.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2739,'I took advantage now of my attainments.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2740,'I painted my face, and to make myself as pitiable as possible I made a good scar and fixed one side of my lip in a twist by the aid of a small slip of flesh-colored plaster.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2741,'Then with a red head of hair, and an appropriate dress, I took my station in the busiest part of the city, ostensibly as a match-seller, but really as a beggar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2742,'For seven hours I plied my trade, and when I returned home in the evening I found, to my surprise, that I had received no less than 26_s._ 4_d.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2743,'_  I wrote my articles, and thought little more of the matter until, some time later, I backed a bill for a friend, and had a writ served upon me for £25.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2744,'I was at my wits’ end where to get the money, but a sudden idea came to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2745,'I begged a fortnight’s grace from the creditor, asked for a holiday from my employers, and spent the time in begging in the city under my disguise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2746,'In ten days I had the money, and had paid the debt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2747,'Well, you can imagine how hard it was to settle down to arduous work at £2 a week, when I knew that I could earn as much in a day by smearing my face with a little paint, laying my cap on the ground, and sitting still.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2748,'It was a long fight between my pride and the money, but the dollars won at last, and I threw up reporting, and sat day after day in the corner which I had first chosen, inspiring pity by my ghastly face, and filling my pockets with coppers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2749,'Only one man knew my secret.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2750,'He was the keeper of a low den in which I used to lodge in Swandam Lane, where I could every morning emerge as a squalid beggar, and in the evenings transform myself into a well-dressed man about town.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2751,'This fellow, a Lascar, was well paid by me for his rooms, so that I knew that my secret was safe in his possession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2752,'Well, very soon I found that I was saving considerable sums of money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2753,'I do not mean that any beggar in the streets of London could earn £700 a year—which is less than my average takings—but I had exceptional advantages in my power of making up, and also in a facility of repartee, which improved by practice, and made me quite a recognized character in the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2754,'All day a stream of pennies, varied by silver, poured in upon me, and it was a very bad day in which I failed to take £2.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2755,'As I grew richer I grew more ambitious, took a house in the country, and eventually married, without any one having a suspicion as to my real occupation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2756,'My dear wife knew that I had business in the city.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2757,'She little knew what.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2758,'Last Monday I had finished for the day, and was dressing in my room above the opium den, when I looked out of my window, and saw, to my horror and astonishment, that my wife was standing in the street, with her eyes fixed full upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2759,'I gave a cry of surprise, threw up my arms to cover my face, and, rushing to my confidant, the Lascar, entreated him to prevent any one from coming up to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2760,'I heard her voice down-stairs, but I knew that she could not ascend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2761,'Swiftly I threw off my clothes, pulled on those of a beggar, and put on my pigments and wig.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2762,'Even a wife’s eyes could not pierce so complete a disguise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2763,'But then it occurred to me that there might be a search in the room, and that the clothes might betray me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2764,'I threw open the window, reopening by my violence a small cut which I had inflicted upon myself in the bedroom that morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2765,'Then I seized my coat, which was weighted by the coppers which I had just transferred to it from the leather bag in which I carried my takings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2766,'I hurled it out of the window, and it disappeared into the Thames.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2767,'The other clothes would have followed, but at that moment there was a rush of constables up the stair, and a few minutes after I found, rather, I confess, to my relief, that instead of being identified as Mr. Neville St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2768,'Clair, I was arrested as his murderer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2769,'I do not know that there is anything else for me to explain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2770,'I was determined to preserve my disguise as long as possible, and hence my preference for a dirty face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2771,'Knowing that my wife would be terribly anxious, I slipped off my ring, and confided it to the Lascar at a moment when no constable was watching me, together with a hurried scrawl, telling her that she had no cause to fear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2772,'That note only reached her yesterday, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2773,'Good God! What a week she must have spent!  The police have watched this Lascar, said Inspector Bradstreet, and I can quite understand that he might find it difficult to post a letter unobserved.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2774,'Probably he handed it to some sailor customer of his, who forgot all about it for some days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2775,'That was it, said Holmes, nodding approvingly; I have no doubt of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2776,'But have you never been prosecuted for begging?  Many times; but what was a fine to me?  It must stop here, however, said Bradstreet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2777,'If the police are to hush this thing up, there must be no more of Hugh Boone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2778,'I have sworn it by the most solemn oaths which a man can take.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2779,'In that case I think that it is probable that no further steps may be taken.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2780,'But if you are found again, then all must come out. I am sure, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2781,'Holmes, that we are very much indebted to you for having cleared the matter up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2782,'I wish I knew how you reach your results.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2783,'I reached this one, said my friend, by sitting upon five pillows and consuming an ounce of shag.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2784,'I think, Watson, that if we drive to Baker Street we shall just be in time for breakfast.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2785,'Adventure VII  THE ADVENTURE OF THE BLUE CARBUNCLE   I had called upon my friend Sherlock Holmes upon the second morning after Christmas, with the intention of wishing him the compliments of the season.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2786,'He was lounging upon the sofa in a purple dressing-gown, a pipe-rack within his reach upon the right, and a pile of crumpled morning papers, evidently newly studied, near at hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2787,'Beside the couch was a wooden chair, and on the angle of the back hung a very seedy and disreputable hard-felt hat, much the worse for wear, and cracked in several places.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2788,'A lens and a forceps lying upon the seat of the chair suggested that the hat had been suspended in this manner for the purpose of examination.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2789,'You are engaged, said I; perhaps I interrupt you.  Not at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2790,'I am glad to have a friend with whom I can discuss my results.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2791,'The matter is a perfectly trivial one (he jerked his thumb in the direction of the old hat), but there are points in connection with it which are not entirely devoid of interest and even of instruction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2792,'I seated myself in his arm-chair and warmed my hands before his crackling fire, for a sharp frost had set in, and the windows were thick with the ice crystals.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2793,'I suppose, I remarked, that, homely as it looks, this thing has some deadly story linked on to it—that it is the clew which will guide you in the solution of some mystery and the punishment of some crime.  No, no.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2794,'No crime, said Sherlock Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2795,'Only one of those whimsical little incidents which will happen when you have four million human beings all jostling each other within the space of a few square miles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2796,'Amid the action and reaction of so dense a swarm of humanity, every possible combination of events may be expected to take place, and many a little problem will be presented which may be striking and bizarre without being criminal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2797,'We have already had experience of such.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2798,'So much so, I remarked, that of the last six cases which I have added to my notes, three have been entirely free of any legal crime.  Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2799,'You allude to my attempt to recover the Irene Adler papers, to the singular case of Miss Mary Sutherland, and to the adventure of the man with the twisted lip.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2800,'Well, I have no doubt that this small matter will fall into the same innocent category.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2801,'You know Peterson, the commissionaire?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2802,'It is to him that this trophy belongs.  It is his hat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2803,'No, no; he found it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2804,'Its owner is unknown.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2805,'I beg that you will look upon it, not as a battered billycock, but as an intellectual problem.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2806,'And, first, as to how it came here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2807,'It arrived upon Christmas morning, in company with a good fat goose, which is, I have no doubt, roasting at this moment in front of Peterson’s fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2808,'The facts are these: about four o’clock on Christmas morning, Peterson, who, as you know, is a very honest fellow, was returning from some small jollification, and was making his way homeward down Tottenham Court Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2809,'In front of him he saw, in the gaslight, a tallish man, walking with a slight stagger, and carrying a white goose slung over his shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2810,'As he reached the corner of Goodge Street, a row broke out between this stranger and a little knot of roughs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2811,'One of the latter knocked off the man’s hat, on which he raised his stick to defend himself, and, swinging it over his head, smashed the shop window behind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2812,'Peterson had rushed forward to protect the stranger from his assailants; but the man, shocked at having broken the window, and seeing an official-looking person in uniform rushing towards him, dropped his goose, took to his heels, and vanished amid the labyrinth of small streets which lie at the back of Tottenham Court Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2813,'The roughs had also fled at the appearance of Peterson, so that he was left in possession of the field of battle, and also of the spoils of victory in the shape of this battered hat and a most unimpeachable Christmas goose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2814,'Which surely he restored to their owner?  My dear fellow, there lies the problem.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2815,'It is true that ‘For Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2816,'Henry Baker’ was printed upon a small card which was tied to the bird’s left leg, and it is also true that the initials ‘H. B.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2817,'’ are legible upon the lining of this hat; but as there are some thousands of Bakers, and some hundreds of Henry Bakers in this city of ours, it is not easy to restore lost property to any one of them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2818,'What, then, did Peterson do?  He brought round both hat and goose to me on Christmas morning, knowing that even the smallest problems are of interest to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2819,'The goose we retained until this morning, when there were signs that, in spite of the slight frost, it would be well that it should be eaten without unnecessary delay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2820,'Its finder has carried it off, therefore, to fulfil the ultimate destiny of a goose, while I continue to retain the hat of the unknown gentleman who lost his Christmas dinner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2821,'Did he not advertise?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2822,'Then, what clue could you have as to his identity?  Only as much as we can deduce.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2823,'From his hat?  Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2824,'But you are joking.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2825,'What can you gather from this old battered felt?  Here is my lens. You know my methods.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2826,'What can you gather yourself as to the individuality of the man who has worn this article?  I took the tattered object in my hands and turned it over rather ruefully.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2827,'It was a very ordinary black hat of the usual round shape, hard, and much the worse for wear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2828,'The lining had been of red silk, but was a good deal discolored.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2829,'There was no maker’s name; but, as Holmes had remarked, the initials H. B.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2830,'were scrawled upon one side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2831,'It was pierced in the brim for a hat-securer, but the elastic was missing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2832,'For the rest, it was cracked, exceedingly dusty, and spotted in several places, although there seemed to have been some attempt to hide the discolored patches by smearing them with ink.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2833,'I can see nothing, said I, handing it back to my friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2834,'On the contrary, Watson, you can see everything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2835,'You fail, however, to reason from what you see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2836,'You are too timid in drawing your inferences.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2837,'Then, pray tell me what it is that you can infer from this hat?  He picked it up and gazed at it in the peculiar introspective fashion which was characteristic of him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2838,'It is perhaps less suggestive than it might have been, he remarked, and yet there are a few inferences which are very distinct, and a few others which represent at least a strong balance of probability.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2839,'That the man was highly intellectual is of course obvious upon the face of it, and also that he was fairly well-to-do within the last three years, although he has now fallen upon evil days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2840,'He had foresight, but has less now than formerly, pointing to a moral retrogression, which, when taken with the decline of his fortunes, seems to indicate some evil influence, probably drink, at work upon him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2841,'This may account also for the obvious fact that his wife has ceased to love him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2842,'My dear Holmes!  He has, however, retained some degree of self-respect, he continued, disregarding my remonstrance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2843,'He is a man who leads a sedentary life, goes out little, is out of training entirely, is middle-aged, has grizzled hair which he has had cut within the last few days, and which he anoints with lime-cream.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2844,'These are the more patent facts which are to be deduced from his hat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2845,'Also, by-the-way, that it is extremely improbable that he has gas laid on in his house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2846,'You are certainly joking, Holmes.  Not in the least.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2847,'Is it possible that even now, when I give you these results, you are unable to see how they are attained?  I have no doubt that I am very stupid; but I must confess that I am unable to follow you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2848,'For example, how did you deduce that this man was intellectual?  For answer Holmes clapped the hat upon his head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2849,'It came right over the forehead and settled upon the bridge of his nose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2850,'It is a question of cubic capacity, said he; a man with so large a brain must have something in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2851,'The decline of his fortunes, then?  This hat is three years old.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2852,'These flat brims curled at the edge came in then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2853,'It is a hat of the very best quality.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2854,'Look at the band of ribbed silk and the excellent lining.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2855,'If this man could afford to buy so expensive a hat three years ago, and has had no hat since, then he has assuredly gone down in the world.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2856,'Well, that is clear enough, certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2857,'But how about the foresight and the moral retrogression?  Sherlock Holmes laughed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2858,'Here is the foresight, said he, putting his finger upon the little disk and loop of the hat-securer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2859,'They are never sold upon hats.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2860,'If this man ordered one, it is a sign of a certain amount of foresight, since he went out of his way to take this precaution against the wind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2861,'But since we see that he has broken the elastic, and has not troubled to replace it, it is obvious that he has less foresight now than formerly, which is a distinct proof of a weakening nature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2862,'On the other hand, he has endeavored to conceal some of these stains upon the felt by daubing them with ink, which is a sign that he has not entirely lost his self-respect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2863,'Your reasoning is certainly plausible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2864,'The further points, that he is middle-aged, that his hair is grizzled, that it has been recently cut, and that he uses lime-cream, are all to be gathered from a close examination of the lower part of the lining.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2865,'The lens discloses a large number of hair-ends, clean cut by the scissors of the barber.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2866,'They all appear to be adhesive, and there is a distinct odor of lime-cream.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2867,'This dust, you will observe, is not the gritty, gray dust of the street, but the fluffy brown dust of the house, showing that it has been hung up in-doors most of the time; while the marks of moisture upon the inside are proof positive that the wearer perspired very freely, and could, therefore, hardly be in the best of training.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2868,'But his wife—you said that she had ceased to love him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2869,'This hat has not been brushed for weeks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2870,'When I see you, my dear Watson, with a week’s accumulation of dust upon your hat, and when your wife allows you to go out in such a state, I shall fear that you also have been unfortunate enough to lose your wife’s affection.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2871,'But he might be a bachelor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2872,'Nay, he was bringing home the goose as a peace-offering to his wife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2873,'Remember the card upon the bird’s leg.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2874,'You have an answer to everything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2875,'But how on earth do you deduce that the gas is not laid on in his house?  One tallow stain, or even two, might come by chance; but when I see no less than five, I think that there can be little doubt that the individual must be brought into frequent contact with burning tallow—walks up-stairs at night probably with his hat in one hand and a guttering candle in the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2876,'Anyhow, he never got tallow-stains from a gas-jet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2877,'Are you satisfied?  Well, it is very ingenious, said I, laughing; but since, as you said just now, there has been no crime committed, and no harm done, save the loss of a goose, all this seems to be rather a waste of energy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2878,'Sherlock Holmes had opened his mouth to reply, when the door flew open, and Peterson, the commissionaire, rushed into the apartment with flushed cheeks and the face of a man who is dazed with astonishment.  The goose, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2879,'Holmes! The goose, sir! he gasped.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2880,'Eh? What of it, then? Has it returned to life and flapped off through the kitchen window? Holmes twisted himself round upon the sofa to get a fairer view of the man’s excited face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2881,'See here, sir! See what my wife found in its crop! He held out his hand and displayed upon the centre of the palm a brilliantly scintillating blue stone, rather smaller than a bean in size, but of such purity and radiance that it twinkled like an electric point in the dark hollow of his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2882,'Sherlock Holmes sat up with a whistle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2883,'By Jove, Peterson! said he, this is treasure trove indeed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2884,'I suppose you know what you have got?  A diamond, sir? A precious stone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2885,'It cuts into glass as though it were putty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2886,'It’s more than a precious stone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2887,'It is _the_ precious stone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2888,'Not the Countess of Morcar’s blue carbuncle! I ejaculated.  Precisely so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2889,'I ought to know its size and shape, seeing that I have read the advertisement about it in _The Times_ every day lately.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2890,'It is absolutely unique, and its value can only be conjectured, but the reward offered of £1000 is certainly not within a twentieth part of the market price.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2891,'A thousand pounds! Great Lord of mercy! The commissionaire plumped down into a chair, and stared from one to the other of us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2892,'That is the reward, and I have reason to know that there are sentimental considerations in the background which would induce the countess to part with half her fortune if she could but recover the gem.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2893,'It was lost, if I remember aright, at the ‘Hotel Cosmopolitan,’ I remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2894,'Precisely so, on December 22d, just five days ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2895,'John Horner, a plumber, was accused of having abstracted it from the lady’s jewel-case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2896,'The evidence against him was so strong that the case has been referred to the Assizes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2897,'I have some account of the matter here, I believe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2898,'He rummaged amid his newspapers, glancing over the dates, until at last he smoothed one out, doubled it over, and read the following paragraph:  ‘Hotel Cosmopolitan Jewel Robbery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2899,'John Horner, 26, plumber, was brought up upon the charge of having upon the 22d inst.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2900,'abstracted from the jewel-case of the Countess of Morcar the valuable gem known as the blue carbuncle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2901,'James Ryder, upper-attendant at the hotel, gave his evidence to the effect that he had shown Horner up to the dressing-room of the Countess of Morcar upon the day of the robbery, in order that he might solder the second bar of the grate, which was loose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2902,'He had remained with Horner some little time, but had finally been called away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2903,'On returning, he found that Horner had disappeared, that the bureau had been forced open, and that the small morocco casket in which, as it afterwards transpired, the countess was accustomed to keep her jewel, was lying empty upon the dressing-table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2904,'Ryder instantly gave the alarm, and Horner was arrested the same evening; but the stone could not be found either upon his person or in his rooms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2905,'Catherine Cusack, maid to the countess, deposed to having heard Ryder’s cry of dismay on discovering the robbery, and to having rushed into the room, where she found matters as described by the last witness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2906,'Inspector Bradstreet, B division, gave evidence as to the arrest of Horner, who struggled frantically, and protested his innocence in the strongest terms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2907,'Evidence of a previous conviction for robbery having been given against the prisoner, the magistrate refused to deal summarily with the offence, but referred it to the Assizes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2908,'Horner, who had shown signs of intense emotion during the proceedings, fainted away at the conclusion, and was carried out of court.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2909,'’  Hum! So much for the police-court, said Holmes, thoughtfully, tossing aside the paper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2910,'The question for us now to solve is the sequence of events leading from a rifled jewel-case at one end to the crop of a goose in Tottenham Court Road at the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2911,'You see, Watson, our little deductions have suddenly assumed a much more important and less innocent aspect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2912,'Here is the stone; the stone came from the goose, and the goose came from Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2913,'Henry Baker, the gentleman with the bad hat and all the other characteristics with which I have bored you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2914,'So now we must set ourselves very seriously to finding this gentleman, and ascertaining what part he has played in this little mystery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2915,'To do this, we must try the simplest means first, and these lie undoubtedly in an advertisement in all the evening papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2916,'If this fails, I shall have recourse to other methods.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2917,'What will you say?  Give me a pencil and that slip of paper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2918,'Now, then: ‘Found at the corner of Goodge Street, a goose and a black felt hat. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2919,'Henry Baker can have the same by applying at 6.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2920,'30 this evening at 221B, Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2921,'’ That is clear and concise.  Very.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2922,'But will he see it?  Well, he is sure to keep an eye on the papers, since, to a poor man, the loss was a heavy one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2923,'He was clearly so scared by his mischance in breaking the window and by the approach of Peterson, that he thought of nothing but flight; but since then he must have bitterly regretted the impulse which caused him to drop his bird.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2924,'Then, again, the introduction of his name will cause him to see it, for every one who knows him will direct his attention to it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2925,'Here you are, Peterson, run down to the advertising agency, and have this put in the evening papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2926,'In which, sir?  Oh, in the _Globe_, _Star_, _Pall Mall_, _St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2927,'James’s_, _Evening News_, _Standard_, _Echo_, and any others that occur to you.  Very well, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2928,'And this stone?  Ah, yes, I shall keep the stone. Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2929,'And, I say, Peterson, just buy a goose on your way back, and leave it here with me, for we must have one to give to this gentleman in place of the one which your family is now devouring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2930,'When the commissionaire had gone, Holmes took up the stone and held it against the light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2931,'It’s a bonny thing, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2932,'Just see how it glints and sparkles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2933,'Of course it is a nucleus and focus of crime. Every good stone is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2934,'They are the devil’s pet baits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2935,'In the larger and older jewels every facet may stand for a bloody deed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2936,'This stone is not yet twenty years old.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2937,'It was found in the banks of the Amoy River in Southern China, and is remarkable in having every characteristic of the carbuncle, save that it is blue in shade, instead of ruby red.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2938,'In spite of its youth, it has already a sinister history.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2939,'There have been two murders, a vitriol-throwing, a suicide, and several robberies brought about for the sake of this forty-grain weight of crystallized charcoal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2940,'Who would think that so pretty a toy would be a purveyor to the gallows and the prison? I’ll lock it up in my strong box now, and drop a line to the countess to say that we have it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2941,'Do you think that this man Horner is innocent?  I cannot tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2942,'Well, then, do you imagine that this other one, Henry Baker, had anything to do with the matter?  It is, I think, much more likely that Henry Baker is an absolutely innocent man, who had no idea that the bird which he was carrying was of considerably more value than if it were made of solid gold.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2943,'That, however, I shall determine by a very simple test, if we have an answer to our advertisement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2944,'And you can do nothing until then?  Nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2945,'In that case I shall continue my professional round.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2946,'But I shall come back in the evening at the hour you have mentioned, for I should like to see the solution of so tangled a business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2947,'Very glad to see you. I dine at seven.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2948,'There is a woodcock, I believe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2949,'By-the-way, in view of recent occurrences, perhaps I ought to ask Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2950,'Hudson to examine its crop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2951,'I had been delayed at a case, and it was a little after half-past six when I found myself in Baker Street once more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2952,'As I approached the house I saw a tall man in a Scotch bonnet with a coat which was buttoned up to his chin, waiting outside in the bright semicircle which was thrown from the fanlight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2953,'Just as I arrived, the door was opened, and we were shown up together to Holmes’s room.  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2954,'Henry Baker, I believe, said he, rising from his arm-chair, and greeting his visitor with the easy air of geniality which he could so readily assume.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2955,'Pray take this chair by the fire, Mr. Baker.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2956,'It is a cold night, and I observe that your circulation is more adapted for summer than for winter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2957,'Ah, Watson, you have just come at the right time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2958,'Is that your hat, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2959,'Baker?  Yes, sir, that is undoubtedly my hat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2960,'He was a large man, with rounded shoulders, a massive head, and a broad, intelligent face, sloping down to a pointed beard of grizzled brown.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2961,'A touch of red in nose and cheeks, with a slight tremor of his extended hand, recalled Holmes’s surmise as to his habits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2962,'His rusty black frock-coat was buttoned right up in front, with the collar turned up, and his lank wrists protruded from his sleeves without a sign of cuff or shirt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2963,'He spoke in a slow staccato fashion, choosing his words with care, and gave the impression generally of a man of learning and letters who had had ill-usage at the hands of fortune.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2964,'We have retained these things for some days, said Holmes, because we expected to see an advertisement from you giving your address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2965,'I am at a loss to know now why you did not advertise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2966,'Our visitor gave a rather shamefaced laugh.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2967,'Shillings have not been so plentiful with me as they once were, he remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2968,'I had no doubt that the gang of roughs who assaulted me had carried off both my hat and the bird.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2969,'I did not care to spend more money in a hopeless attempt at recovering them.  Very naturally.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2970,'By-the-way, about the bird, we were compelled to eat it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2971,'To eat it! Our visitor half rose from his chair in his excitement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2972,'Yes, it would have been of no use to any one had we not done so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2973,'But I presume that this other goose upon the sideboard, which is about the same weight and perfectly fresh, will answer your purpose equally well?  Oh, certainly, certainly; answered Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2974,'Baker, with a sigh of relief.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2975,'Of course, we still have the feathers, legs, crop, and so on of your own bird, so if you wish—  The man burst into a hearty laugh.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2976,'They might be useful to me as relics of my adventure, said he, but beyond that I can hardly see what use the _disjecta membra_ of my late acquaintance are going to be to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2977,'No, sir, I think that, with your permission, I will confine my attentions to the excellent bird which I perceive upon the sideboard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2978,'Sherlock Holmes glanced sharply across at me with a slight shrug of his shoulders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2979,'There is your hat, then, and there your bird, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2980,'By-the-way, would it bore you to tell me where you got the other one from? I am somewhat of a fowl fancier, and I have seldom seen a better grown goose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2981,'Certainly, sir, said Baker, who had risen and tucked his newly-gained property under his arm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2982,'There are a few of us who frequent the ‘Alpha Inn,’ near the Museum—we are to be found in the Museum itself during the day, you understand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2983,'This year our good host, Windigate by name, instituted a goose club, by which, on consideration of some few pence every week, we were each to receive a bird at Christmas.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2984,'My pence were duly paid, and the rest is familiar to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2985,'I am much indebted to you, sir, for a Scotch bonnet is fitted neither to my years nor my gravity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2986,'With a comical pomposity of manner he bowed solemnly to both of us and strode off upon his way.  So much for Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2987,'Henry Baker, said Holmes, when he had closed the door behind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2988,'It is quite certain that he knows nothing whatever about the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2989,'Are you hungry, Watson?  Not particularly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2990,'Then I suggest that we turn our dinner into a supper, and follow up this clew while it is still hot.  By all means.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2991,'It was a bitter night, so we drew on our ulsters and wrapped cravats about our throats.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2992,'Outside, the stars were shining coldly in a cloudless sky, and the breath of the passers-by blew out into smoke like so many pistol shots.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2993,'Our footfalls rang out crisply and loudly as we swung through the Doctors’ quarter, Wimpole Street, Harley Street, and so through Wigmore Street into Oxford Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2994,'In a quarter of an hour we were in Bloomsbury at the Alpha Inn, which is a small public-house at the corner of one of the streets which runs down into Holborn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2995,'Holmes pushed open the door of the private bar, and ordered two glasses of beer from the ruddy-faced, white-aproned landlord.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2996,'Your beer should be excellent if it is as good as your geese, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2997,'My geese! The man seemed surprised.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2998,'I was speaking only half an hour ago to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(2999,'Henry Baker, who was a member of your goose club.  Ah! yes, I see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3000,'But you see, sir, them’s not _our_ geese.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3001,'Indeed! Whose, then?  Well, I got the two dozen from a salesman in Covent Garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3002,'Indeed? I know some of them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3003,'Which was it?  Breckinridge is his name.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3004,'Ah! I don’t know him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3005,'Well, here’s your good health, landlord, and prosperity to your house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3006,'Good-night?  Now for Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3007,'Breckinridge, he continued, buttoning up his coat, as we came out into the frosty air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3008,'Remember, Watson, that though we have so homely a thing as a goose at one end of this chain, we have at the other a man who will certainly get seven years’ penal servitude unless we can establish his innocence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3009,'It is possible that our inquiry may but confirm his guilt; but, in any case, we have a line of investigation which has been missed by the police, and which a singular chance has placed in our hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3010,'Let us follow it out to the bitter end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3011,'Faces to the south, then, and quick march!  We passed across Holborn, down Endell Street, and so through a zigzag of slums to Covent Garden Market.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3012,'One of the largest stalls bore the name of Breckinridge upon it, and the proprietor, a horsey-looking man, with a sharp face and trim side-whiskers, was helping a boy to put up the shutters.  Good-evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3013,'It’s a cold night, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3014,'The salesman nodded, and shot a questioning glance at my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3015,'Sold out of geese, I see, continued Holmes, pointing at the bare slabs of marble.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3016,'Let you have 500 to-morrow morning.  That’s no good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3017,'Well, there are some on the stall with the gas-flare.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3018,'Ah, but I was recommended to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3019,'Who by?  The landlord of the ‘Alpha.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3020,'’  Oh, yes; I sent him a couple of dozen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3021,'Fine birds they were, too.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3022,'Now where did you get them from?  To my surprise the question provoked a burst of anger from the salesman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3023,'Now, then, mister, said he, with his head cocked and his arms akimbo, what are you driving at? Let’s have it straight, now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3024,'It is straight enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3025,'I should like to know who sold you the geese which you supplied to the ‘Alpha.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3026,'’  Well, then, I sha’n’t tell you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3027,'So now!  Oh, it is a matter of no importance; but I don’t know why you should be so warm over such a trifle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3028,'Warm! You’d be as warm, maybe, if you were as pestered as I am.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3029,'When I pay good money for a good article there should be an end of the business; but it’s ‘Where are the geese?’ and ‘Who did you sell the geese to?’ and ‘What will you take for the geese?’ One would think they were the only geese in the world, to hear the fuss that is made over them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3030,'Well, I have no connection with any other people who have been making inquiries, said Holmes, carelessly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3031,'If you won’t tell us the bet is off, that is all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3032,'But I’m always ready to back my opinion on a matter of fowls, and I have a fiver on it that the bird I ate is country bred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3033,'Well, then, you’ve lost your fiver, for it’s town bred, snapped the salesman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3034,'It’s nothing of the kind.  I say it is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3035,'I don’t believe it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3036,'D’you think you know more about fowls than I, who have handled them ever since I was a nipper? I tell you, all those birds that went to the ‘Alpha’ were town bred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3037,'You’ll never persuade me to believe that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3038,'Will you bet, then?  It’s merely taking your money, for I know that I am right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3039,'But I’ll have a sovereign on with you, just to teach you not to be obstinate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3040,'The salesman chuckled grimly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3041,'Bring me the books, Bill, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3042,'The small boy brought round a small thin volume and a great greasy-backed one, laying them out together beneath the hanging lamp.  Now then, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3043,'Cocksure, said the salesman, I thought that I was out of geese, but before I finish you’ll find that there is still one left in my shop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3044,'You see this little book?  Well?  That’s the list of the folk from whom I buy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3045,'D’you see? Well, then, here on this page are the country folk, and the numbers after their names are where their accounts are in the big ledger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3046,'Now, then! You see this other page in red ink? Well, that is a list of my town suppliers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3047,'Now, look at that third name.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3048,'Just read it out to me.  Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3049,'Oakshott, 117, Brixton Road—249, read Holmes.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3050,'Now turn that up in the ledger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3051,'Holmes turned to the page indicated. Here you are, ‘Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3052,'Oakshott, 117, Brixton Road, egg and poultry supplier.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3053,'’  Now, then, what’s the last entry?  ‘December 22.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3054,'Twenty-four geese at 7_s._ 6_d._’  Quite so. There you are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3055,'And underneath?  ‘Sold to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3056,'Windigate of the ‘Alpha,’ at 12_s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3057,'_’  What have you to say now?  Sherlock Holmes looked deeply chagrined.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3058,'He drew a sovereign from his pocket and threw it down upon the slab, turning away with the air of a man whose disgust is too deep for words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3059,'A few yards off he stopped under a lamp-post, and laughed in the hearty, noiseless fashion which was peculiar to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3060,'When you see a man with whiskers of that cut and the ‘pink ‘un’ protruding out of his pocket, you can always draw him by a bet, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3061,'I dare say that if I had put £100 down in front of him, that man would not have given me such complete information as was drawn from him by the idea that he was doing me on a wager.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3062,'Well, Watson, we are, I fancy, nearing the end of our quest, and the only point which remains to be determined is whether we should go on to this Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3063,'Oakshott to-night, or whether we should reserve it for to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3064,'It is clear from what that surly fellow said that there are others besides ourselves who are anxious about the matter, and I should—  His remarks were suddenly cut short by a loud hubbub which broke out from the stall which we had just left.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3065,'Turning round we saw a little rat-faced fellow standing in the centre of the circle of yellow light which was thrown by the swinging lamp, while Breckinridge the salesman, framed in the door of his stall, was shaking his fists fiercely at the cringing figure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3066,'I’ve had enough of you and your geese, he shouted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3067,'I wish you were all at the devil together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3068,'If you come pestering me any more with your silly talk I’ll set the dog at you. You bring Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3069,'Oakshott here and I’ll answer her, but what have you to do with it? Did I buy the geese off you?  No; but one of them was mine all the same, whined the little man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3070,'Well, then, ask Mrs. Oakshott for it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3071,'She told me to ask you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3072,'Well, you can ask the King of Proosia, for all I care.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3073,'I’ve had enough of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3074,'Get out of this! He rushed fiercely forward, and the inquirer flitted away into the darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3075,'Ha! this may save us a visit to Brixton Road, whispered Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3076,'Come with me, and we will see what is to be made of this fellow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3077,'Striding through the scattered knots of people who lounged round the flaring stalls, my companion speedily overtook the little man and touched him upon the shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3078,'He sprang round, and I could see in the gaslight that every vestige of color had been driven from his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3079,'Who are you, then? What do you want? he asked, in a quavering voice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3080,'You will excuse me, said Holmes, blandly, but I could not help overhearing the questions which you put to the salesman just now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3081,'I think that I could be of assistance to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3082,'You? Who are you? How could you know anything of the matter?  My name is Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3083,'It is my business to know what other people don’t know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3084,'But you can know nothing of this?  Excuse me, I know everything of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3085,'You are endeavoring to trace some geese which were sold by Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3086,'Oakshott, of Brixton Road, to a salesman named Breckinridge, by him in turn to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3087,'Windigate, of the ‘Alpha,’ and by him to his club, of which Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3088,'Henry Baker is a member.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3089,'Oh, sir, you are the very man whom I have longed to meet, cried the little fellow, with outstretched hands and quivering fingers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3090,'I can hardly explain to you how interested I am in this matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3091,'Sherlock Holmes hailed a four-wheeler which was passing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3092,'In that case we had better discuss it in a cosey room rather than in this windswept market-place, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3093,'But pray tell me, before we go farther, who it is that I have the pleasure of assisting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3094,'The man hesitated for an instant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3095,'My name is John Robinson, he answered, with a sidelong glance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3096,'No, no; the real name, said Holmes, sweetly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3097,'It is always awkward doing business with an _alias_.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3098,'A flush sprang to the white cheeks of the stranger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3099,'Well, then, said he, my real name is James Ryder.  Precisely so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3100,'Head attendant at the ‘Hotel Cosmopolitan.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3101,'’ Pray step into the cab, and I shall soon be able to tell you everything which you would wish to know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3102,'The little man stood glancing from one to the other of us with half-frightened, half-hopeful eyes, as one who is not sure whether he is on the verge of a windfall or of a catastrophe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3103,'Then he stepped into the cab, and in half an hour we were back in the sitting-room at Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3104,'Nothing had been said during our drive, but the high, thin breathing of our new companion, and the claspings and unclaspings of his hands, spoke of the nervous tension within him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3105,'Here we are! said Holmes, cheerily, as we filed into the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3106,'The fire looks very seasonable in this weather. You look cold, Mr. Ryder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3107,'Pray take the basket-chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3108,'I will just put on my slippers before we settle this little matter of yours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3109,'Now, then! You want to know what became of those geese?  Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3110,'Or rather, I fancy, of that goose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3111,'It was one bird, I imagine, in which you were interested—white, with a black bar across the tail.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3112,'Ryder quivered with emotion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3113,'Oh, sir, he cried, can you tell me where it went to?  It came here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3114,'Here?  Yes, and a most remarkable bird it proved.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3115,'I don’t wonder that you should take an interest in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3116,'It laid an egg after it was dead—the bonniest, brightest little blue egg that ever was seen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3117,'I have it here in my museum.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3118,'Our visitor staggered to his feet and clutched the mantel-piece with his right hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3119,'Holmes unlocked his strong-box, and held up the blue carbuncle, which shone out like a star, with a cold, brilliant, many-pointed radiance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3120,'Ryder stood glaring with a drawn face, uncertain whether to claim or to disown it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3121,'The game’s up, Ryder, said Holmes, quietly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3122,'Hold up, man, or you’ll be into the fire! Give him an arm back into his chair, Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3123,'He’s not got blood enough to go in for felony with impunity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3124,'Give him a dash of brandy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3125,'So! Now he looks a little more human.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3126,'What a shrimp it is, to be sure!  For a moment he had staggered and nearly fallen, but the brandy brought a tinge of color into his cheeks, and he sat staring with frightened eyes at his accuser.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3127,'I have almost every link in my hands, and all the proofs which I could possibly need, so there is little which you need tell me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3128,'Still, that little may as well be cleared up to make the case complete.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3129,'You had heard, Ryder, of this blue stone of the Countess of Morcar’s?  It was Catherine Cusack who told me of it, said he, in a crackling voice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3130,'I see—her ladyship’s waiting-maid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3131,'Well, the temptation of sudden wealth so easily acquired was too much for you, as it has been for better men before you; but you were not very scrupulous in the means you used.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3132,'It seems to me, Ryder, that there is the making of a very pretty villain in you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3133,'You knew that this man Horner, the plumber, had been concerned in some such matter before, and that suspicion would rest the more readily upon him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3134,'What did you do, then? You made some small job in my lady’s room—you and your confederate Cusack—and you managed that he should be the man sent for.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3135,'Then, when he had left, you rifled the jewel-case, raised the alarm, and had this unfortunate man arrested.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3136,'You then—  Ryder threw himself down suddenly upon the rug and clutched at my companion’s knees.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3137,'For God’s sake, have mercy! he shrieked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3138,'Think of my father! of my mother! It would break their hearts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3139,'I never went wrong before! I never will again. I swear it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3140,'I’ll swear it on a Bible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3141,'Oh, don’t bring it into court! For Christ’s sake, don’t!  Get back into your chair! said Holmes, sternly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3142,'It is very well to cringe and crawl now, but you thought little enough of this poor Horner in the dock for a crime of which he knew nothing.  I will fly, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3143,'I will leave the country, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3144,'Then the charge against him will break down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3145,'Hum! We will talk about that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3146,'And now let us hear a true account of the next act.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3147,'How came the stone into the goose, and how came the goose into the open market? Tell us the truth, for there lies your only hope of safety.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3148,'[Illustration: ‘HAVE MERCY!’ HE SHRIEKED]  Ryder passed his tongue over his parched lips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3149,'I will tell you it just as it happened, sir, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3150,'When Horner had been arrested, it seemed to me that it would be best for me to get away with the stone at once, for I did not know at what moment the police might not take it into their heads to search me and my room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3151,'There was no place about the hotel where it would be safe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3152,'I went out, as if on some commission, and I made for my sister’s house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3153,'She had married a man named Oakshott, and lived in Brixton Road, where she fattened fowls for the market.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3154,'All the way there every man I met seemed to me to be a policeman or a detective; and, for all that it was a cold night, the sweat was pouring down my face before I came to the Brixton Road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3155,'My sister asked me what was the matter, and why I was so pale; but I told her that I had been upset by the jewel robbery at the hotel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3156,'Then I went into the back yard and smoked a pipe, and wondered what it would be best to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3157,'I had a friend once called Maudsley, who went to the bad, and has just been serving his time in Pentonville.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3158,'One day he had met me, and fell into talk about the ways of thieves, and how they could get rid of what they stole.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3159,'I knew that he would be true to me, for I knew one or two things about him; so I made up my mind to go right on to Kilburn, where he lived, and take him into my confidence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3160,'He would show me how to turn the stone into money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3161,'But how to get to him in safety? I thought of the agonies I had gone through in coming from the hotel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3162,'I might at any moment be seized and searched, and there would be the stone in my waistcoat pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3163,'I was leaning against the wall at the time, and looking at the geese which were waddling about round my feet, and suddenly an idea came into my head which showed me how I could beat the best detective that ever lived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3164,'My sister had told me some weeks before that I might have the pick of her geese for a Christmas present, and I knew that she was always as good as her word.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3165,'I would take my goose now, and in it I would carry my stone to Kilburn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3166,'There was a little shed in the yard, and behind this I drove one of the birds—a fine big one, white, with a barred tail.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3167,'I caught it, and, prying its bill open, I thrust the stone down its throat as far as my finger could reach.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3168,'The bird gave a gulp, and I felt the stone pass along its gullet and down into its crop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3169,'But the creature flapped and struggled, and out came my sister to know what was the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3170,'As I turned to speak to her the brute broke loose and fluttered off among the others.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3171,'‘Whatever were you doing with that bird, Jem?’ says she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3172,'‘Well,’ said I, ‘you said you’d give me one for Christmas, and I was feeling which was the fattest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3173,'’  ‘Oh,’ says she, ‘we’ve set yours aside for you—Jem’s bird, we call it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3174,'It’s the big white one over yonder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3175,'There’s twenty-six of them, which makes one for you, and one for us, and two dozen for the market.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3176,'’  ‘Thank you, Maggie,’ says I; ‘but if it is all the same to you, I’d rather have that one I was handling just now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3177,'’  ‘The other is a good three pound heavier,’ said she, ‘and we fattened it expressly for you.’  ‘Never mind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3178,'I’ll have the other, and I’ll take it now,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3179,'‘Oh, just as you like,’ said she, a little huffed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3180,'‘Which is it you want, then?’  ‘That white one with the barred tail, right in the middle of the flock.’  ‘Oh, very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3181,'Kill it and take it with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3182,'’  Well, I did what she said, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3183,'Holmes, and I carried the bird all the way to Kilburn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3184,'I told my pal what I had done, for he was a man that it was easy to tell a thing like that to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3185,'He laughed until he choked, and we got a knife and opened the goose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3186,'My heart turned to water, for there was no sign of the stone, and I knew that some terrible mistake had occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3187,'I left the bird, rushed back to my sister’s, and hurried into the back yard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3188,'There was not a bird to be seen there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3189,'‘Where are they all, Maggie?’ I cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3190,'‘Gone to the dealer’s, Jem.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3191,'’  ‘Which dealer’s?’  ‘Breckinridge, of Covent Garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3192,'’  ‘But was there another with a barred tail?’ I asked, ‘the same as the one I chose?’  ‘Yes, Jem; there were two barred-tailed ones, and I could never tell them apart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3193,'’  Well, then, of course I saw it all, and I ran off as hard as my feet would carry me to this man Breckinridge; but he had sold the lot at once, and not one word would he tell me as to where they had gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3194,'You heard him yourselves to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3195,'Well, he has always answered me like that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3196,'My sister thinks that I am going mad.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3197,'Sometimes I think that I am myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3198,'And now—and now I am myself a branded thief, without ever having touched the wealth for which I sold my character.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3199,'God help me! God help me! He burst into convulsive sobbing, with his face buried in his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3200,'There was a long silence, broken only by his heavy breathing, and by the measured tapping of Sherlock Holmes’s finger-tips upon the edge of the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3201,'Then my friend rose and threw open the door.  Get out! said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3202,'What, sir! Oh, heaven bless you!  No more words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3203,'Get out!  And no more words were needed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3204,'There was a rush, a clatter upon the stairs, the bang of a door, and the crisp rattle of running footfalls from the street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3205,'After all, Watson, said Holmes, reaching up his hand for his clay pipe, I am not retained by the police to supply their deficiencies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3206,'If Horner were in danger it would be another thing; but this fellow will not appear against him, and the case must collapse.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3207,'I suppose that I am commuting a felony, but it is just possible that I am saving a soul.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3208,'This fellow will not go wrong again; he is too terribly frightened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3209,'Send him to jail now, and you make him a jail-bird for life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3210,'Besides, it is the season of forgiveness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3211,'Chance has put in our way a most singular and whimsical problem, and its solution is its own reward.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3212,'If you will have the goodness to touch the bell, doctor, we will begin another investigation, in which, also, a bird will be the chief feature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3213,'Adventure VIII  THE ADVENTURE OF THE SPECKLED BAND   On glancing over my notes of the seventy odd cases in which I have during the last eight years studied the methods of my friend Sherlock Holmes, I find many tragic, some comic, a large number merely strange, but none commonplace; for, working as he did rather for the love of his art than for the acquirement of wealth, he refused to associate himself with any investigation which did not tend towards the unusual, and even the fantastic.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3214,'Of all these varied cases, however, I cannot recall any which presented more singular features than that which was associated with the well-known Surrey family of the Roylotts of Stoke Moran.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3215,'The events in question occurred in the early days of my association with Holmes, when we were sharing rooms as bachelors in Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3216,'It is possible that I might have placed them upon record before, but a promise of secrecy was made at the time, from which I have only been freed during the last month by the untimely death of the lady to whom the pledge was given.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3217,'It is perhaps as well that the facts should now come to light, for I have reasons to know that there are wide-spread rumors as to the death of Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3218,'Grimesby Roylott which tend to make the matter even more terrible than the truth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3219,'It was early in April in the year ’83 that I woke one morning to find Sherlock Holmes standing, fully dressed, by the side of my bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3220,'He was a late riser as a rule, and as the clock on the mantel-piece showed me that it was only a quarter past seven, I blinked up at him in some surprise, and perhaps just a little resentment, for I was myself regular in my habits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3221,'Very sorry to knock you up, Watson, said he, but it’s the common lot this morning. Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3222,'Hudson has been knocked up, she retorted upon me, and I on you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3223,'What is it, then—a fire?  No; a client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3224,'It seems that a young lady has arrived in a considerable state of excitement, who insists upon seeing me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3225,'She is waiting now in the sitting-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3226,'Now, when young ladies wander about the metropolis at this hour of the morning, and knock sleepy people up out of their beds, I presume that it is something very pressing which they have to communicate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3227,'Should it prove to be an interesting case, you would, I am sure, wish to follow it from the outset.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3228,'I thought, at any rate, that I should call you and give you the chance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3229,'My dear fellow, I would not miss it for anything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3230,'I had no keener pleasure than in following Holmes in his professional investigations, and in admiring the rapid deductions, as swift as intuitions, and yet always founded on a logical basis, with which he unravelled the problems which were submitted to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3231,'I rapidly threw on my clothes, and was ready in a few minutes to accompany my friend down to the sitting-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3232,'A lady dressed in black and heavily veiled, who had been sitting in the window, rose as we entered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3233,'Good-morning, madam, said Holmes, cheerily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3234,'My name is Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3235,'This is my intimate friend and associate, Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3236,'Watson, before whom you can speak as freely as before myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3237,'Ha! I am glad to see that Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3238,'Hudson has had the good sense to light the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3239,'Pray draw up to it, and I shall order you a cup of hot coffee, for I observe that you are shivering.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3240,'It is not cold which makes me shiver, said the woman, in a low voice, changing her seat as requested.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3241,'What, then?  It is fear, Mr. Holmes. It is terror.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3242,'She raised her veil as she spoke, and we could see that she was indeed in a pitiable state of agitation, her face all drawn and gray, with restless, frightened eyes, like those of some hunted animal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3243,'Her features and figure were those of a woman of thirty, but her hair was shot with premature gray, and her expression was weary and haggard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3244,'Sherlock Holmes ran her over with one of his quick, all-comprehensive glances.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3245,'You must not fear, said he, soothingly, bending forward and patting her forearm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3246,'We shall soon set matters right, I have no doubt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3247,'You have come in by train this morning, I see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3248,'You know me, then?  No, but I observe the second half of a return ticket in the palm of your left glove.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3249,'You must have started early, and yet you had a good drive in a dog-cart, along heavy roads, before you reached the station.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3250,'The lady gave a violent start, and stared in bewilderment at my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3251,'There is no mystery, my dear madam, said he, smiling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3252,'The left arm of your jacket is spattered with mud in no less than seven places.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3253,'The marks are perfectly fresh.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3254,'There is no vehicle save a dog-cart which throws up mud in that way, and then only when you sit on the left-hand side of the driver.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3255,'Whatever your reasons may be, you are perfectly correct, said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3256,'I started from home before six, reached Leatherhead at twenty past, and came in by the first train to Waterloo.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3257,'Sir, I can stand this strain no longer; I shall go mad if it continues.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3258,'I have no one to turn to—none, save only one, who cares for me, and he, poor fellow, can be of little aid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3259,'I have heard of you, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3260,'Holmes; I have heard of you from Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3261,'Farintosh, whom you helped in the hour of her sore need.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3262,'It was from her that I had your address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3263,'Oh, sir, do you not think that you could help me, too, and at least throw a little light through the dense darkness which surrounds me? At present it is out of my power to reward you for your services, but in a month or six weeks I shall be married, with the control of my own income, and then at least you shall not find me ungrateful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3264,'Holmes turned to his desk, and unlocking it, drew out a small case-book, which he consulted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3265,'Farintosh, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3266,'Ah yes, I recall the case; it was concerned with an opal tiara.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3267,'I think it was before your time, Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3268,'I can only say, madam, that I shall be happy to devote the same care to your case as I did to that of your friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3269,'As to reward, my profession is its own reward; but you are at liberty to defray whatever expenses I may be put to, at the time which suits you best.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3270,'And now I beg that you will lay before us everything that may help us in forming an opinion upon the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3271,'Alas! replied our visitor, the very horror of my situation lies in the fact that my fears are so vague, and my suspicions depend so entirely upon small points, which might seem trivial to another, that even he to whom of all others I have a right to look for help and advice looks upon all that I tell him about it as the fancies of a nervous woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3272,'He does not say so, but I can read it from his soothing answers and averted eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3273,'But I have heard, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3274,'Holmes, that you can see deeply into the manifold wickedness of the human heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3275,'You may advise me how to walk amid the dangers which encompass me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3276,'I am all attention, madam.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3277,'My name is Helen Stoner, and I am living with my step-father, who is the last survivor of one of the oldest Saxon families in England, the Roylotts of Stoke Moran, on the western border of Surrey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3278,'Holmes nodded his head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3279,'The name is familiar to me, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3280,'The family was at one time among the richest in England, and the estates extended over the borders into Berkshire in the north, and Hampshire in the west.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3281,'In the last century, however, four successive heirs were of a dissolute and wasteful disposition, and the family ruin was eventually completed by a gambler in the days of the Regency.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3282,'Nothing was left save a few acres of ground, and the two-hundred-year-old house, which is itself crushed under a heavy mortgage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3283,'The last squire dragged out his existence there, living the horrible life of an aristocratic pauper; but his only son, my step-father, seeing that he must adapt himself to the new conditions, obtained an advance from a relative, which enabled him to take a medical degree, and went out to Calcutta, where, by his professional skill and his force of character, he established a large practice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3284,'In a fit of anger, however, caused by some robberies which had been perpetrated in the house, he beat his native butler to death, and narrowly escaped a capital sentence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3285,'As it was, he suffered a long term of imprisonment, and afterwards returned to England a morose and disappointed man.  When Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3286,'Roylott was in India he married my mother, Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3287,'Stoner, the young widow of Major-general Stoner, of the Bengal Artillery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3288,'My sister Julia and I were twins, and we were only two years old at the time of my mother’s re-marriage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3289,'She had a considerable sum of money—not less than £1000 a year—and this she bequeathed to Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3290,'Roylott entirely while we resided with him, with a provision that a certain annual sum should be allowed to each of us in the event of our marriage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3291,'Shortly after our return to England my mother died—she was killed eight years ago in a railway accident near Crewe. Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3292,'Roylott then abandoned his attempts to establish himself in practice in London, and took us to live with him in the old ancestral house at Stoke Moran.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3293,'The money which my mother had left was enough for all our wants, and there seemed to be no obstacle to our happiness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3294,'But a terrible change came over our step-father about this time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3295,'Instead of making friends and exchanging visits with our neighbors, who had at first been overjoyed to see a Roylott of Stoke Moran back in the old family seat, he shut himself up in his house, and seldom came out save to indulge in ferocious quarrels with whoever might cross his path.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3296,'Violence of temper approaching to mania has been hereditary in the men of the family, and in my step-father’s case it had, I believe, been intensified by his long residence in the tropics.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3297,'A series of disgraceful brawls took place, two of which ended in the police-court, until at last he became the terror of the village, and the folks would fly at his approach, for he is a man of immense strength, and absolutely uncontrollable in his anger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3298,'Last week he hurled the local blacksmith over a parapet into a stream, and it was only by paying over all the money which I could gather together that I was able to avert another public exposure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3299,'He had no friends at all save the wandering gypsies, and he would give these vagabonds leave to encamp upon the few acres of bramble-covered land which represent the family estate, and would accept in return the hospitality of their tents, wandering away with them sometimes for weeks on end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3300,'He has a passion also for Indian animals, which are sent over to him by a correspondent, and he has at this moment a cheetah and a baboon, which wander freely over his grounds, and are feared by the villagers almost as much as their master.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3301,'You can imagine from what I say that my poor sister Julia and I had no great pleasure in our lives.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3302,'No servant would stay with us, and for a long time we did all the work of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3303,'She was but thirty at the time of her death, and yet her hair had already begun to whiten, even as mine has.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3304,'Your sister is dead, then?  She died just two years ago, and it is of her death that I wish to speak to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3305,'You can understand that, living the life which I have described, we were little likely to see anyone of our own age and position.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3306,'We had, however, an aunt, my mother’s maiden sister, Miss Honoria Westphail, who lives near Harrow, and we were occasionally allowed to pay short visits at this lady’s house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3307,'Julia went there at Christmas two years ago, and met there a half-pay major of marines, to whom she became engaged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3308,'My step-father learned of the engagement when my sister returned, and offered no objection to the marriage; but within a fortnight of the day which had been fixed for the wedding, the terrible event occurred which has deprived me of my only companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3309,'Sherlock Holmes had been leaning back in his chair with his eyes closed and his head sunk in a cushion, but he half opened his lids now and glanced across at his visitor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3310,'Pray be precise as to details, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3311,'It is easy for me to be so, for every event of that dreadful time is seared into my memory.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3312,'The manor-house is, as I have already said, very old, and only one wing is now inhabited.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3313,'The bedrooms in this wing are on the ground floor, the sitting-rooms being in the central block of the buildings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3314,'Of these bedrooms the first is Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3315,'Roylott’s, the second my sister’s, and the third my own.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3316,'There is no communication between them, but they all open out into the same corridor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3317,'Do I make myself plain?  Perfectly so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3318,'The windows of the three rooms open out upon the lawn. That fatal night Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3319,'Roylott had gone to his room early, though we knew that he had not retired to rest, for my sister was troubled by the smell of the strong Indian cigars which it was his custom to smoke.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3320,'She left her room, therefore, and came into mine, where she sat for some time, chatting about her approaching wedding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3321,'At eleven o’clock she rose to leave me but she paused at the door and looked back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3322,'‘Tell me, Helen,’ said she, ‘have you ever heard any one whistle in the dead of the night?’  ‘Never,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3323,'‘I suppose that you could not possibly whistle, yourself, in your sleep?’  ‘Certainly not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3324,'But why?’  ‘Because during the last few nights I have always, about three in the morning, heard a low, clear whistle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3325,'I am a light sleeper, and it has awakened me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3326,'I cannot tell where it came from—perhaps from the next room, perhaps from the lawn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3327,'I thought that I would just ask you whether you had heard it.’  ‘No, I have not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3328,'It must be those wretched gypsies in the plantation.’  ‘Very likely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3329,'And yet if it were on the lawn, I wonder that you did not hear it also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3330,'’  ‘Ah, but I sleep more heavily than you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3331,'’  ‘Well, it is of no great consequence, at any rate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3332,'’ She smiled back at me, closed my door, and a few moments later I heard her key turn in the lock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3333,'Indeed, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3334,'Was it your custom always to lock yourselves in at night?  Always.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3335,'And why?  I think that I mentioned to you that the doctor kept a cheetah and a baboon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3336,'We had no feeling of security unless our doors were locked.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3337,'Pray proceed with your statement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3338,'I could not sleep that night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3339,'A vague feeling of impending misfortune impressed me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3340,'My sister and I, you will recollect, were twins, and you know how subtle are the links which bind two souls which are so closely allied. It was a wild night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3341,'The wind was howling outside, and the rain was beating and splashing against the windows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3342,'Suddenly, amid all the hubbub of the gale, there burst forth the wild scream of a terrified woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3343,'I knew that it was my sister’s voice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3344,'I sprang from my bed, wrapped a shawl round me, and rushed into the corridor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3345,'As I opened my door I seemed to hear a low whistle, such as my sister described, and a few moments later a clanging sound, as if a mass of metal had fallen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3346,'As I ran down the passage, my sister’s door was unlocked, and revolved slowly upon its hinges.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3347,'I stared at it horror-stricken, not knowing what was about to issue from it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3348,'By the light of the corridor-lamp I saw my sister appear at the opening, her face blanched with terror, her hands groping for help, her whole figure swaying to and fro like that of a drunkard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3349,'I ran to her and threw my arms round her, but at that moment her knees seemed to give way and she fell to the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3350,'She writhed as one who is in terrible pain, and her limbs were dreadfully convulsed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3351,'At first I thought that she had not recognized me, but as I bent over her she suddenly shrieked out in a voice which I shall never forget, ‘Oh, my God! Helen! It was the band! The speckled band!’ There was something else which she would fain have said, and she stabbed with her finger into the air in the direction of the doctor’s room, but a fresh convulsion seized her and choked her words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3352,'I rushed out, calling loudly for my step-father, and I met him hastening from his room in his dressing-gown.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3353,'When he reached my sister’s side she was unconscious, and though he poured brandy down her throat and sent for medical aid from the village, all efforts were in vain, for she slowly sank and died without having recovered her consciousness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3354,'Such was the dreadful end of my beloved sister.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3355,'One moment, said Holmes; are you sure about this whistle and metallic sound? Could you swear to it?  That was what the county coroner asked me at the inquiry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3356,'It is my strong impression that I heard it, and yet, among the crash of the gale and the creaking of an old house, I may possibly have been deceived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3357,'Was your sister dressed?  No, she was in her night-dress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3358,'In her right hand was found the charred stump of a match, and in her left a matchbox.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3359,'Showing that she had struck a light and looked about her when the alarm took place. That is important.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3360,'And what conclusions did the coroner come to?  He investigated the case with great care, for Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3361,'Roylott’s conduct had long been notorious in the county, but he was unable to find any satisfactory cause of death.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3362,'My evidence showed that the door had been fastened upon the inner side, and the windows were blocked by old-fashioned shutters with broad iron bars, which were secured every night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3363,'The walls were carefully sounded, and were shown to be quite solid all round, and the flooring was also thoroughly examined, with the same result.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3364,'The chimney is wide, but is barred up by four large staples.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3365,'It is certain, therefore, that my sister was quite alone when she met her end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3366,'Besides, there were no marks of any violence upon her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3367,'How about poison?  The doctors examined her for it, but without success.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3368,'What do you think that this unfortunate lady died of, then?  It is my belief that she died of pure fear and nervous shock, though what it was that frightened her I cannot imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3369,'Were there gypsies in the plantation at the time?  Yes, there are nearly always some there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3370,'Ah, and what did you gather from this allusion to a band—a speckled band?  Sometimes I have thought that it was merely the wild talk of delirium, sometimes that it may have referred to some band of people, perhaps to these very gypsies in the plantation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3371,'I do not know whether the spotted handkerchiefs which so many of them wear over their heads might have suggested the strange adjective which she used.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3372,'Holmes shook his head like a man who is far from being satisfied.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3373,'These are very deep waters, said he; pray go on with your narrative.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3374,'Two years have passed since then, and my life has been until lately lonelier than ever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3375,'A month ago, however, a dear friend, whom I have known for many years, has done me the honor to ask my hand in marriage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3376,'His name is Armitage—Percy Armitage—the second son of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3377,'Armitage, of Crane Water, near Reading.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3378,'My step-father has offered no opposition to the match, and we are to be married in the course of the spring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3379,'Two days ago some repairs were started in the west wing of the building, and my bedroom wall has been pierced, so that I have had to move into the chamber in which my sister died, and to sleep in the very bed in which she slept.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3380,'Imagine, then, my thrill of terror when last night, as I lay awake, thinking over her terrible fate, I suddenly heard in the silence of the night the low whistle which had been the herald of her own death.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3381,'I sprang up and lit the lamp, but nothing was to be seen in the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3382,'I was too shaken to go to bed again, however, so I dressed, and as soon as it was daylight I slipped down, got a dog-cart at the ‘Crown Inn,’ which is opposite, and drove to Leatherhead, from whence I have come on this morning with the one object of seeing you and asking your advice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3383,'You have done wisely, said my friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3384,'But have you told me all?  Yes, all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3385,'Miss Roylott, you have not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3386,'You are screening your step-father.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3387,'Why, what do you mean?  For answer Holmes pushed back the frill of black lace which fringed the hand that lay upon our visitor’s knee.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3388,'Five little livid spots, the marks of four fingers and a thumb, were printed upon the white wrist.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3389,'You have been cruelly used, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3390,'The lady colored deeply and covered over her injured wrist.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3391,'He is a hard man, she said, and perhaps he hardly knows his own strength.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3392,'There was a long silence, during which Holmes leaned his chin upon his hands and stared into the crackling fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3393,'This is a very deep business, he said, at last.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3394,'There are a thousand details which I should desire to know before I decide upon our course of action.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3395,'Yet we have not a moment to lose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3396,'If we were to come to Stoke Moran to-day, would it be possible for us to see over these rooms without the knowledge of your step-father?  As it happens, he spoke of coming into town to-day upon some most important business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3397,'It is probable that he will be away all day, and that there would be nothing to disturb you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3398,'We have a house-keeper now, but she is old and foolish, and I could easily get her out of the way.  Excellent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3399,'You are not averse to this trip, Watson?  By no means.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3400,'Then we shall both come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3401,'What are you going to do yourself?  I have one or two things which I would wish to do now that I am in town.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3402,'But I shall return by the twelve o’clock train, so as to be there in time for your coming.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3403,'And you may expect us early in the afternoon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3404,'I have myself some small business matters to attend to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3405,'Will you not wait and breakfast?  No, I must go.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3406,'My heart is lightened already since I have confided my trouble to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3407,'I shall look forward to seeing you again this afternoon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3408,'She dropped her thick black veil over her face and glided from the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3409,'And what do you think of it all, Watson? asked Sherlock Holmes, leaning back in his chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3410,'It seems to me to be a most dark and sinister business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3411,'Dark enough and sinister enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3412,'Yet if the lady is correct in saying that the flooring and walls are sound, and that the door, window, and chimney are impassable, then her sister must have been undoubtedly alone when she met her mysterious end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3413,'What becomes, then, of these nocturnal whistles, and what of the very peculiar words of the dying woman?  I cannot think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3414,'When you combine the ideas of whistles at night, the presence of a band of gypsies who are on intimate terms with this old doctor, the fact that we have every reason to believe that the doctor has an interest in preventing his step-daughter’s marriage, the dying allusion to a band, and, finally, the fact that Miss Helen Stoner heard a metallic clang, which might have been caused by one of those metal bars which secured the shutters falling back into their place, I think that there is good ground to think that the mystery may be cleared along those lines.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3415,'But what, then, did the gypsies do?  I cannot imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3416,'I see many objections to any such theory.  And so do I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3417,'It is precisely for that reason that we are going to Stoke Moran this day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3418,'I want to see whether the objections are fatal, or if they may be explained away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3419,'But what in the name of the devil!  The ejaculation had been drawn from my companion by the fact that our door had been suddenly dashed open, and that a huge man had framed himself in the aperture.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3420,'His costume was a peculiar mixture of the professional and of the agricultural, having a black top-hat, a long frock-coat, and a pair of high gaiters, with a hunting-crop swinging in his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3421,'So tall was he that his hat actually brushed the cross bar of the doorway, and his breadth seemed to span it across from side to side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3422,'A large face, seared with a thousand wrinkles, burned yellow with the sun, and marked with every evil passion, was turned from one to the other of us, while his deep-set, bile-shot eyes, and his high, thin, fleshless nose, gave him somewhat the resemblance to a fierce old bird of prey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3423,'Which of you is Holmes? asked this apparition.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3424,'My name, sir; but you have the advantage of me, said my companion, quietly.  I am Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3425,'Grimesby Roylott, of Stoke Moran.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3426,'Indeed, doctor, said Holmes, blandly. Pray take a seat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3427,'I will do nothing of the kind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3428,'My step-daughter has been here. I have traced her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3429,'What has she been saying to you?  It is a little cold for the time of the year, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3430,'What has she been saying to you? screamed the old man, furiously.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3431,'But I have heard that the crocuses promise well, continued my companion, imperturbably.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3432,'Ha! You put me off, do you? said our new visitor, taking a step forward and shaking his hunting-crop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3433,'I know you, you scoundrel! I have heard of you before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3434,'You are Holmes, the meddler.  My friend smiled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3435,'Holmes, the busybody!  His smile broadened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3436,'Holmes, the Scotland-yard Jack-in-office!  Holmes chuckled heartily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3437,'Your conversation is most entertaining, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3438,'When you go out close the door, for there is a decided draught.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3439,'I will go when I have said my say.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3440,'Don’t you dare to meddle with my affairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3441,'I know that Miss Stoner has been here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3442,'I traced her! I am a dangerous man to fall foul of! See here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3443,'He stepped swiftly forward, seized the poker, and bent it into a curve with his huge brown hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3444,'See that you keep yourself out of my grip, he snarled, and hurling the twisted poker into the fireplace, he strode out of the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3445,'He seems a very amiable person, said Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3446,'I am not quite so bulky, but if he had remained I might have shown him that my grip was not much more feeble than his own.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3447,'As he spoke he picked up the steel poker, and with a sudden effort straightened it out again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3448,'Fancy his having the insolence to confound me with the official detective force! This incident gives zest to our investigation, however, and I only trust that our little friend will not suffer from her imprudence in allowing this brute to trace her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3449,'And now, Watson, we shall order breakfast, and afterwards I shall walk down to Doctors’ Commons, where I hope to get some data which may help us in this matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3450,'*       *       *       *       *  It was nearly one o’clock when Sherlock Holmes returned from his excursion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3451,'He held in his hand a sheet of blue paper, scrawled over with notes and figures.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3452,'I have seen the will of the deceased wife, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3453,'To determine its exact meaning I have been obliged to work out the present prices of the investments with which it is concerned.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3454,'The total income, which at the time of the wife’s death was little short of £1100, is now, through the fall in agricultural prices, not more than £750.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3455,'Each daughter can claim an income of £250, in case of marriage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3456,'It is evident, therefore, that if both girls had married, this beauty would have had a mere pittance, while even one of them would cripple him to a very serious extent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3457,'My morning’s work has not been wasted, since it has proved that he has the very strongest motives for standing in the way of anything of the sort.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3458,'And now, Watson, this is too serious for dawdling, especially as the old man is aware that we are interesting ourselves in his affairs; so if you are ready, we shall call a cab and drive to Waterloo.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3459,'I should be very much obliged if you would slip your revolver into your pocket. An Eley’s No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3460,'2 is an excellent argument with gentlemen who can twist steel pokers into knots.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3461,'That and a tooth-brush are, I think, all that we need.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3462,'At Waterloo we were fortunate in catching a train for Leatherhead, where we hired a trap at the station inn, and drove for four or five miles through the lovely Surrey lanes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3463,'It was a perfect day, with a bright sun and a few fleecy clouds in the heavens.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3464,'The trees and way-side hedges were just throwing out their first green shoots, and the air was full of the pleasant smell of the moist earth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3465,'To me at least there was a strange contrast between the sweet promise of the spring and this sinister quest upon which we were engaged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3466,'My companion sat in the front of the trap, his arms folded, his hat pulled down over his eyes, and his chin sunk upon his breast, buried in the deepest thought.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3467,'Suddenly, however, he started, tapped me on the shoulder, and pointed over the meadows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3468,'Look there! said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3469,'A heavily-timbered park stretched up in a gentle slope, thickening into a grove at the highest point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3470,'From amid the branches there jutted out the gray gables and high roof-tree of a very old mansion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3471,'Stoke Moran? said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3472,'Yes, sir, that be the house of Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3473,'Grimesby Roylott, remarked the driver.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3474,'There is some building going on there, said Holmes; that is where we are going.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3475,'There’s the village, said the driver, pointing to a cluster of roofs some distance to the left; but if you want to get to the house, you’ll find it shorter to get over this stile, and so by the foot-path over the fields.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3476,'There it is, where the lady is walking.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3477,'And the lady, I fancy, is Miss Stoner, observed Holmes, shading his eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3478,'Yes, I think we had better do as you suggest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3479,'We got off, paid our fare, and the trap rattled back on its way to Leatherhead.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3480,'I thought it as well, said Holmes, as we climbed the stile, that this fellow should think we had come here as architects, or on some definite business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3481,'It may stop his gossip.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3482,'Good-afternoon, Miss Stoner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3483,'You see that we have been as good as our word.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3484,'Our client of the morning had hurried forward to meet us with a face which spoke her joy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3485,'I have been waiting so eagerly for you, she cried, shaking hands with us warmly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3486,'All has turned out splendidly. Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3487,'Roylott has gone to town, and it is unlikely that he will be back before evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3488,'We have had the pleasure of making the doctor’s acquaintance, said Holmes, and in a few words he sketched out what had occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3489,'Miss Stoner turned white to the lips as she listened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3490,'Good heavens! she cried, he has followed me, then.  So it appears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3491,'He is so cunning that I never know when I am safe from him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3492,'What will he say when he returns?  He must guard himself, for he may find that there is some one more cunning than himself upon his track.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3493,'You must lock yourself up from him to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3494,'If he is violent, we shall take you away to your aunt’s at Harrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3495,'Now, we must make the best use of our time, so kindly take us at once to the rooms which we are to examine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3496,'The building was of gray, lichen-blotched stone, with a high central portion, and two curving wings, like the claws of a crab, thrown out on each side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3497,'In one of these wings the windows were broken, and blocked with wooden boards, while the roof was partly caved in, a picture of ruin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3498,'The central portion was in little better repair, but the right-hand block was comparatively modern, and the blinds in the windows, with the blue smoke curling up from the chimneys, showed that this was where the family resided.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3499,'Some scaffolding had been erected against the end wall, and the stone-work had been broken into, but there were no signs of any workmen at the moment of our visit.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3500,'Holmes walked slowly up and down the ill-trimmed lawn, and examined with deep attention the outsides of the windows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3501,'This, I take it, belongs to the room in which you used to sleep, the centre one to your sister’s, and the one next to the main building to Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3502,'Roylott’s chamber?  Exactly so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3503,'But I am now sleeping in the middle one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3504,'Pending the alterations, as I understand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3505,'By-the-way, there does not seem to be any very pressing need for repairs at that end wall.  There were none.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3506,'I believe that it was an excuse to move me from my room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3507,'Ah! that is suggestive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3508,'Now, on the other side of this narrow wing runs the corridor from which these three rooms open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3509,'There are windows in it, of course?  Yes, but very small ones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3510,'Too narrow for any one to pass through.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3511,'As you both locked your doors at night, your rooms were unapproachable from that side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3512,'Now, would you have the kindness to go into your room and bar your shutters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3513,'Miss Stoner did so, and Holmes, after a careful examination through the open window, endeavored in every way to force the shutter open, but without success.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3514,'There was no slit through which a knife could be passed to raise the bar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3515,'Then with his lens he tested the hinges, but they were of solid iron, built firmly into the massive masonry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3516,'Hum! said he, scratching his chin in some perplexity; my theory certainly presents some difficulties.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3517,'No one could pass these shutters if they were bolted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3518,'Well, we shall see if the inside throws any light upon the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3519,'A small side door led into the whitewashed corridor from which the three bedrooms opened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3520,'Holmes refused to examine the third chamber, so we passed at once to the second, that in which Miss Stoner was now sleeping, and in which her sister had met with her fate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3521,'It was a homely little room, with a low ceiling and a gaping fireplace, after the fashion of old country-houses.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3522,'A brown chest of drawers stood in one corner, a narrow white-counterpaned bed in another, and a dressing-table on the left-hand side of the window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3523,'These articles, with two small wicker-work chairs, made up all the furniture in the room, save for a square of Wilton carpet in the centre.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3524,'The boards round and the panelling of the walls were of brown, worm-eaten oak, so old and discolored that it may have dated from the original building of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3525,'Holmes drew one of the chairs into a corner and sat silent, while his eyes travelled round and round and up and down, taking in every detail of the apartment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3526,'Where does that bell communicate with? he asked, at last, pointing to a thick bell-rope which hung down beside the bed, the tassel actually lying upon the pillow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3527,'It goes to the house-keeper’s room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3528,'It looks newer than the other things?  Yes, it was only put there a couple of years ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3529,'Your sister asked for it, I suppose?  No, I never heard of her using it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3530,'We used always to get what we wanted for ourselves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3531,'Indeed, it seemed unnecessary to put so nice a bell-pull there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3532,'You will excuse me for a few minutes while I satisfy myself as to this floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3533,'He threw himself down upon his face with his lens in his hand, and crawled swiftly backward and forward, examining minutely the cracks between the boards.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3534,'Then he did the same with the wood-work with which the chamber was panelled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3535,'Finally he walked over to the bed, and spent some time in staring at it, and in running his eye up and down the wall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3536,'Finally he took the bell-rope in his hand and gave it a brisk tug.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3537,'Why, it’s a dummy, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3538,'Won’t it ring?  No, it is not even attached to a wire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3539,'This is very interesting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3540,'You can see now that it is fastened to a hook just above where the little opening for the ventilator is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3541,'How very absurd! I never noticed that before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3542,'Very strange! muttered Holmes, pulling at the rope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3543,'There are one or two very singular points about this room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3544,'For example, what a fool a builder must be to open a ventilator into another room, when, with the same trouble, he might have communicated with the outside air!  That is also quite modern, said the lady.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3545,'Done about the same time as the bell-rope? remarked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3546,'Yes, there were several little changes carried out about that time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3547,'They seem to have been of a most interesting character—dummy bell-ropes, and ventilators which do not ventilate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3548,'With your permission, Miss Stoner, we shall now carry our researches into the inner apartment.  Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3549,'Grimesby Roylott’s chamber was larger than that of his step-daughter, but was as plainly furnished.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3550,'A camp-bed, a small wooden shelf full of books, mostly of a technical character, an arm-chair beside the bed, a plain wooden chair against the wall, a round table, and a large iron safe were the principal things which met the eye.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3551,'Holmes walked slowly round and examined each and all of them with the keenest interest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3552,'What’s in here? he asked, tapping the safe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3553,'My step-father’s business papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3554,'Oh! you have seen inside, then?  Only once, some years ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3555,'I remember that it was full of papers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3556,'There isn’t a cat in it, for example?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3557,'What a strange idea!  Well, look at this! He took up a small saucer of milk which stood on the top of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3558,'No; we don’t keep a cat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3559,'But there is a cheetah and a baboon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3560,'Ah, yes, of course! Well, a cheetah is just a big cat, and yet a saucer of milk does not go very far in satisfying its wants, I dare say.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3561,'There is one point which I should wish to determine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3562,'He squatted down in front of the wooden chair, and examined the seat of it with the greatest attention.  Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3563,'That is quite settled, said he, rising and putting his lens in his pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3564,'Hello! Here is something interesting!  The object which had caught his eye was a small dog-lash hung on one corner of the bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3565,'The lash, however, was curled upon itself, and tied so as to make a loop of whip-cord.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3566,'What do you make of that, Watson?  It’s a common enough lash.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3567,'But I don’t know why it should be tied.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3568,'That is not quite so common, is it? Ah, me! it’s a wicked world, and when a clever man turns his brains to crime it is the worst of all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3569,'I think that I have seen enough now, Miss Stoner, and with your permission we shall walk out upon the lawn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3570,'I had never seen my friend’s face so grim or his brow so dark as it was when we turned from the scene of this investigation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3571,'We had walked several times up and down the lawn, neither Miss Stoner nor myself liking to break in upon his thoughts before he roused himself from his reverie.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3572,'It is very essential, Miss Stoner, said he, that you should absolutely follow my advice in every respect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3573,'I shall most certainly do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3574,'The matter is too serious for any hesitation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3575,'Your life may depend upon your compliance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3576,'I assure you that I am in your hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3577,'In the first place, both my friend and I must spend the night in your room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3578,'Both Miss Stoner and I gazed at him in astonishment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3579,'Yes, it must be so. Let me explain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3580,'I believe that that is the village inn over there?  Yes, that is the ‘Crown.’  Very good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3581,'Your windows would be visible from there?  Certainly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3582,'You must confine yourself to your room, on pretence of a headache, when your step-father comes back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3583,'Then when you hear him retire for the night, you must open the shutters of your window, undo the hasp, put your lamp there as a signal to us, and then withdraw quietly with everything which you are likely to want into the room which you used to occupy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3584,'I have no doubt that, in spite of the repairs, you could manage there for one night.  Oh yes, easily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3585,'The rest you will leave in our hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3586,'But what will you do?  We shall spend the night in your room, and we shall investigate the cause of this noise which has disturbed you.  I believe, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3587,'Holmes, that you have already made up your mind, said Miss Stoner, laying her hand upon my companion’s sleeve.  Perhaps I have.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3588,'Then for pity’s sake tell me what was the cause of my sister’s death.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3589,'I should prefer to have clearer proofs before I speak.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3590,'You can at least tell me whether my own thought is correct, and if she died from some sudden fright.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3591,'[Illustration: ‘GOOD-BYE, AND BE BRAVE’]  No, I do not think so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3592,'I think that there was probably some more tangible cause.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3593,'And now, Miss Stoner, we must leave you, for if Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3594,'Roylott returned and saw us, our journey would be in vain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3595,'Good-bye, and be brave, for if you will do what I have told you, you may rest assured that we shall soon drive away the dangers that threaten you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3596,'Sherlock Holmes and I had no difficulty in engaging a bedroom and sitting-room at the Crown Inn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3597,'They were on the upper floor, and from our window we could command a view of the avenue gate, and of the inhabited wing of Stoke Moran Manor House. At dusk we saw Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3598,'Grimesby Roylott drive past, his huge form looming up beside the little figure of the lad who drove him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3599,'The boy had some slight difficulty in undoing the heavy iron gates, and we heard the hoarse roar of the doctor’s voice, and saw the fury with which he shook his clinched fists at him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3600,'The trap drove on, and a few minutes later we saw a sudden light spring up among the trees as the lamp was lit in one of the sitting-rooms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3601,'Do you know, Watson, said Holmes, as we sat together in the gathering darkness, I have really some scruples as to taking you to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3602,'There is a distinct element of danger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3603,'Can I be of assistance?  Your presence might be invaluable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3604,'Then I shall certainly come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3605,'It is very kind of you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3606,'You speak of danger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3607,'You have evidently seen more in these rooms than was visible to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3608,'No, but I fancy that I may have deduced a little more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3609,'I imagine that you saw all that I did.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3610,'I saw nothing remarkable save the bell-rope, and what purpose that could answer I confess is more than I can imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3611,'You saw the ventilator, too?  Yes, but I do not think that it is such a very unusual thing to have a small opening between two rooms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3612,'It was so small that a rat could hardly pass through.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3613,'I knew that we should find a ventilator before ever we came to Stoke Moran.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3614,'My dear Holmes!  Oh yes, I did.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3615,'You remember in her statement she said that her sister could smell Dr. Roylott’s cigar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3616,'Now, of course that suggested at once that there must be a communication between the two rooms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3617,'It could only be a small one, or it would have been remarked upon at the coroner’s inquiry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3618,'I deduced a ventilator.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3619,'But what harm can there be in that?  Well, there is at least a curious coincidence of dates.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3620,'A ventilator is made, a cord is hung, and a lady who sleeps in the bed dies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3621,'Does not that strike you?  I cannot as yet see any connection.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3622,'Did you observe anything very peculiar about that bed?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3623,'It was clamped to the floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3624,'Did you ever see a bed fastened like that before?  I cannot say that I have.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3625,'The lady could not move her bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3626,'It must always be in the same relative position to the ventilator and to the rope—for so we may call it, since it was clearly never meant for a bell-pull.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3627,'Holmes, I cried, I seem to see dimly what you are hinting at.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3628,'We are only just in time to prevent some subtle and horrible crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3629,'Subtle enough and horrible enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3630,'When a doctor does go wrong, he is the first of criminals.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3631,'He has nerve and he has knowledge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3632,'Palmer and Pritchard were among the heads of their profession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3633,'This man strikes even deeper, but I think, Watson, that we shall be able to strike deeper still.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3634,'But we shall have horrors enough before the night is over; for goodness’ sake let us have a quiet pipe, and turn our minds for a few hours to something more cheerful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3635,'*       *       *       *       *  About nine o’clock the light among the trees was extinguished, and all was dark in the direction of the Manor House.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3636,'Two hours passed slowly away, and then, suddenly, just at the stroke of eleven, a single bright light shone out right in front of us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3637,'That is our signal, said Holmes, springing to his feet; it comes from the middle window.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3638,'As we passed out he exchanged a few words with the landlord, explaining that we were going on a late visit to an acquaintance, and that it was possible that we might spend the night there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3639,'A moment later we were out on the dark road, a chill wind blowing in our faces, and one yellow light twinkling in front of us through the gloom to guide us on our sombre errand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3640,'There was little difficulty in entering the grounds, for unrepaired breaches gaped in the old park wall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3641,'Making our way among the trees, we reached the lawn, crossed it, and were about to enter through the window, when out from a clump of laurel bushes there darted what seemed to be a hideous and distorted child, who threw itself upon the grass with writhing limbs, and then ran swiftly across the lawn into the darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3642,'My God! I whispered; did you see it?  Holmes was for the moment as startled as I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3643,'His hand closed like a vice upon my wrist in his agitation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3644,'Then he broke into a low laugh, and put his lips to my ear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3645,'It is a nice household, he murmured. That is the baboon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3646,'I had forgotten the strange pets which the doctor affected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3647,'There was a cheetah, too; perhaps we might find it upon our shoulders at any moment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3648,'I confess that I felt easier in my mind when, after following Holmes’s example and slipping off my shoes, I found myself inside the bedroom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3649,'My companion noiselessly closed the shutters, moved the lamp onto the table, and cast his eyes round the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3650,'All was as we had seen it in the daytime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3651,'Then creeping up to me and making a trumpet of his hand, he whispered into my ear again so gently that it was all that I could do to distinguish the words:  The least sound would be fatal to our plans.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3652,'I nodded to show that I had heard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3653,'We must sit without light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3654,'He would see it through the ventilator.  I nodded again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3655,'Do not go asleep; your very life may depend upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3656,'Have your pistol ready in case we should need it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3657,'I will sit on the side of the bed, and you in that chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3658,'I took out my revolver and laid it on the corner of the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3659,'Holmes had brought up a long thin cane, and this he placed upon the bed beside him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3660,'By it he laid the box of matches and the stump of a candle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3661,'Then he turned down the lamp, and we were left in darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3662,'How shall I ever forget that dreadful vigil? I could not hear a sound, not even the drawing of a breath, and yet I knew that my companion sat open-eyed, within a few feet of me, in the same state of nervous tension in which I was myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3663,'The shutters cut off the least ray of light, and we waited in absolute darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3664,'From outside came the occasional cry of a night-bird, and once at our very window a long drawn cat-like whine, which told us that the cheetah was indeed at liberty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3665,'Far away we could hear the deep tones of the parish clock, which boomed out every quarter of an hour.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3666,'How long they seemed, those quarters! Twelve struck, and one and two and three, and still we sat waiting silently for whatever might befall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3667,'Suddenly there was the momentary gleam of a light up in the direction of the ventilator, which vanished immediately, but was succeeded by a strong smell of burning oil and heated metal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3668,'Some one in the next room had lit a dark-lantern.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3669,'I heard a gentle sound of movement, and then all was silent once more, though the smell grew stronger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3670,'For half an hour I sat with straining ears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3671,'Then suddenly another sound became audible—a very gentle, soothing sound, like that of a small jet of steam escaping continually from a kettle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3672,'The instant that we heard it, Holmes sprang from the bed, struck a match, and lashed furiously with his cane at the bell-pull.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3673,'You see it, Watson? he yelled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3674,'You see it?  But I saw nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3675,'At the moment when Holmes struck the light I heard a low, clear whistle, but the sudden glare flashing into my weary eyes made it impossible for me to tell what it was at which my friend lashed so savagely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3676,'I could, however, see that his face was deadly pale, and filled with horror and loathing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3677,'He had ceased to strike, and was gazing up at the ventilator, when suddenly there broke from the silence of the night the most horrible cry to which I have ever listened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3678,'It swelled up louder and louder, a hoarse yell of pain and fear and anger all mingled in the one dreadful shriek.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3679,'They say that away down in the village, and even in the distant parsonage, that cry raised the sleepers from their beds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3680,'It struck cold to our hearts, and I stood gazing at Holmes, and he at me, until the last echoes of it had died away into the silence from which it rose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3681,'What can it mean? I gasped.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3682,'It means that it is all over, Holmes answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3683,'And perhaps, after all, it is for the best.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3684,'Take your pistol, and we will enter Dr. Roylott’s room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3685,'With a grave face he lit the lamp and led the way down the corridor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3686,'Twice he struck at the chamber door without any reply from within.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3687,'Then he turned the handle and entered, I at his heels, with the cocked pistol in my hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3688,'It was a singular sight which met our eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3689,'On the table stood a dark-lantern with the shutter half open, throwing a brilliant beam of light upon the iron safe, the door of which was ajar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3690,'Beside this table, on the wooden chair, sat Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3691,'Grimesby Roylott, clad in a long gray dressing-gown, his bare ankles protruding beneath, and his feet thrust into red heelless Turkish slippers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3692,'Across his lap lay the short stock with the long lash which we had noticed during the day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3693,'His chin was cocked upward and his eyes were fixed in a dreadful, rigid stare at the corner of the ceiling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3694,'Round his brow he had a peculiar yellow band, with brownish speckles, which seemed to be bound tightly round his head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3695,'As we entered he made neither sound nor motion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3696,'The band! the speckled band! whispered Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3697,'I took a step forward.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3698,'In an instant his strange head-gear began to move, and there reared itself from among his hair the squat diamond-shaped head and puffed neck of a loathsome serpent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3699,'It is a swamp adder! cried Holmes; the deadliest snake in India.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3700,'He has died within ten seconds of being bitten.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3701,'Violence does, in truth, recoil upon the violent, and the schemer falls into the pit which he digs for another.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3702,'Let us thrust this creature back into its den, and we can then remove Miss Stoner to some place of shelter, and let the county police know what has happened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3703,'As he spoke he drew the dog-whip swiftly from the dead man’s lap, and throwing the noose round the reptile’s neck, he drew it from its horrid perch, and carrying it at arm’s length, threw it into the iron safe, which he closed upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3704,'*       *       *       *       *  Such are the true facts of the death of Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3705,'Grimesby Roylott, of Stoke Moran.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3706,'It is not necessary that I should prolong a narrative which has already run to too great a length, by telling how we broke the sad news to the terrified girl, how we conveyed her by the morning train to the care of her good aunt at Harrow, of how the slow process of official inquiry came to the conclusion that the doctor met his fate while indiscreetly playing with a dangerous pet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3707,'The little which I had yet to learn of the case was told me by Sherlock Holmes as we travelled back next day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3708,'I had, said he, come to an entirely erroneous conclusion, which shows, my dear Watson, how dangerous it always is to reason from insufficient data.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3709,'The presence of the gypsies, and the use of the word ‘band,’ which was used by the poor girl, no doubt to explain the appearance which she had caught a hurried glimpse of by the light of her match, were sufficient to put me upon an entirely wrong scent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3710,'I can only claim the merit that I instantly reconsidered my position when, however, it became clear to me that whatever danger threatened an occupant of the room could not come either from the window or the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3711,'My attention was speedily drawn, as I have already remarked to you, to this ventilator, and to the bell-rope which hung down to the bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3712,'The discovery that this was a dummy, and that the bed was clamped to the floor, instantly gave rise to the suspicion that the rope was there as bridge for something passing through the hole, and coming to the bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3713,'The idea of a snake instantly occurred to me, and when I coupled it with my knowledge that the doctor was furnished with a supply of creatures from India, I felt that I was probably on the right track.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3714,'The idea of using a form of poison which could not possibly be discovered by any chemical test was just such a one as would occur to a clever and ruthless man who had had an Eastern training.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3715,'The rapidity with which such a poison would take effect would also, from his point of view, be an advantage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3716,'It would be a sharp-eyed coroner, indeed, who could distinguish the two little dark punctures which would show where the poison fangs had done their work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3717,'Then I thought of the whistle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3718,'Of course he must recall the snake before the morning light revealed it to the victim.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3719,'He had trained it, probably by the use of the milk which we saw, to return to him when summoned.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3720,'He would put it through this ventilator at the hour that he thought best, with the certainty that it would crawl down the rope and land on the bed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3721,'It might or might not bite the occupant, perhaps she might escape every night for a week, but sooner or later she must fall a victim.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3722,'I had come to these conclusions before ever I had entered his room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3723,'An inspection of his chair showed me that he had been in the habit of standing on it, which of course would be necessary in order that he should reach the ventilator.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3724,'The sight of the safe, the saucer of milk, and the loop of whip-cord were enough to finally dispel any doubts which may have remained.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3725,'The metallic clang heard by Miss Stoner was obviously caused by her step-father hastily closing the door of his safe upon its terrible occupant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3726,'Having once made up my mind, you know the steps which I took in order to put the matter to the proof.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3727,'I heard the creature hiss, as I have no doubt that you did also, and I instantly lit the light and attacked it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3728,'With the result of driving it through the ventilator.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3729,'And also with the result of causing it to turn upon its master at the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3730,'Some of the blows of my cane came home, and roused its snakish temper, so that it flew upon the first person it saw.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3731,'In this way I am no doubt indirectly responsible for Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3732,'Grimesby Roylott’s death, and I cannot say that it is likely to weigh very heavily upon my conscience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3733,'Adventure IX  THE ADVENTURE OF THE ENGINEER’S THUMB   Of all the problems which have been submitted to my friend Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3734,'Sherlock Holmes for solution during the years of our intimacy, there were only two which I was the means of introducing to his notice—that of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3735,'Hatherley’s thumb, and that of Colonel Warburton’s madness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3736,'Of these the latter may have afforded a finer field for an acute and original observer, but the other was so strange in its inception and so dramatic in its details, that it may be the more worthy of being placed upon record, even if it gave my friend fewer openings for those deductive methods of reasoning by which he achieved such remarkable results.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3737,'The story has, I believe, been told more than once in the newspapers, but, like all such narratives, its effect is much less striking when set forth _en bloc_ in a single half-column of print than when the facts slowly evolve before your own eyes, and the mystery clears gradually away as each new discovery furnishes a step which leads on to the complete truth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3738,'At the time the circumstances made a deep impression upon me, and the lapse of two years has hardly served to weaken the effect.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3739,'It was in the summer of ’89, not long after my marriage, that the events occurred which I am now about to summarize.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3740,'I had returned to civil practice, and had finally abandoned Holmes in his Baker Street rooms, although I continually visited him, and occasionally even persuaded him to forego his Bohemian habits so far as to come and visit us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3741,'My practice had steadily increased, and as I happened to live at no very great distance from Paddington Station, I got a few patients from among the officials.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3742,'One of these, whom I had cured of a painful and lingering disease, was never weary of advertising my virtues, and of endeavoring to send me on every sufferer over whom he might have any influence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3743,'One morning, at a little before seven o’clock, I was awakened by the maid tapping at the door, to announce that two men had come from Paddington, and were waiting in the consulting-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3744,'I dressed hurriedly, for I knew by experience that railway cases were seldom trivial, and hastened down-stairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3745,'As I descended, my old ally, the guard, came out of the room and closed the door tightly behind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3746,'I’ve got him here, he whispered, jerking his thumb over his shoulder; he’s all right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3747,'What is it, then? I asked, for his manner suggested that it was some strange creature which he had caged up in my room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3748,'It’s a new patient, he whispered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3749,'I thought I’d bring him round myself; then he couldn’t slip away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3750,'There he is, all safe and sound.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3751,'I must go now, doctor; I have my dooties, just the same as you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3752,'And off he went, this trusty tout, without even giving me time to thank him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3753,'I entered my consulting-room and found a gentleman seated by the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3754,'He was quietly dressed in a suit of heather tweed, with a soft cloth cap, which he had laid down upon my books.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3755,'Round one of his hands he had a handkerchief wrapped, which was mottled all over with blood-stains.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3756,'He was young, not more than five-and-twenty, I should say, with a strong, masculine face; but he was exceedingly pale, and gave me the impression of a man who was suffering from some strong agitation, which it took all his strength of mind to control.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3757,'I am sorry to knock you up so early, doctor, said he, but I have had a very serious accident during the night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3758,'I came in by train this morning, and on inquiring at Paddington as to where I might find a doctor, a worthy fellow very kindly escorted me here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3759,'I gave the maid a card, but I see that she has left it upon the side-table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3760,'I took it up and glanced at it. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3761,'Victor Hatherley, hydraulic engineer, 16A, Victoria Street (3d floor).');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3762,'That was the name, style, and abode of my morning visitor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3763,'I regret that I have kept you waiting, said I, sitting down in my library-chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3764,'You are fresh from a night journey, I understand, which is in itself a monotonous occupation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3765,'Oh, my night could not be called monotonous, said he, and laughed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3766,'He laughed very heartily, with a high, ringing note, leaning back in his chair and shaking his sides.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3767,'All my medical instincts rose up against that laugh.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3768,'Stop it! I cried; pull yourself together! and I poured out some water from a caraffe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3769,'It was useless, however.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3770,'He was off in one of those hysterical outbursts which come upon a strong nature when some great crisis is over and gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3771,'Presently he came to himself once more, very weary and blushing hotly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3772,'I have been making a fool of myself, he gasped.  Not at all. Drink this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3773,'I dashed some brandy into the water, and the color began to come back to his bloodless cheeks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3774,'That’s better! said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3775,'And now, doctor, perhaps you would kindly attend to my thumb, or rather to the place where my thumb used to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3776,'He unwound the handkerchief and held out his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3777,'It gave even my hardened nerves a shudder to look at it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3778,'There were four protruding fingers and a horrid red, spongy surface where the thumb should have been.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3779,'It had been hacked or torn right out from the roots.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3780,'Good heavens! I cried, this is a terrible injury.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3781,'It must have bled considerably.  Yes, it did.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3782,'I fainted when it was done, and I think that I must have been senseless for a long time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3783,'When I came to I found that it was still bleeding, so I tied one end of my handkerchief very tightly round the wrist, and braced it up with a twig.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3784,'Excellent! You should have been a surgeon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3785,'It is a question of hydraulics, you see, and came within my own province.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3786,'This has been done, said I, examining the wound, by a very heavy and sharp instrument.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3787,'A thing like a cleaver, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3788,'An accident, I presume?  By no means.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3789,'What! a murderous attack?  Very murderous indeed.  You horrify me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3790,'I sponged the wound, cleaned it, dressed it, and finally covered it over with cotton wadding and carbolized bandages.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3791,'He lay back without wincing, though he bit his lip from time to time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3792,'How is that? I asked, when I had finished.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3793,'Capital! Between your brandy and your bandage, I feel a new man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3794,'I was very weak, but I have had a good deal to go through.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3795,'Perhaps you had better not speak of the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3796,'It is evidently trying to your nerves.  Oh no, not now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3797,'I shall have to tell my tale to the police; but, between ourselves, if it were not for the convincing evidence of this wound of mine, I should be surprised if they believed my statement; for it is a very extraordinary one, and I have not much in the way of proof with which to back it up; and, even if they believe me, the clews which I can give them are so vague that it is a question whether justice will be done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3798,'Ha! cried I, if it is anything in the nature of a problem which you desire to see solved, I should strongly recommend you to come to my friend Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3799,'Sherlock Holmes before you go to the official police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3800,'Oh, I have heard of that fellow, answered my visitor, and I should be very glad if he would take the matter up, though of course I must use the official police as well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3801,'Would you give me an introduction to him?  I’ll do better.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3802,'I’ll take you round to him myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3803,'I should be immensely obliged to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3804,'We’ll call a cab and go together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3805,'We shall just be in time to have a little breakfast with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3806,'Do you feel equal to it?  Yes; I shall not feel easy until I have told my story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3807,'Then my servant will call a cab, and I shall be with you in an instant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3808,'I rushed up-stairs, explained the matter shortly to my wife, and in five minutes was inside a hansom, driving with my new acquaintance to Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3809,'Sherlock Holmes was, as I expected, lounging about his sitting-room in his dressing-gown, reading the agony column of _The Times_, and smoking his before-breakfast pipe, which was composed of all the plugs and dottels left from his smokes of the day before, all carefully dried and collected on the corner of the mantel-piece.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3810,'He received us in his quietly genial fashion, ordered fresh rashers and eggs, and joined us in a hearty meal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3811,'When it was concluded he settled our new acquaintance upon the sofa, placed a pillow beneath his head, and laid a glass of brandy-and-water within his reach.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3812,'It is easy to see that your experience has been no common one, Mr. Hatherley, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3813,'Pray, lie down there and make yourself absolutely at home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3814,'Tell us what you can, but stop when you are tired, and keep up your strength with a little stimulant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3815,'Thank you, said my patient, but I have felt another man since the doctor bandaged me, and I think that your breakfast has completed the cure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3816,'I shall take up as little of your valuable time as possible, so I shall start at once upon my peculiar experiences.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3817,'Holmes sat in his big arm-chair with the weary, heavy-lidded expression which veiled his keen and eager nature, while I sat opposite to him, and we listened in silence to the strange story which our visitor detailed to us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3818,'You must know, said he, that I am an orphan and a bachelor, residing alone in lodgings in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3819,'By profession I am an hydraulic engineer, and I have had considerable experience of my work during the seven years that I was apprenticed to Venner & Matheson, the well-known firm, of Greenwich.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3820,'Two years ago, having served my time, and having also come into a fair sum of money through my poor father’s death, I determined to start in business for myself, and took professional chambers in Victoria Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3821,'I suppose that every one finds his first independent start in business a dreary experience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3822,'To me it has been exceptionally so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3823,'During two years I have had three consultations and one small job, and that is absolutely all that my profession has brought me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3824,'My gross takings amount to £27 10_s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3825,'_ Every day, from nine in the morning until four in the afternoon, I waited in my little den, until at last my heart began to sink, and I came to believe that I should never have any practice at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3826,'Yesterday, however, just as I was thinking of leaving the office, my clerk entered to say there was a gentleman waiting who wished to see me upon business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3827,'He brought up a card, too, with the name of ‘Colonel Lysander Stark’ engraved upon it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3828,'Close at his heels came the colonel himself, a man rather over the middle size, but of an exceeding thinness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3829,'I do not think that I have ever seen so thin a man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3830,'His whole face sharpened away into nose and chin, and the skin of his cheeks was drawn quite tense over his outstanding bones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3831,'Yet this emaciation seemed to be his natural habit, and due to no disease, for his eye was bright, his step brisk, and his bearing assured.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3832,'He was plainly but neatly dressed, and his age, I should judge, would be nearer forty than thirty.  ‘Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3833,'Hatherley?’ said he, with something of a German accent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3834,'‘You have been recommended to me, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3835,'Hatherley, as being a man who is not only proficient in his profession, but is also discreet and capable of preserving a secret.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3836,'’  I bowed, feeling as flattered as any young man would at such an address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3837,'‘May I ask who it was who gave me so good a character?’  ‘Well, perhaps it is better that I should not tell you that just at this moment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3838,'I have it from the same source that you are both an orphan and a bachelor, and are residing alone in London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3839,'’  ‘That is quite correct,’ I answered, ‘but you will excuse me if I say that I cannot see how all this bears upon my professional qualifications.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3840,'I understood that it was on a professional matter that you wished to speak to me?’  ‘Undoubtedly so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3841,'But you will find that all I say is really to the point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3842,'I have a professional commission for you, but absolute secrecy is quite essential—_absolute_ secrecy, you understand, and of course we may expect that more from a man who is alone than from one who lives in the bosom of his family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3843,'’  ‘If I promise to keep a secret,’ said I, ‘you may absolutely depend upon my doing so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3844,'’  He looked very hard at me as I spoke, and it seemed to me that I had never seen so suspicious and questioning an eye.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3845,'‘Do you promise, then?’ said he, at last.  ‘Yes, I promise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3846,'’  ‘Absolute and complete silence before, during, and after? No reference to the matter at all, either in word or writing?’  ‘I have already given you my word.’  ‘Very good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3847,'’ He suddenly sprang up, and darting like lightning across the room, he flung open the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3848,'The passage outside was empty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3849,'‘That’s all right,’ said he, coming back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3850,'‘I know that clerks are sometimes curious as to their master’s affairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3851,'Now we can talk in safety.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3852,'’ He drew up his chair very close to mine, and began to stare at me again with the same questioning and thoughtful look.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3853,'A feeling of repulsion, and of something akin to fear had begun to rise within me at the strange antics of this fleshless man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3854,'Even my dread of losing a client could not restrain me from showing my impatience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3855,'‘I beg that you will state your business, sir,’ said I; ‘my time is of value.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3856,'’ Heaven forgive me for that last sentence, but the words came to my lips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3857,'‘How would fifty guineas for a night’s work suit you?’ he asked.  ‘Most admirably.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3858,'’  ‘I say a night’s work, but an hour’s would be nearer the mark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3859,'I simply want your opinion about a hydraulic stamping machine which has got out of gear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3860,'If you show us what is wrong we shall soon set it right ourselves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3861,'What do you think of such a commission as that?’  ‘The work appears to be light and the pay munificent.’  ‘Precisely so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3862,'We shall want you to come to-night by the last train.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3863,'’  ‘Where to?’  ‘To Eyford, in Berkshire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3864,'It is a little place near the borders of Oxfordshire, and within seven miles of Reading.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3865,'There is a train from Paddington which would bring you there at about 11.15.’  ‘Very good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3866,'’  ‘I shall come down in a carriage to meet you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3867,'’  ‘There is a drive, then?’  ‘Yes, our little place is quite out in the country.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3868,'It is a good seven miles from Eyford Station.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3869,'’  ‘Then we can hardly get there before midnight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3870,'I suppose there would be no chance of a train back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3871,'I should be compelled to stop the night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3872,'’  ‘Yes, we could easily give you a shake-down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3873,'’  ‘That is very awkward.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3874,'Could I not come at some more convenient hour?’  ‘We have judged it best that you should come late.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3875,'It is to recompense you for any inconvenience that we are paying to you, a young and unknown man, a fee which would buy an opinion from the very heads of your profession.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3876,'Still, of course, if you would like to draw out of the business, there is plenty of time to do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3877,'’  I thought of the fifty guineas, and of how very useful they would be to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3878,'‘Not at all,’ said I, ‘I shall be very happy to accommodate myself to your wishes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3879,'I should like, however, to understand a little more clearly what it is that you wish me to do.’  ‘Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3880,'It is very natural that the pledge of secrecy which we have exacted from you should have aroused your curiosity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3881,'I have no wish to commit you to anything without your having it all laid before you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3882,'I suppose that we are absolutely safe from eavesdroppers?’  ‘Entirely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3883,'’  ‘Then the matter stands thus.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3884,'You are probably aware that fuller’s-earth is a valuable product, and that it is only found in one or two places in England?’  ‘I have heard so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3885,'’  ‘Some little time ago I bought a small place—a very small place—within ten miles of Reading.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3886,'I was fortunate enough to discover that there was a deposit of fuller’s-earth in one of my fields.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3887,'On examining it, however, I found that this deposit was a comparatively small one, and that it formed a link between two very much larger ones upon the right and left—both of them, however, in the grounds of my neighbors.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3888,'These good people were absolutely ignorant that their land contained that which was quite as valuable as a gold-mine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3889,'Naturally, it was to my interest to buy their land before they discovered its true value; but, unfortunately, I had no capital by which I could do this.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3890,'I took a few of my friends into the secret, however, and they suggested that we should quietly and secretly work our own little deposit, and that in this way we should earn the money which would enable us to buy the neighboring fields.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3891,'This we have now been doing for some time, and in order to help us in our operations we erected an hydraulic press.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3892,'This press, as I have already explained, has got out of order, and we wish your advice upon the subject.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3893,'We guard our secret very jealously, however, and if it once became known that we had hydraulic engineers coming to our little house, it would soon rouse inquiry, and then, if the facts came out, it would be good-bye to any chance of getting these fields and carrying out our plans.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3894,'That is why I have made you promise me that you will not tell a human being that you are going to Eyford to-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3895,'I hope that I make it all plain?’  ‘I quite follow you,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3896,'‘The only point which I could not quite understand, was what use you could make of an hydraulic press in excavating fuller’s-earth, which, as I understand, is dug out like gravel from a pit.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3897,'’  ‘Ah!’ said he, carelessly, ‘we have our own process.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3898,'We compress the earth into bricks, so as to remove them without revealing what they are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3899,'But that is a mere detail.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3900,'I have taken you fully into my confidence now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3901,'Hatherley, and I have shown you how I trust you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3902,'’ He rose as he spoke.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3903,'‘I shall expect you, then, at Eyford at 11.15.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3904,'’  ‘I shall certainly be there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3905,'’  ‘And not a word to a soul.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3906,'’ He looked at me with a last, long, questioning gaze, and then, pressing my hand in a cold, dank grasp, he hurried from the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3907,'Well, when I came to think it all over in cool blood I was very much astonished, as you may both think, at this sudden commission which had been intrusted to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3908,'On the one hand, of course, I was glad, for the fee was at least tenfold what I should have asked had I set a price upon my own services, and it was possible that this order might lead to other ones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3909,'On the other hand, the face and manner of my patron had made an unpleasant impression upon me, and I could not think that his explanation of the fuller’s-earth was sufficient to explain the necessity for my coming at midnight, and his extreme anxiety lest I should tell any one of my errand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3910,'However, I threw all fears to the winds, ate a hearty supper, drove to Paddington, and started off, having obeyed to the letter the injunction as to holding my tongue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3911,'[Illustration: ‘NOT A WORD TO A SOUL’]  At Reading I had to change not only my carriage, but my station.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3912,'However, I was in time for the last train to Eyford, and I reached the little dim-lit station after eleven o’clock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3913,'I was the only passenger who got out there, and there was no one upon the platform save a single sleepy porter with a lantern.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3914,'As I passed out through the wicket gate, however, I found my acquaintance of the morning waiting in the shadow upon the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3915,'Without a word he grasped my arm and hurried me into a carriage, the door of which was standing open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3916,'He drew up the windows on either side, tapped on the wood-work, and away we went as fast as the horse could go.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3917,'One horse? interjected Holmes.  Yes, only one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3918,'Did you observe the color?  Yes, I saw it by the side-lights when I was stepping into the carriage. It was a chestnut.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3919,'Tired-looking or fresh?  Oh, fresh and glossy.  Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3920,'I am sorry to have interrupted you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3921,'Pray continue your most interesting statement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3922,'Away we went then, and we drove for at least an hour.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3923,'Colonel Lysander Stark had said that it was only seven miles, but I should think, from the rate that we seemed to go, and from the time that we took, that it must have been nearer twelve.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3924,'He sat at my side in silence all the time, and I was aware, more than once when I glanced in his direction, that he was looking at me with great intensity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3925,'The country roads seem to be not very good in that part of the world, for we lurched and jolted terribly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3926,'I tried to look out of the windows to see something of where we were, but they were made of frosted glass, and I could make out nothing save the occasional bright blur of a passing light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3927,'Now and then I hazarded some remark to break the monotony of the journey, but the colonel answered only in monosyllables, and the conversation soon flagged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3928,'At last, however, the bumping of the road was exchanged for the crisp smoothness of a gravel-drive, and the carriage came to a stand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3929,'Colonel Lysander Stark sprang out, and, as I followed after him, pulled me swiftly into a porch which gaped in front of us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3930,'We stepped, as it were, right out of the carriage and into the hall, so that I failed to catch the most fleeting glance of the front of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3931,'The instant that I had crossed the threshold the door slammed heavily behind us, and I heard faintly the rattle of the wheels as the carriage drove away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3932,'It was pitch dark inside the house, and the colonel fumbled about looking for matches, and muttering under his breath.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3933,'Suddenly a door opened at the other end of the passage, and a long, golden bar of light shot out in our direction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3934,'It grew broader, and a woman appeared with a lamp in her hand, which she held above her head, pushing her face forward and peering at us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3935,'I could see that she was pretty, and from the gloss with which the light shone upon her dark dress I knew that it was a rich material.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3936,'She spoke a few words in a foreign tongue in a tone as though asking a question, and when my companion answered in a gruff monosyllable she gave such a start that the lamp nearly fell from her hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3937,'Colonel Stark went up to her, whispered something in her ear, and then, pushing her back into the room from whence she had come, he walked towards me again with the lamp in his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3938,'‘Perhaps you will have the kindness to wait in this room for a few minutes,’ said he, throwing open another door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3939,'It was a quiet, little, plainly-furnished room, with a round table in the centre, on which several German books were scattered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3940,'Colonel Stark laid down the lamp on the top of a harmonium beside the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3941,'‘I shall not keep you waiting an instant,’ said he, and vanished into the darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3942,'I glanced at the books upon the table, and in spite of my ignorance of German I could see that two of them were treatises on science, the others being volumes of poetry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3943,'Then I walked across to the window, hoping that I might catch some glimpse of the country-side, but an oak shutter, heavily barred, was folded across it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3944,'It was a wonderfully silent house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3945,'There was an old clock ticking loudly somewhere in the passage, but otherwise everything was deadly still.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3946,'A vague feeling of uneasiness began to steal over me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3947,'Who were these German people, and what were they doing, living in this strange, out-of-the-way place? And where was the place? I was ten miles or so from Eyford, that was all I knew, but whether north, south, east, or west I had no idea.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3948,'For that matter, Reading, and possibly other large towns, were within that radius, so the place might not be so secluded, after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3949,'Yet it was quite certain, from the absolute stillness, that we were in the country.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3950,'I paced up and down the room, humming a tune under my breath to keep up my spirits, and feeling that I was thoroughly earning my fifty-guinea fee.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3951,'Suddenly, without any preliminary sound in the midst of the utter stillness, the door of my room swung slowly open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3952,'The woman was standing in the aperture, the darkness of the hall behind her, the yellow light from my lamp beating upon her eager and beautiful face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3953,'I could see at a glance that she was sick with fear, and the sight sent a chill to my own heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3954,'She held up one shaking finger to warn me to be silent, and she shot a few whispered words of broken English at me, her eyes glancing back, like those of a frightened horse, into the gloom behind her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3955,'‘I would go,’ said she, trying hard, as it seemed to me, to speak calmly; ‘I would go.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3956,'I should not stay here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3957,'There is no good for you to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3958,'’  ‘But, madam,’ said I, ‘I have not yet done what I came for.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3959,'I cannot possibly leave until I have seen the machine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3960,'’  ‘It is not worth your while to wait,’ she went on.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3961,'‘You can pass through the door; no one hinders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3962,'’ And then, seeing that I smiled and shook my head, she suddenly threw aside her constraint and made a step forward, with her hands wrung together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3963,'‘For the love of Heaven!’ she whispered, ‘get away from here before it is too late!’  But I am somewhat headstrong by nature, and the more ready to engage in an affair when there is some obstacle in the way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3964,'I thought of my fifty-guinea fee, of my wearisome journey, and of the unpleasant night which seemed to be before me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3965,'Was it all to go for nothing? Why should I slink away without having carried out my commission, and without the payment which was my due? This woman might, for all I knew, be a monomaniac.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3966,'With a stout bearing, therefore, though her manner had shaken me more than I cared to confess, I still shook my head, and declared my intention of remaining where I was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3967,'She was about to renew her entreaties, when a door slammed overhead, and the sound of several footsteps were heard upon the stairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3968,'She listened for an instant, threw up her hands with a despairing gesture, and vanished as suddenly and as noiselessly as she had come.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3969,'The new-comers were Colonel Lysander Stark and a short, thick man with a chinchilla beard growing out of the creases of his double chin, who was introduced to me as Mr. Ferguson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3970,'‘This is my secretary and manager,’ said the colonel.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3971,'‘By-the-way, I was under the impression that I left this door shut just now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3972,'I fear that you have felt the draught.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3973,'’  ‘On the contrary,’ said I, ‘I opened the door myself, because I felt the room to be a little close.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3974,'’  He shot one of his suspicious looks at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3975,'‘Perhaps we had better proceed to business, then,’ said he. ‘Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3976,'Ferguson and I will take you up to see the machine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3977,'’  ‘I had better put my hat on, I suppose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3978,'’  ‘Oh no, it is in the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3979,'’  ‘What, you dig fuller’s-earth in the house?’  ‘No, no.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3980,'This is only where we compress it. But never mind that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3981,'All we wish you to do is to examine the machine, and to let us know what is wrong with it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3982,'’  We went up-stairs together, the colonel first with the lamp, the fat manager, and I behind him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3983,'It was a labyrinth of an old house, with corridors, passages, narrow winding staircases, and little low doors, the thresholds of which were hollowed out by the generations who had crossed them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3984,'There were no carpets and no signs of any furniture above the ground floor, while the plaster was peeling off the walls, and the damp was breaking through in green, unhealthy blotches.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3985,'I tried to put on as unconcerned an air as possible, but I had not forgotten the warnings of the lady, even though I disregarded them, and I kept a keen eye upon my two companions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3986,'Ferguson appeared to be a morose and silent man, but I could see from the little that he said that he was at least a fellow-countryman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3987,'Colonel Lysander Stark stopped at last before a low door, which he unlocked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3988,'Within was a small, square room, in which the three of us could hardly get at one time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3989,'Ferguson remained outside, and the colonel ushered me in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3990,'‘We are now,’ said he, ‘actually within the hydraulic press, and it would be a particularly unpleasant thing for us if any one were to turn it on.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3991,'The ceiling of this small chamber is really the end of the descending piston, and it comes down with the force of many tons upon this metal floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3992,'There are small lateral columns of water outside which receive the force, and which transmit and multiply it in the manner which is familiar to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3993,'The machine goes readily enough, but there is some stiffness in the working of it, and it has lost a little of its force.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3994,'Perhaps you will have the goodness to look it over and to show us how we can set it right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3995,'’  I took the lamp from him, and I examined the machine very thoroughly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3996,'It was indeed a gigantic one, and capable of exercising enormous pressure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3997,'When I passed outside, however, and pressed down the levers which controlled it, I knew at once by the whishing sound that there was a slight leakage, which allowed a regurgitation of water through one of the side cylinders.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3998,'An examination showed that one of the india-rubber bands which was round the head of a driving-rod had shrunk so as not quite to fill the socket along which it worked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(3999,'This was clearly the cause of the loss of power, and I pointed it out to my companions, who followed my remarks very carefully, and asked several practical questions as to how they should proceed to set it right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4000,'When I had made it clear to them, I returned to the main chamber of the machine and took a good look at it to satisfy my own curiosity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4001,'It was obvious at a glance that the story of the fuller’s-earth was the merest fabrication, for it would be absurd to suppose that so powerful an engine could be designed for so inadequate a purpose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4002,'The walls were of wood, but the floor consisted of a large iron trough, and when I came to examine it I could see a crust of metallic deposit all over it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4003,'I had stooped and was scraping at this to see exactly what it was, when I heard a muttered exclamation in German, and saw the cadaverous face of the colonel looking down at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4004,'‘What are you doing there?’ he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4005,'I felt angry at having been tricked by so elaborate a story as that which he had told me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4006,'‘I was admiring your fuller’s-earth,’ said I; ‘I think that I should be better able to advise you as to your machine if I knew what the exact purpose was for which it was used.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4007,'’  The instant that I uttered the words I regretted the rashness of my speech.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4008,'His face set hard, and a baleful light sprang up in his gray eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4009,'‘Very well,’ said he, ‘you shall know all about the machine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4010,'’ He took a step backward, slammed the little door, and turned the key in the lock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4011,'I rushed towards it and pulled at the handle, but it was quite secure, and did not give in the least to my kicks and shoves. ‘Hello!’ I yelled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4012,'‘Hello! Colonel! Let me out!’  And then suddenly in the silence I heard a sound which sent my heart into my mouth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4013,'It was the clank of the levers and the swish of the leaking cylinder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4014,'He had set the engine at work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4015,'The lamp still stood upon the floor where I had placed it when examining the trough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4016,'By its light I saw that the black ceiling was coming down upon me, slowly, jerkily, but, as none knew better than myself, with a force which must within a minute grind me to a shapeless pulp.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4017,'I threw myself, screaming, against the door, and dragged with my nails at the lock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4018,'I implored the colonel to let me out, but the remorseless clanking of the levers drowned my cries.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4019,'The ceiling was only a foot or two above my head, and with my hand upraised I could feel its hard, rough surface.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4020,'Then it flashed through my mind that the pain of my death would depend very much upon the position in which I met it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4021,'If I lay on my face the weight would come upon my spine, and I shuddered to think of that dreadful snap.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4022,'Easier the other way, perhaps; and yet, had I the nerve to lie and look up at that deadly black shadow wavering down upon me? Already I was unable to stand erect, when my eye caught something which brought a gush of hope back to my heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4023,'I have said that though the floor and ceiling were of iron, the walls were of wood.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4024,'As I gave a last hurried glance around, I saw a thin line of yellow light between two of the boards, which broadened and broadened as a small panel was pushed backward.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4025,'For an instant I could hardly believe that here was indeed a door which led away from death.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4026,'The next instant I threw myself through, and lay half-fainting upon the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4027,'The panel had closed again behind me, but the crash of the lamp, and a few moments afterwards the clang of the two slabs of metal, told me how narrow had been my escape.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4028,'I was recalled to myself by a frantic plucking at my wrist, and I found myself lying upon the stone floor of a narrow corridor, while a woman bent over me and tugged at me with her left hand, while she held a candle in her right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4029,'It was the same good friend whose warning I had so foolishly rejected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4030,'‘Come! come!’ she cried, breathlessly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4031,'‘They will be here in a moment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4032,'They will see that you are not there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4033,'Oh, do not waste the so-precious time, but come!’  This time, at least, I did not scorn her advice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4034,'I staggered to my feet and ran with her along the corridor and down a winding stair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4035,'The latter led to another broad passage, and, just as we reached it, we heard the sound of running feet and the shouting of two voices, one answering the other, from the floor on which we were and from the one beneath.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4036,'My guide stopped and looked about her like one who is at her wits’ end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4037,'Then she threw open a door which led into a bedroom, through the window of which the moon was shining brightly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4038,'‘It is your only chance,’ said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4039,'‘It is high, but it may be that you can jump it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4040,'’  As she spoke a light sprang into view at the further end of the passage, and I saw the lean figure of Colonel Lysander Stark rushing forward with a lantern in one hand and a weapon like a butcher’s cleaver in the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4041,'I rushed across the bedroom, flung open the window, and looked out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4042,'How quiet and sweet and wholesome the garden looked in the moonlight, and it could not be more than thirty feet down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4043,'I clambered out upon the sill, but I hesitated to jump until I should have heard what passed between my savior and the ruffian who pursued me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4044,'If she were ill-used, then at any risks I was determined to go back to her assistance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4045,'The thought had hardly flashed through my mind before he was at the door, pushing his way past her; but she threw her arms round him and tried to hold him back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4046,'‘Fritz! Fritz!’ she cried, in English, ‘remember your promise after the last time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4047,'You said it should not be again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4048,'He will be silent! Oh, he will be silent!’  ‘You are mad, Elise!’ he shouted, struggling to break away from her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4049,'‘You will be the ruin of us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4050,'He has seen too much.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4051,'Let me pass, I say!’ He dashed her to one side, and, rushing to the window, cut at me with his heavy weapon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4052,'I had let myself go, and was hanging by the hands to the sill, when his blow fell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4053,'I was conscious of a dull pain, my grip loosened, and I fell into the garden below.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4054,'I was shaken but not hurt by the fall; so I picked myself up and rushed off among the bushes as hard as I could run, for I understood that I was far from being out of danger yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4055,'Suddenly, however, as I ran, a deadly dizziness and sickness came over me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4056,'I glanced down at my hand, which was throbbing painfully, and then, for the first time, saw that my thumb had been cut off and that the blood was pouring from my wound.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4057,'I endeavored to tie my handkerchief round it, but there came a sudden buzzing in my ears, and next moment I fell in a dead faint among the rose-bushes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4058,'How long I remained unconscious I cannot tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4059,'It must have been a very long time, for the moon had sunk, and a bright morning was breaking when I came to myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4060,'My clothes were all sodden with dew, and my coat-sleeve was drenched with blood from my wounded thumb.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4061,'The smarting of it recalled in an instant all the particulars of my night’s adventure, and I sprang to my feet with the feeling that I might hardly yet be safe from my pursuers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4062,'But, to my astonishment, when I came to look round me, neither house nor garden were to be seen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4063,'I had been lying in an angle of the hedge close by the high-road, and just a little lower down was a long building, which proved, upon my approaching it, to be the very station at which I had arrived upon the previous night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4064,'Were it not for the ugly wound upon my hand, all that had passed during those dreadful hours might have been an evil dream.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4065,'Half dazed, I went into the station and asked about the morning train.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4066,'There would be one to Reading in less than an hour.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4067,'The same porter was on duty, I found, as had been there when I arrived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4068,'I inquired of him whether he had ever heard of Colonel Lysander Stark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4069,'The name was strange to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4070,'Had he observed a carriage the night before waiting for me? No, he had not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4071,'Was there a police-station anywhere near? There was one about three miles off.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4072,'It was too far for me to go, weak and ill as I was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4073,'I determined to wait until I got back to town before telling my story to the police.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4074,'It was a little past six when I arrived, so I went first to have my wound dressed, and then the doctor was kind enough to bring me along here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4075,'I put the case into your hands, and shall do exactly what you advise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4076,'We both sat in silence for some little time after, listening to this extraordinary narrative.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4077,'Then Sherlock Holmes pulled down from the shelf one of the ponderous commonplace books in which he placed his cuttings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4078,'Here is an advertisement which will interest you, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4079,'It appeared in all the papers about a year ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4080,'Listen to this: ‘Lost, on the 9th inst., Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4081,'Jeremiah Hayling, aged twenty-six, an hydraulic engineer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4082,'Left his lodgings at ten o’clock at night, and has not been heard of since.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4083,'Was dressed in,’ etc., etc.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4084,'Ha! That represents the last time that the colonel needed to have his machine overhauled, I fancy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4085,'Good heavens! cried my patient.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4086,'Then that explains what the girl said.  Undoubtedly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4087,'It is quite clear that the colonel was a cool and desperate man, who was absolutely determined that nothing should stand in the way of his little game, like those out-and-out pirates who will leave no survivor from a captured ship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4088,'Well, every moment now is precious, so if you feel equal to it, we shall go down to Scotland Yard at once as a preliminary to starting for Eyford.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4089,'Some three hours or so afterwards we were all in the train together, bound from Reading to the little Berkshire village.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4090,'There were Sherlock Holmes, the hydraulic engineer, Inspector Bradstreet, of Scotland Yard, a plain-clothes man, and myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4091,'Bradstreet had spread an ordnance map of the county out upon the seat, and was busy with his compasses drawing a circle with Eyford for its centre.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4092,'There you are, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4093,'That circle is drawn at a radius of ten miles from the village.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4094,'The place we want must be somewhere near that line.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4095,'You said ten miles, I think, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4096,'It was an hour’s good drive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4097,'And you think that they brought you back all that way when you were unconscious?  They must have done so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4098,'I have a confused memory, too, of having been lifted and conveyed somewhere.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4099,'What I cannot understand, said I, is why they should have spared you when they found you lying fainting in the garden.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4100,'Perhaps the villain was softened by the woman’s entreaties.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4101,'I hardly think that likely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4102,'I never saw a more inexorable face in my life.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4103,'Oh, we shall soon clear up all that, said Bradstreet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4104,'Well, I have drawn my circle, and I only wish I knew at what point upon it the folk that we are in search of are to be found.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4105,'I think I could lay my finger on it, said Holmes, quietly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4106,'Really, now! cried the inspector, you have formed your opinion! Come, now, we shall see who agrees with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4107,'I say it is south, for the country is more deserted there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4108,'And I say east, said my patient.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4109,'I am for west, remarked the plain-clothes man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4110,'There are several quiet little villages up there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4111,'And I am for north, said I, because there are no hills there, and our friend says that he did not notice the carriage go up any.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4112,'Come, cried the inspector, laughing; it’s a very pretty diversity of opinion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4113,'We have boxed the compass among us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4114,'Who do you give your casting vote to?  You are all wrong.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4115,'But we can’t _all_ be.  Oh yes, you can.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4116,'This is my point; he placed his finger in the centre of the circle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4117,'This is where we shall find them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4118,'But the twelve-mile drive? gasped Hatherley.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4119,'Six out and six back. Nothing simpler.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4120,'You say yourself that the horse was fresh and glossy when you got in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4121,'How could it be that if it had gone twelve miles over heavy roads?  Indeed, it is a likely ruse enough, observed Bradstreet, thoughtfully.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4122,'Of course there can be no doubt as to the nature of this gang.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4123,'None at all, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4124,'They are coiners on a large scale, and have used the machine to form the amalgam which has taken the place of silver.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4125,'We have known for some time that a clever gang was at work, said the inspector.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4126,'They have been turning out half-crowns by the thousand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4127,'We even traced them as far as Reading, but could get no farther, for they had covered their traces in a way that showed that they were very old hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4128,'But now, thanks to this lucky chance, I think that we have got them right enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4129,'But the inspector was mistaken, for those criminals were not destined to fall into the hands of justice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4130,'As we rolled into Eyford Station we saw a gigantic column of smoke which streamed up from behind a small clump of trees in the neighborhood, and hung like an immense ostrich feather over the landscape.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4131,'A house on fire? asked Bradstreet, as the train steamed off again on its way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4132,'Yes, sir! said the station-master.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4133,'When did it break out?  I hear that it was during the night, sir, but it has got worse, and the whole place is in a blaze.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4134,'Whose house is it?  Dr. Becher’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4135,'Tell me, broke in the engineer, is Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4136,'Becher a German, very thin, with a long, sharp nose?  The station-master laughed heartily. No, sir, Dr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4137,'Becher is an Englishman, and there isn’t a man in the parish who has a better-lined waistcoat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4138,'But he has a gentleman staying with him, a patient, as I understand, who is a foreigner, and he looks as if a little good Berkshire beef would do him no harm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4139,'The station-master had not finished his speech before we were all hastening in the direction of the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4140,'The road topped a low hill, and there was a great wide-spread whitewashed building in front of us, spouting fire at every chink and window, while in the garden in front three fire-engines were vainly striving to keep the flames under.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4141,'That’s it! cried Hatherley, in intense excitement.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4142,'There is the gravel-drive, and there are the rose-bushes where I lay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4143,'That second window is the one that I jumped from.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4144,'Well, at least, said Holmes, you have had your revenge upon them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4145,'There can be no question that it was your oil-lamp which, when it was crushed in the press, set fire to the wooden walls, though no doubt they were too excited in the chase after you to observe it at the time.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4146,'Now keep your eyes open in this crowd for your friends of last night, though I very much fear that they are a good hundred miles off by now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4147,'And Holmes’s fears came to be realized, for from that day to this no word has ever been heard either of the beautiful woman, the sinister German, or the morose Englishman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4148,'Early that morning a peasant had met a cart containing several people and some very bulky boxes driving rapidly in the direction of Reading, but there all traces of the fugitives disappeared, and even Holmes’s ingenuity failed ever to discover the least clew as to their whereabouts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4149,'The firemen had been much perturbed at the strange arrangements which they had found within, and still more so by discovering a newly severed human thumb upon a window-sill of the second floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4150,'About sunset, however, their efforts were at last successful, and they subdued the flames, but not before the roof had fallen in, and the whole place been reduced to such absolute ruin that, save some twisted cylinders and iron piping, not a trace remained of the machinery which had cost our unfortunate acquaintance so dearly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4151,'Large masses of nickel and of tin were discovered stored in an out-house, but no coins were to be found, which may have explained the presence of those bulky boxes which have been already referred to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4152,'How our hydraulic engineer had been conveyed from the garden to the spot where he recovered his senses might have remained forever a mystery were it not for the soft mould, which told us a very plain tale.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4153,'He had evidently been carried down by two persons, one of whom had remarkably small feet and the other unusually large ones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4154,'On the whole, it was most probable that the silent Englishman, being less bold or less murderous than his companion, had assisted the woman to bear the unconscious man out of the way of danger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4155,'Well, said our engineer ruefully, as we took our seats to return once more to London, it has been a pretty business for me! I have lost my thumb and I have lost a fifty-guinea fee, and what have I gained?  Experience, said Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4156,'Indirectly it may be of value, you know; you have only to put it into words to gain the reputation of being excellent company for the remainder of your existence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4157,'Adventure X  THE ADVENTURE OF THE NOBLE BACHELOR   The Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4158,'Simon marriage, and its curious termination, have long ceased to be a subject of interest in those exalted circles in which the unfortunate bridegroom moves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4159,'Fresh scandals have eclipsed it, and their more piquant details have drawn the gossips away from this four-year-old drama.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4160,'As I have reason to believe, however, that the full facts have never been revealed to the general public, and as my friend Sherlock Holmes had a considerable share in clearing the matter up, I feel that no memoir of him would be complete without some little sketch of this remarkable episode.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4161,'It was a few weeks before my own marriage, during the days when I was still sharing rooms with Holmes in Baker Street, that he came home from an afternoon stroll to find a letter on the table waiting for him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4162,'I had remained in-doors all day, for the weather had taken a sudden turn to rain, with high autumnal winds, and the jezail bullet which I had brought back in one of my limbs as a relic of my Afghan campaign, throbbed with dull persistency.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4163,'With my body in one easy-chair and my legs upon another, I had surrounded myself with a cloud of newspapers, until at last, saturated with the news of the day, I tossed them all aside and lay listless, watching the huge crest and monogram upon the envelope upon the table, and wondering lazily who my friend’s noble correspondent could be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4164,'Here is a very fashionable epistle, I remarked, as he entered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4165,'Your morning letters, if I remember right, were from a fish-monger and a tide-waiter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4166,'Yes, my correspondence has certainly the charm of variety, he answered, smiling, and the humbler are usually the more interesting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4167,'This looks like one of those unwelcome social summonses which call upon a man either to be bored or to lie.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4168,'He broke the seal and glanced over the contents.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4169,'Oh, come, it may prove to be something of interest after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4170,'Not social, then?  No, distinctly professional.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4171,'And from a noble client?  One of the highest in England.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4172,'My dear fellow, I congratulate you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4173,'I assure you, Watson, without affectation, that the status of my client is a matter of less moment to me than the interest of his case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4174,'It is just possible, however, that that also may not be wanting in this new investigation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4175,'You have been reading the papers diligently of late, have you not?  It looks like it, said I, ruefully, pointing to a huge bundle in the corner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4176,'I have had nothing else to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4177,'It is fortunate, for you will perhaps be able to post me up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4178,'I read nothing except the criminal news and the agony column.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4179,'The latter is always instructive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4180,'But if you have followed recent events so closely you must have read about Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4181,'Simon and his wedding?  Oh yes, with the deepest interest.  That is well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4182,'The letter which I hold in my hand is from Lord St. Simon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4183,'I will read it to you, and in return you must turn over these papers and let me have whatever bears upon the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4184,'This is what he says:    ‘MY DEAR MR.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4185,'SHERLOCK HOLMES,—Lord Backwater tells me that I   may place implicit reliance upon your judgment and discretion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4186,'I have determined, therefore, to call upon you, and to consult   you in reference to the very painful event which has occurred   in connection with my wedding. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4187,'Lestrade, of Scotland Yard,   is acting already in the matter, but he assures me that he sees   no objection to your co-operation, and that he even thinks that   it might be of some assistance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4188,'I will call at four o’clock in   the afternoon, and, should you have any other engagement at   that time, I hope that you will postpone it, as this matter is   of paramount importance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4189,'Yours faithfully,   ST. SIMON.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4190,'’  It is dated from Grosvenor Mansions, written with a quill pen, and the noble lord has had the misfortune to get a smear of ink upon the outer side of his right little finger, remarked Holmes, as he folded up the epistle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4191,'He says four o’clock. It is three now.');
