INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4239,'It is headed, ‘Singular Occurrence at a Fashionable Wedding’:  ‘The family of Lord Robert St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4240,'Simon has been thrown into the greatest consternation by the strange and painful episodes which have taken place in connection with his wedding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4241,'The ceremony, as shortly announced in the papers of yesterday, occurred on the previous morning; but it is only now that it has been possible to confirm the strange rumors which have been so persistently floating about.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4242,'In spite of the attempts of the friends to hush the matter up, so much public attention has now been drawn to it that no good purpose can be served by affecting to disregard what is a common subject for conversation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4243,'‘The ceremony, which was performed at St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4244,'George’s, Hanover Square, was a very quiet one, no one being present save the father of the bride, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4245,'Aloysius Doran, the Duchess of Balmoral, Lord Backwater, Lord Eustace, and Lady Clara St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4246,'Simon (the younger brother and sister of the bridegroom), and Lady Alicia Whittington.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4247,'The whole party proceeded afterwards to the house of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4248,'Aloysius Doran, at Lancaster Gate, where breakfast had been prepared.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4249,'It appears that some little trouble was caused by a woman, whose name has not been ascertained, who endeavored to force her way into the house after the bridal party, alleging that she had some claim upon Lord St. Simon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4250,'It was only after a painful and prolonged scene that she was ejected by the butler and the footman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4251,'The bride, who had fortunately entered the house before this unpleasant interruption, had sat down to breakfast with the rest, when she complained of a sudden indisposition, and retired to her room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4252,'Her prolonged absence having caused some comment, her father followed her, but learned from her maid that she had only come up to her chamber for an instant, caught up an ulster and bonnet, and hurried down to the passage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4253,'One of the footmen declared that he had seen a lady leave the house thus apparelled, but had refused to credit that it was his mistress, believing her to be with the company.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4254,'On ascertaining that his daughter had disappeared, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4255,'Aloysius Doran, in conjunction with the bridegroom, instantly put themselves into communication with the police, and very energetic inquiries are being made, which will probably result in a speedy clearing up of this very singular business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4256,'Up to a late hour last night, however, nothing had transpired as to the whereabouts of the missing lady.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4257,'There are rumors of foul play in the matter, and it is said that the police have caused the arrest of the woman who had caused the original disturbance, in the belief that, from jealousy or some other motive, she may have been concerned in the strange disappearance of the bride.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4258,'’  And is that all?  Only one little item in another of the morning papers, but it is a suggestive one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4259,'And it is—  That Miss Flora Millar, the lady who had caused the disturbance, has actually been arrested.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4260,'It appears that she was formerly a _danseuse_ at the ‘Allegro,’ and that she has known the bridegroom for some years.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4261,'There are no further particulars, and the whole case is in your hands now—so far as it has been set forth in the public press.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4262,'And an exceedingly interesting case it appears to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4263,'I would not have missed it for worlds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4264,'But there is a ring at the bell, Watson, and as the clock makes it a few minutes after four, I have no doubt that this will prove to be our noble client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4265,'Do not dream of going, Watson, for I very much prefer having a witness, if only as a check to my own memory.  Lord Robert St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4266,'Simon, announced our page-boy, throwing open the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4267,'A gentleman entered, with a pleasant, cultured face, high-nosed and pale, with something perhaps of petulance about the mouth, and with the steady, well-opened eye of a man whose pleasant lot it had ever been to command and to be obeyed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4268,'His manner was brisk, and yet his general appearance gave an undue impression of age, for he had a slight forward stoop and a little bend of the knees as he walked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4269,'His hair, too, as he swept off his very curly-brimmed hat, was grizzled round the edges and thin upon the top.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4270,'As to his dress, it was careful to the verge of foppishness, with high collar, black frock-coat, white waistcoat, yellow gloves, patent-leather shoes, and light-colored gaiters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4271,'He advanced slowly into the room, turning his head from left to right, and swinging in his right hand the cord which held his golden eye-glasses.  Good-day, Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4272,'Simon, said Holmes, rising and bowing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4273,'Pray take the basket-chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4274,'This is my friend and colleague, Dr. Watson.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4275,'Draw up a little to the fire, and we will talk this matter over.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4276,'A most painful matter to me, as you can most readily imagine, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4277,'I have been cut to the quick.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4278,'I understand that you have already managed several delicate cases of this sort, sir, though I presume that they were hardly from the same class of society.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4279,'No, I am descending.  I beg pardon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4280,'My last client of the sort was a king.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4281,'Oh, really! I had no idea.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4282,'And which king?  The King of Scandinavia.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4283,'What! Had he lost his wife?  You can understand, said Holmes, suavely, that I extend to the affairs of my other clients the same secrecy which I promise to you in yours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4284,'Of course! Very right! very right! I’m sure I beg pardon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4285,'As to my own case, I am ready to give you any information which may assist you in forming an opinion.  Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4286,'I have already learned all that is in the public prints, nothing more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4287,'I presume that I may take it as correct—this article, for example, as to the disappearance of the bride.  Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4288,'Simon glanced over it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4289,'Yes, it is correct, as far as it goes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4290,'But it needs a great deal of supplementing before any one could offer an opinion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4291,'I think that I may arrive at my facts most directly by questioning you.  Pray do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4292,'When did you first meet Miss Hatty Doran?  In San Francisco, a year ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4293,'You were travelling in the States?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4294,'Did you become engaged then?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4295,'But you were on a friendly footing?  I was amused by her society, and she could see that I was amused.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4296,'Her father is very rich?  He is said to be the richest man on the Pacific slope.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4297,'And how did he make his money?  In mining.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4298,'He had nothing a few years ago.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4299,'Then he struck gold, invested it, and came up by leaps and bounds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4300,'Now, what is your own impression as to the young lady’s—your wife’s character?  The nobleman swung his glasses a little faster and stared down into the fire. You see, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4301,'Holmes, said he, my wife was twenty before her father became a rich man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4302,'During that time she ran free in a mining camp, and wandered through woods or mountains, so that her education has come from Nature rather than from the school-master.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4303,'She is what we call in England a tomboy, with a strong nature, wild and free, unfettered by any sort of traditions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4304,'She is impetuous—volcanic, I was about to say.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4305,'She is swift in making up her mind, and fearless in carrying out her resolutions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4306,'On the other hand, I would not have given her the name which I have the honor to bear—he gave a little stately cough—had not I thought her to be at bottom a noble woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4307,'I believe that she is capable of heroic self-sacrifice, and that anything dishonorable would be repugnant to her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4308,'Have you her photograph?  I brought this with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4309,'He opened a locket, and showed us the full face of a very lovely woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4310,'It was not a photograph, but an ivory miniature, and the artist had brought out the full effect of the lustrous black hair, the large dark eyes, and the exquisite mouth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4311,'Holmes gazed long and earnestly at it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4312,'Then he closed the locket and handed it back to Lord St. Simon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4313,'The young lady came to London, then, and you renewed your acquaintance?  Yes, her father brought her over for this last London season.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4314,'I met her several times, became engaged to her, and have now married her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4315,'She brought, I understand, a considerable dowry?  A fair dowry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4316,'Not more than is usual in my family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4317,'And this, of course, remains to you, since the marriage is a _fait accompli_?  I really have made no inquiries on the subject.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4318,'Very naturally not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4319,'Did you see Miss Doran on the day before the wedding?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4320,'Was she in good spirits?  Never better.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4321,'She kept talking of what we should do in our future lives.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4322,'Indeed! That is very interesting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4323,'And on the morning of the wedding?  She was as bright as possible—at least, until after the ceremony.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4324,'And did you observe any change in her then?  Well, to tell the truth, I saw then the first signs that I had ever seen that her temper was just a little sharp.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4325,'The incident, however, was too trivial to relate, and can have no possible bearing upon the case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4326,'Pray let us have it, for all that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4327,'Oh, it is childish.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4328,'She dropped her bouquet as we went towards the vestry.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4329,'She was passing the front pew at the time, and it fell over into the pew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4330,'There was a moment’s delay, but the gentleman in the pew handed it up to her again, and it did not appear to be the worse for the fall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4331,'Yet, when I spoke to her of the matter, she answered me abruptly; and in the carriage, on our way home, she seemed absurdly agitated over this trifling cause.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4332,'Indeed! You say that there was a gentleman in the pew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4333,'Some of the general public were present, then?  Oh yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4334,'It is impossible to exclude them when the church is open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4335,'This gentleman was not one of your wife’s friends?  No, no; I call him a gentleman by courtesy, but he was quite a common-looking person.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4336,'I hardly noticed his appearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4337,'But really I think that we are wandering rather far from the point.  Lady St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4338,'Simon, then, returned from the wedding in a less cheerful frame of mind than she had gone to it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4339,'What did she do on re-entering her father’s house?  I saw her in conversation with her maid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4340,'And who is her maid?  Alice is her name.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4341,'She is an American, and came from California with her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4342,'A confidential servant?  A little too much so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4343,'It seemed to me that her mistress allowed her to take great liberties.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4344,'Still, of course, in America they look upon these things in a different way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4345,'How long did she speak to this Alice?  Oh, a few minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4346,'I had something else to think of.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4347,'You did not overhear what they said?  Lady St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4348,'Simon said something about ‘jumping a claim.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4349,'’ She was accustomed to use slang of the kind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4350,'I have no idea what she meant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4351,'American slang is very expressive sometimes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4352,'And what did your wife do when she finished speaking to her maid?  She walked into the breakfast-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4353,'On your arm?  No, alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4354,'She was very independent in little matters like that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4355,'Then, after we had sat down for ten minutes or so, she rose hurriedly, muttered some words of apology, and left the room. She never came back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4356,'But this maid, Alice, as I understand, deposes that she went to her room, covered her bride’s dress with a long ulster, put on a bonnet, and went out.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4357,'And she was afterwards seen walking into Hyde Park in company with Flora Millar, a woman who is now in custody, and who had already made a disturbance at Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4358,'Doran’s house that morning.  Ah, yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4359,'I should like a few particulars as to this young lady, and your relations to her.  Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4360,'Simon shrugged his shoulders and raised his eyebrows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4361,'We have been on a friendly footing for some years—I may say on a _very_ friendly footing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4362,'She used to be at the ‘Allegro.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4363,'’ I have not treated her ungenerously, and she has no just cause of complaint against me; but you know what women are, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4364,'Flora was a dear little thing, but exceedingly hot-headed, and devotedly attached to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4365,'She wrote me dreadful letters when she heard that I was about to be married; and, to tell the truth, the reason why I had the marriage celebrated so quietly was that I feared lest there might be a scandal in the church. She came to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4366,'Doran’s door just after we returned, and she endeavored to push her way in, uttering very abusive expressions towards my wife, and even threatening her, but I had foreseen the possibility of something of the sort, and I had two police fellows there in private clothes, who soon pushed her out again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4367,'She was quiet when she saw that there was no good in making a row.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4368,'Did your wife hear all this?  No, thank goodness, she did not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4369,'And she was seen walking with this very woman afterwards?  Yes. That is what Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4370,'Lestrade, of Scotland Yard, looks upon as so serious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4371,'It is thought that Flora decoyed my wife out, and laid some terrible trap for her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4372,'Well, it is a possible supposition.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4373,'You think so, too?  I did not say a probable one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4374,'But you do not yourself look upon this as likely?  I do not think Flora would hurt a fly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4375,'Still, jealousy is a strange transformer of characters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4376,'Pray what is your own theory as to what took place?  Well, really, I came to seek a theory, not to propound one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4377,'I have given you all the facts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4378,'Since you ask me, however, I may say that it has occurred to me as possible that the excitement of this affair, the consciousness that she had made so immense a social stride, had the effect of causing some little nervous disturbance in my wife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4379,'In short, that she had become suddenly deranged?  Well, really, when I consider that she has turned her back—I will not say upon me, but upon so much that many have aspired to without success—I can hardly explain it in any other fashion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4380,'Well, certainly that is also a conceivable hypothesis, said Holmes, smiling. And now, Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4381,'Simon, I think that I have nearly all my data.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4382,'May I ask whether you were seated at the breakfast-table so that you could see out of the window?  We could see the other side of the road and the Park.  Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4383,'Then I do not think that I need to detain you longer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4384,'I shall communicate with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4385,'Should you be fortunate enough to solve this problem, said our client, rising.  I have solved it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4386,'Eh? What was that?  I say that I have solved it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4387,'Where, then, is my wife?  That is a detail which I shall speedily supply.  Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4388,'Simon shook his head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4389,'I am afraid that it will take wiser heads than yours or mine, he remarked, and bowing in a stately, old-fashioned manner, he departed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4390,'It is very good of Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4391,'Simon to honor my head by putting it on a level with his own, said Sherlock Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4392,'I think that I shall have a whiskey-and-soda and a cigar after all this cross-questioning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4393,'I had formed my conclusions as to the case before our client came into the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4394,'My dear Holmes!  I have notes of several similar cases, though none, as I remarked before, which were quite as prompt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4395,'My whole examination served to turn my conjecture into a certainty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4396,'Circumstantial evidence is occasionally very convincing, as when you find a trout in the milk, to quote Thoreau’s example.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4397,'But I have heard all that you have heard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4398,'Without, however, the knowledge of pre-existing cases which serves me so well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4399,'There was a parallel instance in Aberdeen some years back, and something on very much the same lines at Munich the year after the Franco-Prussian war.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4400,'It is one of these cases—but, hello, here is Lestrade! Good-afternoon, Lestrade! You will find an extra tumbler upon the sideboard, and there are cigars in the box.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4401,'The official detective was attired in a pea-jacket and cravat, which gave him a decidedly nautical appearance, and he carried a black canvas bag in his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4402,'With a short greeting he seated himself and lit the cigar which had been offered to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4403,'What’s up, then? asked Holmes, with a twinkle in his eye.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4404,'You look dissatisfied.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4405,'And I feel dissatisfied.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4406,'It is this infernal St. Simon marriage case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4407,'I can make neither head nor tail of the business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4408,'Really! You surprise me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4409,'Who ever heard of such a mixed affair? Every clew seems to slip through my fingers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4410,'I have been at work upon it all day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4411,'And very wet it seems to have made you, said Holmes, laying his hand upon the arm of the pea-jacket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4412,'Yes, I have been dragging the Serpentine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4413,'In Heaven’s name, what for?  In search of the body of Lady St. Simon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4414,'Sherlock Holmes leaned back in his chair and laughed heartily.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4415,'Have you dragged the basin of Trafalgar Square fountain? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4416,'Why? What do you mean?  Because you have just as good a chance of finding this lady in the one as in the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4417,'Lestrade shot an angry glance at my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4418,'I suppose you know all about it, he snarled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4419,'Well, I have only just heard the facts, but my mind is made up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4420,'Oh, indeed! Then you think that the Serpentine plays no part in the matter?  I think it very unlikely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4421,'Then perhaps you will kindly explain how it is that we found this in it? He opened his bag as he spoke, and tumbled onto the floor a wedding-dress of watered silk, a pair of white satin shoes, and a bride’s wreath and veil, all discolored and soaked in water.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4422,'There, said he, putting a new wedding-ring upon the top of the pile.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4423,'There is a little nut for you to crack, Master Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4424,'Oh, indeed! said my friend, blowing blue rings into the air.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4425,'You dragged them from the Serpentine?  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4426,'They were found floating near the margin by a park-keeper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4427,'They have been identified as her clothes, and it seemed to me that if the clothes were there the body would not be far off.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4428,'By the same brilliant reasoning, every man’s body is to be found in the neighborhood of his wardrobe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4429,'And pray what did you hope to arrive at through this?  At some evidence implicating Flora Millar in the disappearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4430,'I am afraid that you will find it difficult.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4431,'Are you, indeed, now? cried Lestrade, with some bitterness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4432,'I am afraid, Holmes, that you are not very practical with your deductions and your inferences.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4433,'You have made two blunders in as many minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4434,'This dress does implicate Miss Flora Millar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4435,'And how?  In the dress is a pocket.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4436,'In the pocket is a card-case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4437,'In the card-case is a note.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4438,'And here is the very note.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4439,'He slapped it down upon the table in front of him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4440,'Listen to this: ‘You will see me when all is ready. Come at once. F. H. M.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4441,'’ Now my theory all along has been that Lady St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4442,'Simon was decoyed away by Flora Millar, and that she, with confederates, no doubt, was responsible for her disappearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4443,'Here, signed with her initials, is the very note which was no doubt quietly slipped into her hand at the door, and which lured her within their reach.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4444,'Very good, Lestrade, said Holmes, laughing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4445,'You really are very fine indeed. Let me see it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4446,'He took up the paper in a listless way, but his attention instantly became riveted, and he gave a little cry of satisfaction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4447,'This is indeed important, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4448,'Ha! you find it so?  Extremely so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4449,'I congratulate you warmly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4450,'Lestrade rose in his triumph and bent his head to look.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4451,'Why, he shrieked, you’re looking at the wrong side!  On the contrary, this is the right side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4452,'The right side? You’re mad! Here is the note written in pencil over here.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4453,'And over here is what appears to be the fragment of a hotel bill, which interests me deeply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4454,'There’s nothing in it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4455,'I looked at it before, said Lestrade. ‘Oct. 4th, rooms 8_s._, breakfast 2_s._ 6_d._, cocktail 1_s._, lunch 2_s._ 6_d._, glass sherry, 8_d.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4456,'_’ I see nothing in that.  Very likely not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4457,'It is most important, all the same.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4458,'As to the note, it is important also, or at least the initials are, so I congratulate you again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4459,'I’ve wasted time enough, said Lestrade, rising.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4460,'I believe in hard work, and not in sitting by the fire spinning fine theories. Good-day, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4461,'Holmes, and we shall see which gets to the bottom of the matter first.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4462,'He gathered up the garments, thrust them into the bag, and made for the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4463,'Just one hint to you, Lestrade, drawled Holmes, before his rival vanished; I will tell you the true solution of the matter. Lady St. Simon is a myth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4464,'There is not, and there never has been, any such person.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4465,'Lestrade looked sadly at my companion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4466,'Then he turned to me, tapped his forehead three times, shook his head solemnly, and hurried away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4467,'He had hardly shut the door behind him when Holmes rose and put on his overcoat.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4468,'There is something in what the fellow says about out-door work, he remarked, so I think, Watson, that I must leave you to your papers for a little.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4469,'It was after five o’clock when Sherlock Holmes left me, but I had no time to be lonely, for within an hour there arrived a confectioner’s man with a very large flat box.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4470,'This he unpacked with the help of a youth whom he had brought with him, and presently, to my very great astonishment, a quite epicurean little cold supper began to be laid out upon our humble lodging-house mahogany.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4471,'There were a couple of brace of cold woodcock, a pheasant, a _pâté de foie gras_ pie, with a group of ancient and cobwebby bottles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4472,'Having laid out all these luxuries, my two visitors vanished away, like the genii of the Arabian Nights, with no explanation save that the things had been paid for and were ordered to this address.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4473,'Just before nine o’clock Sherlock Holmes stepped briskly into the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4474,'His features were gravely set, but there was a light in his eye which made me think that he had not been disappointed in his conclusions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4475,'They have laid the supper, then, he said, rubbing his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4476,'You seem to expect company.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4477,'They have laid for five.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4478,'Yes, I fancy we may have some company dropping in, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4479,'I am surprised that Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4480,'Simon has not already arrived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4481,'Ha! I fancy that I hear his step now upon the stairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4482,'It was indeed our visitor of the morning who came bustling in, dangling his glasses more vigorously than ever, and with a very perturbed expression upon his aristocratic features.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4483,'My messenger reached you, then? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4484,'Yes, and I confess that the contents startled me beyond measure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4485,'Have you good authority for what you say?  The best possible.  Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4486,'Simon sank into a chair and passed his hand over his forehead.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4487,'What will the duke say, he murmured, when he hears that one of the family has been subjected to such humiliation?  It is the purest accident.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4488,'I cannot allow that there is any humiliation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4489,'Ah, you look on these things from another stand-point.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4490,'I fail to see that any one is to blame.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4491,'I can hardly see how the lady could have acted otherwise, though her abrupt method of doing it was undoubtedly to be regretted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4492,'Having no mother, she had no one to advise her at such a crisis.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4493,'It was a slight, sir, a public slight, said Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4494,'Simon, tapping his fingers upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4495,'You must make allowance for this poor girl, placed in so unprecedented a position.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4496,'I will make no allowance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4497,'I am very angry indeed, and I have been shamefully used.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4498,'I think that I heard a ring, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4499,'Yes, there are steps on the landing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4500,'If I cannot persuade you to take a lenient view of the matter, Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4501,'Simon, I have brought an advocate here who may be more successful.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4502,'He opened the door and ushered in a lady and gentleman. Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4503,'Simon, said he, allow me to introduce you to Mr. and Mrs. Francis Hay Moulton.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4504,'The lady, I think, you have already met.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4505,'At the sight of these new-comers our client had sprung from his seat and stood very erect, with his eyes cast down and his hand thrust into the breast of his frock-coat, a picture of offended dignity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4506,'The lady had taken a quick step forward and had held out her hand to him, but he still refused to raise his eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4507,'It was as well for his resolution, perhaps, for her pleading face was one which it was hard to resist.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4508,'You’re angry, Robert, said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4509,'Well, I guess you have every cause to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4510,'Pray make no apology to me, said Lord St. Simon, bitterly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4511,'Oh yes, I know that I have treated you real bad, and that I should have spoken to you before I went; but I was kind of rattled, and from the time when I saw Frank here again I just didn’t know what I was doing or saying.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4512,'I only wonder I didn’t fall down and do a faint right there before the altar.  Perhaps, Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4513,'Moulton, you would like my friend and me to leave the room while you explain this matter?  If I may give an opinion, remarked the strange gentleman, we’ve had just a little too much secrecy over this business already.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4514,'For my part, I should like all Europe and America to hear the rights of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4515,'He was a small, wiry, sunburnt man, clean shaven, with a sharp face and alert manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4516,'Then I’ll tell our story right away, said the lady.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4517,'Frank here and I met in ’84, in McQuire’s camp, near the Rockies, where pa was working a claim.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4518,'We were engaged to each other, Frank and I; but then one day father struck a rich pocket and made a pile, while poor Frank here had a claim that petered out and came to nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4519,'The richer pa grew, the poorer was Frank; so at last pa wouldn’t hear of our engagement lasting any longer, and he took me away to ’Frisco.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4520,'Frank wouldn’t throw up his hand, though; so he followed me there, and he saw me without pa knowing anything about it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4521,'It would only have made him mad to know, so we just fixed it all up for ourselves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4522,'Frank said that he would go and make his pile, too, and never come back to claim me until he had as much as pa.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4523,'So then I promised to wait for him to the end of time, and pledged myself not to marry any one else while he lived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4524,'‘Why shouldn’t we be married right away, then,’ said he, ‘and then I will feel sure of you; and I won’t claim to be your husband until I come back?’ Well, we talked it over, and he had fixed it all up so nicely, with a clergyman all ready in waiting, that we just did it right there; and then Frank went off to seek his fortune, and I went back to pa.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4525,'The next I heard of Frank was that he was in Montana, and then he went prospecting in Arizona, and then I heard of him from New Mexico.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4526,'After that came a long newspaper story about how a miners’ camp had been attacked by Apache Indians, and there was my Frank’s name among the killed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4527,'I fainted dead away, and I was very sick for months after.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4528,'Pa thought I had a decline, and took me to half the doctors in ’Frisco.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4529,'Not a word of news came for a year and more, so that I never doubted that Frank was really dead. Then Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4530,'Simon came to ’Frisco, and we came to London, and a marriage was arranged, and pa was very pleased, but I felt all the time that no man on this earth would ever take the place in my heart that had been given to my poor Frank.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4531,'Still, if I had married Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4532,'Simon, of course I’d have done my duty by him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4533,'We can’t command our love, but we can our actions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4534,'I went to the altar with him with the intention to make him just as good a wife as it was in me to be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4535,'But you may imagine what I felt when, just as I came to the altar rails, I glanced back and saw Frank standing and looking at me out of the first pew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4536,'I thought it was his ghost at first; but when I looked again, there he was still, with a kind of question in his eyes as if to ask me whether I were glad or sorry to see him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4537,'I wonder I didn’t drop.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4538,'I know that everything was turning round, and the words of the clergyman were just like the buzz of a bee in my ear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4539,'I didn’t know what to do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4540,'Should I stop the service and make a scene in the church? I glanced at him again, and he seemed to know what I was thinking, for he raised his finger to his lips to tell me to be still.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4541,'Then I saw him scribble on a piece of paper, and I knew that he was writing me a note.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4542,'As I passed his pew on the way out I dropped my bouquet over to him, and he slipped the note into my hand when he returned me the flowers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4543,'It was only a line asking me to join him when he made the sign to me to do so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4544,'Of course I never doubted for a moment that my first duty was now to him, and I determined to do just whatever he might direct.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4545,'When I got back I told my maid, who had known him in California, and had always been his friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4546,'I ordered her to say nothing, but to get a few things packed and my ulster ready.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4547,'I know I ought to have spoken to Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4548,'Simon, but it was dreadful hard before his mother and all those great people.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4549,'I just made up my mind to run away and explain afterwards.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4550,'I hadn’t been at the table ten minutes before I saw Frank out of the window at the other side of the road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4551,'He beckoned to me, and then began walking into the Park.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4552,'I slipped out, put on my things, and followed him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4553,'Some woman came talking something or other about Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4554,'Simon to me—seemed to me from the little I heard as if he had a little secret of his own before marriage also—but I managed to get away from her, and soon overtook Frank.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4555,'We got into a cab together, and away we drove to some lodgings he had taken in Gordon Square, and that was my true wedding after all those years of waiting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4556,'Frank had been a prisoner among the Apaches, had escaped, came on to ’Frisco, found that I had given him up for dead and had gone to England, followed me there, and had come upon me at last on the very morning of my second wedding.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4557,'I saw it in a paper, explained the American.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4558,'It gave the name and the church, but not where the lady lived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4559,'Then we had a talk as to what we should do, and Frank was all for openness, but I was so ashamed of it all that I felt as if I should like to vanish away and never see any of them again—just sending a line to pa, perhaps, to show him that I was alive.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4560,'It was awful to me to think of all those lords and ladies sitting round that breakfast-table and waiting for me to come back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4561,'So Frank took my wedding-clothes and things and made a bundle of them, so that I should not be traced, and dropped them away somewhere where no one could find them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4562,'It is likely that we should have gone on to Paris to-morrow, only that this good gentleman, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4563,'Holmes, came round to us this evening, though how he found us is more than I can think, and he showed us very clearly and kindly that I was wrong and that Frank was right, and that we should be putting ourselves in the wrong if we were so secret.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4564,'Then he offered to give us a chance of talking to Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4565,'Simon alone, and so we came right away round to his rooms at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4566,'Now, Robert, you have heard it all, and I am very sorry if I have given you pain, and I hope that you do not think very meanly of me.  Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4567,'Simon had by no means relaxed his rigid attitude, but had listened with a frowning brow and a compressed lip to this long narrative.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4568,'Excuse me, he said, but it is not my custom to discuss my most intimate personal affairs in this public manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4569,'Then you won’t forgive me? You won’t shake hands before I go?  Oh, certainly, if it would give you any pleasure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4570,'He put out his hand and coldly grasped that which she extended to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4571,'I had hoped, suggested Holmes, that you would have joined us in a friendly supper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4572,'I think that there you ask a little too much, responded his lordship.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4573,'I may be forced to acquiesce in these recent developments, but I can hardly be expected to make merry over them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4574,'I think that, with your permission, I will now wish you all a very good-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4575,'He included us all in a sweeping bow and stalked out of the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4576,'Then I trust that you at least will honor me with your company, said Sherlock Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4577,'It is always a joy to meet an American, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4578,'Moulton, for I am one of those who believe that the folly of a monarch and the blundering of a minister in far-gone years will not prevent our children from being some day citizens of the same world-wide country under a flag which shall be a quartering of the Union Jack with the Stars and Stripes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4579,'*       *       *       *       *  The case has been an interesting one, remarked Holmes, when our visitors had left us, because it serves to show very clearly how simple the explanation may be of an affair which at first sight seems to be almost inexplicable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4580,'Nothing could be more natural than the sequence of events as narrated by this lady, and nothing stranger than the result when viewed, for instance, by Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4581,'Lestrade, of Scotland Yard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4582,'[Illustration: ‘I WILL WISH YOU ALL A VERY GOOD NIGHT.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4583,'’]  You were not yourself at fault at all, then?  From the first, two facts were very obvious to me, the one that the lady had been quite willing to undergo the wedding ceremony, the other that she had repented of it within a few minutes of returning home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4584,'Obviously something had occurred during the morning, then, to cause her to change her mind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4585,'What could that something be? She could not have spoken to any one when she was out, for she had been in the company of the bridegroom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4586,'Had she seen some one, then? If she had, it must be some one from America, because she had spent so short a time in this country that she could hardly have allowed any one to acquire so deep an influence over her that the mere sight of him would induce her to change her plans so completely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4587,'You see we have already arrived, by a process of exclusion, at the idea that she might have seen an American.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4588,'Then who could this American be, and why should he possess so much influence over her? It might be a lover; it might be a husband.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4589,'Her young womanhood had, I knew, been spent in rough scenes and under strange conditions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4590,'So far I had got before I ever heard Lord St. Simon’s narrative.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4591,'When he told us of a man in a pew, of the change in the bride’s manner, of so transparent a device for obtaining a note as the dropping of a bouquet, of her resort to her confidential maid, and of her very significant allusion to claim-jumping—which in miners’ parlance means taking possession of that which another person has a prior claim to—the whole situation became absolutely clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4592,'She had gone off with a man, and the man was either a lover or was a previous husband—the chances being in favor of the latter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4593,'And how in the world did you find them?  It might have been difficult, but friend Lestrade held information in his hands the value of which he did not himself know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4594,'The initials were of course of the highest importance, but more valuable still was it to know that within a week he had settled his bill at one of the most select London hotels.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4595,'How did you deduce the select?  By the select prices.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4596,'Eight shillings for a bed and eight-pence for a glass of sherry pointed to one of the most expensive hotels.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4597,'There are not many in London which charge at that rate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4598,'In the second one which I visited in Northumberland Avenue, I learned by an inspection of the book that Francis H.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4599,'Moulton, an American gentleman, had left only the day before, and on looking over the entries against him, I came upon the very items which I had seen in the duplicate bill.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4600,'His letters were to be forwarded to 226 Gordon Square; so thither I travelled, and being fortunate enough to find the loving couple at home, I ventured to give them some paternal advice, and to point out to them that it would be better in every way that they should make their position a little clearer both to the general public and to Lord St. Simon in particular.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4601,'I invited them to meet him here, and, as you see, I made him keep the appointment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4602,'But with no very good result, I remarked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4603,'His conduct was certainly not very gracious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4604,'Ah, Watson, said Holmes, smiling, perhaps you would not be very gracious either, if, after all the trouble of wooing and wedding, you found yourself deprived in an instant of wife and of fortune.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4605,'I think that we may judge Lord St.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4606,'Simon very mercifully, and thank our stars that we are never likely to find ourselves in the same position.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4607,'Draw your chair up, and hand me my violin, for the only problem we have still to solve is how to while away these bleak autumnal evenings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4608,'Adventure XI  THE ADVENTURE OF THE BERYL CORONET   Holmes, said I, as I stood one morning in our bow-window looking down the street, here is a madman coming along.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4609,'It seems rather sad that his relatives should allow him to come out alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4610,'My friend rose lazily from his arm-chair and stood with his hands in the pockets of his dressing-gown, looking over my shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4611,'It was a bright, crisp February morning, and the snow of the day before still lay deep upon the ground, shimmering brightly in the wintry sun.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4612,'Down the centre of Baker Street it had been ploughed into a brown crumbly band by the traffic, but at either side and on the heaped-up edges of the foot-paths it still lay as white as when it fell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4613,'The gray pavement had been cleaned and scraped, but was still dangerously slippery, so that there were fewer passengers than usual.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4614,'Indeed, from the direction of the Metropolitan Station no one was coming save the single gentleman whose eccentric conduct had drawn my attention.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4615,'He was a man of about fifty, tall, portly, and imposing, with a massive, strongly marked face and a commanding figure.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4616,'He was dressed in a sombre yet rich style, in black frock-coat, shining hat, neat brown gaiters, and well-cut pearl-gray trousers.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4617,'Yet his actions were in absurd contrast to the dignity of his dress and features, for he was running hard, with occasional little springs, such as a weary man gives who is little accustomed to set any tax upon his legs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4618,'As he ran he jerked his hands up and down, waggled his head, and writhed his face into the most extraordinary contortions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4619,'What on earth can be the matter with him? I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4620,'He is looking up at the numbers of the houses.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4621,'I believe that he is coming here, said Holmes, rubbing his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4622,'Here?  Yes; I rather think he is coming to consult me professionally.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4623,'I think that I recognize the symptoms.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4624,'Ha! did I not tell you? As he spoke, the man, puffing and blowing, rushed at our door and pulled at our bell until the whole house resounded with the clanging.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4625,'A few moments later he was in our room, still puffing, still gesticulating, but with so fixed a look of grief and despair in his eyes that our smiles were turned in an instant to horror and pity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4626,'For a while he could not get his words out, but swayed his body and plucked at his hair like one who has been driven to the extreme limits of his reason.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4627,'Then, suddenly springing to his feet, he beat his head against the wall with such force that we both rushed upon him and tore him away to the centre of the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4628,'Sherlock Holmes pushed him down into the easy-chair, and, sitting beside him, patted his hand, and chatted with him in the easy, soothing tones which he knew so well how to employ.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4629,'You have come to me to tell your story, have you not? said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4630,'You are fatigued with your haste.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4631,'Pray wait until you have recovered yourself, and then I shall be most happy to look into any little problem which you may submit to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4632,'The man sat for a minute or more with a heaving chest, fighting against his emotion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4633,'Then he passed his handkerchief over his brow, set his lips tight, and turned his face towards us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4634,'No doubt you think me mad? said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4635,'I see that you have had some great trouble, responded Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4636,'God knows I have!—a trouble which is enough to unseat my reason, so sudden and so terrible is it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4637,'Public disgrace I might have faced, although I am a man whose character has never yet borne a stain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4638,'Private affliction also is the lot of every man; but the two coming together, and in so frightful a form, have been enough to shake my very soul.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4639,'Besides, it is not I alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4640,'The very noblest in the land may suffer, unless some way be found out of this horrible affair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4641,'Pray compose yourself, sir, said Holmes, and let me have a clear account of who you are, and what it is that has befallen you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4642,'My name, answered our visitor, is probably familiar to your ears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4643,'I am Alexander Holder, of the banking firm of Holder & Stevenson, of Threadneedle Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4644,'The name was indeed well known to us as belonging to the senior partner in the second largest private banking concern in the City of London.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4645,'What could have happened, then, to bring one of the foremost citizens of London to this most pitiable pass? We waited, all curiosity, until with another effort he braced himself to tell his story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4646,'I feel that time is of value, said he; that is why I hastened here when the police inspector suggested that I should secure your co-operation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4647,'I came to Baker Street by the Underground, and hurried from there on foot, for the cabs go slowly through this snow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4648,'That is why I was so out of breath, for I am a man who takes very little exercise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4649,'I feel better now, and I will put the facts before you as shortly and yet as clearly as I can.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4650,'It is, of course, well known to you that in a successful banking business as much depends upon our being able to find remunerative investments for our funds as upon our increasing our connection and the number of our depositors.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4651,'One of our most lucrative means of laying out money is in the shape of loans, where the security is unimpeachable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4652,'We have done a good deal in this direction during the last few years, and there are many noble families to whom we have advanced large sums upon the security of their pictures, libraries, or plate.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4653,'Yesterday morning I was seated in my office at the bank when a card was brought in to me by one of the clerks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4654,'I started when I saw the name, for it was that of none other than—well, perhaps even to you I had better say no more than that it was a name which is a household word all over the earth—one of the highest, noblest, most exalted names in England.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4655,'I was overwhelmed by the honor, and attempted, when he entered, to say so, but he plunged at once into business with the air of a man who wishes to hurry quickly through a disagreeable task.  ‘Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4656,'Holder,’ said he, ‘I have been informed that you are in the habit of advancing money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4657,'’  ‘The firm do so when the security is good,’ I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4658,'‘It is absolutely essential to me,’ said he, ‘that I should have £50,000 at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4659,'I could of course borrow so trifling a sum ten times over from my friends, but I much prefer to make it a matter of business, and to carry out that business myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4660,'In my position you can readily understand that it is unwise to place one’s self under obligations.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4661,'’  ‘For how long, may I ask, do you want this sum?’ I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4662,'‘Next Monday I have a large sum due to me, and I shall then most certainly repay what you advance, with whatever interest you think it right to charge.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4663,'But it is very essential to me that the money should be paid at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4664,'’  ‘I should be happy to advance it without further parley from my own private purse,’ said I, ‘were it not that the strain would be rather more than it could bear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4665,'If, on the other hand, I am to do it in the name of the firm, then in justice to my partner I must insist that, even in your case, every business-like precaution should be taken.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4666,'’  ‘I should much prefer to have it so,’ said he, raising up a square, black morocco case which he had laid beside his chair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4667,'‘You have doubtless heard of the Beryl Coronet?’  ‘One of the most precious public possessions of the empire,’ said I.  ‘Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4668,'’ He opened the case, and there, imbedded in soft, flesh-colored velvet, lay the magnificent piece of jewelry which he had named.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4669,'‘There are thirty-nine enormous beryls,’ said he, ‘and the price of the gold chasing is incalculable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4670,'The lowest estimate would put the worth of the coronet at double the sum which I have asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4671,'I am prepared to leave it with you as my security.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4672,'’  I took the precious case into my hands and looked in some perplexity from it to my illustrious client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4673,'‘You doubt its value?’ he asked.  ‘Not at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4674,'I only doubt—’  ‘The propriety of my leaving it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4675,'You may set your mind at rest about that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4676,'I should not dream of doing so were it not absolutely certain that I should be able in four days to reclaim it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4677,'It is a pure matter of form.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4678,'Is the security sufficient?’  ‘Ample.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4679,'’  ‘You understand, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4680,'Holder, that I am giving you a strong proof of the confidence which I have in you, founded upon all that I have heard of you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4681,'I rely upon you not only to be discreet and to refrain from all gossip upon the matter, but, above all, to preserve this coronet with every possible precaution, because I need not say that a great public scandal would be caused if any harm were to befall it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4682,'Any injury to it would be almost as serious as its complete loss, for there are no beryls in the world to match these, and it would be impossible to replace them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4683,'I leave it with you, however, with every confidence, and I shall call for it in person on Monday morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4684,'’  Seeing that my client was anxious to leave, I said no more; but, calling for my cashier, I ordered him to pay over fifty £1000 notes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4685,'When I was alone once more, however, with the precious case lying upon the table in front of me, I could not but think with some misgivings of the immense responsibility which it entailed upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4686,'There could be no doubt that, as it was a national possession, a horrible scandal would ensue if any misfortune should occur to it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4687,'I already regretted having ever consented to take charge of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4688,'However, it was too late to alter the matter now, so I locked it up in my private safe, and turned once more to my work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4689,'When evening came I felt that it would be an imprudence to leave so precious a thing in the office behind me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4690,'Bankers’ safes had been forced before now, and why should not mine be? If so, how terrible would be the position in which I should find myself! I determined, therefore, that for the next few days I would always carry the case backward and forward with me, so that it might never be really out of my reach.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4691,'With this intention, I called a cab, and drove out to my house at Streatham, carrying the jewel with me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4692,'I did not breathe freely until I had taken it up-stairs and locked it in the bureau of my dressing-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4693,'And now a word as to my household, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4694,'Holmes, for I wish you to thoroughly understand the situation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4695,'My groom and my page sleep out of the house, and may be set aside altogether.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4696,'I have three maid-servants who have been with me a number of years, and whose absolute reliability is quite above suspicion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4697,'Another, Lucy Parr, the second waiting-maid, has only been in my service a few months.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4698,'She came with an excellent character, however, and has always given me satisfaction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4699,'She is a very pretty girl, and has attracted admirers who have occasionally hung about the place.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4700,'That is the only drawback which we have found to her, but we believe her to be a thoroughly good girl in every way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4701,'So much for the servants.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4702,'My family itself is so small that it will not take me long to describe it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4703,'I am a widower, and have an only son, Arthur.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4704,'He has been a disappointment to me, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4705,'Holmes—a grievous disappointment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4706,'I have no doubt that I am myself to blame.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4707,'People tell me that I have spoiled him. Very likely I have.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4708,'When my dear wife died I felt that he was all I had to love.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4709,'I could not bear to see the smile fade even for a moment from his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4710,'I have never denied him a wish.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4711,'Perhaps it would have been better for both of us had I been sterner, but I meant it for the best.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4712,'It was naturally my intention that he should succeed me in my business, but he was not of a business turn.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4713,'He was wild, wayward, and, to speak the truth, I could not trust him in the handling of large sums of money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4714,'When he was young he became a member of an aristocratic club, and there, having charming manners, he was soon the intimate of a number of men with long purses and expensive habits.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4715,'He learned to play heavily at cards and to squander money on the turf, until he had again and again to come to me and implore me to give him an advance upon his allowance, that he might settle his debts of honor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4716,'He tried more than once to break away from the dangerous company which he was keeping, but each time the influence of his friend Sir George Burnwell was enough to draw him back again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4717,'And, indeed, I could not wonder that such a man as Sir George Burnwell should gain an influence over him, for he has frequently brought him to my house, and I have found myself that I could hardly resist the fascination of his manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4718,'He is older than Arthur, a man of the world to his finger-tips, one who had been everywhere, seen everything, a brilliant talker, and a man of great personal beauty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4719,'Yet when I think of him in cold blood, far away from the glamour of his presence, I am convinced from his cynical speech, and the look which I have caught in his eyes, that he is one who should be deeply distrusted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4720,'So I think, and so, too, thinks my little Mary, who has a woman’s quick insight into character.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4721,'And now there is only she to be described.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4722,'She is my niece; but when my brother died five years ago and left her alone in the world I adopted her, and have looked upon her ever since as my daughter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4723,'She is a sunbeam in my house—sweet, loving, beautiful, a wonderful manager and house-keeper, yet as tender and quiet and gentle as a woman could be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4724,'She is my right hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4725,'I do not know what I could do without her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4726,'In only one matter has she ever gone against my wishes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4727,'Twice my boy has asked her to marry him, for he loves her devotedly, but each time she has refused him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4728,'I think that if any one could have drawn him into the right path it would have been she, and that his marriage might have changed his whole life; but now, alas! it is too late—for ever too late!  Now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4729,'Holmes, you know the people who live under my roof, and I shall continue with my miserable story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4730,'When we were taking coffee in the drawing-room that night, after dinner, I told Arthur and Mary my experience, and of the precious treasure which we had under our roof, suppressing only the name of my client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4731,'Lucy Parr, who had brought in the coffee, had, I am sure, left the room; but I cannot swear that the door was closed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4732,'Mary and Arthur were much interested, and wished to see the famous coronet, but I thought it better not to disturb it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4733,'‘Where have you put it?’ asked Arthur.  ‘In my own bureau.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4734,'’  ‘Well, I hope to goodness the house won’t be burgled during the night,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4735,'‘It is locked up,’ I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4736,'‘Oh, any old key will fit that bureau.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4737,'When I was a youngster I have opened it myself with the key of the box-room cupboard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4738,'’  He often had a wild way of talking, so that I thought little of what he said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4739,'He followed me to my room, however, that night with a very grave face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4740,'‘Look here, dad,’ said he, with his eyes cast down, ‘can you let me have £200?’  ‘No, I cannot!’ I answered, sharply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4741,'‘I have been far too generous with you in money matters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4742,'’  ‘You have been very kind,’ said he: ‘but I must have this money, or else I can never show my face inside the club again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4743,'’  ‘And a very good thing, too!’ I cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4744,'‘Yes, but you would not have me leave it a dishonored man,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4745,'‘I could not bear the disgrace.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4746,'I must raise the money in some way, and if you will not let me have it, then I must try other means.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4747,'’  I was very angry, for this was the third demand during the month.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4748,'‘You shall not have a farthing from me,’ I cried; on which he bowed and left the room without another word.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4749,'When he was gone I unlocked my bureau, made sure that my treasure was safe, and locked it again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4750,'Then I started to go round the house to see that all was secure—a duty which I usually leave to Mary, but which I thought it well to perform myself that night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4751,'As I came down the stairs I saw Mary herself at the side window of the hall, which she closed and fastened as I approached.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4752,'‘Tell me, dad,’ said she, looking, I thought, a little disturbed, ‘did you give Lucy, the maid, leave to go out to-night?’  ‘Certainly not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4753,'’  ‘She came in just now by the back door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4754,'I have no doubt that she has only been to the side gate to see some one; but I think that it is hardly safe, and should be stopped.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4755,'‘You must speak to her in the morning, or I will, if you prefer it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4756,'Are you sure that everything is fastened?’  ‘Quite sure, dad.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4757,'’  ‘Then, good-night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4758,'’ I kissed her, and went up to my bedroom again, where I was soon asleep.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4759,'I am endeavoring to tell you everything, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4760,'Holmes, which may have any bearing upon the case, but I beg that you will question me upon any point which I do not make clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4761,'On the contrary, your statement is singularly lucid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4762,'I come to a part of my story now in which I should wish to be particularly so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4763,'I am not a very heavy sleeper, and the anxiety in my mind tended, no doubt, to make me even less so than usual.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4764,'About two in the morning, then, I was awakened by some sound in the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4765,'It had ceased ere I was wide awake, but it had left an impression behind it as though a window had gently closed somewhere.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4766,'I lay listening with all my ears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4767,'Suddenly, to my horror, there was a distinct sound of footsteps moving softly in the next room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4768,'I slipped out of bed, all palpitating with fear, and peeped round the corner of my dressing-room door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4769,'‘Arthur!’ I screamed, ‘you villain! you thief! How dare you touch that coronet?’  The gas was half up, as I had left it, and my unhappy boy, dressed only in his shirt and trousers, was standing beside the light, holding the coronet in his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4770,'He appeared to be wrenching at it, or bending it with all his strength.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4771,'At my cry he dropped it from his grasp, and turned as pale as death.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4772,'I snatched it up and examined it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4773,'One of the gold corners, with three of the beryls in it, was missing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4774,'‘You blackguard!’ I shouted, beside myself with rage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4775,'‘You have destroyed it! You have dishonored me for ever! Where are the jewels which you have stolen?’  ‘Stolen!’ he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4776,'‘Yes, you thief!’ I roared, shaking him by the shoulder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4777,'‘There are none missing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4778,'There cannot be any missing,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4779,'‘There are three missing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4780,'And you know where they are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4781,'Must I call you a liar as well as a thief? Did I not see you trying to tear off another piece?’  ‘You have called me names enough,’ said he; ‘I will not stand it any longer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4782,'I shall not say another word about this business since you have chosen to insult me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4783,'I will leave your house in the morning and make my own way in the world.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4784,'’  ‘You shall leave it in the hands of the police!’ I cried, half-mad with grief and rage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4785,'‘I shall have this matter probed to the bottom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4786,'’  ‘You shall learn nothing from me,’ said he, with a passion such as I should not have thought was in his nature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4787,'‘If you choose to call the police, let the police find what they can.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4788,'’  By this time the whole house was astir, for I had raised my voice in my anger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4789,'Mary was the first to rush into my room, and, at the sight of the coronet and of Arthur’s face, she read the whole story, and, with a scream, fell down senseless on the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4790,'I sent the house-maid for the police, and put the investigation into their hands at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4791,'When the inspector and a constable entered the house, Arthur, who had stood sullenly with his arms folded, asked me whether it was my intention to charge him with theft.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4792,'I answered that it had ceased to be a private matter, but had become a public one, since the ruined coronet was national property.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4793,'I was determined that the law should have its way in everything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4794,'‘At least,’ said he, ‘you will not have me arrested at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4795,'It would be to your advantage as well as mine if I might leave the house for five minutes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4796,'’  ‘That you may get away, or perhaps that you may conceal what you have stolen,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4797,'And then realizing the dreadful position in which I was placed, I implored him to remember that not only my honor, but that of one who was far greater than I was at stake; and that he threatened to raise a scandal which would convulse the nation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4798,'He might avert it all if he would but tell me what he had done with the three missing stones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4799,'‘You may as well face the matter,’ said I; ‘you have been caught in the act, and no confession could make your guilt more heinous.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4800,'If you but make such reparation as is in your power, by telling us where the beryls are, all shall be forgiven and forgotten.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4801,'’  ‘Keep your forgiveness for those who ask for it,’ he answered, turning away from me, with a sneer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4802,'I saw that he was too hardened for any words of mine to influence him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4803,'There was but one way for it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4804,'I called in the inspector, and gave him into custody.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4805,'A search was made at once, not only of his person, but of his room, and of every portion of the house where he could possibly have concealed the gems; but no trace of them could be found, nor would the wretched boy open his mouth for all our persuasions and our threats.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4806,'This morning he was removed to a cell, and I, after going through all the police formalities, have hurried round to you, to implore you to use your skill in unravelling the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4807,'The police have openly confessed that they can at present make nothing of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4808,'You may go to any expense which you think necessary.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4809,'I have already offered a reward of £1000.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4810,'My God, what shall I do! I have lost my honor, my gems, and my son in one night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4811,'Oh, what shall I do!  He put a hand on either side of his head, and rocked himself to and fro, droning to himself like a child whose grief has got beyond words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4812,'Sherlock Holmes sat silent for some few minutes, with his brows knitted and his eyes fixed upon the fire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4813,'Do you receive much company? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4814,'None, save my partner with his family, and an occasional friend of Arthur’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4815,'Sir George Burnwell has been several times lately.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4816,'No one else, I think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4817,'Do you go out much in society?  Arthur does.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4818,'Mary and I stay at home.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4819,'We neither of us care for it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4820,'That is unusual in a young girl.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4821,'She is of a quiet nature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4822,'Besides, she is not so very young.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4823,'She is four-and-twenty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4824,'This matter, from what you say, seems to have been a shock to her also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4825,'Terrible! She is even more affected than I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4826,'You have neither of you any doubt as to your son’s guilt?  How can we have, when I saw him with my own eyes with the coronet in his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4827,'I hardly consider that a conclusive proof.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4828,'Was the remainder of the coronet at all injured?  Yes, it was twisted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4829,'Do you not think, then, that he might have been trying to straighten it?  God bless you! You are doing what you can for him and for me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4830,'But it is too heavy a task.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4831,'What was he doing there at all? If his purpose were innocent, why did he not say so?  Precisely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4832,'And if it were guilty, why did he not invent a lie? His silence appears to me to cut both ways.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4833,'There are several singular points about the case.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4834,'What did the police think of the noise which awoke you from your sleep?  They considered that it might be caused by Arthur’s closing his bedroom door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4835,'A likely story! As if a man bent on felony would slam his door so as to wake a household.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4836,'What did they say, then, of the disappearance of these gems?  They are still sounding the planking and probing the furniture in the hope of finding them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4837,'Have they thought of looking outside the house?  Yes, they have shown extraordinary energy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4838,'The whole garden has already been minutely examined.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4839,'Now, my dear sir, said Holmes, is it not obvious to you now that this matter really strikes very much deeper than either you or the police were at first inclined to think? It appeared to you to be a simple case; to me it seems exceedingly complex.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4840,'Consider what is involved by your theory.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4841,'You suppose that your son came down from his bed, went, at great risk, to your dressing-room, opened your bureau, took out your coronet, broke off by main force a small portion of it, went off to some other place, concealed three gems out of the thirty-nine, with such skill that nobody can find them, and then returned with the other thirty-six into the room in which he exposed himself to the greatest danger of being discovered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4842,'I ask you now, is such a theory tenable?  But what other is there? cried the banker, with a gesture of despair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4843,'If his motives were innocent, why does he not explain them?  It is our task to find that out, replied Holmes; so now, if you please, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4844,'Holder, we will set off for Streatham together, and devote an hour to glancing a little more closely into details.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4845,'My friend insisted upon my accompanying them in their expedition, which I was eager enough to do, for my curiosity and sympathy were deeply stirred by the story to which we had listened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4846,'I confess that the guilt of the banker’s son appeared to me to be as obvious as it did to his unhappy father, but still I had such faith in Holmes’s judgment that I felt that there must be some grounds for hope as long as he was dissatisfied with the accepted explanation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4847,'He hardly spoke a word the whole way out to the southern suburb, but sat with his chin upon his breast and his hat drawn over his eyes, sunk in the deepest thought.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4848,'Our client appeared to have taken fresh heart at the little glimpse of hope which had been presented to him, and he even broke into a desultory chat with me over his business affairs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4849,'A short railway journey and a shorter walk brought us to Fairbank, the modest residence of the great financier.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4850,'Fairbank was a good-sized square house of white stone, standing back a little from the road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4851,'A double carriage-sweep, with a snow-clad lawn, stretched down in front to two large iron gates which closed the entrance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4852,'On the right side was a small wooden thicket, which led into a narrow path between two neat hedges stretching from the road to the kitchen door, and forming the tradesmen’s entrance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4853,'On the left ran a lane which led to the stables, and was not itself within the grounds at all, being a public, though little used, thoroughfare.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4854,'Holmes left us standing at the door, and walked slowly all round the house, across the front, down the tradesmen’s path, and so round by the garden behind into the stable lane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4855,'So long was he that Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4856,'Holder and I went into the dining-room and waited by the fire until he should return.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4857,'We were sitting there in silence when the door opened and a young lady came in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4858,'She was rather above the middle height, slim, with dark hair and eyes, which seemed the darker against the absolute pallor of her skin.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4859,'I do not think that I have ever seen such deadly paleness in a woman’s face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4860,'Her lips, too, were bloodless, but her eyes were flushed with crying.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4861,'As she swept silently into the room she impressed me with a greater sense of grief than the banker had done in the morning, and it was the more striking in her as she was evidently a woman of strong character, with immense capacity for self-restraint.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4862,'Disregarding my presence, she went straight to her uncle, and passed her hand over his head with a sweet womanly caress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4863,'You have given orders that Arthur should be liberated, have you not, dad? she asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4864,'No, no, my girl, the matter must be probed to the bottom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4865,'But I am so sure that he is innocent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4866,'You know what women’s instincts are.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4867,'I know that he has done no harm and that you will be sorry for having acted so harshly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4868,'Why is he silent, then, if he is innocent?  Who knows? Perhaps because he was so angry that you should suspect him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4869,'How could I help suspecting him, when I actually saw him with the coronet in his hand?  Oh, but he had only picked it up to look at it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4870,'Oh do, do take my word for it that he is innocent.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4871,'Let the matter drop and say no more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4872,'It is so dreadful to think of our dear Arthur in prison!  I shall never let it drop until the gems are found—never, Mary! Your affection for Arthur blinds you as to the awful consequences to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4873,'Far from hushing the thing up, I have brought a gentleman down from London to inquire more deeply into it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4874,'This gentleman? she asked, facing round to me.  No, his friend.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4875,'He wished us to leave him alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4876,'He is round in the stable lane now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4877,'The stable lane? She raised her dark eyebrows.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4878,'What can he hope to find there? Ah! this, I suppose, is he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4879,'I trust, sir, that you will succeed in proving, what I feel sure is the truth, that my cousin Arthur is innocent of this crime.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4880,'I fully share your opinion, and I trust, with you, that we may prove it, returned Holmes, going back to the mat to knock the snow from his shoes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4881,'I believe I have the honor of addressing Miss Mary Holder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4882,'Might I ask you a question or two?  Pray do, sir, if it may help to clear this horrible affair up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4883,'You heard nothing yourself last night?  Nothing, until my uncle here began to speak loudly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4884,'I heard that, and I came down.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4885,'You shut up the windows and doors the night before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4886,'Did you fasten all the windows?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4887,'Were they all fastened this morning?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4888,'You have a maid who has a sweetheart? I think that you remarked to your uncle last night that she had been out to see him?  Yes, and she was the girl who waited in the drawing-room, and who may have heard uncle’s remarks about the coronet.  I see.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4889,'You infer that she may have gone out to tell her sweetheart, and that the two may have planned the robbery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4890,'But what is the good of all these vague theories, cried the banker, impatiently, when I have told you that I saw Arthur with the coronet in his hands?  Wait a little, Mr. Holder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4891,'We must come back to that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4892,'About this girl, Miss Holder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4893,'You saw her return by the kitchen door, I presume?  Yes; when I went to see if the door was fastened for the night I met her slipping in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4894,'I saw the man, too, in the gloom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4895,'Do you know him?  Oh yes; he is the green-grocer who brings our vegetables round.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4896,'His name is Francis Prosper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4897,'He stood, said Holmes, to the left of the door—that is to say, farther up the path than is necessary to reach the door?  Yes, he did.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4898,'And he is a man with a wooden leg?  Something like fear sprang up in the young lady’s expressive black eyes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4899,'Why, you are like a magician, said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4900,'How do you know that? She smiled, but there was no answering smile in Holmes’s thin, eager face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4901,'I should be very glad now to go up-stairs, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4902,'I shall probably wish to go over the outside of the house again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4903,'Perhaps I had better take a look at the lower windows before I go up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4904,'He walked swiftly round from one to the other, pausing only at the large one which looked from the hall onto the stable lane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4905,'This he opened, and made a very careful examination of the sill with his powerful magnifying lens.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4906,'Now we shall go up-stairs, said he, at last.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4907,'The banker’s dressing-room was a plainly furnished little chamber, with a gray carpet, a large bureau, and a long mirror.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4908,'Holmes went to the bureau first and looked hard at the lock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4909,'Which key was used to open it? he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4910,'That which my son himself indicated—that of the cupboard of the lumber-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4911,'Have you it here?  That is it on the dressing-table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4912,'Sherlock Holmes took it up and opened the bureau.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4913,'It is a noiseless lock, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4914,'It is no wonder that it did not wake you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4915,'This case, I presume, contains the coronet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4916,'We must have a look at it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4917,'He opened the case, and, taking out the diadem, he laid it upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4918,'It was a magnificent specimen of the jeweller’s art, and the thirty-six stones were the finest that I have ever seen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4919,'At one side of the coronet was a cracked edge, where a corner holding three gems had been torn away.  Now, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4920,'Holder, said Holmes, here is the corner which corresponds to that which has been so unfortunately lost.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4921,'Might I beg that you will break it off.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4922,'The banker recoiled in horror.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4923,'I should not dream of trying, said he.  Then I will.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4924,'Holmes suddenly bent his strength upon it, but without result.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4925,'I feel it give a little, said he; but, though I am exceptionally strong in the fingers, it would take me all my time to break it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4926,'An ordinary man could not do it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4927,'Now, what do you think would happen if I did break it, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4928,'Holder? There would be a noise like a pistol shot.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4929,'Do you tell me that all this happened within a few yards of your bed, and that you heard nothing of it?  I do not know what to think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4930,'It is all dark to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4931,'But perhaps it may grow lighter as we go.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4932,'What do you think, Miss Holder?  I confess that I still share my uncle’s perplexity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4933,'Your son had no shoes or slippers on when you saw him?  He had nothing on save only his trousers and shirt.  Thank you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4934,'We have certainly been favored with extraordinary luck during this inquiry, and it will be entirely our own fault if we do not succeed in clearing the matter up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4935,'With your permission, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4936,'Holder, I shall now continue my investigations outside.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4937,'He went alone, at his own request, for he explained that any unnecessary footmarks might make his task more difficult.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4938,'For an hour or more he was at work, returning at last with his feet heavy with snow and his features as inscrutable as ever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4939,'I think that I have seen now all that there is to see, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4940,'Holder, said he; I can serve you best by returning to my rooms.  But the gems, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4941,'Where are they?  I cannot tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4942,'The banker wrung his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4943,'I shall never see them again! he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4944,'And my son? You give me hopes?  My opinion is in no way altered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4945,'Then, for God’s sake, what was this dark business which was acted in my house last night?  If you can call upon me at my Baker Street rooms to-morrow morning between nine and ten I shall be happy to do what I can to make it clearer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4946,'I understand that you give me _carte blanche_ to act for you, provided only that I get back the gems, and that you place no limit on the sum I may draw.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4947,'I would give my fortune to have them back.  Very good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4948,'I shall look into the matter between this and then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4949,'Good-bye; it is just possible that I may have to come over here again before evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4950,'It was obvious to me that my companion’s mind was now made up about the case, although what his conclusions were was more than I could even dimly imagine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4951,'Several times during our homeward journey I endeavored to sound him upon the point, but he always glided away to some other topic, until at last I gave it over in despair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4952,'It was not yet three when we found ourselves in our room once more.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4953,'He hurried to his chamber, and was down again in a few minutes dressed as a common loafer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4954,'With his collar turned up, his shiny, seedy coat, his red cravat, and his worn boots, he was a perfect sample of the class.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4955,'I think that this should do, said he, glancing into the glass above the fireplace.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4956,'I only wish that you could come with me, Watson, but I fear that it won’t do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4957,'I may be on the trail in this matter, or I may be following a will-of-the-wisp, but I shall soon know which it is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4958,'I hope that I may be back in a few hours.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4959,'He cut a slice of beef from the joint upon the sideboard, sandwiched it between two rounds of bread, and, thrusting this rude meal into his pocket, he started off upon his expedition.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4960,'I had just finished my tea when he returned, evidently in excellent spirits, swinging an old elastic-sided boot in his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4961,'He chucked it down into a corner and helped himself to a cup of tea.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4962,'I only looked in as I passed, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4963,'I am going right on.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4964,'Where to?  Oh, to the other side of the West End.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4965,'It may be some time before I get back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4966,'Don’t wait up for me in case I should be late.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4967,'How are you getting on?  Oh, so so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4968,'Nothing to complain of.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4969,'I have been out to Streatham since I saw you last, but I did not call at the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4970,'It is a very sweet little problem, and I would not have missed it for a good deal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4971,'However, I must not sit gossiping here, but must get these disreputable clothes off and return to my highly respectable self.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4972,'I could see by his manner that he had stronger reasons for satisfaction than his words alone would imply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4973,'His eyes twinkled, and there was even a touch of color upon his sallow cheeks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4974,'He hastened up-stairs, and a few minutes later I heard the slam of the hall door, which told me that he was off once more upon his congenial hunt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4975,'I waited until midnight, but there was no sign of his return, so I retired to my room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4976,'It was no uncommon thing for him to be away for days and nights on end when he was hot upon a scent, so that his lateness caused me no surprise.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4977,'I do not know at what hour he came in, but when I came down to breakfast in the morning, there he was with a cup of coffee in one hand and the paper in the other, as fresh and trim as possible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4978,'You will excuse my beginning without you, Watson, said he; but you remember that our client has rather an early appointment this morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4979,'Why, it is after nine now, I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4980,'I should not be surprised if that were he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4981,'I thought I heard a ring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4982,'It was, indeed, our friend the financier.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4983,'I was shocked by the change which had come over him, for his face, which was naturally of a broad and massive mould, was now pinched and fallen in, while his hair seemed to me at least a shade whiter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4984,'He entered with a weariness and lethargy which was even more painful than his violence of the morning before, and he dropped heavily into the arm-chair which I pushed forward for him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4985,'I do not know what I have done to be so severely tried, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4986,'Only two days ago I was a happy and prosperous man, without a care in the world.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4987,'Now I am left to a lonely and dishonored age.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4988,'One sorrow comes close upon the heels of another.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4989,'My niece, Mary, has deserted me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4990,'Deserted you?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4991,'Her bed this morning had not been slept in, her room was empty, and a note for me lay upon the hall table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4992,'I had said to her last night, in sorrow and not in anger, that if she had married my boy all might have been well with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4993,'Perhaps it was thoughtless of me to say so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4994,'It is to that remark that she refers in this note:    ‘MY DEAREST UNCLE,—I feel that I have brought trouble   upon you, and that if I had acted differently this terrible   misfortune might never have occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4995,'I cannot, with this   thought in my mind, ever again be happy under your roof, and   I feel that I must leave you for ever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4996,'Do not worry about my   future, for that is provided for; and, above all, do not search   for me, for it will be fruitless labor and an ill-service to   me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4997,'In life or in death, I am ever your loving       MARY.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4998,'’  What could she mean by that note, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(4999,'Holmes? Do you think it points to suicide?  No, no, nothing of the kind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5000,'It is perhaps the best possible solution. I trust, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5001,'Holder, that you are nearing the end of your troubles.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5002,'Ha! You say so! You have heard something, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5003,'Holmes; you have learned something! Where are the gems?  You would not think £1000 apiece an excessive sum for them?  I would pay ten.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5004,'That would be unnecessary.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5005,'Three thousand will cover the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5006,'And there is a little reward, I fancy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5007,'Have you your check-book? Here is a pen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5008,'Better make it out for £4000 pounds.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5009,'With a dazed face the banker made out the required check.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5010,'Holmes walked over to his desk, took out a little triangular piece of gold with three gems in it, and threw it down upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5011,'With a shriek of joy our client clutched it up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5012,'You have it! he gasped.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5013,'I am saved! I am saved!  The reaction of joy was as passionate as his grief had been, and he hugged his recovered gems to his bosom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5014,'There is one other thing you owe, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5015,'Holder, said Sherlock Holmes, rather sternly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5016,'Owe! He caught up a pen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5017,'Name the sum, and I will pay it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5018,'No, the debt is not to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5019,'You owe a very humble apology to that noble lad, your son, who has carried himself in this matter as I should be proud to see my own son do, should I ever chance to have one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5020,'Then it was not Arthur who took them?  I told you yesterday, and I repeat to-day, that it was not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5021,'You are sure of it! Then let us hurry to him at once, to let him know that the truth is known.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5022,'He knows it already.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5023,'When I had cleared it all up I had an interview with him, and, finding that he would not tell me the story, I told it to him, on which he had to confess that I was right, and to add the very few details which were not yet quite clear to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5024,'Your news of this morning, however, may open his lips.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5025,'For Heaven’s sake, tell me, then, what is this extraordinary mystery!  I will do so, and I will show you the steps by which I reached it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5026,'And let me say to you, first, that which it is hardest for me to say and for you to hear: there has been an understanding between Sir George Burnwell and your niece Mary.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5027,'They have now fled together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5028,'My Mary? Impossible!  It is, unfortunately, more than possible; it is certain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5029,'Neither you nor your son knew the true character of this man when you admitted him into your family circle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5030,'He is one of the most dangerous men in England—a ruined gambler, an absolutely desperate villain, a man without heart or conscience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5031,'Your niece knew nothing of such men.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5032,'When he breathed his vows to her, as he had done to a hundred before her, she flattered herself that she alone had touched his heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5033,'The devil knows best what he said, but at least she became his tool, and was in the habit of seeing him nearly every evening.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5034,'I cannot, and I will not, believe it! cried the banker, with an ashen face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5035,'I will tell you, then, what occurred in your house last night.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5036,'Your niece, when you had, as she thought, gone to your room, slipped down and talked to her lover through the window which leads into the stable lane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5037,'His footmarks had pressed right through the snow, so long had he stood there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5038,'She told him of the coronet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5039,'His wicked lust for gold kindled at the news, and he bent her to his will.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5040,'I have no doubt that she loved you, but there are women in whom the love of a lover extinguishes all other loves, and I think that she must have been one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5041,'She had hardly listened to his instructions when she saw you coming down-stairs, on which she closed the window rapidly, and told you about one of the servants’ escapade with her wooden-legged lover, which was all perfectly true.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5042,'Your boy, Arthur, went to bed after his interview with you, but he slept badly on account of his uneasiness about his club debts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5043,'In the middle of the night he heard a soft tread pass his door, so he rose, and looking out, was surprised to see his cousin walking very stealthily along the passage, until she disappeared into your dressing-room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5044,'Petrified with astonishment, the lad slipped on some clothes, and waited there in the dark to see what would come of this strange affair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5045,'Presently she emerged from the room again, and in the light of the passage-lamp your son saw that she carried the precious coronet in her hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5046,'She passed down the stairs, and he, thrilling with horror, ran along and slipped behind the curtain near your door, whence he could see what passed in the hall beneath.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5047,'He saw her stealthily open the window, hand out the coronet to some one in the gloom, and then closing it once more hurry back to her room, passing quite close to where he stood hid behind the curtain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5048,'As long as she was on the scene he could not take any action without a horrible exposure of the woman whom he loved.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5049,'But the instant that she was gone he realized how crushing a misfortune this would be for you, and how all-important it was to set it right.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5050,'He rushed down, just as he was, in his bare feet, opened the window, sprang out into the snow, and ran down the lane, where he could see a dark figure in the moonlight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5051,'Sir George Burnwell tried to get away, but Arthur caught him, and there was a struggle between them, your lad tugging at one side of the coronet, and his opponent at the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5052,'In the scuffle, your son struck Sir George, and cut him over the eye.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5053,'Then something suddenly snapped, and your son, finding that he had the coronet in his hands, rushed back, closed the window, ascended to your room, and had just observed that the coronet had been twisted in the struggle, and was endeavoring to straighten it when you appeared upon the scene.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5054,'Is it possible? gasped the banker.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5055,'You then roused his anger by calling him names at a moment when he felt that he had deserved your warmest thanks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5056,'He could not explain the true state of affairs without betraying one who certainly deserved little enough consideration at his hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5057,'He took the more chivalrous view, however, and preserved her secret.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5058,'And that was why she shrieked and fainted when she saw the coronet, cried Mr. Holder.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5059,'Oh, my God! what a blind fool I have been! And his asking to be allowed to go out for five minutes! The dear fellow wanted to see if the missing piece were at the scene of the struggle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5060,'How cruelly I have misjudged him!  When I arrived at the house, continued Holmes, I at once went very carefully round it to observe if there were any traces in the snow which might help me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5061,'I knew that none had fallen since the evening before, and also that there had been a strong frost to preserve impressions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5062,'I passed along the tradesmen’s path, but found it all trampled down and indistinguishable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5063,'Just beyond it, however, at the far side of the kitchen door, a woman had stood and talked with a man, whose round impressions on one side showed that he had a wooden leg.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5064,'I could even tell that they had been disturbed, for the woman had run back swiftly to the door, as was shown by the deep toe and light heel marks, while Wooden-leg had waited a little, and then had gone away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5065,'I thought at the time that this might be the maid and her sweetheart, of whom you had already spoken to me, and inquiry showed it was so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5066,'I passed round the garden without seeing anything more than random tracks, which I took to be the police; but when I got into the stable lane a very long and complex story was written in the snow in front of me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5067,'There was a double line of tracks of a booted man, and a second double line which I saw with delight belonged to a man with naked feet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5068,'I was at once convinced from what you had told me that the latter was your son.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5069,'The first had walked both ways, but the other had run swiftly, and, as his tread was marked in places over the depression of the boot, it was obvious that he had passed after the other.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5070,'I followed them up, and found that they led to the hall window, where Boots had worn all the snow away while waiting.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5071,'Then I walked to the other end, which was a hundred yards or more down the lane.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5072,'I saw where Boots had faced round, where the snow was cut up as though there had been a struggle, and, finally, where a few drops of blood had fallen, to show me that I was not mistaken.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5073,'Boots had then run down the lane, and another little smudge of blood showed that it was he who had been hurt.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5074,'When he came to the high-road at the other end, I found that the pavement had been cleared, so there was an end to that clew.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5075,'On entering the house, however, I examined, as you remember, the sill and framework of the hall window with my lens, and I could at once see that some one had passed out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5076,'I could distinguish the outline of an instep where the wet foot had been placed in coming in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5077,'I was then beginning to be able to form an opinion as to what had occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5078,'A man had waited outside the window, some one had brought the gems; the deed had been overseen by your son, he had pursued the thief, had struggled with him, they had each tugged at the coronet, their united strength causing injuries which neither alone could have effected.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5079,'He had returned with the prize, but had left a fragment in the grasp of his opponent. So far I was clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5080,'The question now was, who was the man, and who was it brought him the coronet?  It is an old maxim of mine that when you have excluded the impossible, whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5081,'Now, I knew that it was not you who had brought it down, so there only remained your niece and the maids.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5082,'But if it were the maids, why should your son allow himself to be accused in their place? There could be no possible reason.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5083,'As he loved his cousin, however, there was an excellent explanation why he should retain her secret—the more so as the secret was a disgraceful one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5084,'When I remembered that you had seen her at that window, and how she had fainted on seeing the coronet again, my conjecture became a certainty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5085,'And who could it be who was her confederate? A lover evidently, for who else could outweigh the love and gratitude which she must feel to you? I knew that you went out little, and that your circle of friends was a very limited one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5086,'But among them was Sir George Burnwell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5087,'I had heard of him before as being a man of evil reputation among women.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5088,'It must have been he who wore those boots and retained the missing gems.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5089,'Even though he knew that Arthur had discovered him, he might still flatter himself that he was safe, for the lad could not say a word without compromising his own family.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5090,'Well, your own good sense will suggest what measures I took next.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5091,'I went in the shape of a loafer to Sir George’s house, managed to pick up an acquaintance with his valet, learned that his master had cut his head the night before, and, finally, at the expense of six shillings, made all sure by buying a pair of his cast-off shoes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5092,'With these I journeyed down to Streatham, and saw that they exactly fitted the tracks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5093,'[Illustration: I CLAPPED A PISTOL TO HIS HEAD]  I saw an ill-dressed vagabond in the lane yesterday evening, said Mr. Holder.  Precisely. It was I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5094,'I found that I had my man, so I came home and changed my clothes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5095,'It was a delicate part which I had to play then, for I saw that a prosecution must be avoided to avert scandal, and I knew that so astute a villain would see that our hands were tied in the matter. I went and saw him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5096,'At first, of course, he denied everything.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5097,'But when I gave him every particular that had occurred, he tried to bluster, and took down a life-preserver from the wall.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5098,'I knew my man, however, and I clapped a pistol to his head before he could strike.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5099,'Then he became a little more reasonable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5100,'I told him that we would give him a price for the stones he held—£1000 apiece.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5101,'That brought out the first signs of grief that he had shown.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5102,'‘Why, dash it all!’ said he, ‘I’ve let them go at six hundred for the three!’ I soon managed to get the address of the receiver who had them, on promising him that there would be no prosecution.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5103,'Off I set to him, and after much chaffering I got our stones at £1000 apiece.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5104,'Then I looked in upon your son, told him that all was right, and eventually got to my bed about two o’clock, after what I may call a really hard day’s work.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5105,'A day which has saved England from a great public scandal, said the banker, rising.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5106,'Sir, I cannot find words to thank you, but you shall not find me ungrateful for what you have done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5107,'Your skill has indeed exceeded all that I have heard of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5108,'And now I must fly to my dear boy to apologize to him for the wrong which I have done him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5109,'As to what you tell me of poor Mary, it goes to my very heart.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5110,'Not even your skill can inform me where she is now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5111,'I think that we may safely say, returned Holmes, that she is wherever Sir George Burnwell is.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5112,'It is equally certain, too, that whatever her sins are, they will soon receive a more than sufficient punishment.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5113,'Adventure XII  THE ADVENTURE OF THE COPPER BEECHES   To the man who loves art for its own sake, remarked Sherlock Holmes, tossing aside the advertisement sheet of _The Daily Telegraph_, it is frequently in its least important and lowliest manifestations that the keenest pleasure is to be derived.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5114,'It is pleasant to me to observe, Watson, that you have so far grasped this truth that in these little records of our cases which you have been good enough to draw up, and, I am bound to say, occasionally to embellish, you have given prominence not so much to the many _causes célèbres_ and sensational trials in which I have figured, but rather to those incidents which may have been trivial in themselves, but which have given room for those faculties of deduction and of logical synthesis which I have made my special province.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5115,'And yet, said I, smiling, I cannot quite hold myself absolved from the charge of sensationalism which has been urged against my records.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5116,'You have erred, perhaps, he observed, taking up a glowing cinder with the tongs, and lighting with it the long cherry-wood pipe which was wont to replace his clay when he was in a disputatious, rather than a meditative mood—you have erred perhaps in attempting to put color and life into each of your statements, instead of confining yourself to the task of placing upon record that severe reasoning from cause to effect which is really the only notable feature about the thing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5117,'It seems to me that I have done you full justice in the matter, I remarked, with some coldness, for I was repelled by the egotism which I had more than once observed to be a strong factor in my friend’s singular character.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5118,'No, it is not selfishness or conceit, said he, answering, as was his wont, my thoughts rather than my words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5119,'If I claim full justice for my art, it is because it is an impersonal thing—a thing beyond myself. Crime is common. Logic is rare.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5120,'Therefore it is upon the logic rather than upon the crime that you should dwell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5121,'You have degraded what should have been a course of lectures into a series of tales.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5122,'It was a cold morning of the early spring, and we sat after breakfast on either side of a cheery fire in the old room at Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5123,'A thick fog rolled down between the lines of dun-colored houses, and the opposing windows loomed like dark, shapeless blurs through the heavy yellow wreaths.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5124,'Our gas was lit, and shone on the white cloth and glimmer of china and metal, for the table had not been cleared yet.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5125,'Sherlock Holmes had been silent all the morning, dipping continuously into the advertisement columns of a succession of papers, until at last, having apparently given up his search, he had emerged in no very sweet temper to lecture me upon my literary shortcomings.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5126,'At the same time, he remarked, after a pause, during which he had sat puffing at his long pipe and gazing down into the fire, you can hardly be open to a charge of sensationalism, for out of these cases which you have been so kind as to interest yourself in, a fair proportion do not treat of crime, in its legal sense, at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5127,'The small matter in which I endeavored to help the King of Bohemia, the singular experience of Miss Mary Sutherland, the problem connected with the man with the twisted lip, and the incident of the noble bachelor, were all matters which are outside the pale of the law.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5128,'But in avoiding the sensational, I fear that you may have bordered on the trivial.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5129,'The end may have been so, I answered, but the methods I hold to have been novel and of interest.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5130,'Pshaw, my dear fellow, what do the public, the great unobservant public, who could hardly tell a weaver by his tooth or a compositor by his left thumb, care about the finer shades of analysis and deduction! But, indeed, if you are trivial, I cannot blame you, for the days of the great cases are past.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5131,'Man, or at least criminal man, has lost all enterprise and originality.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5132,'As to my own little practice, it seems to be degenerating into an agency for recovering lost lead pencils and giving advice to young ladies from boarding-schools.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5133,'I think that I have touched bottom at last, however.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5134,'This note I had this morning marks my zero-point, I fancy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5135,'Read it! He tossed a crumpled letter across to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5136,'It was dated from Montague Place upon the preceding evening, and ran thus:    DEAR MR.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5137,'HOLMES,—I am very anxious to consult you as   to whether I should or should not accept a situation which has   been offered to me as governess.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5138,'I shall call at half-past ten   to-morrow, if I do not inconvenience you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5139,'Yours faithfully,     VIOLET HUNTER.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5140,'Do you know the young lady? I asked.  Not I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5141,'It is half-past ten now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5142,'Yes, and I have no doubt that is her ring.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5143,'It may turn out to be of more interest than you think.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5144,'You remember that the affair of the blue carbuncle, which appeared to be a mere whim at first, developed into a serious investigation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5145,'It may be so in this case, also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5146,'Well, let us hope so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5147,'But our doubts will very soon be solved, for here, unless I am much mistaken, is the person in question.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5148,'As he spoke the door opened and a young lady entered the room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5149,'She was plainly but neatly dressed, with a bright, quick face, freckled like a plover’s egg, and with the brisk manner of a woman who has had her own way to make in the world.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5150,'You will excuse my troubling you, I am sure, said she, as my companion rose to greet her; but I have had a very strange experience, and as I have no parents or relations of any sort from whom I could ask advice, I thought that perhaps you would be kind enough to tell me what I should do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5151,'Pray take a seat, Miss Hunter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5152,'I shall be happy to do anything that I can to serve you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5153,'I could see that Holmes was favorably impressed by the manner and speech of his new client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5154,'He looked her over in his searching fashion, and then composed himself, with his lids drooping and his finger tips together, to listen to her story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5155,'I have been a governess for five years, said she, in the family of Colonel Spence Munro, but two months ago the colonel received an appointment at Halifax, in Nova Scotia, and took his children over to America with him, so that I found myself without a situation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5156,'I advertised, and I answered advertisements, but without success.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5157,'At last the little money which I had saved began to run short, and I was at my wits’ end as to what I should do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5158,'There is a well-known agency for governesses in the West End called Westaway’s, and there I used to call about once a week in order to see whether anything had turned up which might suit me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5159,'Westaway was the name of the founder of the business, but it is really managed by Miss Stoper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5160,'She sits in her own little office, and the ladies who are seeking employment wait in an ante-room, and are then shown in one by one, when she consults her ledgers, and sees whether she has anything which would suit them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5161,'Well, when I called last week I was shown into the little office as usual, but I found that Miss Stoper was not alone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5162,'A prodigiously stout man with a very smiling face, and a great heavy chin which rolled down in fold upon fold over his throat, sat at her elbow with a pair of glasses on his nose, looking very earnestly at the ladies who entered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5163,'As I came in he gave quite a jump in his chair, and turned quickly to Miss Stoper:  ‘That will do,’ said he; ‘I could not ask for anything better.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5164,'Capital! capital!’ He seemed quite enthusiastic, and rubbed his hands together in the most genial fashion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5165,'He was such a comfortable-looking man that it was quite a pleasure to look at him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5166,'‘You are looking for a situation, miss?’ he asked.  ‘Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5167,'’  ‘As governess?’  ‘Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5168,'’  ‘And what salary do you ask?’  ‘I had £4 a month in my last place with Colonel Spence Munro.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5169,'’  ‘Oh, tut, tut! sweating—rank sweating!’ he cried, throwing his fat hands out into the air like a man who is in a boiling passion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5170,'‘How could any one offer so pitiful a sum to a lady with such attractions and accomplishments?’  ‘My accomplishments, sir, may be less than you imagine,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5171,'‘A little French, a little German, music, and drawing—’  ‘Tut, tut!’ he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5172,'‘This is all quite beside the question.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5173,'The point is, have you or have you not the bearing and deportment of a lady? There it is in a nutshell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5174,'If you have not, you are not fitted for the rearing of a child who may some day play a considerable part in the history of the country.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5175,'But if you have, why, then, how could any gentleman ask you to condescend to accept anything under the three figures? Your salary with me, madam, would commence at £100 a year.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5176,'’  You may imagine, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5177,'Holmes, that to me, destitute as I was, such an offer seemed almost too good to be true.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5178,'The gentleman, however, seeing perhaps the look of incredulity upon my face, opened a pocket-book and took out a note.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5179,'‘It is also my custom,’ said he, smiling in the most pleasant fashion until his eyes were just two little shining slits amid the white creases of his face, ‘to advance to my young ladies half their salary beforehand, so that they may meet any little expenses of their journey and their wardrobe.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5180,'’  It seemed to me that I had never met so fascinating and so thoughtful a man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5181,'As I was already in debt to my tradesmen, the advance was a great convenience, and yet there was something unnatural about the whole transaction which made me wish to know a little more before I quite committed myself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5182,'‘May I ask where you live, sir?’ said I.  ‘Hampshire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5183,'Charming rural place.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5184,'The Copper Beeches, five miles on the far side of Winchester.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5185,'It is the most lovely country, my dear young lady, and the dearest old country-house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5186,'’  ‘And my duties, sir? I should be glad to know what they would be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5187,'’  ‘One child—one dear little romper just six years old.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5188,'Oh, if you could see him killing cockroaches with a slipper! Smack! smack! smack! Three gone before you could wink!’ He leaned back in his chair and laughed his eyes into his head again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5189,'I was a little startled at the nature of the child’s amusement, but the father’s laughter made me think that perhaps he was joking.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5190,'‘My sole duties, then,’ I asked, ‘are to take charge of a single child?’  ‘No, no, not the sole, not the sole, my dear young lady,’ he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5191,'‘Your duty would be, as I am sure your good sense would suggest, to obey any little commands my wife might give, provided always that they were such commands as a lady might with propriety obey.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5192,'You see no difficulty, heh?’  ‘I should be happy to make myself useful.’  ‘Quite so.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5193,'In dress now, for example.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5194,'We are faddy people, you know—faddy but kind-hearted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5195,'If you were asked to wear any dress which we might give you, you would not object to our little whim.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5196,'Heh?’  ‘No,’ said I, considerably astonished at his words.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5197,'‘Or to sit here, or sit there, that would not be offensive to you?’  ‘Oh, no.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5198,'’  ‘Or to cut your hair quite short before you come to us?’  I could hardly believe my ears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5199,'As you may observe, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5200,'Holmes, my hair is somewhat luxuriant, and of a rather peculiar tint of chestnut.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5201,'It has been considered artistic.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5202,'I could not dream of sacrificing it in this off-hand fashion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5203,'‘I am afraid that that is quite impossible,’ said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5204,'He had been watching me eagerly out of his small eyes, and I could see a shadow pass over his face as I spoke.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5205,'‘I am afraid that it is quite essential,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5206,'‘It is a little fancy of my wife’s, and ladies’ fancies, you know, madam, ladies’ fancies must be consulted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5207,'And so you won’t cut your hair?’  ‘No, sir, I really could not,’ I answered, firmly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5208,'‘Ah, very well; then that quite settles the matter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5209,'It is a pity, because in other respects you would really have done very nicely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5210,'In that case, Miss Stoper, I had best inspect a few more of your young ladies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5211,'’  The manageress had sat all this while busy with her papers without a word to either of us, but she glanced at me now with so much annoyance upon her face that I could not help suspecting that she had lost a handsome commission through my refusal.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5212,'‘Do you desire your name to be kept upon the books?’ she asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5213,'‘If you please, Miss Stoper.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5214,'’  ‘Well, really, it seems rather useless, since you refuse the most excellent offers in this fashion,’ said she, sharply.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5215,'‘You can hardly expect us to exert ourselves to find another such opening for you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5216,'Good-day to you, Miss Hunter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5217,'’ She struck a gong upon the table, and I was shown out by the page.  Well, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5218,'Holmes, when I got back to my lodgings and found little enough in the cupboard, and two or three bills upon the table, I began to ask myself whether I had not done a very foolish thing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5219,'After all, if these people had strange fads, and expected obedience on the most extraordinary matters, they were at least ready to pay for their eccentricity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5220,'Very few governesses in England are getting £100 a year.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5221,'Besides, what use was my hair to me? Many people are improved by wearing it short, and perhaps I should be among the number.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5222,'Next day I was inclined to think that I had made a mistake, and by the day after I was sure of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5223,'I had almost overcome my pride, so far as to go back to the agency and inquire whether the place was still open, when I received this letter from the gentleman himself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5224,'I have it here, and I will read it to you:      ‘The Copper Beeches, near Winchester.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5225,'‘DEAR MISS HUNTER,—Miss Stoper has very kindly given me your     address, and I write from here to ask you whether you have     reconsidered your decision.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5226,'My wife is very anxious that you     should come, for she has been much attracted by my description     of you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5227,'We are willing to give £30 a quarter, or £120 a year, so     as to recompense you for any little inconvenience which our fads     may cause you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5228,'They are not very exacting, after all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5229,'My wife     is fond of a particular shade of electric blue, and would like     you to wear such a dress in-doors in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5230,'You need not,     however, go to the expense of purchasing one, as we have one     belonging to my dear daughter Alice (now in Philadelphia), which     would, I should think, fit you very well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5231,'Then, as to sitting     here or there, or amusing yourself in any manner indicated, that     need cause you no inconvenience.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5232,'As regards your hair, it is     no doubt a pity, especially as I could not help remarking its     beauty during our short interview, but I am afraid that I must     remain firm upon this point, and I only hope that the increased     salary may recompense you for the loss.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5233,'Your duties, as far as     the child is concerned, are very light.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5234,'Now do try to come, and     I shall meet you with the dog-cart at Winchester.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5235,'Let me know     your train.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5236,'Yours faithfully,      JEPHRO RUCASTLE.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5237,'’  That is the letter which I have just received, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5238,'Holmes, and my mind is made up that I will accept it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5239,'I thought, however, that before taking the final step I should like to submit the whole matter to your consideration.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5240,'Well, Miss Hunter, if your mind is made up, that settles the question, said Holmes, smiling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5241,'But you would not advise me to refuse?  I confess that it is not the situation which I should like to see a sister of mine apply for.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5242,'What is the meaning of it all, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5243,'Holmes?  Ah, I have no data. I cannot tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5244,'Perhaps you have yourself formed some opinion?  Well, there seems to me to be only one possible solution. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5245,'Rucastle seemed to be a very kind, good-natured man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5246,'Is it not possible that his wife is a lunatic, that he desires to keep the matter quiet for fear she should be taken to an asylum, and that he humors her fancies in every way in order to prevent an outbreak.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5247,'That is a possible solution—in fact, as matters stand, it is the most probable one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5248,'But in any case it does not seem to be a nice household for a young lady.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5249,'But the money, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5250,'Holmes, the money!  Well, yes, of course the pay is good—too good.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5251,'That is what makes me uneasy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5252,'Why should they give you £120 a year, when they could have their pick for £40? There must be some strong reason behind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5253,'I thought that if I told you the circumstances you would understand afterwards if I wanted your help.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5254,'I should feel so much stronger if I felt that you were at the back of me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5255,'Oh, you may carry that feeling away with you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5256,'I assure you that your little problem promises to be the most interesting which has come my way for some months.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5257,'There is something distinctly novel about some of the features.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5258,'If you should find yourself in doubt or in danger—  Danger! What danger do you foresee?  Holmes shook his head gravely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5259,'It would cease to be a danger if we could define it, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5260,'But at any time, day or night, a telegram would bring me down to your help.  That is enough.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5261,'She rose briskly from her chair with the anxiety all swept from her face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5262,'I shall go down to Hampshire quite easy in my mind now. I shall write to Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5263,'Rucastle at once, sacrifice my poor hair to-night, and start for Winchester to-morrow.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5264,'With a few grateful words to Holmes she bade us both good-night and bustled off upon her way.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5265,'At least, said I, as we heard her quick, firm step descending the stairs, she seems to be a young lady who is very well able to take care of herself.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5266,'And she would need to be, said Holmes, gravely; I am much mistaken if we do not hear from her before many days are past.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5267,'It was not very long before my friend’s prediction was fulfilled.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5268,'A fortnight went by, during which I frequently found my thoughts turning in her direction, and wondering what strange side-alley of human experience this lonely woman had strayed into.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5269,'The unusual salary, the curious conditions, the light duties, all pointed to something abnormal, though whether a fad or a plot, or whether the man were a philanthropist or a villain, it was quite beyond my powers to determine.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5270,'As to Holmes, I observed that he sat frequently for half an hour on end, with knitted brows and an abstracted air, but he swept the matter away with a wave of his hand when I mentioned it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5271,'Data! data! data! he cried, impatiently.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5272,'I can’t make bricks without clay.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5273,'And yet he would always wind up by muttering that no sister of his should ever have accepted such a situation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5274,'The telegram which we eventually received came late one night, just as I was thinking of turning in, and Holmes was settling down to one of those all-night chemical researches which he frequently indulged in, when I would leave him stooping over a retort and a test-tube at night, and find him in the same position when I came down to breakfast in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5275,'He opened the yellow envelope, and then, glancing at the message, threw it across to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5276,'Just look up the trains in Bradshaw, said he, and turned back to his chemical studies.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5277,'The summons was a brief and urgent one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5278,'Please be at the ‘Black Swan’ Hotel at Winchester at   mid-day to-morrow, it said.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5279,'Do come! I am at my wits’   end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5280,'HUNTER.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5281,'Will you come with me? asked Holmes, glancing up.  I should wish to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5282,'Just look it up, then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5283,'There is a train at half-past nine, said I, glancing over my Bradshaw.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5284,'It is due at Winchester at 11.30.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5285,'That will do very nicely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5286,'Then perhaps I had better postpone my analysis of the acetones, as we may need to be at our best in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5287,'*       *       *       *       *  By eleven o’clock the next day we were well upon our way to the old English capital.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5288,'Holmes had been buried in the morning papers all the way down, but after we had passed the Hampshire border he threw them down, and began to admire the scenery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5289,'It was an ideal spring day, a light blue sky, flecked with little fleecy white clouds drifting across from west to east.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5290,'The sun was shining very brightly, and yet there was an exhilarating nip in the air, which set an edge to a man’s energy.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5291,'All over the country-side, away to the rolling hills around Aldershot, the little red and gray roofs of the farm-steadings peeped out from amid the light green of the new foliage.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5292,'Are they not fresh and beautiful? I cried, with all the enthusiasm of a man fresh from the fogs of Baker Street.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5293,'But Holmes shook his head gravely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5294,'Do you know, Watson, said he, that it is one of the curses of a mind with a turn like mine that I must look at everything with reference to my own special subject.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5295,'You look at these scattered houses, and you are impressed by their beauty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5296,'I look at them, and the only thought which comes to me is a feeling of their isolation and of the impunity with which crime may be committed there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5297,'Good heavens! I cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5298,'Who would associate crime with these dear old homesteads?  They always fill me with a certain horror.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5299,'It is my belief, Watson, founded upon my experience, that the lowest and vilest alleys in London do not present a more dreadful record of sin than does the smiling and beautiful country-side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5300,'You horrify me!  But the reason is very obvious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5301,'The pressure of public opinion can do in the town what the law cannot accomplish.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5302,'There is no lane so vile that the scream of a tortured child, or the thud of a drunkard’s blow, does not beget sympathy and indignation among the neighbors, and then the whole machinery of justice is ever so close that a word of complaint can set it going, and there is but a step between the crime and the dock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5303,'But look at these lonely houses, each in its own fields, filled for the most part with poor ignorant folk who know little of the law.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5304,'Think of the deeds of hellish cruelty, the hidden wickedness which may go on, year in, year out, in such places, and none the wiser.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5305,'Had this lady who appeals to us for help gone to live in Winchester, I should never have had a fear for her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5306,'It is the five miles of country which makes the danger.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5307,'Still, it is clear that she is not personally threatened.  No.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5308,'If she can come to Winchester to meet us she can get away.  Quite so. She has her freedom.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5309,'What _can_ be the matter, then? Can you suggest no explanation?  I have devised seven separate explanations, each of which would cover the facts as far as we know them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5310,'But which of these is correct can only be determined by the fresh information which we shall no doubt find waiting for us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5311,'Well, there is the tower of the cathedral, and we shall soon learn all that Miss Hunter has to tell.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5312,'The Black Swan is an inn of repute in the High Street, at no distance from the station, and there we found the young lady waiting for us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5313,'She had engaged a sitting-room, and our lunch awaited us upon the table.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5314,'I am so delighted that you have come, she said, earnestly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5315,'It is so very kind of you both; but indeed I do not know what I should do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5316,'Your advice will be altogether invaluable to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5317,'Pray tell us what has happened to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5318,'I will do so, and I must be quick, for I have promised Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5319,'Rucastle to be back before three.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5320,'I got his leave to come into town this morning, though he little knew for what purpose.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5321,'Let us have everything in its due order.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5322,'Holmes thrust his long thin legs out towards the fire and composed himself to listen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5323,'In the first place, I may say that I have met, on the whole, with no actual ill-treatment from Mr. and Mrs. Rucastle.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5324,'It is only fair to them to say that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5325,'But I cannot understand them, and I am not easy in my mind about them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5326,'What can you not understand?  Their reasons for their conduct.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5327,'But you shall have it all just as it occurred.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5328,'When I came down, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5329,'Rucastle met me here, and drove me in his dog-cart to the Copper Beeches.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5330,'It is, as he said, beautifully situated, but it is not beautiful in itself, for it is a large square block of a house, whitewashed, but all stained and streaked with damp and bad weather.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5331,'There are grounds round it, woods on three sides, and on the fourth a field which slopes down to the Southampton high-road, which curves past about a hundred yards from the front door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5332,'This ground in front belongs to the house, but the woods all round are part of Lord Southerton’s preserves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5333,'A clump of copper beeches immediately in front of the hall door has given its name to the place.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5334,'[Illustration: ‘I AM SO DELIGHTED THAT YOU HAVE COME’]  I was driven over by my employer, who was as amiable as ever, and was introduced by him that evening to his wife and the child.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5335,'There was no truth, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5336,'Holmes, in the conjecture which seemed to us to be probable in your rooms at Baker Street. Mrs. Rucastle is not mad.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5337,'I found her to be a silent, pale-faced woman, much younger than her husband, not more than thirty, I should think, while he can hardly be less than forty-five.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5338,'From their conversation I have gathered that they have been married about seven years, that he was a widower, and that his only child by the first wife was the daughter who has gone to Philadelphia. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5339,'Rucastle told me in private that the reason why she had left them was that she had an unreasoning aversion to her step-mother.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5340,'As the daughter could not have been less than twenty, I can quite imagine that her position must have been uncomfortable with her father’s young wife.  Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5341,'Rucastle seemed to me to be colorless in mind as well as in feature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5342,'She impressed me neither favorably nor the reverse. She was a nonentity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5343,'It was easy to see that she was passionately devoted both to her husband and to her little son.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5344,'Her light gray eyes wandered continually from one to the other, noting every little want and forestalling it if possible.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5345,'He was kind to her also in his bluff, boisterous fashion, and on the whole they seemed to be a happy couple.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5346,'And yet she had some secret sorrow, this woman.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5347,'She would often be lost in deep thought, with the saddest look upon her face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5348,'More than once I have surprised her in tears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5349,'I have thought sometimes that it was the disposition of her child which weighed upon her mind, for I have never met so utterly spoilt and so ill-natured a little creature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5350,'He is small for his age, with a head which is quite disproportionately large.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5351,'His whole life appears to be spent in an alternation between savage fits of passion and gloomy intervals of sulking.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5352,'Giving pain to any creature weaker than himself seems to be his one idea of amusement, and he shows quite remarkable talent in planning the capture of mice, little birds, and insects.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5353,'But I would rather not talk about the creature, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5354,'Holmes, and, indeed, he has little to do with my story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5355,'I am glad of all details, remarked my friend, whether they seem to you to be relevant or not.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5356,'I shall try not to miss anything of importance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5357,'The one unpleasant thing about the house, which struck me at once, was the appearance and conduct of the servants.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5358,'There are only two, a man and his wife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5359,'Toller, for that is his name, is a rough, uncouth man, with grizzled hair and whiskers, and a perpetual smell of drink.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5360,'Twice since I have been with them he has been quite drunk, and yet Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5361,'Rucastle seemed to take no notice of it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5362,'His wife is a very tall and strong woman with a sour face, as silent as Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5363,'Rucastle, and much less amiable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5364,'They are a most unpleasant couple, but fortunately I spend most of my time in the nursery and my own room, which are next to each other in one corner of the building.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5365,'For two days after my arrival at the Copper Beeches my life was very quiet; on the third, Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5366,'Rucastle came down just after breakfast and whispered something to her husband.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5367,'‘Oh yes,’ said he, turning to me; ‘we are very much obliged to you, Miss Hunter, for falling in with our whims so far as to cut your hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5368,'I assure you that it has not detracted in the tiniest iota from your appearance.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5369,'We shall now see how the electric-blue dress will become you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5370,'You will find it laid out upon the bed in your room, and if you would be so good as to put it on we should both be extremely obliged.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5371,'’  The dress which I found waiting for me was of a peculiar shade of blue.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5372,'It was of excellent material, a sort of beige, but it bore unmistakable signs of having been worn before.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5373,'It could not have been a better fit if I had been measured for it. Both Mr. and Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5374,'Rucastle expressed a delight at the look of it, which seemed quite exaggerated in its vehemence.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5375,'They were waiting for me in the drawing-room, which is a very large room, stretching along the entire front of the house, with three long windows reaching down to the floor.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5376,'A chair had been placed close to the central window, with its back turned towards it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5377,'In this I was asked to sit, and then Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5378,'Rucastle, walking up and down on the other side of the room, began to tell me a series of the funniest stories that I have ever listened to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5379,'You cannot imagine how comical he was, and I laughed until I was quite weary. Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5380,'Rucastle, however, who has evidently no sense of humor, never so much as smiled, but sat with her hands in her lap, and a sad, anxious look upon her face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5381,'After an hour or so, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5382,'Rucastle suddenly remarked that it was time to commence the duties of the day, and that I might change my dress and go to little Edward in the nursery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5383,'Two days later this same performance was gone through under exactly similar circumstances.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5384,'Again I changed my dress, again I sat in the window, and again I laughed very heartily at the funny stories of which my employer had an immense _répertoire_, and which he told inimitably.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5385,'Then he handed me a yellow-backed novel, and, moving my chair a little sideways, that my own shadow might not fall upon the page, he begged me to read aloud to him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5386,'I read for about ten minutes, beginning in the heart of a chapter, and then suddenly, in the middle of a sentence, he ordered me to cease and to change my dress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5387,'You can easily imagine, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5388,'Holmes, how curious I became as to what the meaning of this extraordinary performance could possibly be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5389,'They were always very careful, I observed, to turn my face away from the window, so that I became consumed with the desire to see what was going on behind my back.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5390,'At first it seemed to be impossible, but I soon devised a means.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5391,'My hand-mirror had been broken, so a happy thought seized me, and I concealed a piece of the glass in my handkerchief.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5392,'On the next occasion, in the midst of my laughter, I put my handkerchief up to my eyes, and was able with a little management to see all that there was behind me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5393,'I confess that I was disappointed. There was nothing.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5394,'At least that was my first impression.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5395,'At the second glance, however, I perceived that there was a man standing in the Southampton Road, a small bearded man in a gray suit, who seemed to be looking in my direction.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5396,'The road is an important highway, and there are usually people there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5397,'This man, however, was leaning against the railings which bordered our field, and was looking earnestly up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5398,'I lowered my handkerchief and glanced at Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5399,'Rucastle, to find her eyes fixed upon me with a most searching gaze.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5400,'She said nothing, but I am convinced that she had divined that I had a mirror in my hand, and had seen what was behind me. She rose at once.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5401,'‘Jephro,’ said she, ‘there is an impertinent fellow upon the road there who stares up at Miss Hunter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5402,'’  ‘No friend of yours, Miss Hunter?’ he asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5403,'‘No; I know no one in these parts.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5404,'’  ‘Dear me! How very impertinent! Kindly turn round and motion to him to go away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5405,'’  ‘Surely it would be better to take no notice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5406,'’  ‘No, no, we should have him loitering here always.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5407,'Kindly turn round and wave him away like that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5408,'’  I did as I was told, and at the same instant Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5409,'Rucastle drew down the blind.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5410,'That was a week ago, and from that time I have not sat again in the window, nor have I worn the blue dress, nor seen the man in the road.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5411,'Pray continue, said Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5412,'Your narrative promises to be a most interesting one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5413,'You will find it rather disconnected, I fear, and there may prove to be little relation between the different incidents of which I speak.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5414,'On the very first day that I was at the Copper Beeches, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5415,'Rucastle took me to a small out-house which stands near the kitchen door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5416,'As we approached it I heard the sharp rattling of a chain, and the sound as of a large animal moving about.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5417,'‘Look in here!’ said Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5418,'Rucastle, showing me a slit between two planks.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5419,'‘Is he not a beauty?’  I looked through, and was conscious of two glowing eyes, and of a vague figure huddled up in the darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5420,'‘Don’t be frightened,’ said my employer, laughing at the start which I had given.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5421,'‘It’s only Carlo, my mastiff.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5422,'I call him mine, but really old Toller, my groom, is the only man who can do anything with him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5423,'We feed him once a day, and not too much then, so that he is always as keen as mustard.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5424,'Toller lets him loose every night, and God help the trespasser whom he lays his fangs upon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5425,'For goodness’ sake don’t you ever on any pretext set your foot over the threshold at night, for it is as much as your life is worth.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5426,'’  The warning was no idle one, for two nights later I happened to look out of my bedroom window about two o’clock in the morning.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5427,'It was a beautiful moonlight night, and the lawn in front of the house was silvered over and almost as bright as day.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5428,'I was standing, rapt in the peaceful beauty of the scene, when I was aware that something was moving under the shadow of the copper beeches.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5429,'As it emerged into the moonshine I saw what it was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5430,'It was a giant dog, as large as a calf, tawny tinted, with hanging jowl, black muzzle, and huge projecting bones.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5431,'It walked slowly across the lawn and vanished into the shadow upon the other side.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5432,'That dreadful silent sentinel sent a chill to my heart which I do not think that any burglar could have done.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5433,'And now I have a very strange experience to tell you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5434,'I had, as you know, cut off my hair in London, and I had placed it in a great coil at the bottom of my trunk.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5435,'One evening, after the child was in bed, I began to amuse myself by examining the furniture of my room and by rearranging my own little things.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5436,'There was an old chest of drawers in the room, the two upper ones empty and open, the lower one locked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5437,'I had filled the first two with my linen, and, as I had still much to pack away, I was naturally annoyed at not having the use of the third drawer.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5438,'It struck me that it might have been fastened by a mere oversight, so I took out my bunch of keys and tried to open it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5439,'The very first key fitted to perfection, and I drew the drawer open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5440,'There was only one thing in it, but I am sure that you would never guess what it was.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5441,'It was my coil of hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5442,'I took it up and examined it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5443,'It was of the same peculiar tint, and the same thickness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5444,'But then the impossibility of the thing obtruded itself upon me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5445,'How _could_ my hair have been locked in the drawer? With trembling hands I undid my trunk, turned out the contents, and drew from the bottom my own hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5446,'I laid the two tresses together, and I assure you that they were identical.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5447,'Was it not extraordinary? Puzzle as I would, I could make nothing at all of what it meant.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5448,'I returned the strange hair to the drawer, and I said nothing of the matter to the Rucastles, as I felt that I had put myself in the wrong by opening a drawer which they had locked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5449,'I am naturally observant, as you may have remarked, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5450,'Holmes, and I soon had a pretty good plan of the whole house in my head.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5451,'There was one wing, however, which appeared not to be inhabited at all.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5452,'A door which faced that which led into the quarters of the Tollers opened into this suite, but it was invariably locked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5453,'One day, however, as I ascended the stair, I met Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5454,'Rucastle coming out through this door, his keys in his hand, and a look on his face which made him a very different person to the round, jovial man to whom I was accustomed.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5455,'His cheeks were red, his brow was all crinkled with anger, and the veins stood out at his temples with passion.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5456,'He locked the door and hurried past me without a word or a look.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5457,'This aroused my curiosity; so when I went out for a walk in the grounds with my charge, I strolled round to the side from which I could see the windows of this part of the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5458,'There were four of them in a row, three of which were simply dirty, while the fourth was shuttered up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5459,'They were evidently all deserted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5460,'As I strolled up and down, glancing at them occasionally, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5461,'Rucastle came out to me, looking as merry and jovial as ever.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5462,'‘Ah!’ said he, ‘you must not think me rude if I passed you without a word, my dear young lady.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5463,'I was preoccupied with business matters.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5464,'’  I assured him that I was not offended.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5465,'‘By-the-way,’ said I, ‘you seem to have quite a suite of spare rooms up there, and one of them has the shutters up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5466,'’  He looked surprised, and, as it seemed to me, a little startled at my remark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5467,'‘Photography is one of my hobbies,’ said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5468,'‘I have made my dark room up there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5469,'But, dear me! what an observant young lady we have come upon.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5470,'Who would have believed it? Who would have ever believed it?’ He spoke in a jesting tone, but there was no jest in his eyes as he looked at me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5471,'I read suspicion there and annoyance, but no jest.  Well, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5472,'Holmes, from the moment that I understood that there was something about that suite of rooms which I was not to know, I was all on fire to go over them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5473,'It was not mere curiosity, though I have my share of that.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5474,'It was more a feeling of duty—a feeling that some good might come from my penetrating to this place.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5475,'They talk of woman’s instinct; perhaps it was woman’s instinct which gave me that feeling.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5476,'At any rate, it was there, and I was keenly on the lookout for any chance to pass the forbidden door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5477,'It was only yesterday that the chance came.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5478,'I may tell you that, besides Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5479,'Rucastle, both Toller and his wife find something to do in these deserted rooms, and I once saw him carrying a large black linen bag with him through the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5480,'Recently he has been drinking hard, and yesterday evening he was very drunk; and, when I came up-stairs, there was the key in the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5481,'I have no doubt at all that he had left it there. Mr. and Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5482,'Rucastle were both down-stairs, and the child was with them, so that I had an admirable opportunity.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5483,'I turned the key gently in the lock, opened the door, and slipped through.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5484,'There was a little passage in front of me, unpapered and uncarpeted, which turned at a right angle at the farther end.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5485,'Round this corner were three doors in a line, the first and third of which were open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5486,'They each led into an empty room, dusty and cheerless, with two windows in the one and one in the other, so thick with dirt that the evening light glimmered dimly through them.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5487,'The centre door was closed, and across the outside of it had been fastened one of the broad bars of an iron bed, padlocked at one end to a ring in the wall, and fastened at the other with stout cord.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5488,'The door itself was locked as well, and the key was not there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5489,'This barricaded door corresponded clearly with the shuttered window outside, and yet I could see by the glimmer from beneath it that the room was not in darkness.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5490,'Evidently there was a skylight which let in light from above.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5491,'As I stood in the passage gazing at the sinister door, and wondering what secret it might veil, I suddenly heard the sound of steps within the room, and saw a shadow pass backward and forward against the little slit of dim light which shone out from under the door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5492,'A mad, unreasoning terror rose up in me at the sight, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5493,'My overstrung nerves failed me suddenly, and I turned and ran—ran as though some dreadful hand were behind me clutching at the skirt of my dress.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5494,'I rushed down the passage, through the door, and straight into the arms of Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5495,'Rucastle, who was waiting outside.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5496,'‘So,’ said he, smiling, ‘it was you, then.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5497,'I thought that it must be when I saw the door open.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5498,'’  ‘Oh, I am so frightened!’ I panted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5499,'‘My dear young lady! my dear young lady!’—you cannot think how caressing and soothing his manner was—‘and what has frightened you, my dear young lady?’  But his voice was just a little too coaxing. He overdid it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5500,'I was keenly on my guard against him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5501,'‘I was foolish enough to go into the empty wing,’ I answered.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5502,'‘But it is so lonely and eerie in this dim light that I was frightened and ran out again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5503,'Oh, it is so dreadfully still in there!’  ‘Only that?’ said he, looking at me keenly.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5504,'‘Why, what did you think?’ I asked.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5505,'‘Why do you think that I lock this door?’  ‘I am sure that I do not know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5506,'’  ‘It is to keep people out who have no business there.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5507,'Do you see?’ He was still smiling in the most amiable manner.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5508,'‘I am sure if I had known—’  ‘Well, then, you know now.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5509,'And if you ever put your foot over that threshold again—’ here in an instant the smile hardened into a grin of rage, and he glared down at me with the face of a demon—‘I’ll throw you to the mastiff.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5510,'’  I was so terrified that I do not know what I did.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5511,'I suppose that I must have rushed past him into my room.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5512,'I remember nothing until I found myself lying on my bed trembling all over.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5513,'Then I thought of you, Mr. Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5514,'I could not live there longer without some advice.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5515,'I was frightened of the house, of the man, of the woman, of the servants, even of the child.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5516,'They were all horrible to me.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5517,'If I could only bring you down all would be well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5518,'Of course I might have fled from the house, but my curiosity was almost as strong as my fears.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5519,'My mind was soon made up.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5520,'I would send you a wire.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5521,'I put on my hat and cloak, went down to the office, which is about half a mile from the house, and then returned, feeling very much easier.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5522,'A horrible doubt came into my mind as I approached the door lest the dog might be loose, but I remembered that Toller had drunk himself into a state of insensibility that evening, and I knew that he was the only one in the household who had any influence with the savage creature, or who would venture to set him free.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5523,'I slipped in in safety, and lay awake half the night in my joy at the thought of seeing you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5524,'I had no difficulty in getting leave to come into Winchester this morning, but I must be back before three o’clock, for Mr. and Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5525,'Rucastle are going on a visit, and will be away all the evening, so that I must look after the child.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5526,'Now I have told you all my adventures, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5527,'Holmes, and I should be very glad if you could tell me what it all means, and, above all, what I should do.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5528,'Holmes and I had listened spellbound to this extraordinary story.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5529,'My friend rose now and paced up and down the room, his hands in his pockets, and an expression of the most profound gravity upon his face.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5530,'Is Toller still drunk? he asked.  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5531,'I heard his wife tell Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5532,'Rucastle that she could do nothing with him.  That is well.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5533,'And the Rucastles go out to-night?  Yes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5534,'Is there a cellar with a good strong lock?  Yes, the wine-cellar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5535,'You seem to me to have acted all through this matter like a very brave and sensible girl, Miss Hunter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5536,'Do you think that you could perform one more feat? I should not ask it of you if I did not think you a quite exceptional woman.  I will try.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5537,'What is it?  We shall be at the Copper Beeches by seven o’clock, my friend and I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5538,'The Rucastles will be gone by that time, and Toller will, we hope, be incapable.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5539,'There only remains Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5540,'Toller, who might give the alarm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5541,'If you could send her into the cellar on some errand, and then turn the key upon her, you would facilitate matters immensely.  I will do it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5542,'Excellent! We shall then look thoroughly into the affair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5543,'Of course there is only one feasible explanation.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5544,'You have been brought there to personate some one, and the real person is imprisoned in this chamber. That is obvious.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5545,'As to who this prisoner is, I have no doubt that it is the daughter, Miss Alice Rucastle, if I remember right, who was said to have gone to America.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5546,'You were chosen, doubtless, as resembling her in height, figure, and the color of your hair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5547,'Hers had been cut off, very possibly in some illness through which she has passed, and so, of course, yours had to be sacrificed also.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5548,'By a curious chance you came upon her tresses.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5549,'The man in the road was, undoubtedly, some friend of hers—possibly her _fiancé_—and no doubt, as you wore the girl’s dress and were so like her, he was convinced from your laughter, whenever he saw you, and afterwards from your gesture, that Miss Rucastle was perfectly happy, and that she no longer desired his attentions.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5550,'The dog is let loose at night to prevent him from endeavoring to communicate with her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5551,'So much is fairly clear.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5552,'The most serious point in the case is the disposition of the child.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5553,'What on earth has that to do with it? I ejaculated.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5554,'My dear Watson, you as a medical man are continually gaining light as to the tendencies of a child by the study of the parents.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5555,'Don’t you see that the converse is equally valid.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5556,'I have frequently gained my first real insight into the character of parents by studying their children.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5557,'This child’s disposition is abnormally cruel, merely for cruelty’s sake, and whether he derives this from his smiling father, as I should suspect, or from his mother, it bodes evil for the poor girl who is in their power.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5558,'I am sure that you are right, Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5559,'Holmes, cried our client.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5560,'A thousand things come back to me which make me certain that you have hit it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5561,'Oh, let us lose not an instant in bringing help to this poor creature.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5562,'We must be circumspect, for we are dealing with a very cunning man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5563,'We can do nothing until seven o’clock.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5564,'At that hour we shall be with you, and it will not be long before we solve the mystery.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5565,'We were as good as our word, for it was just seven when we reached the Copper Beeches, having put up our trap at a way-side public-house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5566,'The group of trees, with their dark leaves shining like burnished metal in the light of the setting sun, were sufficient to mark the house even had Miss Hunter not been standing smiling on the door-step.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5567,'Have you managed it? asked Holmes.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5568,'A loud thudding noise came from somewhere down-stairs. That is Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5569,'Toller in the cellar, said she.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5570,'Her husband lies snoring on the kitchen rug.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5571,'Here are his keys, which are the duplicates of Mr. Rucastle’s.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5572,'You have done well indeed! cried Holmes, with enthusiasm.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5573,'Now lead the way, and we shall soon see the end of this black business.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5574,'We passed up the stair, unlocked the door, followed on down a passage, and found ourselves in front of the barricade which Miss Hunter had described.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5575,'Holmes cut the cord and removed the transverse bar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5576,'Then he tried the various keys in the lock, but without success.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5577,'No sound came from within, and at the silence Holmes’s face clouded over.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5578,'I trust that we are not too late, said he.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5579,'I think, Miss Hunter, that we had better go in without you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5580,'Now, Watson, put your shoulder to it, and we shall see whether we cannot make our way in.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5581,'It was an old rickety door, and gave at once before our united strength.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5582,'Together we rushed into the room. It was empty.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5583,'There was no furniture save a little pallet bed, a small table, and a basketful of linen.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5584,'The skylight above was open, and the prisoner gone.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5585,'There has been some villainy here, said Holmes; this beauty has guessed Miss Hunter’s intentions, and has carried his victim off.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5586,'But how?  Through the skylight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5587,'We shall soon see how he managed it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5588,'He swung himself up onto the roof.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5589,'Ah, yes, he cried; here’s the end of a long light ladder against the eaves.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5590,'That is how he did it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5591,'But it is impossible, said Miss Hunter; the ladder was not there when the Rucastles went away.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5592,'He has come back and done it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5593,'I tell you that he is a clever and dangerous man.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5594,'I should not be very much surprised if this were he whose step I hear now upon the stair.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5595,'I think, Watson, that it would be as well for you to have your pistol ready.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5596,'The words were hardly out of his mouth before a man appeared at the door of the room, a very fat and burly man, with a heavy stick in his hand.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5597,'Miss Hunter screamed and shrunk against the wall at the sight of him, but Sherlock Holmes sprang forward and confronted him.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5598,'You villain! said he, where’s your daughter?  The fat man cast his eyes round, and then up at the open skylight.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5599,'It is for me to ask you that, he shrieked, you thieves! Spies and thieves! I have caught you, have I? You are in my power.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5600,'I’ll serve you! He turned and clattered down the stairs as hard as he could go.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5601,'He’s gone for the dog! cried Miss Hunter.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5602,'I have my revolver, said I.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5603,'Better close the front door, cried Holmes, and we all rushed down the stairs together.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5604,'We had hardly reached the hall when we heard the baying of a hound, and then a scream of agony, with a horrible worrying sound which it was dreadful to listen to.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5605,'An elderly man with a red face and shaking limbs came staggering out at a side door.  My God! he cried.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5606,'Some one has loosed the dog.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5607,'It’s not been fed for two days.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5608,'Quick, quick, or it’ll be too late!  Holmes and I rushed out and round the angle of the house, with Toller hurrying behind us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5609,'There was the huge famished brute, its black muzzle buried in Rucastle’s throat, while he writhed and screamed upon the ground.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5610,'Running up, I blew its brains out, and it fell over with its keen white teeth still meeting in the great creases of his neck.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5611,'With much labor we separated them, and carried him, living but horribly mangled, into the house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5612,'We laid him upon the drawing-room sofa, and, having despatched the sobered Toller to bear the news to his wife, I did what I could to relieve his pain.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5613,'We were all assembled round him when the door opened, and a tall, gaunt woman entered the room.  Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5614,'Toller! cried Miss Hunter.  Yes, miss. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5615,'Rucastle let me out when he came back before he went up to you.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5616,'Ah, miss, it is a pity you didn’t let me know what you were planning, for I would have told you that your pains were wasted.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5617,'Ha! said Holmes, looking keenly at her.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5618,'It is clear that Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5619,'Toller knows more about this matter than any one else.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5620,'Yes, sir, I do, and I am ready enough to tell what I know.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5621,'Then, pray, sit down, and let us hear it, for there are several points on which I must confess that I am still in the dark.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5622,'I will soon make it clear to you, said she; and I’d have done so before now if I could ha’ got out from the cellar.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5623,'If there’s police-court business over this, you’ll remember that I was the one that stood your friend, and that I was Miss Alice’s friend too.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5624,'She was never happy at home, Miss Alice wasn’t, from the time that her father married again.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5625,'She was slighted like, and had no say in anything; but it never really became bad for her until after she met Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5626,'Fowler at a friend’s house.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5627,'As well as I could learn, Miss Alice had rights of her own by will, but she was so quiet and patient, she was, that she never said a word about them, but just left everything in Mr. Rucastle’s hands.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5628,'He knew he was safe with her; but when there was a chance of a husband coming forward, who would ask for all that the law would give him, then her father thought it time to put a stop on it.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5629,'He wanted her to sign a paper, so that whether she married or not, he could use her money.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5630,'When she wouldn’t do it, he kept on worrying her until she got brain-fever, and for six weeks was at death’s door.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5631,'Then she got better at last, all worn to a shadow, and with her beautiful hair cut off; but that didn’t make no change in her young man, and he stuck to her as true as man could be.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5632,'Ah, said Holmes, I think that what you have been good enough to tell us makes the matter fairly clear, and that I can deduce all that remains. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5633,'Rucastle then, I presume, took to this system of imprisonment?  Yes, sir.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5634,'And brought Miss Hunter down from London in order to get rid of the disagreeable persistence of Mr. Fowler.  That was it, sir.  But Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5635,'Fowler being a persevering man, as a good seaman should be, blockaded the house, and, having met you, succeeded by certain arguments, metallic or otherwise, in convincing you that your interests were the same as his.  Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5636,'Fowler was a very kind-spoken, free-handed gentleman, said Mrs. Toller, serenely.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5637,'And in this way he managed that your good man should have no want of drink, and that a ladder should be ready at the moment when your master had gone out.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5638,'You have it, sir, just as it happened.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5639,'I am sure we owe you an apology, Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5640,'Toller, said Holmes, for you have certainly cleared up everything which puzzled us.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5641,'And here comes the country surgeon and Mrs.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5642,'Rucastle, so I think, Watson, that we had best escort Miss Hunter back to Winchester, as it seems to me that our _locus standi_ now is rather a questionable one.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5643,'And thus was solved the mystery of the sinister house with the copper beeches in front of the door. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5644,'Rucastle survived, but was always a broken man, kept alive solely through the care of his devoted wife.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5645,'They still live with their old servants, who probably know so much of Rucastle’s past life that he finds it difficult to part from them. Mr.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5646,'Fowler and Miss Rucastle were married, by special license, in Southampton the day after their flight, and he is now the holder of a Government appointment in the Island of Mauritius.');
INSERT INTO sentences VALUES(5647,'As to Miss Violet Hunter, my friend Holmes, rather to my disappointment, manifested no further interest in her when once she had ceased to be the centre of one of his problems, and she is now the head of a private school at Walsall, where I believe that she has met with considerable success.');
